<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENATCHEE-REPORT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OMBUDSMAN CALLS FOR CHANGES IN ABUSE INVESTIGATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREW SCHNEIDER  
 By AND MIKE BARBER  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A review of the state's actions in the Wenatchee child
sex-abuse cases has found enough questions and problems that an
independent ombudsman is calling for changes in the way social
workers and police investigate such crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Better training, tighter supervision and new laws are needed to
prevent investigators from making the kinds of mistakes that are
alleged to have happened in Wenatchee, said Vickie Wallen,
ombudsman for the state's Office of Family and Children.
</P>
<P>
   She issued a 61-page report Wednesday after a seven-month
investigation of Child Protective Services' handling of child-rape
and molestation allegations in 1994 and 1995 that involved more
than 80 adults and at least 55 children. Ultimately, 43 people were
charged. Of those convicted of crimes involving sexual abuse
against children, several have been freed after their sentences
were overturned on appeal. Appellate judges often have criticized
the quality of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Wallen's carefully worded report paints a vivid picture of
children being pressured by social workers and police into accusing
their parents and neighbors of rape and molestation.
</P>
<P>
   But CPS so poorly documented its work that it was ``impossible
to determine what actually happened in these cases,'' Wallen said.
Available documents do show hundreds of investigatory errors and
examples of incorrect or inappropriate professional judgment, she
said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the examples of investigative error cited in the report
were first reported by the Post-Intelligencer in February.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that he had not seen the report when it was
released early Wednesday, Gov. Gary Locke said he was directing the
Department of Social and Health Services ``to review and respond to
the ombudsman's recommendations, which in part are consistent with
the directions the department already has been pursuing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Oreskovich, assistant secretary for the Children's
Administration, which includes CPS, said she was pleased by the
report, saying it ``confirms that there were no findings against''
the CPS staff in Wenatchee.
</P>
<P>
   Wallen agreed the report does not establish clear-cut violations
of law or policy but said it ``neither vindicates nor condemns any
of the families of the children allegedly abused, nor CPS
investigators involved in the Wenatchee cases.''
</P>
<P>
   In the report, Wallen notes that Oreskovich earlier this year
ordered a ``comprehensive, internal record review of the Wenatchee
cases'' that reportedly found no significant problems. The
ombudsman, who examined the same records, questioned that finding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to determine how the department could
meaningfully assess the Wenatchee cases without knowing more about
what occurred in the child interviews,'' the report reads.
</P>
<P>
   ``CPS' investigative process was not documented well enough to
allow our staff to ascertain whether investigative mistakes
occurred that led to errors in the accuracy of how the
investigators were understanding what the children were actually
saying,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot hold the system accountable without knowing more
about what happened,'' Wallen said.
</P>
<P>
   What her investigators did find was troubling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CPS and police records document hundreds of clear and
significant errors dealing with the leading and suggestive
questioning of the children,'' Wallen said. ``There was an obvious
existence of the preconceived notion by CPS and police that the
kids were abused.''
</P>
<P>
   In criticizing the investigations, the ombudsman expressed
particular concern about the manner in which children were
questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interviews of Wenatchee children were never documented in a
format that indicated exactly what questions were asked, by whom
and what the answers were.''
</P>
<P>
   While using only pseuedonyms for the victims and the police, the
report faults the use of leading and suggestive questioning,
particularly by police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Several examples were cited where children denied they had been
abused and were told by police and social workers that their
parents had already confessed, or siblings were counting on them to
tell the truth, or that the investigators knew they were lying.
</P>
<P>
   The report also questions actions of state-contracted mental
health therapists. For example, several children who repeatedly
denied they had been abused were diagnosed by the appointed
therapists as having post-traumatic stress disorder or
disassociation.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a review of the records, the ombudsman ``is concerned
whether these diagnoses were clinically appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the report questioned the conflicting roles of the
Wenatchee therapists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the mental health service providers to the
Wenatchee children were sometimes confused about their roles in
working with child abuse victims,'' Wallen said. ``The record
clearly indicates that some treating therapists were more focused
on investigating the allegations than on the therapy they were
contracted to provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallen said it is possible the abuse occurred as alleged, or
that something went wrong in the child abuse investigative system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately we will never know for sure which of those
possibilities are true,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those expected to address problems cited by Wallen include state
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeanine Long, R-Mill Creek, chairwoman of the Senate Human
Services and Corrections Committee, called the CPS investigator's
common practice of destroying notes taken during interviews, as
described in Wallen's report, to be ``appalling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There will likely be a bill that will require that written
notes be retained,'' introduced in the upcoming legislative
session, Long said.
</P>
<P>
   Long also called for not only better general training of all CPS
workers but the establishment of a group of people ``very specially
trained'' to be brought into cases where child sexual abuse is
suspected.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a big concern about what it would cost,'' Long
said, ``but add up what Wenatchee has cost and it would be
phenomenal, and that's just the monetary costs, not the emotional
costs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
