<HEADER>
A5276 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-HNS &LR;      12-24 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
The end is near.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   If no significant progress is made toward a new
collective-bargaining agreement between NBA owners and the National
Basketball Players Association by Jan. 7, commissioner David Stern
will recommend canceling the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   The league has a Board of Governors meeting scheduled that day
and will hear a report from the owners' negotiating committee on
how the labor talks with the union are progressing.
</P>
<P>
   But NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said that should he and
Stern think the two sides are making sufficient progress toward an
agreement, then negotiations probably will continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on where we are,'' Granik said Wednesday, Day 176
of the lockout. ``We will get a report from the labor-relations
committee, and if the report is that we're not close (to an
agreement) and don't expect to have a deal, they will likely have
to vote on canceling the season, and David and I will recommend it
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik said there are members of the Board of Governors who
think the season already should have been canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are several (who feel that way),'' he said. ``But I
think that in the end, if there's a fair deal by that date, they'll
go with the rest of the group (and allow the season to go on).''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Arn Tellem, who represents Reggie Miller and Kobe Bryant,
among others, thinks cancellation might be inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my view that if the owners are unwilling to move from
their current proposal, the season will then be canceled,'' Tellem
said. ``I believe that ultimately when the players analyze this,
there is no way they will ever take the deal on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the season be canceled, it would be the first time a
major professional sports league in North America lost an entire
season for any reason. Major-league baseball has had eight work
stoppages since 1972, including a 232-day strike that wiped out the
1994 World Series, but it never has lost an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is inching closer to just that.
</P>
<P>
   Union executive director Billy Hunter is in Oakland, Calif., for
Christmas; Stern is vacationing in Aspen, Colo., so no negotiations
are scheduled in the near future. But Granik said he expects there
will be at least one formal meeting between the negotiating
committees before Jan. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll have a meeting or meetings (with the union)
before then,'' Granik said. ``I can't believe we'd let it evaporate
without one or two (meetings). But there's no reason to think
they'll end any differently than the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Some close to the union question Stern's decision to take off
for the ski slopes rather than sit down and negotiate, as the
league teeters on the brink.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our whole negotiating committee in New York this past
weekend,'' said one union source. ``We met with everybody Monday,
so if they (the owners) wanted to meet, they knew where we were.
They knew, but they chose to do what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, whispers that the union's rank and file might demand
a secret ballot on the owners' latest proposal, mailed last week by
Stern to every NBA player, continue to circulate. Karl Malone
started the ball rolling by saying Saturday that the proposal was
``fair'' and needed only minor changes to be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Other players have joined in.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Mitchell, Minnesota's player representative, said: ``If
there is to be a cancellation of the season, every guy should see
those numbers (in Stern's letter) and make their decision. But
we're crazy if we don't play this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Rocket Kevin Willis said, ``The majority would vote for
the owners' latest proposal just to start playing ball again.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hakeem Olajuwon disagreed with the notion of a secret
ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' he said. ``I think if that was the case,
that should have been done in the beginning. Now, we've got to
finish it. We've got to stick with (union leaders). This is what
the owners are banking on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what he (Willis) is saying. It's a difference of
opinion. It's nothing against him. We need to stick together. It
(appears to be) a good idea, but when you look over all the
particulars, it's a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Many disagree with Olajuwon's opinion. Some close to the
negotiations are saying a secret ballot by the union would pass the
new proposal by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be 2-1 in favor of signing,'' said one agent.
``It might be 70-30 in favor of the owners' proposal, but some
people think I'm being optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik said he has heard all the talk about strong union support
for the proposal should there be a secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a number of people have told me that,'' he said. ``But
again, Billy (Hunter) has said that he will not put it up for a
vote or anything like that. Obviously, the NBA doesn't have a right
to demand a vote, so it has to come from the players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I can understand and expect some players, perhaps a
lot of players, would like to make a deal. But the reality from our
end is that we have to deal with union leadership, so until
something changes on the part of leadership, it (support from
players) doesn't make a difference to the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders dispute all the talk about the possibility of
players lobbying for a secret vote on the new proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep hearing about all these players who want a vote,'' one
source said. ``The papers are writing that this player or that
player or several players want this secret vote, but then when we
talk to them we hear, `Oh, that's not what I said.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I'm sure if there was a majority of guys who
wanted to vote on this deal, it would be voted on. But until that
happens, it (a secret ballot) is not going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had enough contact with every guy in the league to know
where they stand.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the stalled negotiations and rampant rumors of union
rumblings, Olajuwon said a different approach might be needed to
save the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we need an arbitrator,'' he said. ``That's why we have
judges. There should be a middle ground. Both parties should work
to be fair. It should go to an arbitrator to decide on what's fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in a deal that is fair; you don't have to get
everything you want. Now, we're playing a losing game, the owners
and the players. That's doesn't benefit anything. You don't want to
get in a game of who can lose the most. That's not the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not in the business to lose money. It's said the owners
can afford to lose it more. I don't agree. They're not in the
business to lose money.''
</P>
<P>
   The union has requested mediation on several occasions, only to
be turned down by the NBA. Jesse Jackson has volunteered his
services in an effort to break the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to help,'' Jackson said. ``I want to see these
players back on the court again. I think it would be a great thing
to, between now and New Year's, get these players back to work
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
