</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-CHASE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECTACULAR 67-MILE CHASE ENDS WITH SHOOTING OF TRUCKER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Ga.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSTADT, N.J. _ In an intense barrage of gunfire, New Jersey
state troopers shot and critically wounded a truck driver Wednesday
after he led them on a 67-mile chase on the New Jersey Turnpike and
then drove into seven police vehicles trying to block him at a toll
gate here, state police officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, identified as Andre Battle, 28, of Atlanta, was shot
at least three times in the neck and chest and was reported to be
in critical condition Wednesday night after three hours of surgery
at the Hackensack University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   A state trooper, Matthew Finnegan, 33, was shot twice in the
left foot, either by himself or another trooper shooting at the
truck, said Col. Carl Williams, superintendent of state police.
Finnegan was reported in satisfactory condition at University
Hospital in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   The chase and shooting tied up traffic on the turnpike for
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said the entire incident began with a routine stop for
a traffic violation in Springfield Township in southern New Jersey
about 9:25 a.m. Trooper Anthony Duckett ``clocked'' Battle
traveling north at 73 mph in the outside lane and pulled him over,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Battle got out of his vehicle, talked briefly with Duckett and
then went to the truck to get his license and registration,
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   When Battle did not leave the cab, the trooper walked over and
told him to come out, according to Williams. Instead, Battle opened
the door and kicked the trooper in the head, knocking him onto the
roadway, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to Williams' account, Duckett went to his patrol
car to summon help as Battle drove off.
</P>
<P>
   In minutes, several other state police vehicles converged on the
truck as it headed north. The big rig and state police cars reached
the toll plaza here shortly before 10:30 a.m. Almost immediately,
Battle was caught in the lines of motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Battle was shot after he ignored a detective's order to stop his
truck and then crashed it into the vehicles, one after another,
that troopers had arrayed to prevent Battle from making a U-turn at
the plaza and escaping, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Battle managed to get the truck turned around. But he drove it
only about 200 yards from the plaza before the hail of bullets
stopped him. Williams said state police investigators had not
established late Wednesday afternoon how many troopers shot at the
truck or how many bullets were fired.
</P>
<P>
   But the windows of both front doors of the gleaming white
18-wheel rig were blown out and the windshield was pockmarked by at
least five bullet holes. An unmarked beige state police van that
Battle drove into was also hit by several bullets. Williams said it
was still unclear who fired at the van.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and the state's attorney general, Peter
Verniero, attended the news conference with Williams to praise the
performance of the troopers. Whitman said a ``great number'' of
motorists could have been injured if Battle had managed to drive
the truck from the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly the season of miracles,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Verniero, New Jersey's chief law enforcement official, said he
had ordered a comprehensive investigation of the incident,
including the gunfire by the troopers. He said that newly installed
video cameras in some of the patrol cars had recorded much, but not
all, of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But, he emphasized, he was satisfied that the troopers had not
violated his office's guidelines on the use of deadly force by
police. ``One thing is very clear, and that is there could have
been a great tragedy on the turnpike today that was avoided because
of good police work, because of good training,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The burst of gunfire at the toll plaza brought a chaotic end to
what officials described as a harrowing hourlong chase at speeds
ranging from 25 to 75 mph.
</P>
<P>
   At times, as many as nine state police cars, sirens screaming
and rooftop lights flashing, were involved in both trying to stop
Battle and to prevent any crashes.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said some of the cars raced ahead of the truck,
ordering motorists to stay to the right so a lane would be clear.
Other state police vehicles created roadblocks at entrance ramps to
the turnpike's northbound lanes, while others stayed abreast of the
truck and still others followed it.
</P>
<P>
   Several times during the chase, troopers issued orders to stop
over the loudspeakers in their cars, Williams said. All were
ignored, he said. At times, Williams said, Battle swerved his rig
toward police cars in the adjacent lane.
</P>
<P>
   Several motorists were waiting to pay tolls at the plaza when
the phalanx of trooper vehicles and the 18-wheeler arrived and
Battle tried to reverse his direction, touching off the barrage.
</P>
<P>
   One man caught up in the turmoil called WCBS News Radio 88 in
Manhattan, describing a wild scene as terrified motorists scurried
to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were diving out of their cars,'' the man told the
station. ``They were running to the side of the road. They didn't
want to get caught in the crossfire. There was shooting all over
the place. It was just incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, Williams said it was unclear whether
Battle was armed or whether he had fired at the troopers either
during the chase or at the toll plaza. By late afternoon, he said,
state police had not obtained a search warrant to inspect the cab
of the truck thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   The chase and shooting forced the New Jersey Turnpike Authority
to close the western leg of the turnpike between Exit 14, near
Newark International Airport, and the toll plaza at 11:14 a.m. This
created major traffic snarls throughout the afternoon and early
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The western leg's northbound lanes were reopened shortly after 7
p.m. The southbound lanes on the western leg, from the toll plaza
to Exit 16W, about five miles south, remained closed throughout the
evening as investigators continued studying the scene.
</P>
<P>
   The rig is owned by Salson Logistics, a trucking company based
in McDonough, Ga. Officials there said Battle was a part-time
driver with both good performance and driving records.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
