<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENO-KIDS-LADN     12-24 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENO-KIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. FIRST-GRADERS LAUGH WITH LENO AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHERRY JOE CROSBY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Like old troupers relishing their encore, the
kids from Sandy Toth's first-grade class at Balboa Magnet
Elementary School in suburban Northridge zipped through their licks
like pros Wednesday on ``The Tonight Show with Jay Leno.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-graders who performed a skit and sang on the show on
Thanksgiving eve were back on stage with Leno on Wednesday with a
Christmas act and song as part of a lineup that included actress
Roma Downey and the Rockettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' said Marisa Rader, 6, an aspiring movie star who
dismissed any notion of stage fright.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was on the show, I was really nervous. I'm not
nervous at all now. You don't have to be. It's a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Two appearances on the nation's top-ranked late night network
talk show in less than a month? Not bad for a group of pint-size
stars who don't even have their Screen Actors Guild cards yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feel like they're veterans now,'' said music teacher
Mandy Brigham, who led the 16 squirming children through their
paces.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing colorful paper hats and equipped with musical
instruments, the children recited their lines and sang a song
called ``The Marvelous Toy.'' And when technicians had to adjust
cameras and sound, the children remained kneeling quietly -- or as
quietly as first-graders can.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do I take this off?'' inquired one boy as he plucked at
the tiny microphone attached to his shirt collar.
</P>
<P>
   The only rehearsal mishap occurred when a boy's slide whistle --
integral to the song -- broke and had to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting one because it wasn't loud enough, the prop
department finally found a whistle loud enough and easy enough for
a 6-year-old boy to handle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one we'll hear,'' the stage manager said approvingly.
</P>
<P>
   Jolie Ancel, segment producer for ``The Tonight Show,'' also
praised the children. ``That was great, you guys!''
</P>
<P>
   For the past several years, students from Balboa Magnet have
appeared on the show, starting with a group of second-graders who
demonstrated their own inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Students from other campuses in Southern California's suburban
San Fernando Valley such as Riverside Elementary School in Sherman
Oaks and Thomas Jefferson School in Burbank also have appeared on
the program but ``Tonight Show'' producers said they've come to
rely on Balboa Magnet when they need tykes in a pinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always come through and they happen to do really good
things,'' Ancel said. ``It's become a nice working relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   During a break in rehearsal, students got a chance to reflect on
their newfound fame.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing himself on television for the first time, Jakov
Peric decided he wants to stay out of the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my family to tape the show,'' the 6-year-old
said. ``They show it to other people. Then I get embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Willem Patterson, 6, said he was intrigued with his newfound
celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting. It's like you're inside the TV,'' said
Willem, who played Santa Claus in Wednesday's skit.
</P>
<P>
   The first-grader also noted the differences between staging a
school play and a television show.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more stuff -- more activity,'' Willem said, struggling
to describe the myriad stage managers, directors, producers and
camera technicians who were on hand before the taping to make sure
the show went smoothly. ``There's so many people.''
</P>
<P>
   And what's his advice for breaking into show business? He
couldn't answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's `advice'? '' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
