<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STRUGGLES TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Schedule a game on Dec. 23 and this is what you
get: a sparse crowd, no noise and less atmosphere than Pluto. Even
Tyra Banks' presence behind the visitor's bench failed to inspire
the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Hold a series of grueling practices, including a game-day
workout, and this is what you get: sluggishness and sloppiness,
turnovers, bad shots and even worse defense.
</P>
<P>
   For those who ventured out two nights before Christmas, UCLA and
American delivered one of the most forgettable games at Pauley
Pavilion in years, a 66-56 Bruins victory in which UCLA's leading
scorer, Baron Davis, had a whopping 11 points.
</P>
<P>
   Looking exhausted from consecutive three-hours practices, the
Bruins sputtered and stuttered all night _ edging to a double-digit
lead in the first half, snoozing through most of the second, then
repelling the 24-point underdogs in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Tyra left early.
</P>
<P>
   Only Davis gave the somnolent crowd reason to cheer. In one
fabulous sequence, Davis stole the ball, outran the Eagles and
converted a windmill dunk; then he grabbed a rebound, dribbled
downcourt and passed the ball off the backboard to himself for a
lay-in.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also made the game-clinching play, snatching a loose ball
and speeding 75 feet for a three-point play that gave UCLA a 57-48
lead with 2:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the starters contributed little except bad defense
(Jerome Moiso), bad shots (JaRon Rush) and turnovers (Earl Watson).
</P>
<P>
   Reserves Sean Farnham, Ray Young and Matt Barnes once again
played well, which was no surprise considering Farnham and Barnes
didn't practice Tuesday and had enough energy to combat American,
which lost to USC 74-59 Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (Note: This was American University-United States, not American
University-Puerto Rico, which recently forfeited a game against
Oklahoma because of fighting.)
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are now one victory (Loyola Marymount) from sweeping
December _ a development that will count most in March when the
NCAA Selection Committee reviews their win total. Unlike previous
seasons, when UCLA could count on 12-15 Pac-10 victories, the
combination of a young roster and rugged conference will make 10
wins a tough task.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, UCLA needs every nonconference win it can get,
and Wednesday night's was No.7.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also need all the practice they can get, and coach
Steve Lavin knows it. He conducted three-hour practices Monday and
Tuesday, then held a rare game-day workout Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the conference is coming up so soon... with a young
team, we need to have a crash course,'' Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   He has two points of emphasis: transition defense and ball
movement. Assistant coach Steve Spencer, who scouts opponents,
always identifies the opponent's best 3-point shooters, but somehow
his instructions get lost in translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drives Spencer crazy,'' Lavin said. ``He's going to tell
them not to guard the 3-point shooters, and they'll probably guard
them. But that's within the realm of reasonable issues for a young
team at this point in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the ball movement dilemma. UCLA's offense functions best
when three things happen: the ball is passed inside to a big man,
back to the perimeter, then swung to the opposite side. The cycle
causes the defense to shift, which creates penetration lanes.
</P>
<P>
   While the coaches don't keep statistics on such matters, Lavin
says production improves dramatically when the ball moves inside
and outside.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense collapses like an accordion,'' he said. ``We just
have to make sure we don't settle for jump shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Freshman center Dan Gadzuric did not play because of
tendinitis in his knees. His availability for next week is
undetermined. ``We want to use this seven-day stretch to get him
some rest,'' Lavin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
