r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LA     12-24 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA STRUGGLES TO VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Schedule a game on Dec. 23 and this is what you
get: a sparse crowd, an indifferent host and less atmosphere than
Pluto. Even Tyra Banks' presence failed to inspire the spectators.
</P>
<P>
   Hold a series of grueling practices, including a game-day
workout, and this is what you get: sluggishness and sloppiness,
turnovers, bad shots and inept defense.
</P>
<P>
   For those who ventured out two nights before Christmas, UCLA and
American delivered one of the most forgettable games in memory, a
66-56 Bruins victory Wednesday before 7,442 at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Looking exhausted from consecutive three-hours practices, the
No. 12 Bruins sputtered and stuttered all night _ edging to a
double-digit lead in the first half, snoozing through most of the
second, then repelling the 24-point underdogs in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor performances across the board,'' UCLA coach Steve Lavin
said. ``If we were going to grade ourselves, I'd give us a failing
grade in every area.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Tyra left early.
</P>
<P>
   Only Baron Davis gave the somnolent crowd reason to cheer. In
one sequence, he stole the ball, outran the Eagles and converted a
windmill dunk; a few seconds later, he grabbed a rebound, dribbled
downcourt and passed the ball off the backboard to himself for a
layup.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also made the game-clinching play, snatching a loose ball
and speeding 75 feet for a three-point play that gave UCLA a 57-48
lead with 2:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the starters contributed little except for bad
defense (Jerome Moiso), bad shots (JaRon Rush) and turnovers (Earl
Watson). Playing without center Dan Gadzuric (tendinitis), the
Bruins were outrebounded 41-32, committed 17 turnovers and shot 57
percent from the foul line.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and don't forget: Arizona visits in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys had probably already left the gym looking ahead
to getting home on the red-eyes,'' guard Rico Hines said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Bruins are now one victory (Loyola Marymount)
from sweeping December _ a development that will count most in
March when the NCAA Selection Committee reviews their win total.
Unlike previous seasons, when UCLA could count on 12 to 15 Pac-10
victories, the combination of a young roster and a rugged
conference will make 10 wins a tough task.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, UCLA needs every nonconference win it can get,
and Wednesday night's was No. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins also need all the practice they can get, and Lavin
knows it. He conducted three-hour practices Monday and Tuesday that
left players gasping and dehydrated, then held a rare game-day
workout Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   It showed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys were a little tired,'' forward Sean Farnham said.
``We're ending school and we've had some long practices, but at the
same time those are not excuses. Our heads were on Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavin has two points of emphasis before conference play begins:
transition defense and ball movement. Assistant coach Steve Spencer
always identifies the opponent's best 3-point shooters, but somehow
his instructions get lost in translation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drives Spencer crazy,'' Lavin said. ``He's going to tell
them not to guard the 3-point shooters, and they'll probably guard
them. But that's within the realm of reasonable issues for a young
team at this point in the season.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the ball movement dilemma. UCLA's offense functions best
when three things happen: the ball is passed inside to a big man,
back to the perimeter, then swung to the opposite side.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle causes the defense to shift, which creates penetration
lanes. While the coaches don't keep statistics on such matters,
Lavin says production improves dramatically when the ball moves
inside and outside.
</P>
<P>
   To wit: The Bruins failed to do just that during an eight-minute
stretch in the second half when they scored just four points and
allowed American to rally. But they executed well in the final
minutes, scoring on five of six possessions to repel the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think (Lavin) would think they played like a top-10
team tonight,'' American coach Art Perry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
