<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE OUT TO SHOW WASHINGTON SIZE DOESN'T MATTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Does size matter?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly it does _ if you're a surfer. Lifeguards had to pluck
three boardheads from the coral reefs this week on Oahu's North
Shore partly because of mammoth waves along the famous Banzai
Pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to college football, the word on Waikiki Beach
is that size does not matter.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, what else would be expected to be heard from Air
Force Academy players?
</P>
<P>
   Little players, little school (4,100 cadets), smallish town,
lightweight conference. The Falcons have heard it all.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions their heart, courage and brains, of course. But
the snug cockpit of an F-16 fighter plane doesn't have room for the
massive body parts mandatory in football.
</P>
<P>
   So the natural expectation for Friday's inaugural Oahu Bowl is
that the Falcons will be tossed about by the Washington Huskies
much like reckless Pipeline surfers. The Falcons can hardly wait
for the Huskies to try.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if they're all 6-5 and 300 pounds,'' defensive
tackle Bryce Fisher said defiantly. ``We go up against bigger guys
all year, and we won 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I want to make sure everybody knows is we do not
have lesser athletes at the Air Force Academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher offered up his blunt assessment unsolicited, not
bothering to wait for obvious questions at a Falcons media briefing
at their hotel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded irked, and at 6-2 and 275 pounds, the Western
Athletic Conference's Mountain Division defensive player of the
year makes his case physically as well as orally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every press conference, we hear we should be just happy to be
playing Washington,'' he said, chin out. ``We should be in awe. But
we know we can play anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence (11-1 record, 16th-ranked in the AP poll, sixth
nationally in scoring defense, 14th in scoring offense, fourth in
turnover margin) is compelling. Air Force is easily the most
successful football program among the service academies, and this
season has produced the highest academy ranking in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it remains a WAC school that also played a soft
non-conference schedule (Wake Forest, Army, Navy) and, for the
league championship, beat a mediocre BYU team 20-13 that a mediocre
Washington team defeated 20-10 in September.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Falcons remain a viable diss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are guys that nobody expected much from,'' Fisher said.
``Air Force is always picked for the second division in the WAC,
and we are always having to prove ourselves to others.''
</P>
<P>
   No better individual example exists than Fisher, who finds some
extra passion in this game because he was dissed before he reached
Colorado Springs _ he was an all-league lineman at Seattle Prep who
was ignored by Husky recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   The Renton native attended the UW's summer camp and received the
standard ``Dear Student Athlete'' questionnaire form. But as a 6-1,
215-pounder, there was no visit, no interest, no shot for the big
time.
</P>
<P>
   For which he is now deeply grateful.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had gone to the UW, it would have been the biggest
mistake of my life,'' said Fisher, whose uncle, Levi, played
basketball for the UW in the 1970s, and brother, Roy, played hoops
at Cal. ``I never would have gotten a chance to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I could have done can compare to my experience at Air
Force. It's the only place where I've ever had fun in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Fun is not normally a word connected with the demands of the
academy, where there are no girlfriends to write papers, no booster
cash and definitely no pampering. But Fisher, a senior who is among
980 remaining in his class that began with 1,500 cadets, is one who
figured the rigors were worth the rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies' starting center, Brad Hutt, spent two years at Air
Force, then transferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was obvious it was not for me,'' he said. ``The strains
they put you under are tough. I mean, these guys every day put on
uniforms, then go into the service and bomb Iraq. I like things a
little more relaxed, where you wear what you want and can live in a
house instead of a barracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the view is a popular one among most Huskies, it is not
unanimous. Quarterback Brock Huard gave the academy a
consideration, but their option style of offense was no fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the ideas of respect, discipline and accountability at
the academy,'' he said. ``But I'm right where I'm supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be in the pocket, throwing deep.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, too, appears to be where he belongs, although it won't
be in a cockpit. The Air Force has many non-pilot jobs, and as a
business major, he is contemplating a service career in contracting
or acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   First, he has some football business to clear up. Fisher and his
teammates were humiliated in last year's Las Vegas Bowl by Oregon,
41-13, making for three straight postseason defeats as well as more
ammo for academy-football bashers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're practicing a lot harder this time, even during finals,''
he said. ``Oregon really put it to us, so we want to show last year
was a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad enough for the Huskies that the little guys don't like to be
told no. Now they've been embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   And there's just so much sand here to kick in the face of a
bully.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 0159EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
