</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-FLYERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GIVE IN TO FLYERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They are viewed as the creme de la creme of the
National Hockey League. The Philadelphia Flyers have size, speed,
scoring ability, depth, and _ finally, some would say _ the
goaltending necessary to win a Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night in front of a sellout crowd at the FleetCenter,
the Bruins threw a great many things at the Flyers, including
another stellar performance from goalie Byron Dafoe, but
Philadelphia nonetheless won the game, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended the Bruins' winning streak at three games. The
Flyers extended their unbeaten skein to six games (3-0-3).
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Bruins stood up to the Flyers, their coach felt
they gave up too much. ``You want to try to let their defense play
the game, not their forwards,'' said Pat Burns. ``We kept on giving
the puck to the forwards all night long. The game plan was to put
the puck in behind the defense and let them carry the play up. We
tried to make plays coming out of our own end a lot of times.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Burns didn't appreciate the efforts of his
players. ``We worked hard and tried hard _ I'm not saying it was an
all-around poor performance _ but you can't give Eric Lindros, John
LeClair, or Rod Brind'Amour the puck,'' he said. ``You can't do
that, because you're not going to win. Our guys had trouble
handling those big guys, especially around the net.''
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't for Dafoe (30 saves), said Burns, the loss could
have looked a whole lot worse. ``He saved us _ that's probably why
I'm not too excited about the score,'' said the coach. ``Byron
saved us quite a few times. The score could've been a lot more
lopsided than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers took more than five minutes to put their first shot
on Dafoe, but they scored on their second. On the play, LeClair
started behind the net, skated in front to Dafoe's right, and
roofed a shot from the lower edge of the left circle. It flew in
and out of the net so fast that referee Stephen Walkom waved it off
though the goal judge had flipped on the light. Video replay showed
that LeClair's shot had made it into the net, however, and the
Flyers were up, 1-0, at 6:49 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unbelievable shot,'' said Dafoe. ``That's why that
guy gets 50 goals every year.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dafoe was keeping his team in the game, second-year center
Joe Thornton was turning in his best performance of the season. He
was physical, he was involved, and he was all over the Philly end.
</P>
<P>
   At 14:50 of the first, Thornton had a good scoring chance when
he beat defenseman Luke Richardson down the right circle and tried
a forehander from the doorstep, but goalie John Vanbiesbrouck
quashed it.
</P>
<P>
   Thornton found the net early in the second. At the start of the
period, the Bruins came out strong and played the Flyers even, and
six seconds after a Boston power play expired, Thornton made it 1-1
at 16:10.
</P>
<P>
   On the play, Steve Heinze skated out of the right corner and
wristed a backhand shot from the right circle that Vanbiesbrouck
stopped. The puck bounced, and after defenseman Dan McGillis tried
to bat it away and missed, Thornton, parked in the crease, whacked
at it twice. His second attempt went under the goalie for his
fourth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins could have had another soon afterward as Jason
Allison set up Kyle McLaren. But McLaren, who had two goals Monday
night against Tampa, was surprised by the pass and couldn't get off
a shot.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied going into the third period, and the Flyers
tallied the winner at 6:51 when Eric Desjardins found the net with
a little help from Lindros and LeClair. It was LeClair's perfect
pass from the left-wing boards to Desjardins going down the slot
that enabled the defenseman to lure Dafoe out of the cage and slip
a backhander by him for the 2-1 edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't read that rush very well,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said it was a well-executed three-on-two. ``Desjardins
jumped in from the red line, and they made a great play over to
him,'' said Dafoe. ``I came across hoping he'd go wide, but he made
a nice move cutting in and I got my pad on his leg but I missed the
puck.''
</P>
<P>
   The homestand over at 3-1-0, the Bruins now head out onto the
road for four games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
