<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-FATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF OCTUPLETS ACCUSED OF ASSAULT ON DAY BABIES NAMED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE BREWER 
and LISA TEACHEY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The father of the first known set of surviving
octuplets is scheduled to be tried in February on a charge of
assaulting his 63-year-old mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   The charge became public on the same day that the Nigerian-born
couple named the eight babies, formerly known as babies A through
H.
</P>
<P>
   Iyke Paul Louis Jr., 41, also known as Iyke Louis Udobi, was
charged Sept. 22 with misdemeanor assault for attacking Janet
Chukwu, according to court documents and police reports. Louis, a
respiratory therapist, is accused of striking and biting his
mother-in-law and hitting her with a chair.
</P>
<P>
   The case is set for trial Feb. 8. The charge is a Class A
misdemeanor punishable by a $4,000 fine and up to a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Louis' attorney, Rick Castleberry, had only a brief statement:
``Iyke is completely innocent of what he's been charged with.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Wednesday, her parents, now U.S. citizens, announced
the names they have chosen for the infants.
</P>
<P>
   The names reflect the faith and heritage of the babies' parents,
and perhaps the infants' fragile state. Formerly known as baby E,
the tiniest girl, who weighed 10.3 ounces at birth, has been named
Chijindu Chidera, which means ``God has my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of pure oxygen the girl, nicknamed Odera, has been
receiving was reduced to 80 percent Wednesday, down from 100
percent Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the type of small, steady progress we hope for in the
NICU,'' said Dr. Leonard Weisman, chief of neonatology at Texas
Children's. ``However, with babies this premature and this small,
the pendulum can swing the other way and back again in a matter of
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Weisman said pure oxygen is given when the body can't get enough
oxygen on its own through ordinary air, possibly because of a
problem with blood flow to the lungs. Premature infants frequently
have heart and lung problems.
</P>
<P>
   The other newborns remained in critical but stable condition in
the hospital's neonatal intensive care unit. The mother, who had
surgery to correct abdominal bleeding Monday, continues to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the names of the seven others, one delivered naturally
Dec. 8, and the rest born Dec. 20. All have the last name Louis.
</P>
<P>
   _ The girl born Dec. 8, formerly known as Baby A, has been named
Chukwuebuka Nkemjika, which means ``God is great.'' Nickname:
``Ebuka.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The first child born Dec. 20, a girl previously known as Baby
B, has been named Chidinma Anulika, which means ``God is
beautiful.'' Nickname: ``Chidi.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby C, a girl, has been named Chinecherem Nwabugwu, which
means ``God thinks of me.'' Nickname: ``Echerem.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby D, a girl, has been named Chimaijem Otito, which means
``God knows my way.'' Nickname: ``Chima.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby F, a boy, has been named Chukwubuikem Mduabuchi, which
means ``God is my strength.'' Nickname: ``Ikem.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby G, a boy, has been named Chijioke Chinedum, which means
``God is my leader.'' Nickname: ``Jioke.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Baby H, a girl, has been named Chinagorum Chidiebere, which
means ``God is merciful.'' Nickname: ``Gorom.''
</P>
<P>
   The family has declined to talk to reporters, but Chido Nwangu,
a Houstonian who publishes USAfrica Online and is in contact with
the family, said Louis asked him to relay this comment about the
assault charge:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an allegation. It has not been proven and pushing that
allegation in the middle of the effort by Africans and Americans
... while they are welcoming his children, did not seem charitable
at all to him.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Prosecutor Danny Dexter declined to comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   According to Houston police arrest records, Louis was arrested
in the early hours of Sept. 22 after officers were called to his
southwest Houston home about 11:25 p.m. CST Sept. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Officers said Louis assaulted Chukwu, who lived with Louis and
his then-pregnant wife, Nkem Chukwu, 29.
</P>
<P>
   Louis told officers he and his wife were arguing when she began
to follow him around the home nagging and pinching him. Janet
Chukwu became involved in the argument, he said, and began hitting
and biting him. Louis told officers he defended himself by hitting
and biting her, then hitting her with a chair.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Chukwu told officers a different story.
</P>
<P>
   She said the three were sitting in the living room about 10:30
p.m. when Louis told her he was going to break his wife's hands and
kick her in the back. When Janet Chukwu told her pregnant daughter
to get away, Louis became angry. Janet Chukwu said he jumped over
the couch, cracked a chair over her head and began to beat and bite
her.
</P>
<P>
   Louis posted a $1,500 bail Sept. 29 and was released.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Hay of Harris County Children's Protective Services said,
``The potential is there for CPS to do some sort of investigation,
but nothing has been discussed. No report's been made. I looked,
and there's no history (of previous incidents).''
</P>
<P>
   She said a domestic violence arrest is enough to justify an
evaluation of a home but said in this case there is plenty of time
before the babies leave the hospital to assess the situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Leigh Hopper contributed to this story. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
