<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRUINS-THORNTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON FLEXES HIS MUSCLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Long before he scored his fourth goal of the season to
temporarily tie Wednesday night's game against the Flyers, center
Joe Thornton had already caught the eye of Bruins coach Pat Burns.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that alley back (of the bench), you can see who's going and
who's not in the first five or 10 shifts of the game,'' said Burns
after his team's 2-1 loss. ``And Joe was on his game tonight. He
wanted to play, and he got the ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not stupid. If you're going to play like that, you're
going to play a lot. And if you're not going to play like that,
you're not going to play a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just Thornton's conversion of a Steve Heinze rebound
late in the second period that made the night for the 19-year-old
selected first in the 1997 entry draft. There were a pair of bursts
around the Flyers defense early on, which caused traffic jams
around the net. And there were his impressive displays of puck
control down low, when Thornton used his size and strength to keep
the puck in the Bruins' possession.
</P>
<P>
   All that and a few body checks.
</P>
<P>
   One game doesn't a career make, of course, but this one didn't
hurt Thornton's self-confidence. ``It helped a lot _ the goal, the
hits,'' he said. ``I got in a couple of hits on my first shift, and
from then on I felt good. On my goal, the puck just popped out and
I slapped it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, who centered for Heinze and Anson Carter, said
Philadelphia's physical style of play and team size prompted him to
get involved. ``You know it's going to be a hard-hitting game
against them,'' he said. ``I've got two good wingers with me, we
had some good chemistry, and that's going to help me out in the
long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton's second professional season has had its ups and downs,
but over his last 12 games he's scored three times and added three
assists. Wednesday night's goal was his second in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   He has tried to work hard and be consistent. ``I'm working
harder in practice and in games and I'm getting more physical,'' he
said, ``and I'm putting more pressure on myself now than a year
ago.''
</P>
<P>
   After scoring 198 points in 125 games in juniors, and becoming
the youngest member of the Team Canada squad that won the 1997
World Junior Championships, Thornton was put under the microscope
upon his arrival in Boston as a rookie last season.
</P>
<P>
   Kyle McLaren, Boston's No. 1 pick (ninth overall) in 1995, was
also 18 when he broke in with the Bruins, but the pressure was
different. ``I wasn't the No. 1 pick in the draft, like Joe,'' said
McLaren. ``My hope then was to just make the Bruins. I didn't feel
the pressure then that he felt last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``His two years here, he's been on a roller coaster. He's played
well at times and he's sat at times. But this year I've seen him
more on a consistent basis go out and play well _ skate, hit, and
do the things that he has to do. When he's doing all that, he's a
good player. I believe he's going to be an all-star in this league.
He's just got to put his mind and heart into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned from the best in Ray Bourque, and there's no
reason that Joe can't learn from him and from other guys on the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Thornton, all 6 feet 4 inches and 220 pounds of him, Wednesday
night made an impression, literally, on Flyers defenseman Eric
Desjardins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a heavy guy,'' said Desjardins, who had the winning goal.
``He fell on me, and I could really feel it. Joe seems to be
skating better this year, and the best thing for the Bruins is that
he's still very young.''
</P>
<P>
   And still learning on the job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
