<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FLYERS-LINDROS-BO     12-24 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FLYERS-LINDROS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE EXTRA WORK FOR BIG FLYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was more ice time than Eric Lindros had seen this
season. With Mikael Renberg having to leave the game in the first
period after hurting his shoulder, Lindros was double-shifted for
much of the night and finished with 26 minutes 10 seconds of
playing time.
</P>
<P>
   It paid off, as the big forward had assists on each of the
Flyers' goals in their 2-1 victory over the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been our big guy all year, and just lately that line
hasn't been scoring _ they usually have two or three goals a
game,'' said Flyers coach Roger Neilson, referring to the top line
of Lindros, Renberg, and John LeClair. ``He played a hard game in
playing a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros most often faced Boston's checking line of Rob DiMaio,
Chris Taylor, and P.J. Axelsson, which paid plenty of attention to
the 6-foot-4-inch, 238-pounder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bruins even tried something different with their checking
line,'' Neilson said. ``Sometimes they even had (Jason) Allison out
there against Eric, and that was a different type of wrinkle. The
Bruins have a good checking line.''
</P>
<P>
   It was nothing new for Lindros to draw such attention. ``Eric is
in great shape,'' said Neilson. ``Whenever he plays, he plays such
a hard game. Sometimes it's hard to double-shift him, because he
goes so hard. He's a big man. We played him a lot, but we've had a
couple days' rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindros's two points give him a league-leading 42 (17 goals, 23
assists).
</P>
<P>
   He loved all the ice time. ``It's like anything else _ any time
you get a lot of ice time, you get right into it,'' he said. ``It's
fun to play. Everybody likes to play, and I'm no different. We had
some injuries, so I had to pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides his two assists, Lindros had two outstanding
opportunities to score. With seven minutes left in the first
period, he had a backhander bounce off the post. Then, in the
second period, he had an open net against Byron Dafoe, with Ray
Bourque chasing him from the back side. ``Raymond was able to sweep
me away on that,'' Lindros said.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros was also impressed by the play of Dafoe. ``He was
especially strong on kick saves,'' said the Flyer.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros felt it was important that the Flyers forged ahead on
the road. ``You just know that you're going to get your chances
here and there,'' he said. ``I beared down in trying to do the
right thing with the puck. Sooner or later, you have the feeling
that you're going to score and you also have to play good defensive
hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers had a meeting of the minds on that topic during the
intermission between the second and third periods. They employed a
strategy of having four forecheckers, one of them playing high, and
it worked. This was the first time the Flyers had maintained a
third period lead since Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gained some confidence in ourselves in that third period,''
Lindros said of the period in which the Bruins had eight shots, the
Flyers' seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 0205EST &QL; 
