<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI &LR;      12-24 1310
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERICKSON'S SO-SO SUCCESS DOESN'T FIT OWNER'S WIN-NOW DEMANDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Sports analysis piece)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Seahawks coach Dennis Erickson will be fired
next week, not because he failed, but because he did not meet the
expectations of his new bosses.
</P>
<P>
   Those now running the Seahawks' franchise for new owner Paul
Allen are results-oriented products of the computer revolution.
They want things done yesterday, not today and definitely not
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson is a stay-the-course type, a trait that has served him
and others in the coaching profession well. But that approach is at
odds with those who control his destiny, and is becoming outdated
in the win-now world of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   As Erickson approaches the 64th and, according to sources, final
game of his stint with the Seahawks, his record is 31-32. Others in
Erickson's coaching class of 1995 have done worse _ Philadelphia's
Ray Rhodes (29-33-1) and Carolina's Dom Capers (29-34), who also
are expected to be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Others have done better _ Denver's Mike Shanahan (46-17) and
Jacksonville's Tom Coughlan (34-29).
</P>
<P>
   Erickson has been average. And average is not enough. Not
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have been eliminated from playoff contention for a
fourth time under Erickson, and the 10th straight season overall.
It would take an upset of the defending Super Bowl champion and
13-2 Broncos in Denver on Sunday for the Seahawks to secure their
only winning record under Erickson, and the franchise's first since
1990.
</P>
<P>
   This was all supposed to change in 1995, when Erickson wasn't
just the obvious choice, he seemed the best choice to coach the
Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, who grew up in Everett and had coached at Washington
State, was coming home. And the excitement generated by his hiring
was just what was needed for a franchise that had deteriorated in
three seasons under Tom Flores and the ownership of the Behrings.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson had a reputation for innovative offense and an
energetic personality that had helped the University of Miami win
two national championships in his six-year tenure. It was expected
that these same traits would allow him to lead his hometown NFL
team back to prominence and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Why didn't Erickson turn things around with the
suddenness and panache that was expected? Why is it that the club's
new management group will not allow him to return for the final
year of his contract?
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, things have been stacked against Erickson since he
first arrived, wide-eyed and wildly optimistic. In other ways,
Erickson has been his own worst enemy, clinging too long to
policies and people that had helped him rise to the top of his
profession.
</P>
<P>
   Three things to remember:
</P>
<P>
   (insert bullet) Erickson could have been fired after last
season, if club president Bob Whitsitt's unsuccessful search for a
general manager had led to the hiring of someone who did not want
to work with Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   (insert bullet) Erickson's original contract was for four years,
with the club's option for a fifth. But the option was guaranteed
in 1996 during then-owner Ken Behring's failed attempt to move the
franchise to Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   (insert bullet) Through the past month of growing speculation
about Erickson's future, management has offered nothing more
definitive than saying his status will be evaluated after the
season. No vote of confidence. Nothing to quell the mounting
uncertainty. It has left Erickson with a false sense of just how
bad the situation has become.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example of this mismatch between Erickson's style and
that of his bosses is his emphasis on loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   It started with the assembling of his first staff. Too many of
Erickson's assistants were, like him, from the college ranks _
defensive coordinator Greg McMackin, then-assistant head coach
Gregg Smith, special teams coach Dave Arnold, quarterbacks coach
Rich Olson and defensive backs coach Willy Robinson. All had been
on Erickson's staff in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of first-time NFL coaches was too high and
prompted one club official to grouse the following season that some
of Erickson's assistants were in over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, special teams gaffes cost the Seahawks at least four
victories in their 8-8 season. Arnold eventually was fired after
the season, but the move should have been made before the season
had become a total loss.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson's loyalty cost him again during the process to find
replacements for three other coaches who left after the season _
line coach Howard Mudd, running backs coach Clarence Shelmon and
linebackers coach Mike Murphy, who had previous NFL experience and
were not part of Erickson's circle of college coaching cronies.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Whitsitt wanted to be impressed by the
replacement candidates Erickson could deliver, Erickson continued
to make a pitch to find Arnold a job somewhere in the organization.
</P>
<P>
   This year, when Erickson knew the offense had become too
predictable and the defense needed to play more aggressively, he
failed to intervene because of his loyalty to and faith in
offensive coordinator Bob Bratkowski and McMackin.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson the man undoubtedly earned some points with his crew.
But Erickson the coach didn't make any points with his bosses.
</P>
<P>
   The one time Erickson went against his principles, he cut Ronnie
Harris after fumbling a punt return in a loss to the Oakland
Raiders. Right idea. Wrong player, one who was popular with his
teammates, many of whom felt resentment.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that hurt Erickson this season was sticking with
Warren Moon as long as he did. It is difficult to fault Erickson
for going with the future Hall of Fame quarterback when his options
were the inexperienced Jon Kitna and John Freisz, whose confidence
has wavered since the club made its commitment to him two years and
two serious injuries ago. But Kitna has provided a needed spark the
past month, making it easy to second-guess Erickson for not making
the move sooner.
</P>
<P>
   The players also have sensed that something needed to be done.
They like Erickson. They play hard for him. But as several pointed
out after their rout of the Chargers two weeks ago, they played
hard for themselves, not as a show of solidarity for the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Too often, there has been a lack of discipline and the lack of
accountability that Pro Bowl linebacker Chad Brown talked about
earlier this season. His comments set off a series of closed-door
meetings, a week of hand wringing and a commitment to more-tightly
scrutinized practices.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching the same linemen who were guilty of false
starts in games jump offsides in practice and the same receivers
who couldn't catch the ball in games drop passes on the practice
field, Erickson would try to tell reporters that the workout had
been crisp and the problems corrected.
</P>
<P>
   As this season has dragged on, practices have become shorter and
players can often be seen laying down when their unit is not on the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson deserves better than this, and the fate that awaits him
next week.
</P>
<P>
   He points to improvement, like the team's 6-2 home record and
the fact that the Seahawks have not been blown out in a game this
season. He knows that if not for the blown call by the officials
against the Jets three weeks ago, his team would be playing this
week for a 10-win season and a chance to host a playoff game. He
remembers his first two seasons under the Behrings, trying to get
by on a shoe-string budget and operating out of a hotel room during
the attempted move of the franchise. He wonders why he wouldn't get
another chance.
</P>
<P>
   It is just too late. He has made too many moves that won't be
forgotten or forgiven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 0206EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
