 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 414 - December 23, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 414 -- Dec. 23, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. EGYPTIAN DIRECTOR'S IRONIC HYMN TO LIBERTY Egyptian director
Youssef Chahine put his creative juices into overdrive for his 33rd
feature, ``Destiny'' (El Maseer,) a drama with music that centres
on the persecution of a philosopher in 12th-century Andalusia.
``Destiny'' is the first film by the Arab world's most accomplished
director to receive American distribution. Chahine, a slight man
with a forceful yet gracious personality, spoke about the genesis
of this historical film that has contemporary relevance. Scrupulous
in his research, Chahine studied sects from all over the world,
including the sect in Waco. ``I wondered, how do educated people
give up their personality and talk according to the way of the
guru?'' By Betsy Sherman. BPI. 1,200 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 2.
NO HOLDS BARD : JOSEPH FIENNES TACKLES SHAKESPEARE They may soon be
calling Ralph Fiennes ``Joseph Fiennes' older brother.'' With his
period drama ``Elizabeth'' already a critical hit and the romantic
comedy ``Shakespeare in Love,'' the younger Fiennes is well on the
way to matching his brother's success. In this interview, Fiennes
talks about his new films, the challenge of playing a character as
mythic - but as little-known - as Shakespeare, how he approached
his torrid sex scenes with Gwyneth Paltrow and why his brother's
success actually makes him less enthusiastic to become a major
star. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 3.
PALTROW AND THE BARD Like the fiercely independent young woman she
portrays in ``Shakespeare in Love,'' Gwyneth Paltrow has always
chafed against the peculiar prison of public perception. As the
daughter of acclaimed actress Blythe Danner and producer-director
Bruce Paltrow, she was considered another example of how having the
right name can open all the right doors. By the time she began to
win more substantial movie roles, she was mainly known as the
girlfriend of actor Brad Pitt. When that relationship went up in
flames, more people were concerned with what went wrong than the
fact that Paltrow was developing into a smart young actress.
Interview by Renee Graham. From The Boston Globe. 1,700 words +
photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
SEAN PENN AT PEACE In film after film, Sean Penn has played bad
guys : from a convicted rapist on death row in ``Dead Man
Walking,'' to a drug dealer turned traitor in ``The Falcon and the
Snowman.'' Now he is adding to that gallery his World War II
soldier under fire in Guadalcanal in the upcoming film ``The Thin
Red Line.'' Penn says his succession of angst-filled roles has
never been a conscious career choice. ``I'm much more interested in
a tiny bit of enduring emotional truth,'' he claims. Interview by
Jay Carr. From The Boston Globe. 2,000 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
DIAGNOSIS : DICK VAN DYKE While no one was looking, the CBS program
``Diagnosis Murder'' has become a surprise hit. And no wonder - the
series, now in its sixth year, stars a true TV icon, the one and
only Dick Van Dyke. In this interview Van Dyke, 73, talks about his
contempt for much of present-day television, his memories of the
glory days of ``The Dick Van Dyke Show,'' and what he said when he
finally met his childhood idol, silent-movie star Stan Laurel of
Laurel &AMP; Hardy. By Andrew Ryan. From TV Guide Canada. 1,400 words +
photo.
_______________________________________________________________6.
READING TOM HANKS' ``MAIL'' Tom Hanks is having a series of very
good years. After his Gary Cooper-esque heroics in this summer's
smash hit, ``Saving Private Ryan,'' Hanks now takes on a role
originally played by Jimmy Stewart in ``You've Got Mail,'' one of
the holiday season's biggest films (the story of two very unlikely
lovers who come together by chance, thanks to the Internet and
e-mail.) The romantic comedy reteams Hanks, Meg Ryan and director
Nora Ephron, who together charmed the world with ``Sleepless in
Seattle.'' Interview by Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________7.
JOEL SINGS A SONG OF RETIREMENT No artist wants to be a parody of
himself (think of Elvis Presley in his twilight years.) That's not
what musician Billy Joel has in mind for his career, so he's taking
himself out of the running. He's now on one of the longest
unofficial farewell tours in memory, but he expects to end it
before his 50th birthday, on May 9 next year. ``It's getting to
that time and, yeah, I don't want to be a parody,'' he says. By
Steve Morse. From the Boston Globe. 1,300 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________
