<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The joy of Clinton-hating
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Each president inspires his own brand of
dislike, special to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan inspired intellectual condescension and easy
dismissivness. ``A maitre d' in a bad restaurant,'' as comedian
Mort Sahl summed him up to knowing applause.
</P>
<P>
   George Bush inspired ridicule for loopy speech habits. The left
and the right could unite in exasperation at his lack of program.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Clinton has inspired a special kind of hatred. The kind
of that we haven't seen since the days when we had both Richard
Nixon and Lyndon Johnson to kick around. We haven't seen this kind
of hate since the Summer of Love.
</P>
<P>
   One would think Clinton's documented failings would be rich and
varied enough to satisfy anybody. No way. Committed Clinton haters
need more. For them, he is guilty of murder, treason and
conspiracies so vast that books, Web sites and videotape series are
devoted to sketching only the broadest outlines of his evil.
</P>
<P>
   In this, Clinton joins the elite ranks of presidents who
provoked a special kind of personal, focused, and all-encompassing
hatred. The kind that becomes a hobby, a unified political theory,
a way of describing the world and all its workings.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon could inspire something close. The Kennedys as a family.
So could Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt-hating was legendary, heartfelt and almost devotional
in character. You can still find traces of it after a half century.
When conservative humorist P.J. O'Rourke evokes the image of FDR
being wheeled into the flames of hell, it can still ignite roars of
appreciative laughter and hearty applause from Republican
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   There's a trace of that in Clinton hating. Like
Roosevelt-hating, Clinton-hating is more than political opposition.
It is A Way, an anchor in confusing times.
</P>
<P>
   It puts a puffy, pink human face to an impersonal world, a world
swirling with evil and complex conspiracies, awash in cultural
decay, bad music and foreigners. Clinton brought us the coarsening
of American life. The Clinton illuminati made possible Jerry
Springer, Puff Daddy, New Age religion, the Y2K computer bug, euro
dollars, girls with tattoos, personal watercraft, the self-esteem
movement and those wretched Teletubbies.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Republican speeches during the House impeachment
vote, many representatives appeared to be laboring under the belief
they were voting to impeach the '60s, moral relativism, secular
humanism and a world too nasty to tell little kids about.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is now the kind of topic that makes people edge slowly
out of the room. Like abortion, gun control, fluoridation of
drinking water and notch babies' Social Security checks, he has
become one of those issues you avoid at the table because its mere
mention can reignite old arguments, strike names from
Christmas-card lists and ruin everyone's desert.
</P>
<P>
   I, too, sometimes wish the president had resigned. Not because
he isn't doing his job, but because I wonder what Clinton-haters
will do after he leaves. Will they be feel loss and emptiness
before moving on with their lives?
</P>
<P>
   Or is this field too rich ever to give up? Will the fixation on
Clinton linger like the weather-beaten ``Impeach Earl Warren''
signs that you could still find along the back roads of the South
years after the chief justice left the Supreme Court?
</P>
<P>
   I suspect so. And he'll be a youngish ex-president, so for
decades his hidden hand will be glimpsed in wrong-doing covered up
by a pliant media.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is the curse of interesting times. For it seems the
presidents who have inspired the richest, most personally
satisfying hatred were always those who presided over times of
great change. Whether it was Calvinists who believed Jefferson
would confiscate Bibles or isolationists who believed FDR
engineered the Pearl Harbor attack to advance international
communism, the president was the ringmaster in a dark circus of
unpleasant change. Hating a person, rather than the world's
uncertain forces, always feels better.
</P>
<P>
   But share it on the Internet and not family gatherings.
Nonbelievers just don't understand.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Lane is an associate editor for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. He may be reached at marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.)
ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-12-23-98 1825E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
