A5486 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATHAM-COLUMN25-COX     12-24 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATHAM-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When you hear the bell it is definitely ringing for you
 &HT;    By Phil Latham
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas _ It was about 6:15 Friday night when I noticed
that the lady on the cell phone was giving me a look.
</P>
<P>
   No, not as in looking me over (though I'm pretty sure you knew
that, didn't you?), but a look as if I was getting on her last
nerve.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been the bell.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing outside Wal-Mart in the chilly wind and just out
of the reach of the bitterly cold rain collecting money for the
Salvation Army. Someone had given me a bell to ring and, by golly,
I was going to ring it for all I was worth. No little
tinkle-tinkle. I was hoping to achieve a full clang. I was, if I do
say so myself, exceeding all expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not particularly good news for the lady on the cell
phone who was in a tough spot. Two steps one direction and she was
inside the store where her phone wasn't picking up the signal. Two
steps in another direction and she would have been standing in a
driving rain.
</P>
<P>
   So she was stuck in the middle with me and my bell.
</P>
<P>
   And I was having a high old time.
</P>
<P>
   Cold and wet though it may have been, I enjoyed every second.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all I enjoyed the faces of the people who gave money to
the cause, and there are few better causes than the Salvation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The givers ranged across the spectrum. There were a few dozen
children who took money given to them by their parents to drop on
in the bucket. Their faces showed a pride in what they were doing.
It is the same feeling everyone gets when they are helping their
community.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Hispanic man who gave me two nickels after
carefully counting
</P>
<P>
   them out of his pocket. Behind him marched his wife and five
children. I figure that 10 cents was probably more than he could
afford to give.
</P>
<P>
   There was Charlie the mechanic, or, if his name wasn't Charlie
he was wearing someone else's work shirt, who stopped in the rain
to pull out his wallet and give me a $1 bill. There was the man of
maybe 23 years with a gold hoop earring who walked back through the
rain after passing me to put in an entire pocket full of change
that totaled several dollars. There were a dozen working Joes who
didn't hesitate to drop money in the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Nor will I forget the man who, after putting a bill into the
bucket said, ``Who knows, maybe someday I'll have to make a
withdrawal.''
</P>
<P>
   Young and old, black and white, they put money into my bucket
and we shared a ``Merry Christmas'' as they did so.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, young and old, black and white, they passed up
putting money in the bucket, too.
</P>
<P>
   Early on I decided to assume that everyone who did not put money
into my
</P>
<P>
   bucket had dropped some coins in some other Salvation Army
receptacle. I never felt the slightest twinge of a bad feeling for
those who passed me by.
</P>
<P>
   I must admit, though, some people will go to remarkable lengths
to pretend they don't hear a clanging bell. If they weren't acting
then we definitely need some hearing aid retailers in this area.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps you think I should have slacked off for the woman
using the cell phone next to me. Sorry, but there wasn't even a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Like the people who pretended not to hear my bell Friday, most
of us don't want to think much about hunger and poverty in this
holiday season. We would all like to pretend that everyone lives
like us, opening presents around the tree while singing Christmas
carols and nibbling off the party tray.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is far different. Even if we are able to put a
plate on everyone's table for Christmas Day, on the day after, or
the week after, those plates will be just as empty as ever before.
</P>
<P>
   When the ringing bell gets on your nerves just a bit, think of
how would be if, instead of hearing that bell, you were constantly
feeling the pang of hunger.
</P>
<P>
   As long as people are hungry in this country, there ought to be
someone clanging a bell in our living rooms. We should never be
able to escape our responsibility to help our fellow man.
</P>
<P>
   If the bell bothers you there is a simple solution: Do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas would actually be a brighter time without the bells.
</P>
<P>
   Latham is editor and publisher of the Marshall (TX) News
Messenger. His
</P>
<P>
   email address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
