<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Tracking time in a young boy's sense of preparation
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ A multicolored string of lights over our porch had
a bad bulb. Unable to find one that matched the string, I fished
one from a disabled set and screwed it in _ all by myself, I might
add.
</P>
<P>
   As Christmas bulbs go, it's a throwback. Instead of having
tinted glass for the bright shine of its new neighbors, its glass
is painted blue, producing something more faint. In the daylight I
had to cup my hand to make sure it was working.
</P>
<P>
   That night, checking the total product, I looked for the faint
blue bulb and found myself transfixed by its almost-velvet
softness. I instantly knew why.
</P>
<P>
   This was the color of Christmas when I was a child.
</P>
<P>
   I had spent a lot of formative hours prone on the floor with
colors like this bathing my face, close enough to feel their heat.
</P>
<P>
   For my sons, other hues will tug when they've grown. And for
them, like me, they will be the colors of anticipation.
</P>
<P>
   Like a chart on the door, growth is marked by how a child
handles the Christmas wait.
</P>
<P>
   No one in our family will ever forget the Christmas eve when
youngest son Rob, then 7 or 8, was absolutely frantic to get home
from a restaurant meal.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of us were inclined to go drive around and see
Christmas lights. Rob found himself alternately shooting glances up
in the sky and hiding his eyes in high anxiety. He was absolutely
certain that it was time for Santa to arrive. If he didn't get home
and into bed, we'd get missed on the red man's rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go home,'' he pleaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax. The night is young,'' we assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. No. Go home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shhh. Shhh.''
</P>
<P>
   Deer in headlights?
</P>
<P>
   At that point, he saw something overhead. Undoubtedly it was a
reflection from passing traffic in the window. Rob, however, was
certain he'd seen a sleigh in friendly air space.
</P>
<P>
   He began stomping his feet. This was a five-alarm Santa alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no. I saw him. I saw him. Hurry. Hurry,'' he said
frantically.
</P>
<P>
   We accelerated home. It was about 7:30. He ran from the van to
the front door, and to the dresser drawers, and to bed _ where he
tossed and turned for the next two hours.
</P>
<P>
   Just past midnight after finally having succumbed, he stumbled
down the hall and tapped on his sleeping mom's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's morning. Wake up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not quite. Go back to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   2 a.m.: ``Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   4 a.m.: ``Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Back to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m. ``Morning.''
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Christmas morning photos show us with faces bleached
of circulation and hair headed back down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Rob is growing up. At 11, he has Santa figured out as a creature
of the muse, not as someone who can navigate through a vent. But
the anticipation does not abate.
</P>
<P>
   Regular under-the-tree inventories continue, as do strategy
sessions about Christmas morning. In particular, this:
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I'm going to do,'' he announced the other day,
``will be to put on my clothes and comb my hair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Huh?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures. I don't want to look so dumb in the pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll see if he has the discipline and focus tomorrow morning to
follow through on that.
</P>
<P>
   My bet is that the magnetism of anticipated joys will drag him
right past the bathroom and into the living room.
</P>
<P>
   May his anticipation, and yours, always feel like velvet.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco
Tribune-Herald. His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday.
E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
