<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5489 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JUNEJONES25-COX     12-24 1540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JUNEJONES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones follows heart to Hawaii
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From the day June Jones signed with the Atlanta
Falcons in 1977 as an undrafted free agent, he tried to convince
himself that he really belonged in the NFL, but he knew that he was
simply an accidental tourist in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, with his brain still begging him to remain on the
NFL merry-go-round for just one more ride, Jones finally heeded the
message of his telltale heart.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Jones, a former Atlanta Falcons coach, to fill
the vacancy at the University of Hawaii instead of staying on with
the San Diego Chargers is a mystery to some. It's more like poetic
justice, though, to those who long ago realized that Jones operates
his life from a values system that barely includes ego.
</P>
<P>
   ``With just about anyone else, you'd ask, `How does a guy turn
his back on the NFL? Isn't this what everyone aspires to?''' said
former Falcons center Roman Fortin, who plays for the Chargers.
``But with June, you understand. When he told the team what he was
doing, no one was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got his own set of priorities, you know?'' said Joe
Haering, a longtime friend and former Falcons assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Just five days before what figures to be his last NFL
appearance, Jones was just as concerned that it was only three days
until Christmas and that he had more gift-buying than game-planning
left to accomplish. And he fretted over the need to get his
youngest daughter, Nikki, enrolled in school on the islands and
about the urgency to purchase a new home in what has become a
buyer's market on Oahu.
</P>
<P>
   But even if he doesn't finish plotting to sabotage the Arizona
Cardinals' playoff plans in time to make it to the mall, Jones
already has delivered a Christmas gift of sorts, by reuniting his
family.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jones accepted the position of quarterbacks coach with the
Chargers 11 months ago, the clan has been far-flung. Wife Diane and
the three youngest of the couple's four children had remained
behind in Cumming. That separation was made even tougher by Diane's
continuing recovery from non-Hodgkins lymphoma, the
15-by-10-centimeter mass in her chest discovered only two weeks
after Jones was dismissed by the Falcons in January of 1997. And
Jones certainly missed son June IV, age 4, whose exuberance had
helped him survive those last dismal months with the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Diane continues to have a clean bill of
health, her checkup Friday indicating no sign of the cancer's
return. The better news is that the June Jones long-term master
plan for his career and his family has succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I took the job out here, we wanted to make sure Diane
stayed under the same doctors' care for a year,'' he said.
``Really, I came to help Kevin (Gilbride) and, of course, when he
got fired, things changed for me. But part of the decision to come
to San Diego was to get closer to Hawaii. At least figuratively
closer. I felt like if I was out of the game for two seasons, I
might not get the job there if it came open. And the people who
know me know how interested I was in going back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since he played one season in Hawaii during an itinerant
college career and served as an assistant there in 1983, Jones has
longed to return full-time. In his time at Suwanee, he would
confide to friends that he could land the job any time it became
available, and he never sold the condominium he bought there years
ago just in case the opportunity presented itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we've always discussed,'' Diane said. ``And the
timing is right.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Jones went into the interview with Hawaii athletics
director Hugh Yoshida, he was prepared to stay in San Diego. Jones,
who was so respected by Atlanta ownership that the franchise
actually gave him a raise after firing him, was ready to reimburse
the contingent from Hawaii for making the trip to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bobby Beathard, who desperately wanted Jones to
stay, had lobbied to keep him. ``He knew the job was his,''
Beathard said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chargers, Jones confirmed, were going to offer a four-year
extension and afford him the time needed to turn around a team that
will finish last in the AFC West for the second season in a row. As
it turned out, Jones' competitiveness and desire to lead the
Chargers back to a Super Bowl were overshadowed by the call of the
islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have loved to have him back, because he really pulled
the team together for us,'' Chargers president Dean Spanos said.
``But any time a guy follows his heart and he does what's best for
his family _ you have to admire that.''
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes into the Hawaii interview, Jones knew he would
take the job. Using the same notes he'd made several years ago when
he had the opportunity to go to Hawaii, Jones got all the answers
he needed. Three hours later, he had a oral agreement to coach the
Rainbows. Not surprisingly, money never became an issue; quality of
life for his family and him was the overriding priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be less stress (for Diane),'' said Jones, who
will earn $400,000 per year, far less than he would have made in
San Diego. ``It's a special place, and it always has been for me. I
don't look at this as turning my back on the NFL, although I doubt
I'll ever coach in the league again. It's just an opportunity I
always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get things going there, it will be the place I
retire from.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be no better place to live than Hawaii and no worse
place to coach football. Turning around a Hawaii program that
requires progress simply to reach shambles status will be a
daunting task, even for the optimistic Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Warriors were 0-12 in 1998, have lost 18 consecutive
games and were 5-31 the past three seasons under Fred vonAppen.
Hawaii travels at least 2,500 miles for every road game and its
league, the Western Athletic Conference, is disintegrating around
it. There are said to be budgetary problems within the athletics
department, and the academic standards at the university make it
difficult to keep the top players on the islands from matriculating
on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   None of that dissuaded Jones, 45, from signing a five-year
contract with an option for a sixth season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun is in the challenge,'' Jones said. ``I have a plan for
getting things done there. As a coach, you get jacked up about the
possibility of taking over something that's at rock bottom and
pushing it up the hill. It's not an impossible situation. I've seen
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The close friends who watched him deal with Diane's cancer, and
who witnessed the way Jones threw himself into that once-dire
situation, aren't about to bet against him beating the odds.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herock, the former Falcons vice president who now captains
the Oakland personnel department, recently recalled calling Jones
during Diane's battle and trying to take his mind off the real-life
fight by talking a little football. Instead, Jones began a lengthy
dissertation on the medical volumes he had checked out of the
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``June said, `Kenny, read everything you can about cancer,
because sooner or later it's going to affect someone close to
you,''' Herock remembered. ``He doesn't go halfway into anything.
He'll do fine over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has remained close with high school coaches on the
islands. His name still has clout. A few years ago, a friend of
Jones took his family to Hawaii and saved a couple hundred dollars
in cover charges merely by using his name. Because the expectations
for the program are so blunted, it won't take annual bowl games and
undefeated seasons to create a lot of excitement with the
knowledgeable fans.
</P>
<P>
   Seven wins and the exciting offense Jones certainly will have
could be enough to make it a lifetime job with the Rainbows. The
university's regents have promised to examine closely the
application requirements, and that could keep some talent at home.
Jones is ready to recruit hard in California and shouldn't have
problems wooing players who are eager to be in a big-time passing
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a quarterback or receiver, who else would you rather
play for?'' former NFL quarterback Jim Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly is among those not surprised at Jones' early exit from the
NFL. As with many jobs, Jones discovered that the reality of having
been to the summit didn't measure up to the anticipation of the
arrival. In Hawaii, he intends to coach during the day, enjoy his
family at night and never have to update his resume again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably, I'm different from some (coaches) in that I get
close to the players and the people I work with,'' Jones said.
``It's never been about money or prestige or power for me. The
thing I love best is the interaction. That's the essence of
coaching at all levels, and I'll be able to enjoy it just as much
in Hawaii as in the NFL. The (coaching) business has changed so
much; I don't know if it's free agency or what.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I'm going to be happy getting back to the basics of
what led me into coaching in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
