A5490 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRACE-CIVIL-ACTION25-     12-24 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRACE-CIVIL-ACTION25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Movie stirs up bitter memories for Boca firm
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ W.R. Grace &AMP; Co.'s old wounds are about to
open on movie screens throughout America.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 8, Disney's Touchstone Pictures will release ``A Civil
Action'' starring John Travolta as the real-life lawyer who
represented families who sued the chemical company 16 years ago for
allegedly contaminating their drinking water and, ergo, killing
their children. Boca Raton-based Grace settled out-of-court in
1986, paying the families $8 million, but never admitted guilt in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Civil Action'' is based on the 1995 award-winning book of
the same name by Jonathan Harr. It traces the four-year court
battle between Grace, corporate giant Beatrice Foods, and the
families from the working-class Boston suburb Woburn where Grace
ran a machine manufacturing plant.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Grace brandishes a modern weapon in this old
publicity battle: the Internet. At www.civil-action.com, Grace
outlines evidence gathered since 1986 which supports the company
claim that it was not the source of contamination in the families'
drinking water. On the site there are links to the reports by the
Environmental Protection Agency and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to retry the case on the site,'' said Grace
spokeswoman Jane McGuinness. ``We just wanted to give our side of
the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace is hoping its site will catch browsers visiting the more
than 10,000 movie pages on the Web. Touchstone Pictures' official
Web site for the movie has an address almost identical to the Grace
one: www.classaction.com (no hyphen).
</P>
<P>
   The Grace site opened just before Thanksgiving, but no accurate
data is available on how many visits it's had, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has been planning its response since Robert Redford, a
producer of ``A Civil Action,'' bought the book's movie rights in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Grace repeatedly contacted Disney to report inaccuracies in the
book or to point out developments since the settlement, but Disney
never responded, McGuinness said. Disney officials in New York and
Los Angeles did not return phone calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Grace executives don't know anything specific about the film _
no company officials have been invited to any advance screenings _
except to expect a supremely unflattering story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly not a picture of Grace today,'' McGuinness
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grace is a specialty chemicals company with 6,300 employees and
revenues last year of $1.5 billion (after a downsizing from $6
billion annually.) It produces for manufacturers things like silica
gel for toothpaste or chemicals that reduce emissions in gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   Grace had a machine manufacturing plant in Woburn from 1960 to
1988. In the course of the Woburn suit, the company admitted to
dumping some solvents including trychloroethylene (TCE) on the
grounds, but asserted that it could not have entered the families'
drinking water systems. An EPA report later upheld that theory.
</P>
<P>
   Also since the settlement in 1986, scientific thought on TCE and
cancer clusters has changed. There are many now who question
whether TCE is a carcinogen, and whether clusters of cancer cases
always must have an outside cause.
</P>
<P>
   This is Hollywood, though, and the movie _ minus these points _
premieres Dec. 25 in New York and Los Angeles. It arrives locally
two weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't think I'll run out and see it the first day,''
McGuinness said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
