<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5493 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-THEGAME25-COX     12-24 2265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THEGAME25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game for the ages
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Amid the colorful ribbons, gleaming trophies and
polished plaques that adorn the wall of Art Donovan's game room in
suburban Baltimore, a black-and-white photograph still stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Neatly framed, hung in a position of prominence and dusted
daily, the picture shows the grainy and somewhat out-of-focus
likeness of Colts fullback Alan Ameche blasting 1 yard over right
guard for the winning touchdown in the 1958 NFL championship game
on Dec. 28, 1958. That dramatic overtime contest, a 23-17 victory
for the Colts against the New York Giants, laid the foundation for
the league's unequaled popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, there remains a certain irony to the fact it
took a sudden-death game to breathe instant life into a
then-floundering NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Even those who played in what has been labeled as the greatest
game in league history acknowledge that it was not an aesthetic
success; they insist that other games in 1958 produced superior
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually had to beat the Browns two weeks in a row, and one
of the games was in a blizzard, just to get to the championship
(game),'' recalled New York running back Frank Gifford, whose two
fumbles in the title matchup led to 10 points for the Colts.
</P>
<P>
   Colts quarterback Johnny Unitas, who drove his team 73 yards in
the final 1:56 to set up the field goal that sent the game into
overtime, recalled a regular-season victory against San Francisco
in which Baltimore overcame a 28-7 halftime deficit. ``Sure, there
were better games,'' he said. ``It's probably a (misnomer) to label
that '58 game the greatest ever played. But it was probably the
most significant game ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, none of those other games were televised to a national
audience just cutting its teeth on professional football, and few
had all the exciting elements included in the Colts triumph against
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   With television in its formative years, the matchup of the
Colts' league-leading offense and Giants' top-rated defense drew
viewers away from their holiday turkey leftovers and onto their
sofas. Sports fans whose idea of a key matchup was watching Bob
Feller try to get his fastball past Ted Williams leaned forward in
their chairs as Ameche and L.G. Dupre attempted to run through New
York middle linebacker Sam Huff, whose scowling countenance graced
the cover of Time magazine a year later.
</P>
<P>
   Because the game was in New York, it created unprecedented media
coverage. Because the game was blacked out in New York, the crowd
was standing room only. The contest included 15 players and coaches
-- including Vince Lombardi, offensive coordinator for the Giants
-- later elected to the Hall of Fame. And no pro football game
before it had gone into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas and players from both teams, in fact, were clueless about
what would transpire after the game ended 17-17 in regulation.
Captains from the teams looked confused as they were led to
midfield for the overtime coin-toss, field judge Chuck Sweeney said
recently. Even the game officials, Sweeney said, were nervous.
</P>
<P>
   The game announcers, Chris Schenkel for the Giants and
Baltimore's Chuck Thompson, each had called a half and argued about
who would broadcast the sudden-death session. After some heated
words, they flipped a coin, and Thompson won.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew,'' Colts offensive tackle Jim Parker said, ``was
that there was a couple of thousand dollars difference between the
loser's share and what the winning team was to get, . . . and I
needed that money even if I had to work overtime to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the champion Colts received $4,718 per player.
The Giants players got $3,111.33. But the payoff was priceless for
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Giants owner Wellington Mara said the late commissioner Pete
Rozelle ``always told me the reason pro football took off was
because that game happened just at that time, in that season, on
television and in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Long-time Giants season-ticket holder Art Modell, who two years
later purchased the Cleveland Browns franchise, recalled the
atmosphere as ``magic'' and noted that as the game wore on he
realized he was an eyewitness to history. ``It wasn't the birth of
the league, but it certainly was its coming-out party,'' Modell
said last week. Modell helped negotiate the NFL's first national
network TV contract three years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the moment sports became something the networks had to
carry,'' said Barry Frank, the noted television negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dec. 28, 1958 is recognized as the day professional
football shook the country's sports landscape with a seismic tremor
rarely caused by one game. ``Before that game,'' Donovan recalled,
``I could be standing outside Mr. Goldberg's candy store in the
Bronx, and he'd see me and say, 'Donovan, you big bum, are you out
of work again?' He had no idea that I played football. The league,
it was in its infancy then. The '58 game took the NFL out of
diapers, really. Up until then, we operated in a vacuum of sorts. A
couple years after that game, we were in every living room in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   An entire generation of Baby Boomers still recalls the ghostly
black-and-white images of the Colts and Giants wallowing around in
the mud at Yankee Stadium as its first real exposure to football.
Young men whose only perspective on sport came during the daily
game of ``catch'' with their fathers in the front yard got hooked
on football that dreary December afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation that later huddled around the TV set as the
world teetered on the brink of a nuclear holocaust, watched soberly
as a funeral cortege escorted the body of its slain president and
held its collective breath every time a rocket lifted off the pad
at Cape Canaveral, the '58 championship game was both respite and
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game,'' author David Halberstam said this week, ``was a
watershed event for professional football, for sports in general,
for this country. It is not hyperbole to say our lives changed
forever that afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   One year after that game, most boys woke up to find shoulder
pads or a football under the Christmas tree. Kids all over America
climbed into barbers' chairs and ordered flat-top haircuts so
they'd look like Unitas and Huff. Wives who grudgingly watched the
game bought Westinghouse washers because they had seen the
company's handsome pitchman, Gifford, playing in the contest. The
mavens of Madison Avenue, who shaped the consumer conscience of the
country, signed dozens of NFL players to endorsement deals in the
weeks after the '58 game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been better games, but that one was the marriage of
professional football and TV,'' Colts defensive back Johnny Sample
said. ``Fans who for years sat around their radios started calling
their neighbors and telling them to come over and watch this NFL
game on television. It was special, and the overtime just added to
it. For weeks after, it was all anyone talked about. People in the
television industry throw around the term 'water-cooler show' now.
Hey, that game was the original 'water-cooler show.' Everyone got
hooked on the NFL that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Halberstam and sociologist D.K. Wittinghouse emphasized that
baseball was in a state of flux at the time -- the Dodgers and
Giants both had bolted New York for new homes on the West Coast --
and that the NBA registered only a blip on the sports radar screen.
Hockey, with only six franchises, was viewed as primarily a
Canadian pastime.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football existed on the fringe, classier than in its
barnstorming days, but it still was regarded by many as
second-fiddle to the college game.
</P>
<P>
   All of that changed, however, on Dec. 28, 1958.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all these years,'' Colts halfback Lenny Moore said,
``people still tell me that was the first (pro) game they had ever
watched. And that's probably the truth.'' Gifford, who had paid
dearly to fly his father in from the Alaskan oil fields for the
title game, said, ``We weren't out trying to make history, just win
a championship. The history part of it just happened.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than three minutes left in regulation, the underdog
Giants were clinging to a 17-14 lead and faced a third-and-four at
their 40-yard line. Coach Jim Lee Howell sent in a running play,
``47-Power,'' for Gifford. The Giants star burst upfield but was
tackled by defensive end Gino Marchetti and linebacker Don
Shinnick. As the play ended, Colts tackle Gene ``Big Daddy''
Lipscomb fell on Marchetti, breaking his right leg. The shriek from
Marchetti, some Giants contend to this day, distracted referee
Charlie Berry so much that he mismarked the placement of the ball,
and Gifford came up inches short of the first down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lipscomb put five of his own players out of (commission) that
day by piling on at the end of plays,'' Donovan said. ``So all this
hollering is going on, and Gifford's laying on the ground saying,
'I made the first down! I made the sticks!' Hell, he didn't even
get back to the line of scrimmage is the way I remember it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing punt by Don Chandler gave the Colts the ball at
their own 14-yard line and provided Unitas a stage he would use to
stake his claim to stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Out of timeouts and behind by three points, the quarterback took
one glance downfield before stepping into the huddle. ``The goal
posts were so far away, they looked like they were back in
Baltimore,'' Unitas said last week.
</P>
<P>
   But with characteristic precision, the analytical Unitas carved
up the Giants defense. Taking advantage of deep drops by Huff and
fellow linebacker Harland Svare, he simply kept throwing underneath
to Raymond Berry, perhaps the most technically proficient wide
receiver in league history. In the eight-play drive, the two
connected for gains of 15, 22 and 25 yards. With seven seconds left
and the ball at the New York 13-yard line, Steve Myhra forced the
overtime with a 20-yard field goal, as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   As the Colts defense huddled on the sideline, Donovan exhorted
his colleagues simply to get the ball back for Unitas, and they
did. The Giants won the overtime toss, failed to move to a first
down and Chandler punted to the Baltimore 20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we ran onto the field, John just had this kind of detached
look like, 'OK, let's go get this thing over with,' `` Berry said.
``In those situations, he was the best, and everyone on both
sidelines knew it.'' Huff recalled: ``There was a sense of
impending doom because you didn't want Unitas with the ball in that
situation. In our hearts, it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   On the field, it took Unitas 10 plays. Twice more he threw to
Berry, the first time his 20-yard bullet on third-and-15 overcoming
an 8-yard sack by Dick Modzelewski.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas ``knew where to attack a defense,'' Giants defensive back
Carl Karilivacz said. ``He found a weakness, and he went after it,
exploited it for everything he could get.'' ``Look at the
play-by-play of that game, and it's Unitas-to-Berry time after
time,'' Huff said. ``I mean, after 40 years, that still rings in my
ears: 'Unitas complete to Berry.' We simply couldn't stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   As if the drive wasn't dramatic enough, it was interrupted, as
televisions all over the country went black when fans in the lower
bleachers accidentally loosened a cable. An employee from NBC
pleaded with game officials to delay the contest until power could
be restored. In his headset, Thompson heard a producer ordering him
to do radio-style play-by-play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew pro football was growing up right in front of everyone
on that afternoon,'' said Sweeney, the field judge. ``I gave the
guy another minute beyond the usual 90 seconds and hoped for the
best.'' The cable was repaired and viewers missed just one snap.
</P>
<P>
   Dupre gained 17 yards on four carries in the final drive and
caught a pass for 8 more. Ameche ran twice for 24 yards, and tight
end Jim Mutscheller caught a 6-yard pass that moved the ball to the
New York 1-yard line. With a third down, neither Unitas nor Colts
coach Weeb Ewbank ever considered kicking a field goal for the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ameche bulled into the end zone, into the record books
and onto Art Donovan's game-room wall.
</P>
<P>
   Buzz Nutter, the Baltimore center, wrestled the ball away from a
security guard and delivered it to Marchetti, who had listened to
the final minutes on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   In the Baltimore locker room, the players celebrated by drinking
orange soda. ``Nowdays guys use champagne for shampoo,'' Donovan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unitas, who finished with 361 yards passing, hugged Berry and
then headed for a warm shower. Ameche quickly signed a $500 deal to
appear on ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' that evening and raced to catch
a cab. Across the hall, a distraught Gifford wept openly over his
two fumbles and had to be consoled by Lombardi.
</P>
<P>
   Berry, the near-sighted receiver with one leg shorter than the
other, finished dressing, pulled on an overcoat and headed out for
the team bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of Yankee Stadium, just standing alone on the sidewalk
as dusk settled, was commissioner Bert Bell,'' said Berry, who had
12 catches for 178 yards. ``Here was a guy who had midwifed the NFL
and shepherded it through all its tough times. I walked up to shake
his hand, and he had tears in his eyes. He knew what that game
meant. The rest of us, we had no perspective on the big picture.
But the commissioner, he knew his baby grew up that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
