<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5494 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PBP-JJREEVES25-COX     12-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PBP-J </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 J REEVES25-COX &HT;    Coaches respond to crises, teams take it in stride
 &HT;    By Mark Woods
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ They stuck to the schedule like it was an ordinary
Wednesday. Same morning meeting. Same lunch break. Same afternoon
practice.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Miami Dolphins and Atlanta Falcons, this Wednesday
was far from ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't include head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the day that two of the NFL's highest
profile coaches _ Miami's Jimmy Johnson and Atlanta's Dan Reeves _
gathered their players and began preparing them for the
regular-season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, four days before that game, both were dealing with
problems that eclipsed football.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was in an Atlanta hospital, recovering from the quadruple
bypass surgery he had 10 days earlier. Johnson was in Groves,
Texas, attending his mother's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   Allene Johnson, 77, died Sunday after a long battle with kidney
disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our sympathies are with coach Johnson,'' Dolphins tight end
Troy Drayton said. ``But at the same time, I'm sure Coach Johnson
is saying, `Hey, the show must go on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson worked Monday, guiding the Dolphins to a 31-21 upset of
Denver. Wednesday, though, he turned the team over to his
assistants, boarded a team plane and flew home to Texas. He was
accompanied by Dolphins president Eddie Jones and media relations
director Harvey Greene. Meanwhile, back in South Florida, the
Dolphins went about the business of preparing for a team that
hasn't lost since October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different not having him around,'' Drayton said. ``But
it's Week 17. We know the routine by now.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary change, the players said, was that Johnson wasn't
there to open the morning meeting. Instead, the team jumped right
to the next step, when the assistant coaches take over and begin
breaking down the gameplan for each unit.
</P>
<P>
   No one assistant took control. Instead, it was a group effort
from Johnson's 17-man staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared for something like this,'' receivers coach
Robert Ford said. ``Jimmy is the kind of coach that gives us a job
and lets us do it.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dolphins know their head coach will be back on the
field today, the Falcons are uncertain when theirs will return.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful he'll be back for the first playoff game,'' said
defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, who is acting as interim coach.
``At this point, that is in jeopardy, quite honestly.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who guided the Falcons to their first AFC West title
since 1980, began experiencing chest pain on the flight home from a
27-17 victory at New Orleans on Jan. 13. The next day he had
quadruple bypass surgery.
</P>
<P>
   He left Piedmont Hospital last Friday, four days after the
surgery and held a teary press conference where he talked of trying
to be tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to distract our team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, he suffered a relapse and had to return to the
hospital. That day the Falcons won 24-17 at Detroit to improve 13-2
_ guaranteeing the best regular season in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This right here is the culmination of Dan's hard work,''
running back Jamal Anderson said. ``We won this game for Dan and
his family. He came in here and built a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the Falcons have tried to change as little as
possible in Reeves' absence. For instance, last weekend at Detroit,
Brooks could have moved onto the field to run the team. Instead, he
opted to stay in the press box. When he had to make decisions _
such as whether to accept or decline a penalty _ relayed it to
general manager Harold Richardson on the field.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive play-calling remained the same. Quarterbacks coach
Jack Burns called a play and relayed it to the sideline. Backup
quarterback Steve DeBerg relayed them to starting quarterback Chris
Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference was that it wasn't filtered through Dan,''
Brooks said. ``Dan ultimately had been making the decision on
whether he would send it in or change it. I have a switch in the
box and have the authority and the ability to overrule any of the
calls, which I did not in Detroit.''
</P>
<P>
   The players insist that everything is running smoothly without
Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that's changed is we don't have as many
jokes,'' Anderson said with a laugh. ``We used to talk bad about
Dan's knees. Now that he's not here, we can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes? Dan Reeves?
</P>
<P>
   That's right. Reeves might be thought of as one of the league's
more staid coaches. But this season the Falcons have shown that he
has another side. After all, this is the team that, three days
after the fiasco involving a coin flip, had linebacker Jessie
Tuggle walk to midfield with a sign that read, ``HEADS.'' It also
is the team that has given us the latest touchdown celebration
dance, The Dirty Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has made progress since being re-admitted. Wednesday, the
doctors allowed him to be a part of the morning team meeting _ via
speakerphone.
</P>
<P>
   His voice was a welcome sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more than anything we miss Dan, the personality and
person,'' Anderson said, before adding a get-well wish. ``The
coaching part of it (the assistant coaches) are handling. Just take
care of yourself right now, Coach Reeves. When we need you is when
the playoff run comes.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he comes back, will there be a ceasefire on the jokes
about Reeves' knees?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course not,'' Anderson said. ``We'll probably give him a
48-hour mercy period, then the jokes fly again.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
