</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories for release Friday, December 25, Saturday,
December 26, and Sunday, December 27, 1998, are moving today to
clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports, business and
commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. All stories have moved
except those with an ETA.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Some of these stories are available in
paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   XMAS-BDAYS _ Eula Mae Johnson has always made one thing clear to
her family: Her birthday is on Dec. 25th. Not the 24th or the 26th.
So instead of being overshadowed by Christmas celebrations,
Johnson's family is planning a big celebration in honor of her
100th birthday. She is not alone. Contrary to popular belief, many
metro Atlantans say they don't feel shortchanged by having
Christmas birthdays -- their families still make them feel special.
Story talks to many metro Atlantans about how they juggle the
Christmas/birthday dilemma. (There are at least three children's
books about Christmas birthdays.) (AHill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS. FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   XMASBDAY-LIST _ A short list of famous people born on Christmas,
including Sir Isaac Newton, Robert Ripley and Humphrey Bogart.
(AHill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHORDER _ As the family gathers around the Christmas tree or
lights the menorah, remember this: you never outgrow your birth
order. ``If I get together with my brother and sister and they're
in the car, they still want to sit in the back seat and put me in
the middle,'' says psychologist Kevin Leman, 55, author of the
newly updated bestseller ``The Birth Order Book.'' ``And that same
older brother or sister who told you how to run your life as a kid
is in the kitchen telling you how to make the stuffing.'' Family
get-togethers bring out the best, the worst and the child in
everyone, Leman says. (White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 29.
FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ A friend for whom I did a slight favor said
lightly, `` When you die you're going to heaven.'' It gave me a bad
couple of minutes. Dying is all right if you must, but heaven? I'm
not sure about that, either getting there or liking it. (Sibley,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHY-FOODS _ If you're resolving to eat more fruits and
vegetables in the new year, it's not as hard as you might think.
Simple ways to incorporate them. (Walker, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 23. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   KWANZAA _ A guide to Kwanzaa, which begins Saturday. (Medearis,
Austin American-Statesman). FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVES
FRIDAY FOR SATURDAY.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE-CHANGES _ It's that time of year once again, when
people vow to change their lives in some fashion. Such change is at
the heart of religious belief, the notion that each of us has the
capacity, with the help of God, to change. We talk with people who
not only made such a vow last year, but managed to carry through on
their hopes to change their lives for the better. In so doing, many
have made a spirtual connection that is now a profound part of who
and what they are today. (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
WITH PHOTOS. FOR SATURDAY
</P>
<P>
   SIBLEY-COLUMN _ The days between Christmas and New Year's are
traditionally time spent with seed catalogs and dreams of spring
planting. I didn't realize that H.G. Hastings, the famed and most
respected seedsman, fostered that idea until I read the new book by
his grandson, Don Hastings. (Sibley, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   GOODLUCK-ROCKS _ Just a stone's throw from U.S. 76, the busy
road that runs through Blue Ridge, to Blairsville, Clayton, and
beyond, there is a valley of crosses _ rock crosses. Officially,
they are staurolite, the state mineral. For the thousands who, over
the years, have come to dig on Ann Williams' old family farm, the
distinctive stones are good-luck charms. Harry Abernathy, who turns
some rocks into bolos but mainly just collects them, has amassed
boxes and boxes of little rocks (including jade and rubies in the
rough) from around the country. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 30. WITH COLOR PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ROCKS-SIDE _ A short appreciation of rocks. (May, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DANCING _ ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' starring Meryl Streep
is based on the Broadway play (also recently performed at Theatre
Gael, here in Atlanta). The story is of sisters who live alone and
have to deal with the return of their somewhat ``damaged'' brother
who is a missionary returning from Africa. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-STEPMOM _ Review of ``Stepmom,'' starring Julia Roberts,
Susan Sarandon and Ed Harris. Sarandon is dying of cancer; Roberts
is the 2nd wife who must care for her kids. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   STEPMOM _ Review of ``Stepmom.'' Susan Sarandon is the ex-wife;
Julia Roberts is the soon-to-be-stepmom. They bare their claws in
this comedy with sniffles. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-DELTA _ Review of ``Down in the Delta.'' Maya Angelou's
directorial debut stars Al Freeman Jr., Mary Alice, Alfre Woodard
and Esther Rolle (in her last screen role). It's about the survival
of a black family in a Chicago ghetto. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-SHAKESPEAR _ Review of ``Shakespeare in Love.''
Shakespeare falls in love and finds the material with which to live
and write ``Romeo &AMP; Juliet.'' Simon Callow, Rupert Everett star.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE _ Review of ``Shakespeare in Love.'' Critics are
red-hot _ and our Alison Macor is no exception _ for this romantic
comedy about how an elegant but unattainable woman inspired young
Will Shakespeare to create ``Romeo and Juliet.'' Joseph Fiennes and
Gwyneth Paltrow are Bard and muse. (Macor, Austin
American-Statesman). MOVED WEDNESDAY FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-VOICE _ Review of ``Little Voice'' starring Jane
Horrocks. Based on Horrocks' one-woman show in which impersonates
the voices of great stars like Judy Garland and Ethel Merman.
(Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-ADAMS _ Review of ``Patch Adams,'' which stars Robin
Williams in a fact-based story about a medical student in the 70's
who treated patients, illegally, at his home, using humor.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-JOEYOUNG _ Review of the gorilla movie ``Mighty Joe
Young.'' After the gorilla Mighty Joe Young is brought to America
for safety reasons, he escapes and rampages through Hollywood. Bill
Paxton stars. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   FACULTY _ Review of ``The Faculty.'' Kevin Williamson
(''Scream'') wrote this sci-fi thriller shot in Austin by Robert
Rodriguez. Cute high school students battle icky alien teachers.
Eclectic cast includes Elijah Wood, Salma Hayek, Robert Patrick,
Piper Laurie, Bebe Neuwirth ... and, in a cameo, Harry Knowles.
(Garcia, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED WEDNESDAY. FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY FOR FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TV-XMASDAY _ A quick guide to the best on TV on Christmas day.
(BLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   GRACE-CIVIL-ACTION _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ W.R. Grace &AMP; Co.'s old
wounds are about to open on movie screens throughout America. On
Jan. 8, Disney's Touchstone Pictures will release ``A Civil
Action'' starring John Travolta as the real-life lawyer who
represented families who sued the chemical company 16 years ago for
allegedly contaminating their drinking water and, ergo, killing
their children. Boca Raton-based Grace settled out-of-court in
1986, paying the families $8 million, but never admitted guilt in
the case. In response, Grace brandishes a modern weapon in this old
publicity battle: the Internet. (Spencer-Wendel, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED FOR FRIDAY
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-HOUSTON _ As part of a series on Atlanta's Endangered Arts
series, Atlanta Jouranl-Constitution arts critic Catherin Fox
visits Houston to contrast the arts scene there with the one in
Atlanta. It may be just another big Sunbelt city, but Houston's
performing arts and museums get the kind of financial support any
town would envy. (Fox, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 53. WITH
COLOR PHOTOS FOR SUNDAY
</P>
