<HEADER>
A5542 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BONG-BULL-NYT &LR;      12-24 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONG-BULL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 No. 499 for Dec. 24  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Dec. 23-24, 1998. Say Newt and the boys, that's a terrible
breast-pounding you took last week, but if it eases the pain any,
the Democrats appreciate the boost in ratings and wish you a Merry
Christmas, says the Burned-Out Newspapercreatures Guild, and this
is BONG Bull No. 499!
</P>
<P>
   OLIVE. Mentioned in this week's column by the Chief Copyboy for
the New York Times News Service, the most noble wire service of
them all, Christmas humor from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what's the name of the 10th reindeer? Why, Olive,
of course. She's prominently mentioned in that popular song playing
on all the stations: ``Olive, the other reindeer, used to laugh and
call him names...''
</P>
<P>
   Well at least they don't play the Little Drummer Boy so much any
more.
</P>
<P>
   LINKS TO LINK-RULES. Robin Netherton on those jewellike gatefold
photo proportion calculators:
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I wish I had one too! We were still using them at the Iowa
City Press-Citizen when I left there in 1984. I should have stolen
one while I had the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know they were called link-rules. We called them
`fences.' If you wind up with a source, please let me know. I would
actually have a use for one in my own graphic work. I still use a
proportion wheel. Have you ever seen the cropping frames that
consist of two L shapes connected by a diagonal metal rod? They're
heavy transparent plastic (mine were orange). The rod is fixed to a
rotating base on one L, and slides through a rotating base on the
other L. You fit your frame to the photo hole, twist the screws on
the bases to stop the rotation, and then slide the frames to as
small or large a size as you wish; the rod preserves the
relationship of the frames so that the rectangles you generate are
all proportional to the original. Much better than the cheap
cardboard free-standing L's we used in journalism school. (Mizzou,
of course.)''
</P>
<P>
   JACOBY WEIGHS IN. Alfred JaCoby, conscience of the Copley chain
in San Diego, Calif., scoffs, ``You used a proportion rule?
Sissy-boy stuff. Out in the hustings, where the reporter-photog
also ran the Fairchild, wrote captions and got his own IDs, we used
a line gauge, held oh-so-high above the print to get the colm width
and then rotated the print slooooowly clockwise to get the depth.
(You had to put your thumb nail right at 12 picas to get the column
measure. Which tells you how long ago that was.)
</P>
<P>
   ``This was, of course, soon after graduation from the Missouri
J-school, world's oldest.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Al, we're relaxing our limit of one Missouri mention per
edition just this once. It frees up next week's BONG Bull, the
500th edition, a collector's item.
</P>
<P>
   Al couldn't resist adding, ``As for sex in the frate elevator
(God bless your memory, Col. McCormick!), how about in the
temporary newsprint storage room, during the press run, with
pressmen getting supplies at the other end of the room, very
quickly?
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the stairway to the composing room, at the Long Beach,
(Calif.) Independent, of blessed memory, the stairway-fire escape
from the composing room was reserved for the printers' nightly
beer-drinking sessions. At the Independent, too, the Linotype
operators were responsible for style (caps, etc) on wire copy. The
late man on the desk took the INS copy, marked grafs, cut the story
to length (nothing more than 6-7 inches due to wartime paper
rationing) and the copyboy, who also kept the morgue-clip file,
carried it to the composing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``(For the benefit of the children among us, wire copy on those
70-word-a-minute teletypes came all-caps and desk men marked
caps.)''
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING TIP. Rick Schwein suggests: ``If you know anybody on
the photo staff at the Lexington (Ky.) Herald-Leader you might be
able to run down a Link-Rule. They still used them when I left
there eight years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   We'll leave it to the Lexington folks to offer a remnant sale,
but the suggestion is that few if any editors use any form of
proportion calculator in the age of computing. Slap that baby into
a scanner, diddle some keys and mouse her into the hole. Photo
sizing is on its way to extinction, along with head counting.
</P>
<P>
   SPEAKING OF HEAD COUNTING. Do they do it at Chinese and Japanese
copy desks? Do they have rules against ending a line with a
preposition? Do they use acronyms and initials? Would they call
Eisenhower ``Ike?''
</P>
<P>
   FIRST IN WAR, FIRST IN PEACE, AND THIRD TO THE PHOTO DESK. Stan
Wellborn of the Annie E. Casey Foundation alleges:
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the sixties, a young and earnest
photographer-in-training at the Topeka (Kan.) Capital-Journal was
known around the world as the world's fastest human. That's because
his name was Jim Ryun, and he held the world record in the mile.
Ryun was a mild and pleasant guy who worked summers with the
vaunted, Pulitzer-winning photo staff at the Capital-Journal.
Trouble was, Ryun was not recognized by reporters as anything close
to fast when it came to getting to photo shoots on time. Reporters
finally resorted to arranging backups for most Ryun assignments,
noting that `unless he is on an oval track, he can't find his way
to the finish line.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Ryun is following a much less exalted and noble career
path: He's a member of Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   COMIX SECTION. The Further Adventures of Herman ``Speed''
Graphic, Ace Photographer for the Chagrin Falls Commercial
Scimitar, and his Faithful Companion, Typo the Wonder Pig.
</P>
<P>
   PANEL ONE: At the office Christmas party, Speed and Typo ponder
their take in the gift exchange as Speed observes, ``A
Perrier-monogrammed insulated water bottle holder, Typo! Just what
I always wanted!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo suggests, ``It also works for other beverages, Boss! Just
don't use it at the Bait Shop while we're keeping a low profile
until your bar tab is arbitrated!''
</P>
<P>
   PANEL TWO: Speed uses his present to brush lint off his
trenchcoat, a deathbed gift from an ancient mystic wire service
executive editor on a fog-shrouded eastern island, and enquires,
``So what was your gift, Typo?''
</P>
<P>
   Typo reports, ``A combination paperweight and wastebasket fire
starter molded from pencil-sharpener dust into a bust of Absentee
Publisher Gimlet Peen, Boss! Same as last year!''
</P>
<P>
   PANEL THREE: Speed notes, ``Look at what Features Editor Hyperba
Lee got, Typo!''
</P>
<P>
   Typo marvels, ``An individual-sized 12-pound fruitcake! What
luck, Boss! She can save that for the gift giving next year!''
</P>
<P>
   PANEL FOUR: A hubbub arises from the Sports end of the buffet
table and Typo warns, ``Duck into the Photo Lab, Boss! The guys who
run the football pool are expressing opinions about their gifts!''
</P>
<P>
   PANEL FIVE: Safely barricaded behind the print washer, Speed
counsels his pal, ``Those Sports guys should be more charitable,
Typo! Don't they know it's the thought that counts?''
</P>
<P>
   Typo agrees, ``I think they know that, Boss! What I wonder is
how they found out that those stockings hung by the chimney with
care are the ones we got out of the locker room laundry bucket!''
</P>
<P>
   Opening his gifts most carefully this year, BONG Chief Copyboy
Charley Stough, Dayton Daily News, 45 S. Ludlow St., Dayton, Ohio
45401 slides the tongs to NYTNS honorees worldwide. Phone (937)
225-2445 after 5 p.m. eastern. Fax 225-2489. E-mail
copyboy(at)dma.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
