<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Dec. 24, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CITRUS-CROP (Undated) _ The deep freeze enveloping California's
citrus crop will soon be felt at the cash register, with experts
predicting that retail prices for the remaining pieces of fruit are
guaranteed to soar given the shortened supply. By ANATASIA HENDRIX.
</P>
<P>
   DINOSAUR-ALEX (Houston) _ Meet Alexander Lin-Moore. He is a
dinosaur whiz. He can name them, size them, explain when, where and
how each type lived. He can even draw them, to scale. This would-be
paleontologist is in reality an 8-year-old boy, rambunctious,
precocious, given to matters of great urgency. By MARTY RACINE.
(Photo available on the New York Time database.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MITCH-AFTERMATH (Posoltega, Nicaragua _ A few days after Dominga
Roja was flooded out of her home by Hurricane Mitch, she went back
to rescue two precious possessions: her rooster and her Bible. Last
week, Roja clutched the Bible to her chest for comfort. The
rooster, however, may be turned into soup for a Christmas eve
supper, she said. By TYCHE HENDRICKS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DAILY-SHOW (Albany, N.Y.) _ He is not an author, but he wrote
a book. He is not an actor, but he is in movies. He is a stand-up
comic, but he doesn't do that anymore. And Jon Stewart is not a
talk show host. Well, actually, he is. Again. On Jan. 11, Stewart
will take over ``The Daily Show,'' Comedy Central's 11 p.m. weekday
satirical alternative to the nightly news. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-HEROES (Undated) _ Mark McGwire and Tara Lipinski, the
large and short of it in big-time sports this year, had a bond, and
what they shared made 1998 a special time in the sports world. What
they each had was spectacular runner-up, a second fiddle who played
the right tune. There was Sammy Sosa and there was Michelle Kwan.
By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KWANZAA (San Francisco) _ Kwanzaa has surged in popularity among
African Americans in the last several years. Having shed its
radical black image, the holiday is now part of mainstream culture,
taught in schools, observed by churches and marketed by corporate
America. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This Christmas there are many
reasons to be joyful. For one thing, we can call it Christmas,
Hanukkah, Ramadan, Kwanzaa, a bad time to try to park, Furby hell,
'tis the season for impeachment, or anything we want. Yes, we have
received one big present in 1998, and we're very thankful: This is
the year political correctness became incorrect. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
