<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5550 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMMEUS-98QUOTES-$ADV     12-24 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMMEUS-98QUOTES-$ADV27-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF NOTHING ELSE, THE YEAR WAS FULL OF STRANGE TALK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL TAMMEUS  
 c. 1998 KANSAS CITY STAR 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the end of 1998 in merciful sight, I've concluded that
people in the news _ especially a certain president _ stayed up
late coming up with cockeyed things to say. As proof, here are my
favorite quotes of the year: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Yes, I am a terrorist and am proud of it.'' _ Ramzi Ahmed
Yousef, convicted mastermind of the World Trade Center bombing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The correct answer is nothing.'' _ ABC's Ted Koppel on
qualifications needed to become an American journalist. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``As long as there are toilets, there'll be newspapers.'' _
Chicago Sun-Times executive Mark Hornung. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I did not have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky.'' _ Guess Who. And, no, it doesn't depend on what I mean
by ``Who.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Indeed, I did have a relationship with Ms. Lewinsky that was
not appropriate.'' _ Who, again, slip-sliding closer to the truth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I misled people, including even my wife.'' _ Who, again,
this time apparently using the past tense of the archaic verb
``misle,'' which has no known meaning. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I made a bad mistake.'' _ Who, again, differentiating
between bad and good mistakes, the latter of which don't result in
getting caught. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I think she's burdened by some unfortunate conditions of her
upbringing but she's basically a good person.'' _ Who, again, on
Monica Lewinsky. By the way, Who himself did not have what you
might call the most fortunate of conditions in his own upbringing.
Hmmmm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I would give anything to go back and undo what I did.'' _
Who, again, though not, as I first thought, talking about his
zipper. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He is an enormously gifted and richly qualified leader for
our nation but someone who is exasperatingly stupid in his personal
life.'' _ Former White House spokesman Mike McCurry on Guess Who. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I was under that desk 35 years ago, and I could tell you
there's barely room for a 3-year-old.'' _ John F. Kennedy Jr. on
sex in the Oval Office. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``I'll never wash it again.'' _ Lewinsky on her ultimately
crucial semen-stained dress. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Look, I will deny it so he will not get screwed in the case,
but I'm not going to get screwed personally.'' _ Lewinsky on
truth-telling, also issuing an apparently accurate sexual
prediction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Comparing him (Saddam Hussein) to cancer gives a bad name to
cancer.'' _ The gentle Sen. Ben Nighthorse Campbell, R-Colo. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``It doesn't say what's going to happen. But as of right now,
I think it is significant for this moment.'' _ Robert Foy, a
Southern Republican Leadership Conference delegate, hedging his
bets on the meaning of a presidential straw poll there led by Gov.
George W. Bush. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``You have to understand that males are made up differently
from women, and I try to be sensitive to women. Men compete, get
along and move on with few emotions. But women break down, get
emotional, get so much more out of the game. These are entirely
different sports cultures.'' _ Mega-sensitive Big East commissioner
Mike Tranghese. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Capitalism without failure is like religion without sin. It
doesn't work.'' _ Alan Metzler, Carnegie Mellon University
economist, suggesting abolishing the International Monetary Fund to
stop its annoying habit of trying to fix world economic crises. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The president is the president and he speaks for our
government.'' _ White House press secretary Joe Lockhart, proving
why he got the job. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He's too young and stupid to understand what he just did.''
_ Cubs' infielder Mark Grace explaining why pitcher Kerry Wood
didn't grasp the significance of striking out 20 players in one
game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The only thing that changes some scientists' opinion is
death.'' _ Louis A. Frank, a University of Iowa physicist often
attacked by other scientists for his snowballs-from-space theory. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``He spoke too long and, in common with other congenitally
prudent bishops, he is not a burning bush.'' _ Tim Unsworth,
writing in the National Catholic Reporter about Cardinal Francis
George of Chicago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``If you make it a referendum on a president with a 67 percent
approval rating, you shouldn't be surprised if the election goes
against you.'' _ Republican Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, on why
the November elections were so disappointing to his party. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``God, I'd like to forget all of this. I mean, who needs it?''
_ Rep. Henry Hyde on impeachment, who then made sure no one would
ever forget it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Depend on God to knock the dreams out of their empty
heads.'' _ Official Iraq Revolutionary Command Council and Baath
Party statement on what they called ``American-British
aggression.'' No response yet from God. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Tammeus is a columnist for The Kansas City Star. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service. E-mail:
tammeus(at)kcstar.com.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This column is for use Sunday, Dec. 27, and thereafter.) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
