<HEADER>
A5567 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRAQ-WEAPONS-DESTROYE     12-24 1327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-WEAPONS-DESTROYED-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRAQ IS DOWN BUT NOT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of the daily New York Times
op-eds. To publish as a ``separate buy'' article, please contact
your New York Times Syndicate sales representative: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: NIRDI RELIS in New York at
1-800-972-3550 or 212-499-3333; fax, 212-499-3382. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By ROD BARTON  
 c.1998 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia _ Iraqi officials have said that United
Nations weapons inspectors will never set foot in their country
again, and the U.N. Security Council has just begun what is likely
to be a lengthy debate on the future of Unscom, its special
commission on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   So when I left Iraq last week with the rest of the Unscom
inspectors, it may have been for the last time. Now seems an
appropriate moment to ask: Did the American air strikes last week
achieve what Unscom could not _ the disarming of Iraq?
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said the mission's objective was to reduce
Iraq's ability to make chemical and biological weapons. Officials
have reported that about 400 cruise missiles were fired at 100
targets.
</P>
<P>
   Among the targets were nine missile development factories, a
petrochemical plant and a biological research laboratory, as well
as military and intelligence establishments, the Republican Guard
headquarters and the building housing the Military Industrial
Commission, which oversees Iraq's special weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   While the list may appear impressive, the damage done to Iraq's
weapon-making ability was probably marginal. It is almost certain
that no missile hit hidden stockpiles of chemical or biological
bombs (not desirable anyway because of the contamination that would
result).
</P>
<P>
   The inspectors working for Unscom had searched for years for
such arsenals; if the inspectors had not found them, it is unlikely
that the United States, even with its impressive intelligence
resources, would know where they were.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, what the air strikes hit were ``dual purpose'' plants _
that is, sites that have nonmilitary functions but also have the
potential to contribute to the weapon programs. These would include
electronics plants that might be able to make missile guidance
components, steel works that could fabricate warheads and
refineries that could produce chemicals for nerve agents.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Persian Gulf War in 1991, such factories were used
for these very purposes. In uncovering Iraq's biological weapons
program in 1995, our Unscom team found a vaccine plant that Iraq
had converted to the production of biological warfare agents. More
than 5,000 liters of botulinum toxin, a horrific food poisoning
agent, had been produced there in less than two months. After the
war, the plant was converted back to vaccine production.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Unscom was monitoring these dual-purpose sites
closely. Until we evacuated just before last week's bombing, we
routinely inspected 63 factories that could contribute to a missile
program, 120 chemical-related plants and 93 biological plants. At
many of these sites, we had installed cameras, air samplers, heat
sensors and other devices to make sure no banned activity was
taking place.
</P>
<P>
   The Unscom inspection effort may have had its problems, but this
was one part of our work that was effective. If Iraq was rebuilding
its programs, it was not at these sites.
</P>
<P>
   So although the latest bombings surely destroyed some
dual-purpose operations, that was hardly a crippling blow. And even
those sites that were destroyed won't stay that way. Shortly after
the gulf war, I visited the vast Taji steel works on the outskirts
of Baghdad. Hardly a building remained standing; the devastation,
it seemed, was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when I visited it last year, the plant had been completely
rebuilt, with some of the large machines, although pockmarked with
shrapnel, operating as before the war.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis had learned from their war with Iran to have plans
for the evacuation of vital equipment in times of crisis, and
certainly this was widely practiced in the gulf war. On one of my
early inspections in 1991, I found more than 100 pieces of
equipment for making chemical weapons hidden in a sugar factory at
Mosul, about 185 miles from the Al Muthanna weapons plant from
which they had originated. In short, buildings may have been
obliterated in last week's bombing, but not necessarily vital
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Probably the biggest blow Iraq suffered in the recent bombing
was to its missile development efforts. The cease-fire resolution
ending the gulf war required Iraq to eliminate missiles with a
range of greater than 150 kilometers, or 93 miles. Iraq was
permitted to develop shorter-range missiles, and since the war has
done so under Unscom monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was that these shorter-range missiles could be
readily modified, by ``stretching'' the fuel tanks and improving
the guidance systems, into missiles with a range of 600 kilometers
_ sufficient to hit Tel Aviv or Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
   Unscom has evidence that Iraq is still hiding missile fuel, an
issue that Iraqi officials have refused to discuss in the past
year. Because of this, many of last week's missiles were aimed at
missile manufacturing, launching and test sites. Since there
probably wasn't time to evacuate most of the heavy equipment from
these sites, the bombing has almost surely set back Iraqi missile
development, perhaps for several years.
</P>
<P>
   The news for Iraq's neighbors, and the world, is not so good
regarding Iraq's chemical and biological programs. It is clear,
even from the little information filtering out, that few of the
many plants capable of contributing to these programs have been
destroyed. I believe Iraq could be producing significant quantities
of biological agents within six months. For chemical agents like
nerve gas, the time range is one to two years.
</P>
<P>
   How to deliver these agents continues to pose a problem for
Iraq, but Unscom has information that Iraq still has about a half
dozen Scud missiles hidden. And if Unscom inspectors or other
monitors are not permitted to return to Baghdad to keep an eye on
Iraq's dual-purpose factories, this threat will grow over the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge now for the Security Council and the world is how
to contain Iraq. President Clinton has not ruled out future
bombings, but this is no solution, and no one wants a permanent
state of war. The administration also wants to bring down the Iraqi
government, but Saddam Hussein seems remarkably resilient and the
opposition divided and weak. In any case, if Hussein is simply
replaced by his son Uday, the world may be no better off, and some
would argue it will be worse off.
</P>
<P>
   What is required is some creative thinking, but the Security
Council is polarized. Chances have to be taken with any solution,
and perhaps now is the time to consider the phased lifting of
sanctions _ say, over a period of seven years. This is not to
reward Iraq but to provide an incentive for it to accept strict
monitoring to ensure that its industries are not used to rebuild
its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Failure to comply would result in the freezing of sanctions at a
particular phase and restrictions on the amount of oil Iraq could
sell. At the same time, tough import controls would be applied to
restrict what it could spend its vast oil wealth on. Through a
combination of carrot and stick, it is possible, just possible,
that Iraq could be brought back to the community of nations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Rod Barton, a microbiologist, has been a senior United Nations
weapons inspector in Iraq since May 1991.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
