<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATT-BUMGARDNER-COX     12-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATT-BUMGARDNER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bumgardner bounces back for Aggies
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Randy Riggs
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Bumgardner's immediate reward for making the biggest catch
of his career was a sore ankle.
</P>
<P>
   It figures.
</P>
<P>
   Bumgardner, Texas A&AMP;M's junior wide receiver from Luling, has
been injured so often during his star-crossed football career that
offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe has joked that the Aggies'
training room should be named after him. But a sore ankle was a
small price to pay for the catch that helped sustain A&AMP;M's
remarkable season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also made up for a lot of frustration for me,'' Bumgardner
said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost overshadowed by the hoopla surrounding the Aggies' 36-33
double-overtime victory over Kansas State in the Big 12
championship game was Bumgardner's remarkable catch. Without it,
quarterback Branndon Stewart and tailback Sirr Parker might never
have had the opportunity to become the anointed heroes who led A&AMP;M
to a Sugar Bowl date against third-ranked Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   With A&AMP;M trailing by eight points and in a first-and-25 hole
from the 50-yard line with about 2 1/2 minutes left, Bumgardner ran
a streak route and used his 6-foot-1-inch frame to establish
position on 5-10 cornerback Jerametrius Butler. Stewart lofted a
rainbow over Bumgardner's head that appeared to be long, but the
former track star at Luling stretched out parallel to the ground
and made a diving, blind catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as fine a catch as I've seen in a long time,'' A&AMP;M
Coach R.C. Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a career-long, 36-yard reception for Bumgardner,
not to mention a sore ankle after Butler fell on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I didn't even feel it until I got back to the sideline,''
Bumgardner reported. ``The adrenaline was really pumping.''
</P>
<P>
   After all Bumgardner's been through, a throbbing ankle doesn't
even register on the radar.
</P>
<P>
   His injury problems began his senior season at Luling. After
catching 56 passes for 1,152 yards and 19 touchdowns as a sophomore
and junior, Bumgardner lasted only until the third game of his
senior year before he was sidelined for the rest of the season with
a torn hamstring in a game against Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his inactivity, Bumgardner continued to be recruited by
several schools, including A&AMP;M, Texas Tech, Oklahoma and Texas,
where his grandfather, Max, was a wide receiver for the Longhorns
in the late 1940s. Matt picked A&AMP;M, where Max had served as Coach
Emory Bellard's academic supervisor in the 1970s. The younger
Bumgardner thus became the first Luling athlete to sign with an
NCAA Division I school since tailback Willis Ray Mackey signed with
the University of Washington in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took him based on his junior year, and the fact that we'd
had him in our (summer) camp and knew how fast he could run,''
Slocum said. ``He's a guy who I've thought the whole time he's been
here could be a good player for us if he can ever stay healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bumgardner has spent an inordinate amount of time running to
the training room. Last year, he caught 10 passes for 127 yards
before missing the Big 12 title game against Nebraska and the
Cotton Bowl against UCLA with a deep thigh bruise. This season, he
caught an 8-yard pass in the opener against Florida State, but
suffered a high ankle sprain in practice the next week that
sidelined him for five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``A cleat stuck to ground while I was coming back to catch a
ball,'' he said. ``I was pretty devastated by it. I hate missing
football. And it's hard enough to play at this level even when
you're 100 percent healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bumgardner has been productive since his return. He has caught
just nine passes this year, but they've been for 173 yards _ a
healthy average of 19.2 yards. He grabbed his first career
touchdown pass at Oklahoma State.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually Bumgardner wants to coach. But because injuries have
deprived him of playing opportunities, he wants to play as long as
he can, although he admits to being aware of the possibility of
another injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always in the back of my mind because you just never
know,'' he said. ``I know there is only a certain amount of time I
have left to play, so it's so frustrating to miss practice and
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love football. I can't see myself getting away from it.
I want to play until they take my pads away from me. I'm going to
play until I can't play anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
