r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DINOSAUR-ALEX-HNS &LR;      12-24 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DINOSAUR-ALEX-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU HAVE A QUESTION ABOUT T-REX, JUST ASK ALEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (Photo available on NYT database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARTY RACINE  
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The would-be paleontologist pondered the question
posed by the inquisitive reporter. After a moment of reflection he
reached his conclusion: ``I'm hungry!''
</P>
<P>
   OK, the scientific hotshot is in reality an 8-year-old boy,
rambunctious, precocious, given to matters of great urgency. And
his refined interest in the natural world, formed since the age of
2, does not preclude a childlike presumption that he is at the
center of it.
</P>
<P>
   Meet, if he will keep still long enough, Alexander Lin-Moore of
the Houston-area city of Bellaire. Alex is a dinosaur whiz. He can
name them, size them, explain when, where and how each type lived.
He can even draw them, to scale.
</P>
<P>
   Alex recently parlayed that knowledge into winning a national
contest.
</P>
<P>
   The online challenge, which spanned several months, presented a
series of clues based on paleontology and general trivia that
indicated the location of a buried dinosaur bone.
</P>
<P>
   Alex answered the dinosaur questions. Those were easy. His
parents David Moore and Judy Lin contributed to the others. That
was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were working hard there toward the end, it took us awhile
to get some of the last ones,'' says David, a molecular biologist
and professor of cell biology at Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   They got it right, beating by three hours another entrant who
also answered all questions correctly. When notified by e-mail,
Alex ran around the house jumping and screaming.
</P>
<P>
   His prize is a rare cast, or replica, of the world's largest
dinosaur bone _ a backbone of the Argentinosaurus. At 100 tons, the
Argentinosaurus was the world's largest plant-eating dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot high, 4-foot wide hollow cast, valued at $5,000, was
presented to Alex recently at the Maryland Science Center in
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Doing the honors were Argentine paleontologist Rodolfo Coria,
who named the Argentinosaurus after it was discovered by a farmer
in Patagonia, and contest organizer ``Dino Don'' Lessem, a
consultant to Steven Spielberg and Universal Studios for ``Jurassic
Park'' and its sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm delighted it was a kid who won,'' said Lessem, ``even if
Alex is half my size and twice as smart about dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   The bone cast will remain in Baltimore until David Letterman's
people decide on a possible appearance by Alex on ``The Late
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in Bellaire, it will briefly reside in Alex's room. Then
the family hopes to loan it to a local museum until Alex turns 21
and can decide what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Alex got to be Alex by visiting museums when the family lived in
Boston, David's hometown. ``To keep him away from Nintendo,'' says
Judy, an ophthalmologist from Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   So it should not surprise that on a nice, normal street in
Bellaire one boy's collection of videos is heavy on National
Geographic specials. Hot topics like ``Dinosaur Hunters'' and
``T-Rex Exposed,'' which rattle loose when Alex opens the cabinet
and impulsively spreads cassettes on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He jumps over to another drawer containing a tangled pile of
plastic and rubber dinosaur models _ one hesitates to call them
toys _ scaled to size and purchased at museum stores. He piles onto
the couch and ruthlessly tosses them about the coffee table,
explaining the properties of each.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite? ``He has rotating favorites,'' Judy says with a
mother's patience.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Alex has seen ``Jurassic Park.'' He was too young
during its theater run, so when he was about 5 he viewed it on home
video. ``We only saw it essentially in fast-forward,'' says Judy.
``He would say, `This is boring.' Or, `This is scary.' ``And he
would say, `That's not right.''' Hollywood can't fool him. Nor can
school automatically teach him. In his third-grade class at
Bellaire's Horn Elementary they do study science and dinosaurs and
stuff, Alex says, shrugging his shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I already know everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1218EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
