<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMIN' OF AN UN-PC CHRISTMAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This Christmas there are many reasons to be
joyful. For one thing, we can call it Christmas, Hanukkah, Ramadan,
Kwanzaa, a bad time to try to park, Furby hell, 'tis the season for
impeachment, or anything we want.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to call it ``the holidays'' when, in fact, we get
no rest. We don't have to call it a ``season'' when it's just the
most expensive part of one.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to say ``the winter solstice'' and sound like
pagans, which so many of us are, as proven by our heathen trees
propped in pans of water.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we have received one big present in 1998, and we're very
thankful: This is the year political correctness became incorrect.
</P>
<P>
   We still ought to be thoughtful and polite. But we don't have to
be self-consciously sensitive and sound like Hillary Rodham Clinton
giving a December speech in the Rose Garden when all we're doing is
thanking a sales clerk.
</P>
<P>
   So I call it Christmas, referring not to Christianity, but to
the most sacred day in the religion of American materialism. Until
the middle of the last century American Puritans considered the
celebration of Christmas blasphemous _ one of several good points
about my much-maligned Puritan ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Count all our new blessings, now that PC is DOA.
</P>
<P>
   During the cold snap this week, my wife walked all over downtown
San Francisco. She wore her fur coat, the first time she's worn it
in the city since I grudgingly bought it for her 11 years ago when
she had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I die, the foxes can skin and wear me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, she didn't die. And fortunately, last week we
didn't walk past a demonstration of paint-throwing anti-fur nuts in
front of a department store.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, punk, we wear fur and leather, and we believe in
the right to keep and bear grudges, so get lost.
</P>
<P>
   We ate veal shank at that festively decorated La Rondalla for
the rich, Le Central. It's a bistro patronized by many Republicans,
including our leading lifestyle Republican, San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown. That's another thing. In San Francisco, you can like
Republicans again. Not only are Republicans almost extinct here,
but they've destroyed themselves in Washington, too.
</P>
<P>
   The people who brought us the Defense of Marriage Act gave a
standing O to a congressman who committed adultery. Right-wing
political correctness has gone down the tubes, too.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking was outlawed in California bars. The war on drugs
certainly teaches us the effectiveness of making things illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Bars have done what comes naturally. Some are non-smoking bars,
while others have remained smoking bars. The latter cater to those
too young to care about dying, or those already embalmed on their
bar stools.
</P>
<P>
   We've reached a truce. If you don't like smoke in a bar, walk on
to one with clear air. You don't dial 911 when you detect
secondhand smoke. The cops have enough to do protecting people from
firsthand bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco police don't want to sort out cigarette
smokers from those legally smoking marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Male chauvinists finally are safe from feminists in San
Francisco and other hotbeds of the cold shoulder and frosty stare.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan and Gloria Steinem issued impassioned defenses of
an executive who cheated on his hard-working wife by having bad sex
with a 21-year-old employee.
</P>
<P>
   The executive claimed she was having sex with him, but he wasn't
having sex with her, and the feminist elite defended him.
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, guys, I'd say anything that isn't actually
illegal goes. As long as you don't get slugged, of course.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have to be as multiculturally sensitive as we used to
be. There's even a group in San Francisco called the Wonderbread 5,
a ``Jackson 5 Tribute Group'' of white guys in Afro wigs, with a
white wig for the one who plays Michael Jackson. They'll be at the
Velvet Lounge on New Year's Eve, and we'll see if they live.
</P>
<P>
   What other joys are there? We can eat hunks of red meat. We can
drink Manhattans or chug Bud. We're recovering from the recovery
movement. As someone told me, ``You don't have to go into recovery
until you hit bottom, and I'm still going down.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, you can be unapologetic about giving your children
violent toys, and I don't just mean ones that do violence to sanity
like the Furby.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, violent video games always take place in a
futuristic Los Angeles, which is fine with me. There is no other
kind of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A video game called Future Cop, L.A.P.D. involves zapping
``mutant crooks packin' thermo nukes, bio-agents, and other bad
mojo (who) are laying siege to the City of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not so bad, compared to the mutant shoppers at the malls
right now.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the violence in toys occurs trying to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   If I get that BB gun I've always wanted for Christmas, just wait
until you hear my riff on guns. It'll put your ear out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
