<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 12:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5626 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY FLYNT'S PARTNERS IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four months ago, Salon magazine reported that ``diehard Clinton
loyalists'' were spreading the word that ``a long-ignored but
fearsome tactic has now resurfaced as an element in the president's
survival strategy: The threat of exposing the sexual improprieties
of Republican critics both in Congress and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about the Doomsday Machine here,'' a close
Clinton ally told the on-line publication. ``Once the Doomsday
Machine is set in motion, there will be no stopping it. The
Republicans with skeletons in their closets must assume everything
is known and will come out. So the question is: Do they really want
to go there?''
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, they really did want to go there. And in the
end, they built a strong enough case to compel a majority of the
House of Representatives to impeach President Clinton on one count
of perjury and one count of obstruction of justice. They were not
deterred by blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   But the Doomsday Machine _ or something like it _ did its
damage. The fact that Representative Dan Burton had fathered a son
out of wedlock was exposed and duly reported in the press.
Representative Helen Chenoweth's affair with a married man was
exposed and duly reported in the press. House Judiciary Committee
chairman Henry Hyde's extramarital affair of 30 years ago was
exposed and duly reported in Salon, which justified publication by
saying ``ugly times require ugly tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend, House Speaker-designate Robert Livingston's
extramarital affairs cost him his job and his political career.
Livingston delivered the news himself, in advance of what he knew
would be certain publication on Hustler magazine's Web site.
``Desperate times,'' said Hustler publisher Larry Flynt, ``deserve
desperate actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynt injected himself into the impeachment process two months
ago. He ran a full-page advertisement in The Washington Post
offering a reward of up to $1 million for anyone who could prove
having had an adulterous sexual encounter with a current member of
Congress or a high-ranking government official. The real purpose of
the ad, Flynt said, was to gather dirt on GOP legislators to derail
the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt is the publisher of what may be the most nihilistic and
misogynistic magazine in America. He is also a self-described
partisan Democrat, a fan of President Clinton's and a friend of
Clinton political strategist James Carville. Many Republican
legislators believe he is an active cog in the Doomsday Machine or
something like it. But they offer no hard evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Flynt chooses his words carefully when asked if the GOP charges
are true. ``I can assure you I've had no contact with the White
House,'' he told Howard Kurtz of The Washington Post. ``I don't get
my marching orders from them.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without White House marching orders, Flynt's desperate
actions will continue. Interviewed Tuesday on National Public
Radio's ``Fresh Air,'' Flynt said he would publish the names of as
many as 12 politicians whose infidelities he could document. Asked
when exactly he would make this information available, Flynt
replied: ``In the next couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday, after he became the first elected president in
American history to be impeached, Clinton piously intoned: ``We
must stop the politics of personal destruction. We must get rid of
the poisonous venom of excessive partisanship, obsessive animosity
and uncontrolled anger.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the president's press secretary, Joe Lockhart, was
asked if the president would call Flynt and request that he desist
from publishing the names of Republican legislators who may have
had extramarital affairs. No, said Lockhart, he would not.
</P>
<P>
   And so the politics of personal destruction continue apace.
Assuming that Flynt has enough evidence to go forward with
publication, the reputations of as many as 12 more politicians will
be destroyed for the stated purpose of enabling one man to keep an
office he has disgraced.
</P>
<P>
   Having lost the vote on impeachment, the president's defenders
are now doing everything they can to discredit that vote. In this
effort they have been so far surprisingly successful. The
president's job approval ratings are at record highs. Two-thirds of
the electorate opposes his removal from office. Sentiment for some
kind of censure resolution is building in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But their efforts reveal the moral bankruptcy of their politics.
They have become partners in the politics of Larry Flynt. They are
burning the village to save it. And with each passing day, their
conduct and complicity in this ongoing disgrace makes censure less
likely and conviction more possible.
</P>
<P>
   (John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1241EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5629 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PRESERVATION-BOS     12-24 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PRESERVATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE AT FIRST SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARGO MILLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Mass. -- The time is soon coming when ``modern'' or
``contemporary'' houses built in this half of the 20th century will
be candidates for preservation. And for the same reasons that
people prize 18th- and 19th-century houses. They are often better
constructed than today's contractor's special. If commissioned from
an architect, they are part of design history. The best of them are
still very livable.
</P>
<P>
   When a house designed by Hugh Stubbins in 1952 recently became
available, Michael and Shelley Peyette McGarry only needed one
look. ``We fell in love with the property and the house,'' says
Shelley. ``On the first visit, we peeked in the windows, and it was
so neat.''
</P>
<P>
   A good thing too, because most real estate people figured the
house for a ``tear down.'' Great land, they could hear clients say,
but my dear, the bathroom! (there was just the one), and the
kitchen's a joke. Better to lose the house and begin again.
</P>
<P>
   The McGarrys were happy with the house as it was. But they faced
one enormous hurdle. The 6 acres on which it sat had been
subdivided. New homes were already under construction on two of the
2-acre parcels. The Stubbins house was within the reconfigured
property line but not quite enough to satisfy the law. The McGarrys
decided to do what 18th- and 19th-century homeowners did: They had
the house jacked up and moved on rollers. Moreover, Gordon Building
Movers of Hingham, Mass. used the traditonal way of lifting the
house _ by giant wooden screws turned by bars. There were 10 screws
and the crew gave each a quarter turn, inching the house up and
over the bedrock.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Studied Stubbins's plans
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moving and saving ``was cheaper than building a new house,''
Mike McGarry told a recent visitor. He laughs and adds, ``it should
have been quicker.'' An engineer by training, he acted as the
renovation designer; for reference he had Stubbins's own plans,
from the archives at the Harvard Graduate School of Design, where
Stubbins had been Walter Gropius's assistant and later the
department chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In Lincoln there's an awful lot of Mother Nature in the form of
boulders and ledge. Stubbins put this to good use, butting the
easterly ``Boston'' end of the house into the hillcrest and decking
the westerly ``Worcester'' end with steps down to the gardens.
Repositioning exactly reverses that. Because the McGarrys moved the
house 94 feet (toward Boston) they had to put in new water and gas
lines and a new leach field, and that meant blasting and more
blasting. ``It was slooow,'' Shelley McGarry agrees.
</P>
<P>
   The family spent the summer on site, living in a trailer in a
grove off the driveway. The hammock is still there, and the two
tree houses. They just made it into the new house for Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The McGarrys had been looking to leave Cambridge and move
farther out, perhaps as far as Southborough. They wanted good
schools for Owen, who's 6, and Marina, 5, and Lincoln has those.
They like the country, and Lincoln, with its conservation land,
guarantees plenty of that. That Hugh Stubbins had actually designed
the house was awesome. If you're the daughter and sibling of
architects _ Shelley's father is Thomas Peyette _ you grow up
knowing Stubbins's contribution to the cityscape.
</P>
<P>
   To name but three: There's the Federal Reserve building in
Boston (``one of my favorites,'' Stubbins said in a phone interview
from retirement in Florida). There's the CitiCorp. building in New
York City. And there's the tallest building in Japan, a 70-story
tower in Yokohama topped by a 600-room hotel overlooking Tokyo Bay
and, on a clear day, a view of Mount Fuji. This was Stubbins's last
project, and when he and his wife, June, stayed there recently he
``was treated like a king,'' he says, sounding pleased.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lots of glass
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was all ahead of Stubbins in the early 1950s, when Mr. &AMP;
Mrs. Arthur Baggs, he an engineer and she an artist, approached him
to design a house for a hilly pasture in Lincoln. Elsewhere in
suburbia developers were buying up old fields and planting them
with ranch houses or Capes; in common with ranches, the Stubbins is
a rectangle, about 24 by 48 feet, and on one level. There the
comparison ends. No picture window but lots and lots of glass. Each
end of the house is glass. In the living room, it goes from the
floor all the way up the gable; at the bedroom end, from waist-high
to gable. Most rooms have a band of windows. Not exactly New
England, you might think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always believed that any building should have a regional
character,'' Stubbins says. He was born Jan. 11, 1912, in
Birmingham, Ala., went to Georgia Tech, and got his master's in
architecture at Harvard's GSD. The Cambridge firm he founded
continues as the Stubbins Associates. ``There's a New England taste
to the houses I built,'' he says, ``certainly the later ones.'' New
England, for him, means high ceilings in living rooms. With the
dining alcove, the Lincoln living room runs the width (24 feet) of
the house, but by taking the ceiling up to the rafters, Stubbins
pumped air into space and made the room light and buoyant. It has a
big feel to it. Nor is your eye stopped by walls. While the house
is not an open plan, there are vistas. If you face the living room
fireplace, there's light to the left from the stair entry and an
immediate connection to arriving guests.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Shelley reports, especially loves the window design.
As an architect, Thomas Peyette specializes in hospitals, medical
centers, labs, and schools. ``My father is very interested in
light. He feels it's important to be able to look out a window and
locate yourself in space. He's a very outdoorsy person, and he
loves this house. We think it's even better now that it has been
moved. The repositioning has made it much more intimate. You look
up into the trees, especially the entertaining end of the house. It
feels like a tree house.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor do the McGarrys lack for flowering shrubs. ``The place is
loaded with lilacs,'' Mike says. ``There's tons of honeysuckle, two
dozen crab apples, and cedars along the driveway.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's furniture took to the new house at once. Shelley
Peyette had grown up with modernist furniture. She then got
interested in Arts &AMP; Crafts. ``I got Mike started. His father,
Robert McGarry, collects early American and native American. The
Arts &AMP; Crafts we have is perfect for here: The wood warms the place
up. Mike loves wood, he's a wood man, he's a wood collector.'' From
curly maple he made a baby's chair; the living room couch is his
creation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Passion for built-ins
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stubbins says he always liked doing built-ins, and the McGarrys
have the benefit of that. The cleverest is the common wall between
the entry stair and the first bedroom. On the entry side is a coat
closet with sliding door. (Arthur Baggs trumped Stubbins by making
the door into gallery space for his wife's art and made a hall into
another gallery.) On the bedroom side is a wall of built-ins. No
door or drawer knobs but big, burnished brass circles, subtle and
insistent, that say: ``Pull me, pull me.'' Pull one, and a desk
flaps forward.
</P>
<P>
   The exterior of the house is clear-heart redwood, vertically
grained, which Stubbins treated with a Cabot bleaching stain to
weather it a New England gray. He used the same wood for some
interior walls. ``Bringing the outdoors indoors,'' he calls it.
Another way of blurring the boundary between the built and the
natural is ending the roof rafter in a lattice. As houses go, this
one looks tiny, when compared with its new neighbors, the hulking
three-garage ``custom Colonials'' down slope. A cunning economy
gives it amplitude. ``Borrowing space from something else,''
Stubbins says.
</P>
<P>
   The McGarrys have followed suit. When the house was moved, space
under the living room was freed up. Here the McGarrys have built a
family room with fireplace and another bathroom, as well as a
utility room and a cavern for storage. Parts of the kitchen will be
refitted. The 1952 plans simply indicated where a dishwasher might
go. Stubbins is all in favor of improvements. ``A lot of kitchen
equipment didn't exist when I designed the house.'' The McGarrys
like the original birch cabinets with their obscured-glass windows.
</P>
<P>
   In Cambridge, traffic made it impossible for the McGarry
children go anywhere alone, says their mother. ``Here, they play
outdoors all the time. They go adventuring. They're discovering
animals. A little girl from one of the new houses has come to play.
The really new thing is having their own bedrooms. They're really
experiencing what it is to be grown-up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perfect match
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing,'' Shelley McGarry continued, ``is a perfect
match for us. I'm just tickled how the move met every single need
of mine. It's the country, but I have friends. The children love
their schools. I have a studio.'' For many years, a graphics
designer who worked on museum and zoo installations, she has moved
into jewelry design. Michael McGarry is an engineer with the
Primary Group of Boston; his most recent project was the new
federal courthouse on Boston's Fan Pier. ``The house is great for
Mike. He's intrigued with the way the structural and the aesthetic
work together. My father loves the way Mike takes a challenge and
makes something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   McGarry has plans to grow the Stubbins house. He stood the other
day on rock outcropping that is a prime candidate for an alpine
garden. The rock is pocketed with holes for future piers for a new
building that will run alongside the original. A bridge will
connect the two. ``Son of Stubbins'' (so to speak) will have the
new living room and dining room and kitchen with a mechanical room
underneath. There is no timetable for this, McGarry says. But a
date to shoot for is 2002, when the original turns 50.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRETARY COHEN, LEAVE THE KID ALONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is now official US policy that it's OK to bomb the Iraqis,
but not to write anything on the bomb casing.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon this week found it necessary to apologize for some
graffiti scrawled on the side of a 2,000-pound laser-guided bomb
being loaded aboard the carrier USS Enterprise for delivery during
the 70-hour air assault on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Among other messages, the bomb bore the inscription: ``Here's a
Ramadan present from Chad Rickenberg.'' After the Associated Press
moved a photo of the bomb, the Defense Department said it was
``distressed'' at the ``thoughtless graffiti'' referring to the
Holy Month of Ramadan, the ninth month of the Islamic year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Religious intolerance is anathema to the Secretary of Defense,
William S. Cohen, and to all Americans who respect the right to
worship freely,'' said Ken Bacon, Cohen's spokesman. The US
appreciates the contributions of Muslim Americans to the military,
he added. ``This incident is a rare exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the ``gotcha'' mentality of Washington and the military,
not to speak of the news media, one hopes that Navy man Rickenberg
is not eating bread and water for his Christmas dinner.
</P>
<P>
   I think official praise for the contributions of Muslim
Americans and respect for Ramadan is a fine thing. But does the
brass have to land like a ton of bricks on a young man, far from
home at Yuletide, doing a very dangerous job, serving his country?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cohen is a topnotch public servant; he and wife Janet
Langhart made a flying holiday tour to Kuwait and two US carriers
for the purpose of saluting the 20,000 American servicemen and
women in the theater, including Lieutenant Kendra Williams, 26, who
flew her FA-18 fighter-bomber off the Enterprise, one of 16 woman
combat pilots aboard. And one careless jibe by an ordnance-handler
scarcely ranks with the destructive power of a 2,000-pound laser
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   To find out if the GIs who won World War II fought under similar
politically correct instructions, I consulted Bob Healy, the
retired Globe political columnist, who at age 18 joined the US
bomber crews that flew out of England to rain destruction upon
Hitler's armies.Did Healy ever see graffiti on bombs destined for
the Axis crowd? ``Sure. It was done all the time. Some of them were
pretty obscene, very hostile. They'd paint stuff on the bombs. In
those days, they'd take your picture for Yank Magazine. There was
no political correctness then. It was us-vs.-them. Now? Forget it.
We've gone overboard on this political correctness, haven't we?''
</P>
<P>
   Healy was a ball-turrent gunner on B-17s, four-engine long-range
bombers that could carry two 1,000-pound bombs, or four
500-pounders, as well as sticks of smaller bombs, or firebombs. ``I
was also an armament guy,'' said Healy, who survived 35 combat
missions. ``So when a bomb would get stuck in the bomb bay, or a
stick got hung up, you'd have to go down there and kick 'em out. I
wasn't one of those guys who painted things on bombs. I always
figured getting back was more important.''
</P>
<P>
   But he saw plenty of nasty messages directed to Hitler and his
helpers. ``Some of the planes had nicknames or stuff painted
outside the cockpit that was pretty raw. It all depended on the
crew.''
</P>
<P>
   Healy has complete sympathy with the young ordnanceman who is
risking his life, handling dangerous munitions, on orders from the
highest reaches of his government. The whole purpose is to prevent
Saddam from getting up another head of steam in the unstable Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong,'' said Healy, who just completed a
diplomatic hitch in the US Embassy in Ireland, where fighting over
religious symbols has been a bloody pastime for 800 years. ``I can
understand the objection to what he wrote. But he's over there
fighting for his country. They don't have to pat the kid on the
back. But they shouldn't kick him in the ass. That's his way of
saying why he's over there.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighters who risk all defending the American way of life at
century's end catch hell if they have illicit love affairs, are gay
and admit it, or run afoul of the rules or get accused, fairly or
unfairly, of sexual or racial indiscretions. At some point, the
country is going to need as many fighters as it can lay hands on at
any given moment. And punishing fighters who are doing their job
adequately for the sake of politically correct rules is not a trend
that, in the long run, will bolster our fighting forces.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone with a modicum of education and cultural awareness can
understand why religious symbolism is a powerful motivator.And the
news photo of an American bomb with a Ramadan reference will
undoubtedly give offense, just as the routine TV news footage of
the burning of American flags is intended to give offense. Our
laser bombs, and the 400 cruise missiles at $1 million a pop, did a
great deal more damage than one jibe painted on a bomb casing can
do to religious sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   I say leave Chad alone. If the brass doesn't like explaining
wisecracks scrawled by young men doing a dangerous job, then keep
photographers away from the bomb-loading. And please, Secretary
Cohen, make sure Chad gets his share of Christmas turkey.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
