<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-ABL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMISE OF THE ABL A SURPRISE TO MOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the receptionist at the Hartford Civic Center walked into
general manager Marty Brooks's office Tuesday afternoon to say that
she'd gotten several calls asking what happened to the New England
Blizzard, he wondered what was up.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks logged onto the Internet and learned from the American
Basketball League web site that the professional women's basketball
league had folded and was filing for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   First he was shocked. Then he was upset. He still is. The Civic
Center is the site of the Blizzard's home games, and the team was
scheduled to play 14 more this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this point, I have not had any official communication from
the Blizzard or the league,'' Brooks said Wednesday. ``This is
unacceptable. People are judged by how they handle pressure and
react to a crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone call to the Blizzard office reaches a recording that
directs callers to the league office in Palo Alto, Calif. A call to
the ABL office reaches a recording saying that the league has
closed its operation.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks was not the only one left out in the cold when the
nine-team league disbanded just two months into its third season.
</P>
<P>
   Sports agent Andrew Brandt of Woolf and Associates returned to
Boston from out of town to be greeted by 27 voice mail messages
``mostly from my clients and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandt represents three ABL players, including Kara Wolters of
the Blizzard. He said the players had been hearing rumors all
afternoon, and Wolters eventually received a message from coach
K.C. Jones confirming that the league had folded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked,'' Brandt said. ``I thought the trouble would be
this summer, but once the season got started it would be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brandt said he knew things were bad when ABL cofounder and
chief executive officer Gary Cavalli recently appealed to players
to give back part of their salaries to be used either for marketing
the league or purchasing tickets for the underprivileged. He said
the league got a 60 percent response.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt said Wolters wants to ``sit back and relax for awhile.''
He said top-level players such as her and teammate Jennifer
Rizzotti shouldn't have a problem finding a job with a team in the
WNBA _ the other professional women's league _ but that ``it's the
second level'' who will have trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Levy, an agent at Levy &AMP; Associates in New York who
represents nine ABL players, wasn't optimistic, either. ``I knew
they were in trouble,'' he said, ``but I had assumed the league
would continue through the All-Star Game (Jan. 24).''
</P>
<P>
   And like the others, Levy said he was caught off guard. ``It's
been a long time since we didn't know something like this,'' he
said. ``And on Sunday we were at the Philly-Columbus game and there
was no sense that this was imminent.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet was that one of the players there was Markita
Aldridge, a client whom Levy had recently convinced to sign with
the Columbus Quest as a temporary replacement rather than go play
in Eurpope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I encouraged her, and after the game Sunday she thanked me,''
he said. ``I had said, `As long as you play two months, it will be
worth it.' But who thought it would be three weeks?''
</P>
<P>
   Levy said he was at his office until 1 Wednesday morning
fielding calls from players and the media. When he got home, he was
on the phone for another four hours with European teams looking for
openings for his newly unemployed clients.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pray, a spokesman for the WNBA, insists that the rival
league is not celebrating the demise of the ABL. ``We always
thought it was better when there were two leagues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pray did not offer any hope that the WNBA might add a franchise
in Hartford, which was one of the ABL's most profitable markets.
``Our long-term goal is to have a team in each NBA city,'' he said.
The 10-team league will expand to Minnesota and Orlando, Fla., next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt and Levy both suggested that one way to retain the
Hartford fan base would be to have the WNBA start a Boston
franchise and co-opt some of its games to Hartford, the way the
Celtics used to.
</P>
<P>
   Which would make sense to Pam Batalis, former general manager of
the Blizzard who was promoted to vice president of sales for the
ABL. ``We are living proof that New England, and especially
Connecticut, is an extremely viable women's sports market,'' she
said. ``I think it would be foolish to not realize that business
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The motto of the WNBA has been ``We Got Game.'' Now they really
do.
</P>
<P>
   (Barbara Huebner of the Globe staff contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
