<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YEARS LATER, HARE TAKES LEAD OVER TORTOISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY AND STEVEN SYRE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack vs. Ed. Ed vs. Jack.
</P>
<P>
   It has been an enduring, friendly rivalry in the little world of
Boston advertising for three decades. Then within a month of each
other, the two big kahunas of Boston advertising, Ed Eskandarian
and Jack Connors, sold their agencies to big national players.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Connors sold his Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos,
Boston's second largest agency, to the world's largest advertising
company, Interpublic Group for $115 million. One month later,
Eskandarian followed by selling the city's biggest ad agency,
Arnold Communications, to Snyder Communications for $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   This is a town that keeps score, and the end of the year is a
time for toting up the results.
</P>
<P>
   Who's ahead? Jack Connors, by a gaudy $47 million.
</P>
<P>
   That, in short, is the difference between what Connor's own
stock in Interpublic has gained _ $30 million _ and what
Eskandarian's has lost _ $17 million _ since both Boston ad
agencies completed their deals with their big publicly held
partners.
</P>
<P>
   While both Arnold and Hill Holliday have had banner years adding
clients, the partners they picked have fared far differently in the
stock market this year. Interpublic's stock is up 40 percent since
the acquisition of Hill Holliday was announced Feb. 24; Snyder's
stock is down 29 percent since the Arnold deal was done March 25.
</P>
<P>
   The market, of course, can turn for either Interpublic or
Snyder, and certainly money is only one measure of any deal. But as
Skip Pile, president of Pile &AMP; Co., a Boston marketing consulting
firm, notes, money ``is one of the major scorecards in life.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a mistake to think these guys do not care who's on
top. Years ago The Boston Globe ran a story about the tortoise _
Eskandarian _ gaining on the hare _ Connors. The story featured
Eskandarian's face imposed over the picture of a turtle and Connors
in a bunny suit. Eskandarian went all over town passing out
porcelain turtles; Connors, to put it mildly, was not amused.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tables are again reversed.
</P>
<P>
   Says Connors: ``While both companies are going very well, their
success is now measured by the success of the companies that own
them. One is hot as a pistol, one is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskandarian did not return our calls Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Arnold and Hill Holliday have long been the class of
Boston's ad community. Eskandarian built his agency on a series of
acquisitions, and has a client list that includes Volkswagen of
America and franchisees for McDonald's Corp. Connors has eschewed
the acquisition route, and instead grown internally with clients
like Fidelity Investments, PriceWaterhouseCoopers and John Hancock.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing to sell out to Interpublic, Connors opted for a
company that had first approached him 15 years ago. Today New
York-based Interpublic is a giant of the industry with a market
value of $10.5 billion, and the roster of agencies that include
such heavyweights as McCann-Erickson Worldwide, and Ammirati Puris
Lintas and Lowe Group.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder, with a market value of $2.2 billion, is a spunky comer
that broke into the business a decade ago by handing out samples of
cereal and Advil. The Bethesda, Md.-company has grown rapidly by
helping drug giants market to doctors and patients in hospitals,
and by handing out free product samples for companies like Procter
&AMP; Gamble and Johnson &AMP; Johnson. Only recently has it started buying
up more traditional ad agencies like Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interpublic is almost in a different league than Snyder,''
says AdWeek's Judy Warner. ``It is a league Snyder very much wants
to be a part of.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder's stock has slipped as it has moved beyond its direct
marketing niche in the hospitals and begun looking more like
everyone else in the ad industry, albeit smaller. Pile, the
advertising consultant, thinks industry analysts still don't
understand the Snyder business model and that has hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody understands who Daniel Snyder is,'' says Pile. ``It all
feels like a hot market, highly leveraged play.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all six analysts who follow the company rate it a buy.
William Warmington, who covers Snyder for Robinson-Humphrey, thinks
the stock could double in six to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Eskandarian shopped his company to many potential buyers before
settling on Snyder. Among them: Omnicom Group, Interpublic's
archrival, but the two sides are said not to have been able to
agree on a price. Omnicom's stock is up 25 percent since the
Snyder-Arnold deal closed.
</P>
<P>
   One of Eskandarian's handicaps was that he had grown too large
and had too many accounts that might have overlapped with an
acquirer. Clients in the auto and fast-food business are
particularly sensitive of conflicts, and two of his biggest clients
were Volkswagen and McDonalds.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Eskandarian found a partner where that wasn't a
problem. ``Ed got full valuation because there were no conflicts
and he didn't have to resign any business,'' says Pile.
</P>
<P>
   He does, however, have to live with Snyder's stock price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Steve Bailey and Steven Syre can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
