<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5649 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 1370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TOE IN WATER, KERRY EYES PLUNGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Kerry has gone to the mountain in search of revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Ensconced at his wife's vacation home in Sun Valley, Idaho,
Kerry is mulling whether to undertake his most difficult challenge
since . . . well, since the days of his Vietnam War heroism, when
as a young Naval officer with glory in his gaze and ice-water in
his veins, he fearlessly piloted a swift boat through the
enemy-infested fingers of the Mekong Delta _ filming himself all
the while.
</P>
<P>
   That challenge? Whether to run for president. When he returns
east, Kerry expects to have crossed a fundamental threshold. It
will come after some serious family councils and telephone
consultations with as many as 200 fund-raisers, activists, and
party leaders from around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to have a pretty good sense in my mind whether I
think this is the time and whether I am prepared to do what is
necessary to really put my feet it in,'' Kerry said in a telephone
interview from Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he'll open an exploratory committee and begin the kind of
organizing and travel necessary to launch a national run.
</P>
<P>
   But deciding whether to hit the campaign trail in earnest and
actually achieving credibility as a candidate could prove to be two
very different things. And in some ways, Kerry's idealism could
make things harder: His public comments that he won't dip into his
wife Teresa's $800 million fortune to finance a campaign eliminates
an asset that could otherwise establish him as the most serious
challenger to Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably personally rule it out,'' he said. ``I don't think
that's the way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry still carries a $500,000 debt from his bruising 1996
re-election fight against Bill Weld, an obligation he could cancel
with one check from his wife. Instead, he has chipped away at that
debt _ which once totaled $2.5 million _ with concerted
fund-raising in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say expediency couldn't win out; after all, in
1996, Kerry broke his nationally acclaimed
campaign-spending-limitation pact with Weld and borrowed against
the fortune to bail out his cash-starved campaign in the crucial
final month.
</P>
<P>
   Another major problem for the 55-year-old senator is his failure
to secure his political base in Massachusetts, which has allowed
Gore to make serious inroads here. Belatedly realizing the
potential public-relations disaster that could create for his
candidacy, Kerry has launched a rear-guard action in the past few
days to try to shore up that base.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be too late. Gore, aided by ace operative Michael
Whouley (who, adding insult to injury, is a former Kerry aide),
could score a coup by winning the bulk of support from those
political figures who know Kerry best. Knowledgeable sources say
that half or more of the state's congressional delegation may well
end up with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   For example, sources say Richard Neal, Martin Meehan, John
Tierney, and Joseph Moakley all have stronger ties to Gore than to
Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   No one is declaring presidential allegiances yet. Still, the
hints are there. Neal, who labored mightily for Kerry's re-election
in 1996, put it tactfully: ``There is not a lot of evidence that a
sitting vice president who desires the nomination of his party can
be thwarted.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Moakley gave Kerry some blunt advice: It will take a
concerted effort to win his own delegation. ``He can't just sit
back and get them by osmosis,'' Moakley said. ``He is going to have
to work at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Meehan: ``He'd better hurry. Gore's quickly wrapping this
thing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that dynamic a studiously uncommitted Ted Kennedy and a
Tom Menino who leans toward Gore, and you see just how difficult
things will be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even though Kerry concedes Gore has a head start, and
that former New Jersey Senator Bill Bradley (who formed an
exploratory committee earlier this month) takes takes up some space
he'd like for himself, he says his early soundings indicate there's
room for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the reality check comes when you actually get on the phone
and ask people, `Would you be there for me and would you be
prepared to raise X amount of dollars?' '' Kerry said. ``That is a
different task from the initial task of surveying the political
landscape and making a judgment about whether or not you would like
to do the thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Translate X into at least $250,000 a week through 1999, and you
have an idea of just how daunting the challenge is. But knowing he
can raise the cash, Kerry said, is the threshold he'll have to pass
before he decides to join the Democratic presidential campaign.
Recent history has shown that without adequate funding, even a
candidate with a toehold in New Hampshire stands little chance
against a frontrunner like Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul Tsongas came out of New Hampshire (in 1992) and didn't
have a dime and didn't have a strategy,'' Kerry said. ``Gary Hart
came out of New Hampshire (in 1984) and didn't have any money. He
had Walter Mondale off-balance, and if he had had some money, it
might have been a different result.'' Instead, in both cases, the
better-funded candidates _ Bill Clinton in 1992, Mondale in 1984 _
battled back from New Hampshire losses to overtake the victors and
ultimately win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   If political considerations count heavily, so will his family's
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he'll be sitting down with his wife, Teresa Heinz;
her three sons, John, 30, Andre 27, and Christopher, 25; and his
daughters, Alexandra, 24, and Vanessa, who is about to turn 22. No
one quite has a veto; but individual objections will weigh
strongly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry admitted that at his back he's starting to hear Gore's
campaign chariot hurrying near _ and conceded that he may be behind
even in wooing the Massachusetts congressmen he serves with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I behind? The answer is yes,'' he said. ``I am behind where
I would like to be, and where some people say I ought to be, but I
am finding that notwithstanding that, the response has been quite
positive. Now I have to touch base directly to find out what the
realities are.''
</P>
<P>
   One man he hasn't touched based with yet could tell him: former
governor Michael S. Dukakis, the party's 1998 nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's chances?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a long shot,'' Dukakis said. ``But it was a long shot
for me, and given the general atmosphere, there is no way of
knowing.''
</P>
<P>
   So what would he tell Kerry if he called?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the toughest thing you will ever embark on,'' Dukakis
said. ``And I think it is far more punishing now than it was 10
years ago because of all the mishegas in Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   By that, Dukakis means the no-holds-barred politics and
no-limits reporting that increasingly means a candidate's every
indiscretion ends up in the news. Kerry, however, professed not to
be bothered by that _ not after his 1996 re-election campaign,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say you guys did a pretty extensive effort of
vetting,'' he said of the scrutiny he has already endured. It was a
Globe profile of Kerry during that campaign that detailed how he
had carried around a Super 8mm camera in Vietnam to film his
exploits.
</P>
<P>
   So how does it all shift out? Several people who have talked
with the state's junior senator say he really wants to run. The
anxious ambition of middle age and the opportunities of an open
election have collided to make it seem particularly pressing for
Kerry, they say.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, those who haved studied history and thus know
how hard it is to deny a sitting vice president his party's
nomination _ the last time it happened was 1952, when Vice
President Alben Barkley lost the Democratic nod to Adlai Stevenson
_ think Kerry will ultimately decide that 2000 is not his year.
</P>
<P>
   So what would Kerry tell a bettor?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tell them to hold their powder,'' he said, mixing his
metaphors. ``I wouldn't advise anybody to bet, period. It is
against the law, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Lehigh and Frank Phillips cover political news for The
Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
