<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS &LR;      12-24 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-PROJECT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NIGHT THE TREE FELL, AND OTHER HOLIDAY DELIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By P. CLEMENT HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tumult and fury is over, or at least the end is in sight.
The tree is trimmed and all aglow. Now it's a matter of thinking
peace and happiness, basking in the fireplace's glow and in the
love that Christmas brings.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, reading aloud Clement Moore's ``A Visit From St.
Nicholas,'' which the Globe thoughtfully runs every Christmas Eve,
and under its correct title, too, not that Johnny-Come-Lately ``The
Night Before Chrismtas.''
</P>
<P>
   It is in honor of Clement Moore that I call myself P. Clement,
which is my middle name.
</P>
<P>
   But why is it that disasters occur only at holiday time? There
is always that possiblity lurking in our minds, as illogical as
that may seem.
</P>
<P>
   Disasters do occur, and often at other holidays than Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   One of my Christmas disasters is worth telling, another is best
unsaid. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The night the tree fell &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first one was the night the tree fell, more than half a
century ago, when I was a tad and responsible for lighting the tree
while big sis and bro had the fun part of putting on all the
baubles.
</P>
<P>
   That is when the cat _ his name was Mephistopheles, named by my
rather romantic mother _ nearly ruined everything, includng
himself.
</P>
<P>
   The devil must have made him do it, because the cat, batting
some of the baubles hanging down, caught a front paw foot between a
wire and the tree. He let out a squawk heard 'round the world and
took off, pulling the tree on top of him with a whoosh! &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Chrismtas miracle, too &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It must have been a Christmas miracle. The cat survived, paw and
ego bruised, and so did the tree.
</P>
<P>
   We lost surprisingly few of those fragile baubles, but three of
them, heavy glass balls that my grandmother brought from Germany,
survived their fall and went back on the reset tree, minus a few
baubles and 10,000 needles. I found out years later that they are
called kugels.
</P>
<P>
   We can laugh about it now, but it was no laughing matter then. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mortar, mortar everywhere &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Christmas disaster was more recent, maybe 20 years ago,
in my own house. And it was disaster only to the Handyman's wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who in the world would bring a wheelbarrow full of mortar into
the living room in front of the fireplace _ on Chrismas Eve?'' she
asked, her eyes smoking over, something to be feared.
</P>
<P>
   Who else but the handyman, who figured the remortaring of the
hearth had to be done in time for Christmas. It was, and the
wheelbarrow disappeared before midnight, but that didn't make it
less of a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, when everything was done, everything was forgiven. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fire! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They say that any house 50 years old or older has had at least
one fire.
</P>
<P>
   The great Mother's Day fire was the first for our ancestral
house, and, I hope, the last.
</P>
<P>
   It was a disaster, all right, not at Christmas but on a double
holiday, Mother's Day, May 12, 1946, and Pop's 57th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Pop liked to burn cordwood in the old coal boiler, and would put
the wood on top of the boiler to dry it out before burning. The
cordwood was green as grass, and took a lot of drying out.
</P>
<P>
   Why in the world would you have the boiler going on May 12? If
you ever lived in Northern Michigan (the great Upper Peninsula),
you wouldn't have to ask the question. That's ``home,'' where there
never has been a green Christmas, and often has been a white
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the fire started Saturday night, but didn't end until
the holiday. Saturday night it was; I was in the tub, and the folks
had gone to bed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Smoke, but no fireplace &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then I smelled smoke; it was not very strong and was actually
pleasant, like the faint aroma of wood smoke from a fireplace.
Except we didn't have a fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   I heard Pop go downstairs, coughing all the way, and realized
this was more than smoldering wood. I leaped from the tub, not
bothering to drain it (that is significant to the story and
probably saved Mom's life), grabbed a robe, and trotted to the
basement, where I found Pop with a bowl of water, flicking it onto
the blazing wood on top of the boiler.
</P>
<P>
   And, man, it was blazing; the ceiling already had caught fire,
and flames were spreading further along the ceiling and up the
interior walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really efficient, Pop,'' I said in my 18-year-old
wisdom, ready to grab a garden hose and put the fire out.
</P>
<P>
   But we were interrupted by a shriek from Mom, who had seen smoke
coming from virtually every room in the house, thicker and thicker.
She managed to get down the stairs in her nightgown and call the
fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Then, realizing that she was somewhat unclothed, actually went
back upstairs to get a robe in which she could greet the firemen
with dignity.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the firemen, led by Chief Trombley, arrived with
their hoses and axes and went to work. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The lifesaver &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was then that Mom realized she couldn't make it to get her
robe, and staggered to the bathroom, where she dipped a washcloth
into my bath water, and staggered down the stairs, the life-saving
wet cloth clamped over mouth and nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone help that woman,'' Trombley shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's no woman,'' I yelled back, ``that's my mother!'' I
think I really said that, but perhaps 52 years dims the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Another propitious happening, other than the bath water, was the
fact that I never had a chance to hose down the fire; if I had
hosed up the burning wall cavity, the old knob and tube wiring
could have electrocuted us all.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. We kids referred to Chief Trombley as ``Front
Door Trombley'' because that is all we thought was left after he
handled a fire.
</P>
<P>
   With the house scorched but intact and the fire out, I didn't
call him that any more.
</P>
<P>
   The house smelled for months, but eventually the odor went away,
and Mom had a chance to remodel. She also had an oil burner
installed, and Pop didn't have to dry out any more wood. I think he
missed burning wood in the old coal burner.
</P>
<P>
   And, for many years, Mom remarked about getting $100 insurance
for the big oak sliding doors between living and dining room, which
were burned beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
   That other Christmas disaster? It's too embarrassing to retell
now. I could let my big bro tell it, but that wouldn't work because
he laughs so much that he just can't get the words out.
</P>
<P>
   But these words are out, from Clement Moore: ``Merry Christmas
to all and to all a good nght!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
