<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRON REGISTERS SPRUCE UP HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have an old house with forced hot air heat and some ugly
vent covers and grilles. I have to find some metal grilles more
appropriate for the house. I have in mind the rather elaborately
decorated and scrolled cast iron covers, but I don't know where to
look. Do you?
</P>
<P>
   J.S., Dover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Search no further; you have come to the right place, or the
right person, for the handyman has replaced all his ugly vent
covers and grilles with Reggio Registers. He even asked for, and
received some, as Christmas presents some years back. They are
heavy-duty cast iron grilles, handsome, elegant, and appropriate
for old and new houses. They come in many sizes and shapes, varied
enough to fit your needs. They also are expensive, but what isn't
these days? You can also get aluminum grilles that can be painted,
solid brass, and a limited number of styles in wood. Call the
Reggio Register Co. of Ayer (the founder and president of the firm
is named Reggio, which is appropriate for a register company). Call
978-772-3493.
</P>
<P>
   There are other uses for the grilles and vent covers. The
handyman has used them for basement vents. They add a certain
elegance to an otherwise plain (1768) colonial, even though they
are not colonial in design or style.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have two rooms on the second floor of an old Cape-style
house. There are no dormers, and the rooms have two low knee walls
front and back. I checked the crawl spaces behind those knee walls,
and found that the nail points coming through the roof are raining
water. I know I have to ventilate, but how? I have no roof
overhang, so there is no soffit to put vents into.
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL MOORE, Orange, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. There are two ways to ventilate that space behind the knee
walls. One is to install large, square, louvered vents in the gable
wall at each end of the crawl space. The gable wall is a triangular
shape formed by the roofline at each end of the house. The vents
would go at the bottom right and left of that triangle. Look around
your neighborhood or anywhere in Massachusetts and you will see a
few of these vents or windows in old Cape-style houses.
</P>
<P>
   The second way is to install eave vents. Cut a slot at the top
of the fascia board, just under the drip edge. The eave vent is a
special type of drip edge that fits over the existing drip edge of
the roof, allowing air to enter the space and eliminate the rain
from the nail points.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I get the musty, rather dank odor out of my garbage
disposal?
</P>
<P>
   LARRY O'CONNOR, Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Grind through pieces of lemon, orange, lime, or grapefruit,
including rind. Sprinkle baking soda into dispsal once a day.
</P>
<P>
   For further treatment, remove rubber baffle, and with a paper
towel dampened with bleach, reach under rim and remove scum. Wear
skin and eye protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a treatment, for maintenance: Once a week, put two trays
of ice cubes and half a cup of washing soda in disposal and let 'er
rip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I installed a bluestone stoop last June, over an old brick
stoop. Now, I see black on the bluestone. I tried scrubbing it off,
but it didn't work. I understand bleach will handle mildew, if that
is what it is, but won't that lighten the bluestone? I'd like to
keep the blue color.
</P>
<P>
   BOB MAZZA, Burlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Bleach may lighten the stone, but it can't be helped;
besides, the bluestone will darken with age fairly quickly, and any
light part will blend in in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Mix one part liquid bleach and three parts water and paint this
on the black; it should lighten up within five seconds. If it
doesn't, it is not mildew, so scrub the stone with detergent and
water with a cup of bleach added to the wash water. Wear skin and
eye protection when working with bleach.
</P>
<P>
   To make the stone a little more resistant to mildew, apply one
thin coat of a masonry sealer. This will not change the color of
the bluestone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have some handsome wood-hued cherry kitchen cabinets, with
raised panels. I plan to paint them, sanding and washing first,
then using an oil primer and finally an oil enamel. How can I
prevent the raised panels from shrinking so much that an unpainted
line shows beteween panel and frame?
</P>
<P>
   CLINT CABAN, Medfield, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You can't, really. The panels are floating in their frames,
and expand when they gain moisture, and contract when they lose it.
In winter, usually, they lose moisture and shrink, and open the
seams. If you tried gluing the panels, they are likely to explode
with a sharp report as they shrink next spring.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize the showing of this unpainted strip, do all painting
in the dead of winter, or at least during the heating season, when
the wood is at its smallest. A disadvantage to this is that the
paint bead on the joints will crack as the wood dries out, making
the joint ragged, and uglier than it is now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
