<HEADLINE>
_AGING AND BIRTHS OF THE BRITISH ELITE   
 _DYSPEPSIA CAUSE: BACTERIA AT ISSUE   
 _CHEMICALS' EFFECT ON HORMONES SEEN  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
 Aging and births of the British elite
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Women who delay having children, and who have fewer of them over
a lifetime, are more likely to live into their 80s and 90s, at
least according to a scientific review of 1,200 years of
genealogical records kept by the British aristocracy.
</P>
<P>
   The study, in the current issue of the journal Nature, supports
an evolutionary theory that has been observed in fruit flies: that
the energy that goes into having offspring early and often may take
away from an organism's ability to maintain and repair its own
cells.
</P>
<P>
   British and Dutch researchers who specialize in the evolutionary
theory of aging analyzed data for more than 13,000 aristocratic
women born through 1875, looking at such factors as age of first
childbirth and number of children.
</P>
<P>
   Women who lived into their 90s had their first child at the
average age of 27, while women who lived into their 60s had their
firstborn at the average age of 23.8. The women who lived to their
90s had an average of 1.8 children, while those who lived only into
their 60s had an average of 2.36 children.
</P>
<P>
   Of the women who lived into their 80s and 90s, nearly half of
them had no children, while less than a third of women who lived
into their 50s and 60s were childless.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, who statistically took into account such
potentially confusing factors as women dying during childbirth,
also looked at aristocratic men and found similar results: The men
lived longer when they had fewer children and at a later age.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying commentary, a University of Georgia
geneticist welcomed the study, but cautioned that it does not prove
cause and effect or that evolutionary genetics is the only
explanation. The geneticist, Daniel E.L. Promislow, cited other
studies showing that women who have no children have a greater risk
of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, many factors influence lifespan, and readers can rest
assured that having more children will not necessarily send you to
an early grave. After all, Queen Victoria gave birth to nine
offspring . . . and lived to be 81 years old,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dyspepsia cause: Bacteria at issue
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does the bacteria known to cause ulcers also lead to bloating,
belching, nausea, and other symptoms of chronic indigestion, or
dyspepsia?
</P>
<P>
   Two studies in the current issue of the New England Journal of
Medicine come to opposite conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Scottish researchers found that patients who took an antacid
along with antibiotics known to kill the H. pylori bacteria saw
their symptoms disappear at three times the rate of those who took
only the antacid.
</P>
<P>
   But a study by researchers from Switzerland and elsewhere found
no difference in the rate of relief between patients who took the
antacid with antibiotics, or the antacid alone.
</P>
<P>
   In an accompanying editorial, Dr. Lawrence S. Friedman of
Massachusetts General Hospital writes that the contradictory
conclusions may be explained by the studies' different definitions
of indigestion that is unrelated to ulcers. For instance, only one
study included patients with heartburn.
</P>
<P>
   But he points out that in both studies, the majority of patients
got no relief, whether they took antibiotics along with antacid or
not. Friedman says that suggests that other causes and treatments
for chronic indigestion need to be explored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chemicals' effect on hormones seen
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In another piece of evidence suggesting man-made chemicals may
damage human reproductive health, a study of men working at a
Chinese pesticide factory found they had abnormal levels of sex
hormone and decreased sperm counts.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers, led by physicians at the Harvard School of
Public Health, report their findings in this month's issue of the
Journal of Occupational and Environmental Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing 34 male pesticide factory workers to 44 male
textile factory workers, who presumably were not exposed to the
agricultural chemicals, the researchers found that those exposed to
pesticides had slightly, but significantly, higher levels of what
are usually considered ``female'' sex hormones.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that the higher the female hormonal levels
in the pesticide workers, the lower their sperm counts.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have also suggested that pesticides and other
manmade chemicals may decrease sperm counts and otherwise affect
human reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the US Environmental Protection Agency announced
plans to screen pesticides and other materials for substances that
may pose as hormones and disrupt reproductive health.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5669 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV27-B     12-24 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING BLETCHLEY ITS HISTORICAL DUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe Eachus, 87, divides his time now between Cambridge, Mass.
and Florida, but 56 years ago, as a young American Naval officer,
he found himself ordered for two weeks to a ramshackle British
country house 40 miles from London.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1942. The Japanese had just bombed Pearl Harbor. And
young Joe Eachus, who'd been educated from kindergarten through
college at Miami University of Ohio, and had advance degrees from
Syracuse and Illinois, had studied the arcane art of cryptography.
With one other Naval officer, Eachus was part of the first 11-man
US contingent admitted to the super-secret confines of Bletchley
Park, home to the British code-breakers who cracked Hitler's fabled
Enigma machine.
</P>
<P>
   By reading the coded German radio traffic, using material
snatched for the British by Polish forces, the Allies were able to
survive the Nazi onslaught that rolled over Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The contributions people at Bletchley made to shortening the
war were immense,'' said Eachus in an interview last week. He had
to overcome British reserve and suspicion that the Yanks had
nothing to contribute. Several times Eachus and his fellow Navy man
were suspected of being Germans _ ``the American naval uniform and
the German were virtually identical, except for the insignia.''
</P>
<P>
   After his two-week stint, he was ordered back for three months,
and then for three years. What made his work easier was
encountering a young British Foreign Office staffer, Barbara
Abernethy, who has now been his wife for half a century. As a girl
she'd studied European languages in a Belgian convent school. Her
mom knew someone in the government, and in 1937, she was among the
very first contingent of British spy-types sent to Bletchley to
organize a secure code-breaking establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrible old country house, but we loved it,'' said
Barbara Eachus, who was British vice consul-general in Boston
before retirement. ``I opened the place in '37 and closed the gates
in '47, when I turned the key and off we went.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Joe became a civilian employee of the Defense
Dept., specializing in, as he puts it delicately, ``other people's
communications.'' One of the early computer pioneers _ he knew Alan
Turing, the great computer genius of Bletchley _ Eachus did later
stints in high-tech industries, including Honeywell, where he
designed computers for newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara invited Joe for coffee one day, and the young American
was introduced to an engaging collection of very smart, very
secretive British eccentrics, who deciphered thousands of German
radio transmissions in time to enable the Allied forces to counter
Hitler's moves. ``You knew everybody at Bletchley,'' said Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   The talented folk doing the high-stress work of codebreaking are
described in William Stevenson's classic book on espionage, ``A Man
Called Intrepid'' as ``a priesthood of . . . scholars, solvers of
crossword puzzles, mathematicians, linguists and classical dons . .
.'' Joe Eachus fit right in. His job was to sniff out which among
the pile of German secrets might be useful to the US Navy, and send
it back, by coded radio transmission, overnight mail to Washington.
Two of his most important tools? The 25-pound cans of coffee and
sugar which he drew from the Navy supply depot.
</P>
<P>
   In wartime England, coffee and sugar were rationed, and
codebreakers craved their caffeine-sugar connection. ``So I just
set up my coffee pot outside my office, with the sugar, and pretty
soon all kinds of people working on all kinds of interesting stuff
came by,'' shrugged Joe. When he got something hot, he'd hightail
it to London and the US Embassy, where ``I was the only one other
than the ambassador who could use the encrypted radio link.''
</P>
<P>
   At the war's height, more than 1,000 people worked at Bletchley,
whose grounds had been deeded away by William the Conqueror nearly
900 years earlier. The secrets gleaned from breaking Germany's
Enigma codes came to be known as ``Ultra.''
</P>
<P>
   The intercepted communications gave the Allies a crucial
advantage. ``Ultra took the blindfold off our eyes so that we could
see the enemy in detail in a way in which he could not see us,''
wrote Peter Calvocoressi, a Bletchley veteran, in his book ``Top
Secret Ultra.'' The trove was invaluable: ``knowing day by day
where enemy units were; how strong they were; what their supplies
of arms, ammunition and fuel were; and, when occasion arose, where
they were being told to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The breaking of the Enigma machine cyphers helped end the Nazi
wolfpack menance in the Atlantic, and gave Britain's outnumbered
fighter pilots crucial head-starts on intercepting large-scale Nazi
bombing raids. Churchill was able to take the substantial risk of
dispatching tanks by sea to reinforce Allied troops in Africa even
while Hitler was threatening to invade Britain with Operation
Sealion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Churchill's boldness in sending tanks to the Middle East while
the British Isles were still under seige may be likened to the
action of the Senate of Rome when it dispatched an army to Spain
while Hannibal was still at the gates of the city . . . a lesser
man would have quailed,'' wrote Calvocoressi. But the ace up the
Churchillian sleeve was ``a hidden assurance which he owed to
Ultra.'' The Bletchley codebreakers had ascertained that Hitler had
decided it was too risky to attempt invading Britain with his
Operation Sealion.
</P>
<P>
   There was a bit of doggerell titled ``Bumph Palace'' which
memorialized Bletchley types with this ode to bumph, slang for
interminable bureaucratic paperwork:
</P>
<P>
   `` . . . the Air Force types that never fly / Soldiers who
neither do nor die / Landlubber Navy, beards complete / Civilians
slim, long-haired, effete / Yet what they did they never knew / And
if they told it wasn't true / If I should die think only this of me
/ I served my country at BP ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Both Eachuses figure in a new book about Bletchley, ``Station
X,'' which is also the basis for a four-hour television documentary
to be broadcast in Britian in January, and will probably be shown
here later. A fund-raising effort to restore Bletchley as a
memorial to the secret work that helped win the war is under way.
The address: Bletchley Park Trust, Wilton Ave., Milton Keynes, UK,
MK3 6EF.
</P>
<P>
   (David Nyhand is a columniw with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
