<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC LOSES TO MARTHA IN SANTA BUYOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is with mixed feelings that Santa announces he will soon
become a wholly owned subsidiary of Martha Stewart Living.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Santa's accountants conducted an audit of his
operation. The figures were not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Santa was aware he had problems. Outmoded workshop technology.
Antiquated delivery system. Never-ending labor negotiations with
his so-called ``helpers.'' Protests by animal rights activists.
Federal Aviation Administration citations for failing to meet
flying sleigh safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Santa's entrepreneurial ventures have not been going
well. Santa's steamy semi-autobiographical novel ``Fly By Night''
never hit the bestseller lists, despite relentless plugging by Don
Imus. Sales of Santa's signature fragrance, ``Claus,'' are way
down. And as for G.L.B., Great Looking Beard, his amazing spray-on
beard-in-a-can, well, Santa has been forced to admit that it is an
idea whose time has yet to come. He couldn't move the stuff, even
on QVC.
</P>
<P>
   Santa's accountants told him he needs bigger profit margins.
This sort of talk rankles Santa. He has always believed his job is
about giving, not getting. His accountants told him that he is
totally out of touch with reality, which was no news to Santa. They
suggested he declare bankruptcy. He refused. He told them that
bankruptcy would be an unthinkable step for a larger-than-life
figure who serves as a role model for millions of boys and girls.
</P>
<P>
   Then Martha stepped in. Martha made Santa an offer he couldn't
refuse. Perhaps Santa should rephrase that, because he doesn't want
to convey the impression that Martha held a glue gun to his head
and forced him to sign. On the contrary. It was all very civilized.
Martha merely said that she planned to acquire Santa's operation.
It would be a friendly takeover, she said, if he cooperated.
Otherwise, she was prepared to play hardball.
</P>
<P>
   Martha has big plans for Santa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas every day.'' Martha told Santa to keep repeating
that phrase. It's the Santa mantra, she said, the unifying concept
behind all their new ventures, the key to maximizing profits year
round. First she'll trademark Santa's name and image. Then she'll
move Santa's base of operations from the North Pole to Orlando. By
this time next year Santa will have a catalog, a Web site, a
magazine, a television show, a theme park, a chain of restaurants,
a string of factories in Mexico. And that's just for starters.
</P>
<P>
   Martha confessed she was appalled by Santa's outmoded means of
production and delivery. She was amazed that he had managed, year
after year, to provide toys for millions of girls and boys all over
the world. How did he do it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Magic,'' Santa told her.
</P>
<P>
   Martha said that no one, even Santa, can rely on magic anymore
to get the job done in the new global economy. ``Marketing is the
only magic,'' Martha said.
</P>
<P>
   Santa worries about all the boys and girls on his list. Who will
leave them presents if Santa doesn't deliver? Martha assured him
they''ll be just fine, that their parents can order as many gifts
as they like from www.santastewart.com, as long as their credit
cards aren't overextended.
</P>
<P>
   Martha says Santa should strive to be a purely secular icon, in
order to sell the Santa concept to boys and girls of every faith
and nationality. Santa told Martha he thought this idea smacked of
cultural imperialism. Martha said he was being silly, that he
should think of it as reaching out, making Santa more inclusive,
more accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Santa knows the Martha connection is the only way for him to
survive. And yet he finds himself lying awake in the middle of the
night, worrying. What has Santa done?
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is a columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
