<SLUG> BC-KWANZAA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME FEAR SECULAR KWANZAA IS BECOMING A `BLACK CHRISTMAS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Donald Dugan remembers that when he was growing
up, Kwanzaa festivities were intimate events in people's homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody that celebrated used to fit in a house,'' said
Dugan, 41, an insurance agent in Oakland, Calif. ``Now they don't
fit in a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only has Kwanzaa surged in popularity among
African-Americans in the last several years, it has shed its
radical black image. Now firmly a part of mainstream culture, it is
taught in schools, observed by churches and marketed by corporate
America.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa, which grew out of the black power movement in the
1960s, is a secular holiday that celebrates family, community and
the struggles of people of African descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone from just being a novelty to something that makes
sense, something that brings the community together,'' said Kola
Thomas, director of the Center for African and African-American
Arts and Culture in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Henry, professor of black studies at the University of
California at Berkeley, put it in more political terms. ``Up until
1990, it was certainly something that was associated with black
nationalism,'' he said. ``Now it's been mainstreamed. It's
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   With wider acceptance has come commercialization.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go buy a Kwanzaa set at Kmart,'' Blanche Richardson,
manager of Marcus Books in Oakland, said disapprovingly. ``You can
go to Safeway and buy a Kwanzaa card.''
</P>
<P>
   Such developments distort the meaning of Kwanzaa, which was
developed partly as an alternative to the consumerism of Christmas,
its longtime supporters say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear that a number of major corporations have started to
take notice and try to profit from Kwanzaa,'' said Oba T'Shaka, a
professor of black studies at San Francisco State University.
``That's not good. With money comes corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa was started in 1966 by Maulana Karenga, now a professor
of black studies at California State University at Long Beach.
Synthesized from African agricultural celebrations and principles,
it begins Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``Kwanzaa'' comes from Swahili for ``first fruits.''
Each day is marked by focusing on one of the seven principles of
Kwanzaa: unity, self-determination, collective work and
responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose, creativity and
faith.
</P>
<P>
   Gift-giving is optional and usually reserved for children, said
Fette Brown of the Bay Area Kwanzaa Committee, which has been
setting up events for more than 15 years. If exchanged, items
should be handmade or purchased from a black-owned business and be
of educational or cultural value.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to Hallmark and getting a card, you're not
celebrating Kwanzaa _ you're doing something else,'' Richardson
said.
</P>
<P>
   One thing Kwanzaa is not, its participants say, is Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will say it's like black Christmas, dreaming of a black
Christmas,'' Dugan said.
</P>
<P>
   Explained Brown: ``The reason it's not a Christmas substitute is
because Dr. Karenga recognized the undue hardship the
over-commercialization of Christmas has had for people at the
lowest rungs of the economic ladder.''
</P>
<P>
   But with wider acceptance also has come increased popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Kwanzaa has grown not only in the United States but throughout
the world. It is celebrated by blacks in Europe, the Caribbean,
Asia and Latin America, said Chimbuko Tembo, a vice chair of Us,
the Los Angeles-based organization that founded Kwanzaa and is
headed by Karenga.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson said some people started to observe it because
mainstream society legitimized it for them. ``They don't emphasize
the principles, don't talk about the spiritual aspect,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
