<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELTNER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES ARE MADE OF RITUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WELTNER COLUMN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Christmas Eve, my mother used to build a fireplace with large
red cardboard blocks. It never occurred to me to wonder how Santa
got through the solid wall, unlike my friend Chris, who brooded
about Santa coming down his chimney straight into the oil burner.
``He comes in the door,'' his mom reassured him. ``What do you
think, he's stupid?'' an answer, he explains, which made as much
sense as anything else. Chris's family always hung up nylon
stockings and on Christmas morning he came down to lumpy brown
sausages, 5 feet long.
</P>
<P>
   I've been talking to friends about their memories of Christmas
Eve, trying to discover what sticks in the mind. I found that folks
most fondly recall those yearly traditions that contrast with
run-of-the-mill Christmas routines. Not one person mentioned
specific gifts. Most of the stuff in the boxes, it turns out,
disappears into a forgotten file in the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike home-grown, family-invented ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Rob's mother stacked presents behind an ironing board draped
with a sheet. Armed with a bamboo fishing pole, each kid would
``fish'' for his present, hauling in the one Mom tied to the line,
a practice Rob still follows. Holly, who was named for her birth on
Christmas Eve, remembers having her own very satisfying Birthday
Tree, decorated with non-Christmas ornaments. It sat happily beside
the family's larger tree, sheltering the birthday presents Holly
was allowed to open that night.
</P>
<P>
   For many, an abundance of love was symbolized by buffet tables
groaning under ethnic specialties, from exotic Caribbean or German
delicacies to semirepulsive oyster stew. An Italian friend
remembers the Christmas Eve dinner her family called the Feast of
Seven Fishes. Rosalie couldn't tell one fish from another, but
she's never forgotten the eels her aunt kept alive and fresh in her
bathtub or the calamari (squid to non-Italians), tentacles peeking
out of the spaghetti. Emily recalls the magic of eating dinner in
the wee hours after midnight Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Eating together is inseparable from being together, and for many
children, Christmas Eve was the time siblings and cousins could
avoid the supervision of adults. For Magnolia, the informal crush
of adults around a table heaped high with food gave kids the
freedom to run up and down stairs, raising a ruckus that was only
noticed intermittently. Few of my friends noticed whether relatives
were squabbling or bristling at one another. A crowd was excitement
enough.
</P>
<P>
   For some of my friends, it's the sounds of the holiday that
linger. Jeb recalls the Buffalo Philharmonic performing at her
church on Christmas Eve, transporting her into a magical realm.
Mike remembers the exhilaration of staying up until midnight and
singing the Hallelujah Chorus at midnight Mass with his whole
heart. Some families went caroling or spent Christmas Eve singing
around the piano, while others focused on the spoken word, a yearly
retelling of Ellin Greene's ``Legend of the Christmas Rose,'' or
``The Night Before Christmas,'' or Bible readings, repeated year
after year.
</P>
<P>
   There's also more than one way to handle the tree, from cutting
one down in the woods at dusk to waiting to trim it on Christmas
Eve. My daughter, Laura, fondly remembers our family lying under
the tree before bedtime, taking the time to admire the twinkling
lights casting colored shadows on the ceiling. In Mark and
Shannon's ritual honoring their tree, each person expresses thanks
to the tree before dropping a pinch of tobacco into a cloth, which
is then tied at the ends. The littlest child then hangs up this
bundle of gratitude as the first ornament.
</P>
<P>
   I was struck by how the tellers of these tales remembered their
families' rituals with enormous pleasure. Children, I think, come
to count on familiar ceremonies, comforted by predictability. No
matter how chaotic life gets, a ritual anchors a family to solid
ground, providing a safety zone for anticipation and recollection.
It's no wonder moments of repetition appear as peaks of experience
in the level blur of the past.
</P>
<P>
   These last hours before Christmas are a perfect time to rebel
against have-to-do's and concentrate on love-to-do's. Have you
filled your seasonal fun quotient? What could you do _ so silly, so
special, so meaningful _ to bring a smile to your children's faces
years from now? No kids? Why not do something worth remembering
yourself?
</P>
<P>
   Every ritual had its start somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Why not at this very moment?
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1306EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
