<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5677 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV27     12-24 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTFOLIO'S AGGRESSIVE PARTS WORK BEST IN ROTH IRA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. There's one Roth IRA conversion issue I have not yet seen
addressed in the financial media, and that's the priority of which
IRA funds to convert _ income or growth holdings. You wrote in a
recent column that funds with the greatest growth potential should
be converted, but you didn't explain why. I have five IRA funds.
There is $29,000 in Janus, $16,000 in Harbor International, $17,000
in Baron Asset, $6,000 in T. Rowe Price Spectrum Income, and
$10,500 in Fidelity Convertible Securities. I can afford to convert
about half of the current value of these accounts. In trying to
decide which to convert, I was assuming that funds producing income
would be better candidates than growth funds. I base that
assumption on current tax law that taxes dividends at higher rates
than capital gains, so the greatest benefit in the long run would
be with income funds. Is that assumption correct? I am 46 and in
the 28 percent tax bracket.
</P>
<P>
   S.O., Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A. Alas, it doesn't work that way. When withdrawals are taken
from a traditional IRA, Uncle Sam treats the entire amount of the
withdrawal as ordinary income, provided the contributions have been
made on a deductible basis. The rules do not differentiate between
capital gains either long or short, or income; since the entire
balance of a traditional deductible IRA is viewed by Uncle Sam as
money not yet taxed, the full amount of the withdrawal must be
reported as taxable income on line 15b of your 1040 form.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the great advantage of the Roth IRA is that while
you must pay the taxes on money that's contributed to it _ either
through direct deposits or a conversion of a traditional IRA to a
Roth _ that's the end of your tax liability for the account.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose, for example, you transfer half of your traditional IRA
money into Roth IRA accounts. This would mean a total transfer of
$39,250, and special rules for this tax year allow you to spread
the tax liability over four years. Thus you would pay a total of
$10,990 in taxes to make the transfer. But consider that if you put
the transferred money in stock funds, you should be able to
reasonably expect average 10 percent annual total returns over the
next 20 years. Thus at age 66, you should have something in the
neighborhood of $264,054 in the Roth IRA _ and you can take the
money out in retirement with no tax bill at all.
</P>
<P>
   So since you will have no tax liability on the growth of the
Roth account, you would be best putting the most aggressive parts
of your portfolio allocations in the Roth. In the example above,
you would face $10,990 in near-term taxes, but the $206,804
portfolio growth will be entirely tax free.
</P>
<P>
   Now suppose that you did it the other way, using the Roth for
your most conservative investments. If we suppose average annual
growth of only 7 percent, based on a Roth portfolio dominated by
fixed-income holdings, the 20-year growth would take the account to
only $151,885. Your short-term tax liability would be the same,
$10,990, but in exchange for that, you would have accumulated only
$112,635 in tax-free growth.
</P>
<P>
   If the fixed- income end of the portfolio were left in the
traditional IRA accounts, you would have only $151,885 upon which
taxes would be due upon withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   As for your specific portfolio, my suggestion at this point
would be to transfer the entire holdings in Baron Asset (a
small-cap growth fund) and Harbor International, and $6,250 of the
holdings in Janus. Probably over the long term, the Janus position
has better growth potential than Harbor International, a world
stock fund. But in the short-to-intermediate term, I think you're
likely to see better growth in the small-cap and international
markets than in the fast-cooling large-cap stocks favored by Janus.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, both Roth and traditional IRAs allow you to change
your holdings within the accounts without any tax consequences, so
you might in five years decide that prospects for the domestic
large caps are then better than for an international portfolio _ so
you could simply swap Harbor International shares for Janus shares
in the Roth portfolio, and then swap Janus shares for Harbor
International in the traditional portfolio _ maintaining the
identical portfolio balance, but keeping the holdings that seem to
have the best growth potential in the account that won't be taxed
when you eventually withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   One important addendum: people planning to transfer funds from a
traditional IRA to a Roth IRA and spread the tax liability over
four tax years must make the transfer by Dec. 31. Although
contributions to IRAs can be made until April 15 of the year
following the tax year in question, a transfer with the tax
liability spread over four years must be made during this calendar
year. The provision allowing the liability to be spread over four
years is a one-time goodie for 1998, and will not be allowed later.
This can be a critical factor for people who contemplate
transferring large sums to a Roth, since a large transfer could
push many people into a higher tax bracket, while spreading it out
over four years may not have that effect.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In about two years when my wife is 77 and I am 76, we plan to
sell our house and move to a rather expensive retirement community.
We expect to clear about $700,000 from the house, and we would like
to draw about $5,000 a month, after taxes, from the house money.
Our combined state and federal tax bracket is 45.3 percent, and we
will probably remain in that bracket. My first reaction was to buy
an annuity, but after studying the figures, I believe we could do
as well through other investments and have the possibility of
leaving some of the money to our heirs. As of this writing, I am
leaning toward a tax-free mutual fund paying 3.54 percent, which my
amateur figuring says is equivalent to 6.4 percent taxable. If we
go this route, how long could we expect our $700,000 to last with
$5,000 monthly withdrawals?
</P>
<P>
   R.H., La Jolla, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. Presuming that the municipal fund you're looking at is free
of both California and federal taxes, the answer is that the funds
would run out just a bit short of 15 years. If you shopped around a
bit, you could probably find a fund with a better yield than the
one you're considering. Entering this month, the Fidelity Investor
newsletter reported a current yield of 4.01 percent for Fidelity
Spartan California Municipal Income, which it calculated was
equivalent to a 7 percent return for a person in the 36 percent
federal tax bracket. That small change in returns would mean that
the funds would last you about eight months longer than if your
investment averaged a 3.54 percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
