<HEADLINE>
MARTIN DIDN'T HESITATE TO REJOIN HIS OLD COACH IN N.Y. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ The opponent: the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The topic: Curtis Martin.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Any regrets, Bill Parcells, about forking over $36
million of Leon Hess's petrodollars and some draft picks for the
running back?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: What do you think?
</P>
<P>
   Parcells took some heat when he signed Martin last summer,
mainly for the financial implications at the time and down the
road. He heard it then and paid it no heed, and now, almost 1,200
yards and a division title later, there's even further reason to
ignore it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what they say,'' Parcells said Wednesday. ``I
think the guy is a good player. When you see a good player, you try
to get him. You don't just pass on a player like Curtis Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   That is what the Patriots did, however, taking the picks, saving
the money, and allowing Martin, their best running back over the
previous three years, to head south. He already has rushed for more
yards (1,185) this season than in either of his last two years in
New England. His 353 receiving yards are a personal best.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Martin nor Parcells is surprised by the tailback's
season, even though he has been bothered by sore legs for most of
the year. There is a bond at work here, as there is between
Parcells and other ex-Patriots on the team. Martin said he came
here for one reason: the coach. Yeah, the money helped, but that
was not the driving force.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what would have happened if there had been
another team, but with Bill, it was no question,'' Martin said.
``To be reunited with him and (running backs coach) Mo Carthon;
those guys have taught me so much. It was a win-win situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be here. I didn't mention any numbers or amounts
to my agent. It was the only situation for me. But I wasn't
expecting it. I was expecting to be back in New England. When I got
the news, I got on my knees and prayed. It was like a blessing from
God.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin may not have produced a jaw-dropping season, but he is
fifth in the AFC in rushing and already has produced the third-best
rushing season in Jets history. But he hasn't been drop-dead
dazzling on a week-to-week basis, and his 3.5-yard average gain is
a career low. His eight TDs are second only to the four he had last
year; he had 14 in each of his first two years in New England.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some big games (144 yards against Indianapolis)
and some not-so-big ones (38 yards last week against Buffalo), but
all Parcells sees is the big picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take 1,200 (yards) from a back. Just keep giving me
that,'' Parcells said. ``The guys that play this position, the
defenses are after them every week. There are no weeks off for
these guys. Just add up the yards he's got in four years. How many
have that many in their entire careers?''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said what he envies most about Martin, however, has
nothing to do with carrying the football. ``I think the best way to
describe it,'' Parcells said, ``is that he is at peace with himself
at such a young age (25). I wish I was. It doesn't mean he's any
less determined or ambitious. He just has an inner strength. I know
what kind of person he is. He shows up. He works his butt off. He
has no baggage. He's compassionate. What else do you want from a
guy?''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots knew all this, too, but decided the cost was too
steep. In the first meeting of the season between the teams, Martin
rushed for 107 yards as the Jets won, 24-14. He had sat out the
previous game in St. Louis, the only time in his three years with
Parcells that he has been unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   He's looking forward to Sunday, to finishing the regular season
strongly, to the playoffs, and to the unknown. What he's not doing
is looking back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no big deal,'' he said of his departure from New England.
``It's in my past. It's where I used to play and what I used to
represent. You put it behind you. That was the team I once played
for, but now it's over with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
