<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZOLAK IS UP FRONT ON PARCELLS' EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ In the background, a group of sportswriters
were howling as Bill Parcells was making some self-depricating
remarks about his weight on a conference call from Hofstra
University, the Jets' training site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, listen. Let me tell ya something,'' said Parcells,
addressing a Sports Illustrated story that listed his weight at 240
pounds. ``If I fell down, I'd rock myself to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing at a microphone in an adjacent room, Scott Zolak was
speaking over the jocularity, taking about the
second-most-important start of his career Sunday against Parcells
and the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another game,'' said the Patriots quarterback,
unconvincingly. ``Last week the playoffs were on the line. This
week there's the possibility of a home game in the playoffs to play
for, and that would be huge for us _ to host a game against Miami.
We're gonna be scrapping.''
</P>
<P>
   If anyone is above being spooked by Parcells, it might be Zolak.
When Parcells was coaching in New England, he liked his backup
quarterback; if not, Zolak wouldn't have been around. And while he
took his share of criticism from the coach, Zolak often gave as
much as he took. During the 1996 Super Bowl season, for example,
when Parcells mentioned that Zolak needed to lose some weight,
Zolak responded with something to the effect of, ``He should
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about that exchange Wednesday, Zolak shrugged it off,
making it sound like no big deal. ``Quarterbacks are getting
bigger,'' he said with a grin. ``I'm a lot lighter now than I have
been. I've done a lot of extra running, and being involved in
practice as much as I have been the past few weeks keeps the weight
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as Zolak always had a response for his former coach, he
also knows that while the kind words Parcells has been bestowing
upon him the past couple of days may be genuine to some degree,
there's also a method to his madness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players really rally around Zo,'' said Parcells. ``He has
a good arm and he prepares well for games _ at least he did when I
had him. I remember the game we started him in Atlanta in '95, he
hit 15 of his first 20. I thought he played very well last
Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, assistant head coach Bill Belichick, defensive
coordinator Al Groh and Co. probably already have Zolak defensed,
confused, overwhelmed, etc. with their game plan. Belichick has
been the assistant coach of the year in the NFL, the only to
successfully shut down Doug Flutie twice. His defensive game plans
have been impeccable, just as they were during the Patriots'
playoff run in '96. The only time Belichick and Groh failed was in
the Super Bowl when Otis Smith and Willie Clay got beat on long
balls.
</P>
<P>
   That may be precisley where the Patriots are able to do some
damage. After all, as well as Smith has played this season, he is
still Otis Smith. The Jets take away the middle-range passing game
as well as anyone because of their aggressive linebacking corps, so
throwing to Ben Coates may be a little harder than in other weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're doing a great job on the underneath stuff,'' said
Zolak. ``Their linebackers have been glued to the receivers. Otis
Smith, Jerome Henderson, who both played here, have done a great
job in coverage, and Victor Green is a lot like Lawyer Milloy in
that he hits people pretty hard. I'm sure that they're going to put
together a plan they think can bring out my weaknesses. They know
me pretty well over there, so they know what I can do and what I
can't do. Now we have to find a way to put me in a position so my
strengths are utlized.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak still feels the whack in the back of the neck he took from
Ken Norton Jr. last Sunday, and he suspects that the Jets will try
to rattle him with blitzes from the corners and even from Green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say they'd come after me,'' said Zolak. ``Their defense
does something different every game, but where I'm a guy who hasn't
played that much and for a long time, they'll try to make it tough
on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zolak is preparing knowing that he definitely will be at the
helm Sunday. On Monday, Pete Carroll had left the door sightly ajar
for a return by Drew Bledsoe, but that was slammed shut when the
coach said that his usual starting quarterback won't even be active
for the game. In fact, Bledsoe may not be active in the playoffs,
especially if Zolak continues to win.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak certainly put on a winning show last Sunday, and he
reveled in that triumph for as long as he could. He understands
that opportunities to win games that get a team into the playoffs
are few and far between. He also knows that on Sunday ``this could
be the last game I play.'' And he knows if that's the case he'd
like nothing better than to end any jinxes, curses, or ghosts that
hover around the Patriots as related to the former coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has a lot to do with me being here,'' said Zolak. ``Phil
Simms used to say that one of the things Bill does is make you
thick-skinned. And that's true. You learn to take a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why when Parcells got on him about his weight, Zolak
gave it right back. Parcells's former players remember so many
little things that motivate them when they face him.
</P>
<P>
   The players strive to perform better when they're facing
Parcells _ though they tend to say that the legend of their former
coach is a media myth. ``I think that stuff is overblown by the
media,'' said Zolak.
</P>
<P>
   Also overblown, said Zolak, is the notion that Parcells can get
into the heads of his former players, as he seemed to do with
Bledsoe. ``There's no question he's a great coach who knows our
personnel, but we should also know what he might try to do,'' said
Zolak. ``We know him pretty well, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1311EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
