<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAINTING OF THE RINGS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The price of a vote for a wanna-be Olympic host city used to be
a couple of first-class plane tickets, a luxury suite, a jeroboam
of bubbly, and maybe some calfskin luggage. Now, apparently, it's
free knee surgery, college scholarships, or a few hundred grand.
</P>
<P>
   The Lords of the Rings may relish their perks, but they're
supposed to be above bribery. Not so, says longtime International
Olympic Committee insider Marc Hodler, who claims that as many as
two dozen of his fellow members have sold their votes during the
past decade.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City, which spent more than $600,000 (much of it on
school subsidies for IOC family members) to sew up the 2002 Winter
Games, was merely playing the five-ringed game. ``I know of so many
times,'' said Hodler, a Swiss lawyer who has been an IOC member
since 1963. ``There is a good chance it is always the case.''
</P>
<P>
   That came as no surprise to disappointed bid cities such as
Sion, Switzerland, and Oestersund, Sweden, which either didn't know
they had to buy votes or refused to. Hodler claimed that middlemen
demand between $500,000 and $1 million for a bloc of votes and
charge the winning city another $3 million-$5 million.
</P>
<P>
   That's loose change, though, to lasso an event that brings
priceless prestige _ and an estimated $5 billion in tourist
revenues _ to the victor.
</P>
<P>
   As the number of would-be hosts has soared (10 cities bid for
the 2002 Games; 11 wanted the 2004 Summer Games, which went to
Athens; six have lined up for 2006, nine for 2008) and the number
of IOC members has grown from 90 in 1980 to 115, the bidding has
taken on the shady aura of a backstreet bazaar, with cities
offering lavish gifts and services and ``agents'' dangling blocs of
votes (usually from Africa) for a seven-figure price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are four agents we know,'' said Hodler, who claims that
the host-city votes for the 1996, 1998, 2000, and 2002 Games have
all been tainted. ``One is an IOC member. He promises he will give
enough votes so the city can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two decades ago, the Lords couldn't give the Games away.
After Montreal lost a billion dollars on the 1976 Summer Olympics,
only Los Angeles dared bid for 1984. And after the US-led boycott
of Moscow in 1980 only two candidates _ Seoul and Nagoya _ entered
for 1988. What deluded city would be willing to risk a 10-figure
deficit on a 16-day event that half the world might skip?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, it was: Which city can afford to lose this
much money?'' says Richard Pound, an IOC vice president from
Canada. ``Now the Olympics are seen as an economic benefit to the
city. They've become a desirable international multiyear project.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything changed when LA emerged with a $200 million surplus
despite the Soviet boycott. Suddenly, there were six bidders for
the 1992 Summer Games and seven for the Winter Games _ and royal
perks for any IOC member who cared to indulge.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul had already set a handout standard in 1982. The night
before the Lords voted for 1988, the Koreans slipped two
first-class plane tickets, redeemable for cash, under their hotel
doors. Seoul swamped Nagoya, which had been the odds-on favorite,
by a 2-1 margin. Coincidence _ or not?
</P>
<P>
   By 1990, when half a dozen cities were in the chase for 1996,
Hodler says that quid pro quo was the byword. When Atlanta, which
had never before bid for the Olympics, bested Athens for the
Centennial Games, the shocked and furious Greeks cried foul.
``Coca-Cola has won over the Parthenon,'' declared actress Melina
Mercouri, the country's Minister of Culture.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, which clearly had the best bid package, denied paying
anybody off. ``No payments, direct or indirect,'' insisted
organizing committee head Billy Payne. ``No scholarships, direct or
indirect. I have never heard of that and will state positively,
unequivocally, Atlanta did not do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake City, which had already bid unsuccessfully four times,
also believed it had the best package when it went after the 1998
Games a year later. When the Utahns lost to Nagano by four votes,
they realized they'd been playing the wrong game. ``The joke,''
says former SLOC member Fred Ball, ``was that we were giving out
salt water taffy and Japan was giving out Toyotas.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time, it would be scholarships and surgery. Salt Lake
immediately set aside nearly half a million dollars for
``humanitarian aid,'' i.e. 13 college subsidies for foreign
students, six of them relatives of IOC members, most of them from
Africa. And a local hospital provided more than $25,000 in free
medical services (including a knee replacement) to three Africans
with IOC links.
</P>
<P>
   After spending $60 million of public money on facilities and $13
million of private cash on bidding, Salt Lake was leaving nothing
to chance for 2002, even though it easily had the best bid. When
the IOC voted in 1995, Salt Lake slam-dunked Sion, Oestersund, and
Quebec on the first ballot.
</P>
<P>
   When a local television station broke the payoff story last
month, outrage and embarrassment followed. SLOC chairman Frank
Joklik, who claimed he knew nothing of the payoffs, was called on
the carpet by the IOC executive committee at its meeting in
Switzerland two weekends ago to explain and apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody blames Salt Lake City,'' said Hodler. ``We blame those
voters who can be bought. For us, Salt Lake City was a victim of
blackmail and not a villain.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Juan Antonio Samaranch, who has been president for
nearly two decades, nobody knows more about how the bidding game
works than Hodler, who, at 80, is the dean of the Lords. While he
held forth recently in the lobby of IOC headquarters in Lausanne,
Switzerland, past bid committee members from Sydney, Anchorage,
Lillehammer, and Quebec said they had been solicited for bribes.
And Melbourne officials admitted they gave money to IOC members
during their unsuccessful 1996 bid.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
