<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CHROKEE: STILL A JEEP, BUT ALMOST ALL   NEW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)  
 (For release Sunday, December 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN R.WHITE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Jeep Grand Cherokee _ like the company that makes it _ is
brand new this year. It isn't Chrysler Corp. anymore; it's
DaimlerChrysler. The company rep who introduced it to the motor
press at the New England International Auto Show held up a brown
paper grocery sack containing ``all the carryover parts'' _ about
27 pieces in all, if I remember correctly. All small bits.
</P>
<P>
   The body is new, the suspension is new, the engine is new, it is
larger all around. Still, it resembles its forebears _ there's no
mistaking it. It's a Jeep.
</P>
<P>
   So there it was in the driveway, waiting. ``I've got to do
something with this,'' I said to myself _ I talk to myself a lot
lately. ``Something'' involving trucks or sport/utilities usually
includes heavy lifting. ``Something'' this time started with a trip
to a purveyor of used office equipment where there was offered for
a reasonable price an oversized file cabinet, perfect for the
storage of oversize photographs, music folios, and other assorted
miscellany now littering the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   The Jeep Grand Cherokee Limited, at $33,995 plus $525
destination charge, is hardly cheap, not exactly bare utilitarian.
For the money it comes plush _ leather, wood trim, automatic air
conditioning, automatic headlamps, dual heated outside mirrors, and
Chrysler's Quadra-Trac II _ an on-demand 4-wheel-drive system with
low range and automatic gearbox. ``On demand'' means the system
senses loss of traction in slippery going and shifts power to the
wheels with grip to keep you moving.
</P>
<P>
   For $6,250 less, you can get a Grand Cherokee Laredo in 4WD with
Selec-Trac, a full-time 4WD system, cloth upholstery, and manual
air conditioning. Skip the 4WD all together and still the cheapest
Grand is $25,800 plus delivery. Where do all these people who buy
these things get the money?
</P>
<P>
   The Limited in leather is not what one buys for heavy work or
rough cartage, but it is a sure way to get a file cabinet home.
Getting it in was easy _ the seller loaded it _ once I had figured
out how to fold the rear seats flat (the owner's manual was a big
help here, even though it is against the rules of malehood to ask
directions). In this edition of Grand Cherokee, the rear seat
bottoms flip up against the back of the front seat and the backs
fold down flat. No longer is it necessary to remove the headrests;
merely flip the lever on the back of the headrest and yank it
forward, thus folding it to allow the seatback to fold down.
</P>
<P>
   Unloading it was the problem _ the cabinet, judging by its
weight, is of excellent quality. Once eased out of the truck,
removing the drawers lightened the shell sufficiently to nudge it
along to its permanent place of repose _ one has occasion to miss
the teenagers when they grow up and go away.
</P>
<P>
   The new engine is a 4.7-liter V-8 dishing up 235 horsepower in
its standard configuration, 230 in a low-emission mode, and
delivers 295 ft/lb of torque. The 4-speed automatic gearbox is very
smooth with a conveniently placed floor shifter; the low-range
lever is to the left of it, out of the way but easy to reach. The
Laredo, by the way, is offered with 4.0-liter six-cylinder
standard.
</P>
<P>
   The new V-8 replaces the venerable 5.2-liter (318 CID) V-8 that
has been around for eons. What is lost in engine displacement,
however, does not seem to be gained in fuel economy; the Grand
delivered 16.03 miles per gallon over some 500 miles charted. Nor
is there any loss in performance; the Jeep moves out smartly
enough, albeit hard acceleration is more than a trifle noisy. The
tested model, however, is a pre-production vehicle that customers
won't normally get; the pre-pros frequently have bugs that must be
eliminated before full production begins and thus are not always
representative of what the customer will get.
</P>
<P>
   Where this Grand Cherokee disappointed was in ride and handling;
it is not the solid hulk that was the predecessor. The ride on the
'99 is softer; there is a certain vagueness on the road, a lack of
positive feedback that makes me nervous _ but again, this may only
be the anomaly of a prototype. The Grand certainly behaved well
enough, even if it didn't feel quite as surefooted this time
around.
</P>
<P>
   Rear room has certainly improved; while the kneeroom in the back
can be snug with long-legged types up front, there is more than
yesteryear. Headroom is good, even with the space-robbing sunroof.
Rear entry is a bit awkward because of the wheel well intrusion,
exacerbated by the extra height off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Interior storage is a mixed bag. The glove box is pitiful, but a
large covered bin between the seats, seatback pockets, and door
bins help.
</P>
<P>
   Controls are very good, with hefty knobs to set temperature and
control airflow. Some of the radio controls, however, are the
exception _ too small, too close together.
</P>
<P>
   OK, what good is a sport/utility just before Christmas if it
doesn't get put to the tree test? A dusting of snow is beginning to
make it feel like Christmas as I head northwest for the Sundance
Farm to find a tree where hot cider awaits the prospective
customers. I tramp into the woods, select a carefully manicured
balsam of about seven feet, and hack it down (a woodsman I am not)
with the supplied bow saw. It is a well-formed, plump tree that
needs a lot of pushing and pulling to get it far enough into the
Jeep to close the rear hatch _ and then a foot of tree trunk hovers
around my right ear.
</P>
<P>
   I should have used the roof rack _ I had brought rope. Even
fresh trees shed needles, and evergreen needles are vacuum-cleaner
resistant like nothing else on earth, but they sure smell good.
</P>
<P>
   The '99 Grand Cherokee has gained a little, lost a little, I
think, but on balance I'd have to give it a thumbs up for being a
most elegant workhorse with a drive system that is perfect for
winter _ which no part-time 4WD sytem can ever be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1316EST &QL; 
