<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 13:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-WEATHER-BOS &LR;      12-24 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKI SEASON FINALLY HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAY, Vt. _ ``This is not a business for the faint of heart,''
mused Bill Stenger, president of Jay Peak Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Four days before Christmas Stenger was looking at a rain shower
falling from a leaden sky. It felt more like spring than the first
day of winter _ and just four days before the start of the busiest
periods of the ski season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a nail-biter,'' said Stenger, ``but we're going to
pull it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Christmas in the mountains has been a long tradition for Sandy
and Lew Lawson, who are taking their two college-age children to
Quebec's Tremblant this winter. Like thousands of New Englanders,
the Lawsons will leave the day after Christmas for a week of
skiing, ending on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have faith,'' said Sandy. ``I know it hasn't been a great
winter for skiing so far, but it's cold now. I have a sister in
Quebec, and she tells me it's been down in the teens every night.''
</P>
<P>
   The cold did show up in New England, but, as Stenger said, a
little too close for comfort. It is expected to stay cold through
the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   According to bookings at most major ski areas in New England,
many people are planning on heading north, especially next week.
Still, said Lew Lawson, ``When you ski this time of year you take
what you get. Some years it's great, and other years you have to
watch what your skis are going over.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, skiers faced a meltdown at Christmas after an
excellent Thanksgiving snowfall. The period before Christmas was
the best part of last season. This year?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make it,'' Stenger repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Maine's Sunday River, Skip King agreed that the autumn
leg of the season was ``kind of frustrating, but now we're through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   With much relief, ski area operators are looking at a long
period of cold weather in which they can add to the base and open
more trails. Few if any areas will be at 100 percent, but most will
fall between 50 and 75 percent open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have six of eight peaks open this weekend, and probably
get seven peaks open next week,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for all the optimism despite the warmest fall in New
England history is the state of snowmaking in the northeast. Heavy
competition among ski areas the last two decades and advancing
technology that allows the process to take place at higher
temperatures have ensured that a few cold nights equal skiable
snow.
</P>
<P>
   According to meteorologist Mark Breen, who covers northern and
central Vermont, the weather system known as La Nina is about to
take hold, plunging the far north into deep winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the cold air mass expands,'' said Breen, ``it will start to
bring cold and snow to the northern inland areas. Areas to the
south and near the coastal influence won't feel the effect as
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Breen confirmed that the fall was unusual. ``We have a pond
we've watched and kept records on for 30 years,'' he said, ``and
this is the latest that it hasn't frozen over.''
</P>
<P>
   He also confirmed that the cold spell that took hold Tuesday
night will hang in through Christmas. But, he added, aside from
flurries here and there, no big snow dumps appear in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   All this week, open acreage has been expanding at all ski areas,
and should continue through the period, according to area managers.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, Killington had 32 trails open, about 20 percent
of its terrain, but the snowguns are whirling and the area is
expected to have half its terrain skiable by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south in Vermont, Okemo has 31 trails open and is
working on a base between 1 and 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Gunstock has six trails open on a 6-to-18-inch
base, while Cannon has 14 trails open with an 8-20-inch base.
</P>
<P>
   Few glades or outback areas are open, since they need lots of
natural snow. Also, halfpipes and terrain gardens need more
snowfall than most areas have been blessed with.
</P>
<P>
   With conditions variable and changing, skiers should either call
their area ahead or read published listings. The following is a
standard code of the condition symbols.
</P>
<P>
   --New Snow: Natural snowfall that has occurred within the past
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   --Average Base Depth: An average of the high and low amounts of
snow over the entire ski area, both machine and natural.
</P>
<P>
   --Primary Surface Condition: The type of snow that covers at
least 70 percent of the open terrain.
</P>
<P>
   --Powder, PDR: Cold, new, loose, fluffy snow.
</P>
<P>
   --Packed Powder, PP: Man-made or natural snow that has been
packed by skier traffic or grooming machine.
</P>
<P>
   --Hard Pack, HP: Snow that has been packed so hard that it takes
effort to drive a pole into.
</P>
<P>
   --Machine-groomed Snow, MSG: Loose, granular snow that has been
repeatedly packed by power-tillers to the consistency of powder
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   --Wet Snow, WETSN: Powder or packed powder that has become moist
because of rainfall or thaw.
</P>
<P>
   --Loose Granular, LSGR: A consistency of frozen crystalized snow
created by freeze/thaw cycles.
</P>
<P>
   --Frozen Granular. FRGR: A hard surface of old snow formed by
granules of snow thawing and freezing together.
</P>
<P>
   --Wet Granular, WETGR: Loose and frozen granular snow that has
become wet after thaw or rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   --ICE: Hard, glazed surface that will not support a ski pole.
</P>
<P>
   --Variable Conditions, VC: When no primary condition (70
percent) can be determined.
</P>
<P>
   --Corn Snow, CORN: A surface condition consisting of large loose
granules that roll together like ball bearings.
</P>
<P>
   --Spring Conditions, SC: When in warm temperatures no one
surface condition can be determined over 70 percent of the area.
</P>
<P>
   --Windblown Snow, WBLN: Powder or granular snow that has been
blown by the wind into a hard base surface.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1318EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
