<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWAIN REMAINS UNMET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We are looking through the musings of Edith Thys, in which a
feisty former racer from from the US Ski Team makes her case for
Western skiing. Of course, she is a Westerner herself (Squaw
Valley, Calif.) who admits right up front in the current issue of
Ski magazine that because of the polarization of East vs. West, ``I
was quite sure that had I been born in the East I would not have
become a skier.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be unfair to leave her commentary here, for Thys does
go on to write an insightful, very readable, and ultimately fair
comparison of the two areas of skiing which, she concludes, are
profoundly different. She adds that ``many of our differences have
deep cultural roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, we have been around this barn before in this space. But it
still sounds a bit inflexible when people from New England say _ as
they so often do: ``The only skiing I do is the vacation week out
West. I can't face the skiing back in the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, these are not what the industry would call mainstream
skiers, but rather _ as they themselves say _ marginal. The less
they ski in the East, with its particular requirements, the less
they can ski the East.
</P>
<P>
   So the West is easier?
</P>
<P>
   The groomed West, yes. The snow is more uniform and less
susceptible to attacks of moisture and the freeze/thaw cycle that
creates Eastern conditions. It's a question of altitude. At 1 1/2-2
miles high, snow is dry, light, and generally unhazardous to one's
health.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Western areas have been developed on wide-open spaces
where the runs are wide and forgiving. Rarely seen is one of those
Eastern-style narrow, cranking corkscrews through dark woods that
close around us like the trees in ``Sleeping Beauty,'' though many
of those New England classics have since been retrofit over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   But we emphasize the term groomed West, for much of non-tourist
Western skiing involves blasting through deep crud, hydroplaning
through thigh-high powder, learning that straight fall-line skiing
is the only way through deep stuff, and generally knowing how to
shift gears for various kinds of ``soft'' and broken surface
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But Thys, speaking from a racer's viewpoint, sees some deeper
differences. In the East, she says, skiers train rather than ski.
Because of the cold, often hostile climate, Eastern skiers stay in
the lodge when they're not racing, while Westerners are out
freeskiing at every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Western skiers do not deal with cold moisture in the air and
thus dress differently _ lighter, freer, less encumbered. Rather
than just ChapStick, Westerners also use prodigious amounts of
suntan lotion, which underlines, with odor, a certain quality of
laid-back ease to the Western approach.
</P>
<P>
   Thys talks about, when coming East to race a few years ago,
underdressing to the point of ``shivering through a December
morning of training in a cotton turtleneck and sweatshirt, never
having contemplated how to dress for damp cold.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not the first to point out that Easterners feel somewhat
superior to Western skiers because of their necessity to ski with
precision over ice, to ski in terrain that demands disciplined
turning, to brave a tougher climate and hard, unforgiving snow.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely have the two skiing cultures been analyzed to such
depths, to their cultural roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eastern skier behavior can be traced to the Mayflower,'' Thys
says. ``Yankee sensibility and the Puritan work ethic defined
everything from their demeanor to their clothing and their general
resignation that anything worth having is worth suffering for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise,'' Thys adds in a line worthy of Garrison Keillor,
``Western skiers are rooted in the pioneer mentality. They didn't
like the conditions in the East, so they left.''
</P>
<P>
   But one might maintain that the vast superiority of the
Northeastern mentality is its ability to manipulate the environment
in a competitive way. The ``product'' wars of the last two decades
have given nearly every ski area in New England the ability to
create instant winter _ or at least the 48-hour winter.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate aim of the amazing arms race that transformed
Eastern skiing was to create guaranteed winter _ an assurance to
skiers that conditions are not totally dependent on the vagaries of
climate. The Western winter climate in Rocky Mountain high country,
of course, creates its own guarantee.
</P>
<P>
   But skiers and boarders headed north this vacation season
looking for not perfect or even great skiing but skiing just the
same have a well-placed faith in the ability of the East to produce
snow. And, as Thys concludes, in the East, West, or anywhere else,
``Any snow is good snow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-BRIBERY-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     12-24 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... 1996 bid.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With so many cities chasing the Games and more members voting on
them, five-ringed payola seems inevitable. When Baron Pierre de
Coubertin revived the Olympics more than a century ago, he filled
the IOC with princes and dukes and lords because he figured they
would be immune to political and financial influence.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, though, the IOC came to be seen as a private club of
rich, white European octogenarians living in a cloud cuckooland. So
Lord Killanin and Samaranch expanded and diversified the
membership, adding women, former athletes, and sports federation
presidents, and recruited them from around the planet, especially
from Third World nations. Forty percent of the 115 members now are
from Africa, Asia, and Oceania.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Lords now come from countries where bribery has been
an accepted part of doing business for centuries. Some of them
allegedly will accept cash and services in exchange for votes,
particularly if they have no stake in the outcome. A few _ Hodler
estimates 5-7 percent _ reportedly will ask for them.
</P>
<P>
   Though Samaranch insisted that Hodler wasn't speaking for the
IOC, the chief Lord knows a scandal when he smells one. ``If we
have to clean, we will clean,'' said Samaranch, who vowed to expel
any IOC member proven to have taken bribes.
</P>
<P>
   So he has turned over the whole mess to Richard Pound, who will
begin by investigating the Salt Lake City payoffs and see where
they take him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on where the facts lead,'' says Pound, who is a
Montreal attorney and a former Olympic swimmer. ``But I don't think
we're going to run down every rumor involving the IOC for the last
hundred years.''
</P>
<P>
   Bribes or not, the record shows that whichever host city the
Lords select usually puts on excellent Games. ``Leaving aside the
peccadillos of a few IOC members,'' muses Pound, ``you look over a
hundred years or so and we pretty much have gotten it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the IOC would like to rid itself of the backstreet bazaar
aura, and the best way to cut down on the handouts is to reduce the
number of hands. From now on, the Lords will be forbidden to visit
candidate cities, Samaranch says. And instead of having all 115
members vote on host sites, the IOC probably will have the 11
executive committee members do the choosing. ``That's one of the
things we're looking at,'' says Pound.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are no longer a corner clambake. Two hundred
countries are invited with half the planet watching. The host city
is on global display for 16 days and on the international map
forever. Salt Lake City's budget for the Winter Games is $1.4
billion. That ain't salt water taffy.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE INTERNATIONAL OLYMPIC COMMITTEE &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT THE IOC IS &QC; 
The International Olympic Committee, founded in 1894 and
headquartered in Lausanne, Switzerland, oversees the Olympic Games
and promotes the values of `Olympism' across the world. It chooses
its own unpaid members (currently 115) and elects them for life,
with a mandatory retirement age of 80. Countries are generally
limited to one member; those which have hosted the Games are
allotted two. Anita DeFrantz and James Easton are the US members. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOW THE GAMES ARE AWARDED &QC; 
Host cities are chosen seven years in advance. A special IOC
evaluation commission visits each bidder, examining everything from
facilities to transportation to hotels to weather, and makes a
detailed report. If necessary, the IOC reduces the number of
candidates to half a dozen or fewer. The full membership then votes
by secret ballot until one city has a majority. The IOC will choose
the site of the 2006 Winter Games in June at a meeting in Seoul. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE IOC EXECUTIVE BOARD &QC; 
Juan Antonio Samaranch (Spain) president &QL; 
Prince Alexandre de Merode (Belgium) vice president &QL; 
Pal Schmitt (Hungary) vice president &QL; 
Richard Pound (Canada) vice president &QL; 
Anita DeFrantz (US) vice president &QL; 
Keba Mbaye (Senegal) &QL; 
He Zhenliang (China) &QL; 
Kevan Gosper (Australia) &QL; 
Thomas Bach (Germany) &QL; 
Chiharu Igaya (Japan) &QL; 
Un Yong Kim (South Korea) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
