<HEADLINE>
COLD BLAST DEVASTATES CALIFORNIA CITRUS CROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANASTASIA HENDRIX  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A deep freeze that enveloped California's citrus
crop this week is expected to drive up prices for consumers, with
losses to growers already exceeding $590 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consumer will definitely feel the impact,'' said Shawn
Bagley, a produce broker in Salinas. ``It is dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Citrus growers were tallying the damage after the mid-week cold
snap. David Moore, a citrus grower who is president of the Western
Growers Association, said Wednesday that of the 70 percent of his
crop not yet harvested, ``I would say 100 percent of it was lost.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't cut through the oranges, they are frozen. I'd like
to think some stuff in the center part of the tree will be
salvageable, but to be honest, I think that will not take place,''
Moore said of his grove, located in the southeasternmost part of
the San Joaquin Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Food and Agriculture projected an
equally grim picture based on early reports from inspectors in
Central Valley orchards, where the impact of the cold snap was
greatest.
</P>
<P>
   The department estimated damage statewide at $591 million.
</P>
<P>
   As much as 90 percent of the remaining navel orange crop in
Tulare County _ the state's top orange-producing county _ was
destroyed. The damage is likely to cost up to $370 million since
only 15 percent of the crop had been harvested by the time the
chill set in, agriculture department spokeswoman Myrlys Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Fresno County, the entire lemon crop was
destroyed, an estimated $6.6 million loss based on last year's crop
value. Fifty percent of the navel orange crop was expected to be
lost, costing growers some $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $4.3 million grapefruit crop in Kern County was wiped out
along with 70 percent of the navel oranges, valued at $122.5
million. Lemons suffered a $47.5 million loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Only Florida has a larger orange crop than California, and most
of its oranges are used for juice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers, avocados, strawberries and row crops such as celery
also could be in peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some damage to the avocado blooms, and they are
waiting for the frozen broccoli to thaw so they can harvest,'' said
Guy Tingos, deputy agricultural commissioner for Santa Barbara
County. ``They aren't expecting damage to the broccoli.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark Biggs, spokesman for the California Farm Bureau, said the
crop was already much smaller than normal because of heavy rains
from the El Nino weather phenomenon earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the smaller crop from El Nino and damage we've had,
we'll have probably _ at best _ half the crop we had last year,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   El Nino is the name given to the unusual warming of waters in
the Pacific Ocean that affects global wind and temperature
patterns.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the damage to citrus isn't as severe as the 1990 freeze,
which wiped out the crops and ruined many trees, damaging the
following year's crop as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
