<SLUG> BC-FILM-STEPMOM-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STEPMOM'S' STRONG CAST LIFTS WEAK SCRIPT TO LEVELS OF ENDEARMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' is this season's contender for the ``weeper of the
week'' award.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Terms of Endearment'' and even ``Kramer vs. Kramer,''
from which ``Stepmom'' slyly swipes a scene or two, there is a
pervasive tug at the heartstrings that should appeal to viewers and
Oscar voters.
</P>
<P>
   It's not really much of a surprise considering the actors
involved: Susan Sarandon, Julie Roberts and Ed Harris. As a result,
``Stepmom'' feels akin to Carl Franklin's recent ``One True
Thing,'' which starred Meryl Streep, in that it rises above
TV-movie-of-the-week sensibility only through the star power of its
exceptional cast. It's another case of virtuoso acting elevating a
mediocre script to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Columbus directs this hit-and-miss story (credited to five
writers) and, to be fair, it has some abrasive, clever moments.
Unfortunately, they rub up against scenes of such silliness that
``Stepmom'' often sinks to the level of Columbus' ``Mrs.
Doubtfire'' and ``Home Alone.''
</P>
<P>
   While he's at ease exploring a kid's point-of-view in an adult
world, there's a dark, unsettling undertone in the way ``Stepmom''
sets up its female protagonists as adversaries by virtue of their
association with a man. It's surprising it didn't bother its two
politically correct, high-power actresses, real-life pals Sarandon
and Roberts, who not only star but share executive producer credit.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie (Sarandon) and Isabel (Roberts) have one thing in common:
Luke Harrison (Harris). Jackie is his ex-wife and Isabel his new
love, and their styles immediately clash. Jackie is a ferocious
mother bear, ever protective of her ``cubs'' and she gave up a
lucrative career in publishing to raise Anna (Jena Malone) and Ben
(Liam Aiken).
</P>
<P>
   Isabel is a modern, tough, smart fashion photographer who has an
eye for what's ``in'' _ and doesn't particularly want to relinquish
career for family.
</P>
<P>
   When Luke proposes marriage to Isabel, Jackie and the kids
rebel. But when Jackie finds she is terminally ill with cancer, she
must depend upon her adversary to ensure the future well-being of
her children.
</P>
<P>
   The vitriolic sparring match later blossoms into genuine
fondness and respect for alternate ways of life _ and child
rearing. But would these two very different women ever have gotten
together had Jackie not been diagnosed with cancer? It's doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Sarandon is such a dragon of rage and manipulation
that our sympathies ultimately lie with Roberts. Though Isabel
initially feels weak against Jackie's fury, she slowly emerges as a
contained, clear voice of reason. In the end, we root for her
despite her perceived selfishness; she's the only adult who doesn't
use these confused kids as high-stakes pawns.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Stepmom'' never makes any earth-shattering revelations
or has much invention, it does provide Sarandon with an opportunity
to chew up the scenery. Though Jackie is largely an unsympathetic
part, Sarandon makes the most of it. Roberts proves an able match.
But Harris wanders about with little to do, getting lost in the
shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Stepmom. Directed by Chris Columbus. Written by Gigi Levangie,
Jessie Nelson, Steven Rogers, Karen Leigh Hopkins, Ron Bass. Cast:
Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts, Ed Harris. Columbia Pictures. 124
minutes. Rated PG-13 for language, intense themes about death.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
