<HEADLINE>
REMARKABLE CAST DIVES INTO SHALLOW `DOWN IN THE DELTA' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acclaimed writer and preeminent poet Dr. Maya Angelou makes her
directorial debut with ``Down in the Delta.'' Unfortunately, there
are few remarkable moments to give her first film as much emotion
and raw power as her rich, textured stories.
</P>
<P>
   Angelou directs with little flair and an undistinguished,
pedantic eye, but she hasn't been given much to work with.
</P>
<P>
   Myron Goble's flawed, passive script, written in 1993, was his
first stab at writing a screenplay and it never rises above the TV
movie-of-the-week level.
</P>
<P>
   What it does have going for it is a remarkable bunch of actors.
Alfre Woodard plays Loretta, a high school dropout struggling to
raise her kids in the projects of Chicago. She suffers from awful
self-esteem and is full of guilt because her daughter is autistic
but is often mistaken for a crack baby. She soothes her pain with
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Rosa Lynn (Mary Alice), who keeps the family
together, launches a plan to end the emotional rubble Loretta is
creating among them. She decides to pawn the family heirloom _ a
candelabrum that's been passed down from generation to generation
since slave days _ and send Loretta and her kids to the Mississippi
Delta to live with her brother-in-law, Earl (Al Freeman Jr.), for
the summer. Loretta will be forced to straighten herself out, make
some money and take responsibility for her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta'' has many watered down, feel-good moments.
It never reaches too deeply into the pain and despair that
threatens to tear apart this family, and its characters learn their
life lessons easily. Even the flashbacks to slave days are
luminously lit and sanitized.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the always marvelous Woodard lends a dark prickliness and
sly humor to Loretta and Freeman is solid as Earl, the grumbly but
kindly patriarch of the family who has problems of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Down in the Delta. Directed by Maya Angelou. Written by Myron
Goble. Cast: Alfre Woodard, Al Freeman Jr., Mary Alice, Esther
Rolle, Loretta Devine, Wesley Snipes. Miramax Films. 111 minutes.
Rated PG-13 for intense scenes of alcohol/drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1405EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5752 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-LUGHNASA-SPI &LR;      12-24 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LUGHNASA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DANCING' STEPS TO THE BEAT OF IRISH SISTERHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Pat O'Connor (``Cal,'' ``Circle of Friends'') has
performed a small miracle in that he's improved Brian Friel's Tony
award-winning play, ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' by cutting its running
time. As a result, the film version is a more haunting, honed,
actors' tour-de-force.
</P>
<P>
   The play, about five sisters named Mundy who lived on the
ignitable brink of Ireland's involvement with World War II, hit
Broadway at a moment when we were vulnerable to everything Irish:
Jim Sheridan's anti-British films; Michael Whelan and
``Riverdance;'' Enya. It may have lulled us into complacency
against what really composes a good yarn. Still, this film makes no
bones about what makes it tick: It's the visual appeal of the
rugged Donegal countryside, and more, the fine cast.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep (and yes, her Irish accent is impeccable) plays
Kate Mundy, the oldest sister, who is a school teacher on the brink
of losing her job, and who bears the responsibility for her family.
The pressure has aged Kate and turned her into a sour, worried
soul.
</P>
<P>
   But the never-ending Irish economic depression and an impending
world war hasn't daunted the spirits of her four younger siblings:
Maggie (Kathy Burke), Agnes (Brid Brennan, who starred in the
original play); the simple, childlike Rose (Sophie Thompson) and
the ``baby,'' Christina (Catherine McCormack), who has borne a son
named Michael (Darrell Johnston), the film's grown-up narrator who
comments upon his childhood in a voiceover soliloquy as poignant as
a James Joyce story in ``Dubliners.''
</P>
<P>
   Into this matriarchy return two men: big brother Jack (Michael
Gambon), who has been a priest in a leper colony in Africa for 25
years, and Gerry Evans (Rhys Ifans), dad to Michael, who stops in
to say goodbye (and cadge a bit of ``love'' from obliging
girlfriend, Christina) before joining the anti-Fascist army in
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The intrusions will create upheaval, strife and separation among
the women, yet through their differences, they will bond for a
final dance, performed with great, unequivocal joy by both the
actresses and O'Connor's cinema verite camera _ to give us a
symbolic swan song to the old way of Irish family life, where
everyone looked after their own, against a new, more callous,
greedy world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' owes much to the actresses, who latch
onto the unique survival instincts of the Mundy clan. Each is so
distinct that they endear us to them in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Streep shows bitter regret as a woman forced to bear the brunt
of responsibility but who lets loose with small hints of a girl who
probably was a knockout _ and a flirt _ in her youth. And McCormack
is smashing as Christina,who is as beautiful as she is
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Burke, who won a best actress award at Cannes for ``Nil
by Mouth,'' and who played Queen Mary in the recent hit
``Elizabeth,'' who is the warm hearth and soul. Her Maggie is the
nostalgic keeper of the home fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is a film of small, intimate moments
that, upon scrutiny, don't amount to much. Still, those moments are
visually fine, neatly acted and linger in the memory, though they
fail to become anything more than the sum of their parts.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing at Lughnasa. Directed by Pat O'Connor. Written by Brian
Friel, Frank McGuiness. Cast: Meryl Streep, Catherine McCormack,
Michael Gambon, Bris Brennan, Sophie Thompson, Kathy Burke. Sony
Pictures Classics. 94 minutes. Rated PG for mild language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
