</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-VOICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LITTLE VOICE' STRAINS REACHING FOR THE BIG SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Little Voice'' is an example of a movie that's been limited by
its theatrical roots. It's based on the London stage play by Jim
Cartwright, which was written specially for actress Jane Horrocks,
who was a growly marvel in Mike Leigh's ``Life Is Sweet'' and the
air-headed Bubble on the defunct BBC comedy ``Absolutely
Fabulous.'' And the film falters every minute Horrocks isn't center
stage.
</P>
<P>
   In its heart it's a small, fragile piece about a misfit of a
girl struggling with unresolved pain over the death of her dad, who
likewise lived in a fantasy world of music and soulful torch songs.
But it evolves into a chafing oddity about middle-aged angst and
envy. And in a work that demands delicate balancing, guess who
wins? Unfortunately, the loudest half, which co-star Brenda Blethyn
screechingly provides in spades.
</P>
<P>
   Little Voice, or LV (Horrocks), lives in a squalid flat with her
desperate, blowsy and boozy mum, Mari (Blethyn). Mari hates her
life and never quits complaining about the-rat trap existence she's
forced to lead because of inadequate financial planning by her late
husband. LV rarely speaks. She lives in a quiet place of music and
song. Only her beloved father's ghost can pull her out of her
terminal shyness and then she's able to impersonate Judy Garland,
Marilyn Monroe and Billie Holliday to a tee.
</P>
<P>
   One night mum scores and brings home fellow sadsack Ray Say
(Michael Caine), an equally down-on-his-luck talent agent, who just
happens to hear LV singing in her room. He believes she's his
ticket out of the low life he's been living for 40 years. Mom
thinks otherwise and she jealously carps over the attention he pays
LV _ until she shuts up long enough to hear for herself and then
forms her own greedy plan.
</P>
<P>
   Director Mark Herman (``Brassed Off'') conducts with a heavy
hand and allows Blethyn and Caine to run roughshod over the quiet
center of the film. Fortunately Horrocks, who does her own singing
and is an extraordinary impersonator of the great Garland, Monroe
and Holliday, holds her own in this shaky melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Horrocks' touching, deeply felt performance,
``Little Voice'' is still essentially a cabaret act, and shoving
such an intimate, interior work onto big screen proportions sadly
magnifies its limitations and flaws, and ultimately the film is
sunk by sincere but over-extended, intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Little Voice. Directed and written by Mark Herman. Cast: Jane
Horrocks, Michael Caine, Brenda Blethyn, Ewan McGregor. Miramax
Films. 100 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1406EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
