<SLUG> BC-FILM-HURLY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERB CAST SPARKLES IN DARK AND MENACING `HURLYBURLY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The '80s come ragefully back to life in ``Hurlyburly'' _ adapted
from his play by David Rabe _ an angry-young-man, drug-addled look
at confusion and misogynism set in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurlyburly'' was staged off-Broadway by Joseph Papp after
Rabe's success with his Vietnam plays, ``Streamers'' and ``The
Basic Training of Pavel Hummel,'' and starred then up-and-coming
actors William Hurt, Harvey Keitel, Sigourney Weaver and
Christopher Walken. It was, above all, an actors' tour-de-force.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine topping that stellar cast, but director
Tony Drazen isn't apologizing for his lineup: Sean Penn won the
best actor prize at the Venice Film Festival for his portrayal of
the belligerent, bleeding-heart Eddie; Oscar winners Kevin Spacey
(who was an understudy in the original play) and the hardly
recognizable Anna Paquin as street-urchin innocent Donna; Garry
Shandling, Robin Wright Penn, Chazz Palminteri and Meg Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   They all contribute different kinds of threat and menace to the
frightening fantasy world called Hollywood, a place dominated by
drugs, money, testosterone and very little common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie is a casting agent who can't sustain a relationship with a
woman because he's so fearful and untrusting. His roommate is
Mickey (Spacey), an ace at seducing the opposite sex who tolerates
Eddie's rants and raves about the inequity of life in la-la land.
Eddie is struggling to maintain a relationship with Darlene (Wright
Penn) when Mickey moves in and sleeps with her, unleashing all of
Eddie's insecurity and rage.
</P>
<P>
   Men metaphorically wrestling with women, power and success are
the components that compose the frightening realm of
``Hurlyburly.'' Rabe acknowledges he was furious with the world
when he wrote the play and it is a worst-case scenario.
</P>
<P>
   That said, it's some of the best work the actors have done. Penn
is a marvel as Eddie and Spacey is equally deft as Mickey, his
chilly, methodical counterpoint. The pair face off in a bilious
testament to impotence and white male fury at what they perceive to
be female emasculation. But what these characters fail to
understand is they are each other's worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The characters teem with misery, futility and the inability to
emotionally connect in a business that can easily replace them,
where they face a slow, methodical death in a place where feeling
anything at all is a liability.
</P>
<P>
   Rabe's play was a microcosm for an era of greed and selfishness
and though the film feels dated, it manages to make references to
the '90s. It is less confined and claustrophobic and makes a point
about self-delusion and illusion in a town that's notorious for
both.
</P>
<P>
   Though its characters create their own hell on earth, we're
riveted to the screen. It's like watching a car crash; we can't
escape our guilty curiosity at watching human agony and pain.
</P>
<P>
   Hurlyburly. Directed by Anthony Drazen. Written by David Rabe.
Cast: Sean Penn, Kevin Spacey, Robin Wright Penn, Anna Paquin,
Garry Shandling, Chazz Palminteri, Meg Ryan. Fine Line Features.
122 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual content, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1407EST &QL; 
