<SLUG> BC-FILM-JOEYOUNG-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S `JOE YOUNG' IS MIGHTY DISAPPOINTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Did you see the intelligence?'' sighs awestruck zoologist
Gregg O'Hara (Bill Paxton) as he watches mythic Mighty Joe Young, a
titanic gorilla, interact with his best human friend, sexy Jill
Young (Charlize Theron).
</P>
<P>
   Gregg might be able to see some signs of intelligent life, but
in Disney's clunky ``remake'' of the 1949 black-and-white adventure
film ``Mighty Joe Young,'' we're unable to spot one iota of smarts.
Badly written, clumsily directed and only half-heartedly effective
in its visual ``gorilla'' effects, ``Mighty Joe Young'' largely
wastes its top-notch cast.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Paxton and Theron teeter on the brink of career
breakthroughs _ Paxton with ``A Simple Plan'' and Theron with Woody
Allen's ``Celebrity'' and the cover of ``Vanity Fair'' _ they
backslide with this tepid tale of Joe Young, a product of ``a gene
that pops up every four or five generations.''
</P>
<P>
   The gene has made Joe a gentle giant who, along with Jill, was
orphaned when young. Both Jill's mom, a Dian Fosseyish
primatologist studying the apes in the Pangani Mountains of Africa,
and Joe's, are murdered by evil poachers, Strasser (Rade
Sherbedgia) and Garth (Peter Firth).
</P>
<P>
   In his fear and fury, little Joe bites off Strasser's thumb and
finger, causing the man to harbor a vendetta against the great ape
that will last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Joe and Jill grow up happily together in the African hills and a
legend is born about the magnificient gorilla who is a sacred
guardian to the small village. Into their lives comes Gregg O'Hara,
intent on saving Joe from predators by moving him to an animal
preserve in California.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the hunters are hot on the trail. They capture Joe,
just as Jill captures Gregg's heart. Together Jill and Gregg must
race against time to rescue the innocent ape from imminent danger
and possible death.
</P>
<P>
   The 1949 ``Mighty Joe Young'' was itself a loose rehash of the
classic, ``King Kong.'' In the leads it starred Ben Johnson and
Terry Moore, a starlet who later claimed to be married to Howard
Hughes. And it had more humor, heart and edge than this wooden
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Paxton and Theron (and the rest of the actors) are saddled with
such inane, ridiculous lines that ``Mighty Joe Young'' is more of
an embarrassment than anything. Audiences need only recall the film
``Congo'' to get an idea of the dismal fate in store if they opt to
plunk down seven bucks, because in the end, the only star to emerge
undiminished is Joe himself, and that's because the big guy doesn't
have a speaking part.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Joe Young. Directed by Ron Underwood. Written by Mark
Rosenthal, Lawrence Konner. Cast: Charlize Theron, Bill Paxton,
Rade Sherbedgia, Regina King. Walt Disney Pictures. 114 minutes.
Rated PG for scenes depicting animal cruelty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
