<SLUG> BC-GIRLBROS-MUSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUL SISTERS _ ER, BROS.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; ``Girl Bros.'' is a strange title for a record
and an even odder name for a two-girl band.
</P>
<P>
   But the brooding disc by former Prince collaborators Wendy
Melvoin and Lisa Coleman _ the Girl Bros. _ is about to end up on
some 1998 best-of lists.
</P>
<P>
   Melvoin and Coleman have fashioned a dark, semi-acoustic effort
that responds to the death of Melvoin's brother, Smashing Pumpkins
road keyboardist Jonathan, who died of a heroin overdose in July
1996, prior to two shows at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Songs such as ``Bring You Back,'' ``I Will'' and ``Jonathan''
are often stark reminders of Wendy Melvoin's pain and confusion,
while the disc, produced by Latin Playboys member Tchad Blake,
never overlooks melody.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was written after my brother's death,'' Melvoin said.
``Part of it was experimentation. People deal with loss in
different ways. I live with the fact that my brother is dead every
day of my life. Things that used to be important don't seem to have
quite as much importance anymore. The small things don't make any
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends since childhood, Melvoin and Coleman joined Prince's
backup band, the Revolution, in the early '80s. When the Purple One
gave them a pink slip in 1986, Melvoin and Coleman began work on
their self-titled debut in which they played nearly all the
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the pair collaborated on Joni Mitchell's
``Chalk Mark in a Rainstorm.''
</P>
<P>
   Through five of their own albums, Melvoin and Coleman progressed
from a slick neo-psychedelic rock 'n' soul approach toward a
rockier sound. The pair also gained a reputation as song doctors
and co-wrote tunes for Seal's first two albums and helped out on
the soulful pop singer's just-released effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't concerned with the business of making my album
popular at all,'' said Melvoin, who plays guitar on ``My Favorite
Mistake,'' Sheryl Crow's current hit. ``I'm more concerned with
being a creative person and expressing my grace through creativity.
I'm not so interested in living the pop life at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvoin and Coleman, who have scored films for Babyface's
company, are doing sporadic shows in support of ``Girl Bros.'' and
plan collaborations with Me'Shell NdegeOcello.
</P>
<P>
   ``This music started with the two of us at home just trying
things out,'' Coleman said. ``Then, we decided to find a third pair
of ears. That's how Tcke got involved. It turned into a
three-person free-for-all. It was like, `Let's try this _ play that
shaker and put it through this effects peddle and make it
spookier.' We became great friends.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1409EST &QL; 
