<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONSERVATIVES-SENATE-     12-24 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSERVATIVES-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATIVE SENATORS WANT NO PART OF CENSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The idea of censuring President Clinton may be
gathering momentum in the Senate, but a dozen or more conservative
senators want nothing to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   The group includes Republican stalwarts such as Sen. John
Ashcroft of Missouri, Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania, Sen.
Robert Smith of New Hampshire, and Sen. James Inhofe of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not afraid to appear to be at odds with the elite
media viewpoint (favoring censure),'' said Peter Dickinson,
executive director of the Campaign for Working Families, which
raised over $2 million for over 200 mostly Republican
``pro-family'' candidates last November. ``They're the ones who
would question the validity of short- term polls as a guide for
long-term results.''
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions of the group and how much clout it has are open
to debate. There are 55 Republicans and 45 Democrats in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   These conservative ``true believers'' oppose abortion and are
outspoken on other conservative issues such as tax cuts and
privatizing Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to Clinton's impeachment, this group dismisses the
possibility of a Senate censure as ``virtually nothing,'' as Inhofe
put it in an interview. When the Senate reconvenes in January,
these senators are likely to push for a full trial of Clinton on
the two impeachment articles approved by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction in a Senate trial requires a two-thirds vote _ 67
senators and Inhofe acknowledged that the odds of getting 67 votes
are remote.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Inhofe said by telephone from his office in Tulsa,
``I think we should go on with a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look 10, 20 years into the future and the possibility
of a corrupt president in office, we have to make sure we protect
this constitutional process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Inhofe expressed puzzlement about those senators who favor
censure on the basis that there aren't 67 votes now in favor of
convicting Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can (senators) come to the conclusion that the votes are
not there if we haven't weighed the evidence,'' Inhofe said. ``The
White House fears something we don't know may be brought out at
trial. Prejudging the disposition of this is not appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The conservative senators do little to hide their personal
contempt for Clinton. Ashcroft has called for Clinton to resign
because he has ``disgraced himself (and) broken faith with the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   But they also are doubtful that censure of a president is
constitutionally permissible. The Constitution directs the Senate
to hold a trial after the House votes to impeach a president, but
says nothing about censure.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hickey, spokeswoman for Smith of New Hampshire, said
Smith's ``interpretation of the Constitution is that there should
be a Senate trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Other senators are miffed at being overlooked in what they see
as a head-long, media-driven rush to embrace censure.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of my colleagues think this band wagon is gaining
speed,'' Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., told the New York Times.
``Well, nobody called me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate is a far more collegial body than the combative
House, so it is very possible a consensus for censure could arise
over the protests of these senators.
</P>
<P>
   But there are multiple layers of complicating factors. A major
one: A censure deal might require an admission from Clinton that he
lied under oath about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky,
something he has denied. In a television interview with the Rev.
Jesse Jackson to be aired Sunday on CNN, Vice President Al Gore
reiterated Clinton's unwillingness to admit lying.
</P>
<P>
   If the censure movement does not gain more altitude by the time
senators return to Washington next month, the hardline
conservatives may find themselves in the driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that they want to see Clinton strung up,'' said Keith
Appell, an Alexandria, Va.-based political consultant whose clients
include conservatives. ``It's that they believe the process should
adhere to the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   By their very nature, conservatives are bound to the words of
the Constitution and not well disposed to any solution outside its
four corners, Appell said, adding: ``They look at censure as more
of a political quick fix or a Bandaid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1421EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
