A5799 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT25-COX     12-24 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, Dec. 25, 1998.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TAX-MIG-PBP _ WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service is
denying $4.68 million in tax deductions by MIG Management Services
Inc. of West Palm Beach. The IRS ruled that the company's taxable
income should be increased by that amount, because two real estate
ventures are not exempt from federal taxes as the company claimed
on its 1994-95 returns. (Moskal).
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Palm Beach editors.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KIOSK-PAROLE _ As Georgia struggles to balance the increasing
cost of its burgeoning Corrections Department, it is trying a new
approach with people on probation: trust. In metro Atlanta and in
Clarke County, the state is allowing its best probationers to work
on the honor system by reporting to a machine, instead of a person.
The probationer goes to a kiosk, usually in a state building,
inserts a fingerprint card and then responds electronically to a
series of question, such as whether he/she has recently used drugs.
Although the program is in its second year, the state has no
accurate measure of its success because the states tracks probation
recidivism on a three-year cycle. However, the chief probation
officer expects little problems with the 3,000 or so people who
choose this route. Because there is an extra $10 monthly fee for
this type of probation reporting system, the people who do it have
to volunteer. There is reality here, tho. Corrections officials
readily admit that the machines, also being tested in a few other
cities nationwide, can not replace occasional personal contact.
(Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS If a budget line or story is marked
with photos or graphics, those are available from the New York
Times News Service at 212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more
information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
