<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Dec.
25, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SHAKESPEARE (Undated) _ ``Shakespeare In Love'' is a bawdy,
raucous, clever ``skirmish of words.'' Not only is it lovingly,
even lavishly, scribed and staged, it's a great romp of a romance
with real heart in its soul.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-STEPMOM (Undated) _ ``Stepmom'' is this season's contender
for the ``weeper of the week'' award, with a pervasive tug at the
heartstrings that should appeal to viewers and Oscar voters. But it
rises above TV-movie-of-the-week sensibility only through the star
power of its exceptional cast. It's another case of virtuoso acting
elevating a mediocre script to a higher level.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-DELTA (Undated) _ Acclaimed writer and preeminent poet Dr.
Maya Angelou makes her directorial debut with ``Down in the
Delta.'' Unfortunately, there are few remarkable moments to give
her first film as much emotion and raw power as her rich, textured
stories.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-LUGHNASA (Undated) _ Director Pat O'Connor (``Cal,''
``Circle of Friends'') has performed a small miracle in that he's
improved Brian Friel's Tony award-winning play, ``Dancing at
Lughnasa'' by cutting its running time. As a result, the film
version is a more haunting, honed, actors' tour-de-force.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-VOICE (Undated) _ Despite Jane Horrocks' touching, deeply
felt performance, ``Little Voice'' is essentially a cabaret act,
and shoving such an intimate, interior work onto big screen
proportions sadly magnifies its limitations and flaws. Ultimately
the film is sunk by sincere but over-extended, intentions.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HURLY (Undated) _ The '80s come ragefully back to life in
``Hurlyburly'' _ adapted from his play by David Rabe _ an
angry-young-man, drug-addled look at confusion and misogynism set
in Los Angeles. Rabe's play was a microcosm for an era of greed and
selfishness. Though its characters create their own hell on earth,
we're riveted to the screen. It's like watching a car crash; we
can't escape our guilty curiosity at watching human agony and pain.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-JOEYOUNG (Undated) _ In Disney's clunky ``remake'' of the
1949 black-and-white adventure film ``Mighty Joe Young,'' we're
unable to spot one iota of smarts. Badly written, clumsily directed
and only half-heartedly effective in its visual ``gorilla''
effects, ``Mighty Joe Young'' largely wastes its top-notch cast.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FACULTY (Undated) _ ``The Faculty'' is short on scares and
rates only average marks for such a blatant, if occasionally
amusing, Cliff's Notes version of better, more inspired B-movies.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-THIEL-COLUMN (Honolulu) _ With the University of Washington
Huskies preparing for the Oahu Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKC-HUSKIES (Seattle) _ University of Washington hosts New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   By Bud Withers. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
