<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MITCH-AFTERMATH-2TAKE     12-24 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MITCH-AFTERMATH-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAITH BLOSSOMS AMID THE RUINS IN STORM-RAVAGED NICARAGUA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYCHE HENDRICKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   POSOLTEGA, Nicaragua _ A few days after Dominga Roja was flooded
out of her home by the hurricane called Mitch, she went back to
inspect the damage. Her house, like almost every other home in
Villa Sandino, was destroyed by the raging water and mud, but she
rescued two precious possessions: her rooster and her Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, as the rooster strutted around her small room in a
makeshift refugee center on an abandoned cotton farm here, Roja
clutched the Bible to her chest for comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all wet when I found it,'' said the 60-year-old widow,
looking through the stiff, wrinkled pages, ``but I rescued it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep it in my bed beside me,'' she added. ``I can't read,
but when I have it here, it protects me.''
</P>
<P>
   The rooster, however, may be turned into soup for a holiday
supper to share with fellow refugees, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Josepha Aleman, 39, who was also flooded out of her home and
who, like Roja, is a Pentecostal, said the devastation had not
shaken her faith in God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more faith now,'' she said. ``The water was up to our
chests all night but thanks to God, we got out alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Roja and Aleman are among the Nicaraguan peasants who lost their
homes and belongings in the hurricane that began Oct. 26 and
hovered over Central America for days, killing 9,000 people and
leaving as many as 2 million others homeless in Honduras,
Nicaragua, El Salvador and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the woman have managed to keep their hopes up thanks in part
to their devout religious faith.
</P>
<P>
   As in many Latin American countries, religion has long played an
important role in Nicaraguan culture. In the weeks following the
storm, many Nicaraguans have grasped even more firmly to their
faith in an attempt to come to terms with the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Nicaraguans are Catholics, although
evangelical Protestant denominations have attracted roughly 25
percent of the population in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   To protect itself from any potential charges of mismanagement,
the Nicaraguan government designated the Catholic Church to deliver
much of the humanitarian aid that the country received after the
hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Catholic Church is not neutral, and it's not universal,''
said Carlos Fernando Chamorro, a magazine editor and son of former
Nicaraguan President Violeta Chamorro. ``But there's no doubt that
the church is the most credible institution in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Catholic nuns from orders such as the Daughters of
Charity of St. Vincent de Paul have come from other Latin American
countries, including Mexico, Guatemala and Bolivia, to work with
traumatized Nicaraguan children and find homes for orphans.
</P>
<P>
   On the Saturday before Christmas, a Catholic priest from the
regional capital of Chinandega visited the village of Tololar to
say a Mass for the more than 2,000 people who died on or near the
Casita Volcano. On Oct. 29, after three days of torrential rain,
the wall of a crater lake at the top of the volcano collapsed,
unleashing a flood of water, followed by a massive mudslide, onto
the villages scattered down the volcano's western slope.
</P>
<P>
   Tololar, which sits at the foot of the volcano in the township
of Posoltega, has become a center for refugees who survived when
their villages were wiped out. More than 300 people gathered in the
town plaza for the Mass, leading their well-scrubbed children and
dressed in their Sunday best, which for many now consists of
donated clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The event not only brought the shaken community together, but
through the familiar ecclesiastical rituals, gave people a sense of
security and a chance to reaffirm their compact with God.
</P>
<P>
   Because the village has no church, residents had built a frame
of wooden poles, covered it with a green tarpaulin, made walls of
palm fronds and decorated the improvised chapel with white and
yellow balloons.
</P>
<P>
   As a church leader strummed a guitar, a group of children sang a
hymn to welcome the priest, the Rev. Marcos Dessy, a Sardinian who
has lived and preached in Nicaragua for 25 years and runs a
charitable foundation in Chinandega.
</P>
<P>
   With the wind blowing dust across the plaza and stray dogs
wandering through the crowd, people filed into the chapel. Those
who could not fit peered in through the palm leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lord, remember those who have died tragically in the landslide
of the Casita Volcano,'' Dessy said through a bullhorn so all could
hear. ``Accept them into your kingdom and give them peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As women dabbed their eyes with handkerchiefs, and old men
shifted their bare feet in the dust, he continued: ``It's true some
of us leave this earth before others, and we thank you for those
who were with us and have gone. But let us sing with joy that we
are alive here today.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Then, gesturing to the children in the front row, several of
whom had been orphaned by the storm, the priest said: ``When these
children here grow old, I want them to be able to say, `By God's
will, we have survived.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outside the tent, Jasmina Herrera, 34, hugged her two young
daughters as she listened to the priest's words. She had come to
the Mass, she said, to bid goodbye to her brother, her pregnant
sister, her sister's husband and seven nieces and nephews, ranging
in age from 3 to 12, who were swept away by a wall of water and
mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to accept,'' she said. ``The children's bodies
were never found.''
</P>
<P>
   And she had come to say a prayer of thanks that her daughters,
Marta Lorena, 9, and Jessica, 6, were spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the water swept us out of our house, the current ripped
her away from me,'' she said, stroking Jessica's curls. ``I thought
she was lost, but a neighbor rescued her. My daughter says it was
the Virgin who saved her, and I think it's true. My girls are more
dear to me now, and the Virgin is, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Nubia Fletes, another villager attending the Mass, admitted the
disaster had challenged her faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first few days we asked, `Lord, we're your creatures.
Why did you do this to us?''' she said. ``But eventually we
resigned ourselves, because what happened was his will. Now we
realize he can give us strength to endure these hard times. If we
reach out to each other, as the priest said, we will survive
this.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the challenge of the moment is to get through the
holiday season without their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mass, the villagers set up a pinata for the children
and the priest handed out toys from the back of a pick-up truck.
Dozens of eager boys and girls crowded around, waiting for their
names to be called to receive a baby doll, a rubber ball or a bag
of plastic animals.
</P>
<P>
   Holding his 2-year-old daughter and with his 5-year-old son
dancing around his legs, Jose Anastasio Chavarria said that with
his home and its contents washed away, the small gifts were
especially welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, Christmas is a happy time,'' added the 37-year-old
farmer. ``My family always has a big party, but we're too sad this
year. How can we have a party when so many people have died?''
</P>
<P>
   In a nearby refugee camp set up in a community named for Pope
John XXIII, Mariana Mendez Canale, 60, talked with her neighbors
about losing her husband when their village of El Porvenir was
buried by mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing we can do,'' she said. ``When the Lord calls
us, it's our time to go. But it's a sadness that has no name.''
</P>
<P>
   Then her face brightened as she remembered a remarkable moment
in the midst of the terrifying storm. Like Aleman, Herrera and
scores of others overwhelmed by the apocalyptic proportions of the
disaster, Mendez found a miracle in the simple survival of
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man was struggling in the current when a cow came swimming
by,'' she recounted. ``He climbed on that cow, and he was riding
along when he saw a little girl in the water. He scooped her up and
put her on the cow. Then he saw a little boy, and he scooped him up
too, and he got those kids to safety. The cow saved their lives.
That was the Lord's work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
