<HEADLINE>
`STEPMOM' GOES SLOW BEFORE THE TEARS FLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Heavy hankie films such as ``Terms of Endearment,''
``Gone With the Wind,'' ``Fried Green Tomatoes'' and ``Unstrung
Heroes'' always kill off the loving mom, orphaning the needy kids.
</P>
<P>
   If they killed off the father, it wouldn't be a tragedy because
Dad's not around much anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' carries that idea one step further: Not only is Mom
loath to leave her beloved children behind, she also is curdling
inside about leaving them to be raised by her ex-husband's new
trophy wife.
</P>
<P>
   This conflict and the ensuing tears make ``Stepmom'' a
damp-hankie experience for mothers and others from fractured or
blended families.
</P>
<P>
   The story begins in the state of hate with Jackie (Susan
Sarandon) and her two children directing their venom toward Isabel
(Julia Roberts), a busy career woman trying to treat the kids right
when they're in her charge half time.
</P>
<P>
   The harder Isabel works to make 12-year-old Anna (Jena Malone)
like her, the meaner Anna acts.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship shifts when Anna realizes that having a
younger stepmom who knows something about makeup and how to destroy
boys has its advantages.
</P>
<P>
   Jackie shifts when she learns she has cancer and needs to come
to terms with the woman who may play a bigger role than she will in
her children's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' spends the first half wallowing in lumbering vitriol
at a pace that realistically reflects much of child-rearing: It's
repetitive, often boring, brightened by brief moments when someone
says something worth listening to.
</P>
<P>
   The film then veers for the tears when the goodbye looks start
to dominate. The second half has more energy and a stronger gift
for the audience: the sense that caring for children is the most
important reward you can give yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Director Chris Columbus usually makes family comedies: ``Home
Alone,'' ``Mrs. Doubtfire,'' ``Jingle all the Way.'' With Stepmom,
he wants to show that he can handle serious family stories, but he
too often mistakes lethargy for profundity.
</P>
<P>
   The script hits most of the parenting issues but has little to
say about them that we haven't seen in countless advice columns.
</P>
<P>
   Sarandon and Roberts have powerful moments _ usually when
they're not talking but allowing the camera to linger over the
emotional turbulence in their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and Sarandon doubled as producers. Considering the film
was made for women, by women and about women, it's odd they turned
to a man to direct it.
</P>
<P>
   Rated PG-13, ``Stepmom'' should have received an R for
profanity. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
