<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-HEROES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A YEAR OF SPORTS, RUNNERS-UP CAPTIVATED US WITH CLASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mark McGwire and Tara Lipinski, the large and
short of it in big-time sports this year, were captivating in
victory, he with the bear hugs for his son, she with the wide-eyed
yelps as her jumps finished perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't be more different, in girth or in deed. But they
had a bond, and what they shared made 1998 a special time in the
sports world.
</P>
<P>
   What they each had was spectacular runner-up, a second fiddle
who played the right tune.
</P>
<P>
   There was Sammy Sosa blowing kisses to his family, to his rival,
to a home country smitten with the possibilities that he
represented.
</P>
<P>
   And there was Michelle Kwan, who let Olympic gold get away but
held onto her extraordinary grace, who at age 17 had the poise to
say that life guaranteed her no prizes, no matter how hard she
worked for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``C'est la vie, right?'' she said, defining herself in a single
phrase, a perfect mixture of the sophisticated and the
down-to-earth.
</P>
<P>
   That was the best one-liner of the year, although Sosa came
close. ``Mark is The Man,'' he kept saying, as if he and Kwan were
collaborating on a new guidebook to sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   And, oh, how we need a book like that.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. male hockey players certainly could have used copies in
Nagano. But they may have used them as projectiles, tossing them
out a dorm window.
</P>
<P>
   It's not too late, though, for the hockey players to absorb the
lessons of Sosa and Kwan. Someone could still come forward and take
responsibility for throwing furniture through the Olympic Village
windows. The culprits remain in hiding, compounding their
disrespect for the finest hosts an Olympic Games could hope to have
with profound cowardice and a disdain for their teammates, who are
all implicated as long as the real perpetrators stay silent.
</P>
<P>
   They brought sports to a low this year, in a competition almost
as tight as the home-run race and the figure-skating final.
</P>
<P>
   The distinction could have gone to the International Olympic
Committee and its ``Hey bidder, do you have a dime?'' approach to
picking host cities. The lords of the rings will have to settle for
a special award in the crass shakedown division, a tough category
these days, at the peak of the build-me-a-stadium-or-else era in
American professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   The National Basketball Association and its locked-out players
could have been contenders for the overall low-point crown, but
they seem to be striving for irrelevance, and who wants to stand in
their way?
</P>
<P>
   The jury is still out on the doping revelations at the Tour de
France and McGwire's well-publicized use of a fishy dietary
supplement. The riders in the Tour defended their scandalized
brethren, a triumph of cynicism. On the other hand, any open debate
on this subject is worthwhile, and McGwire, though he broke no
rules, forced baseball to confront whether it should follow other
sports and ban androstenedione.
</P>
<P>
   But even open, enlightened debate has a downside. In this case,
it advertised McGwire's use of the supplement to kids, who have
made it a dangerous athletic fad. That's a dubious portion of
1998's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The year closes with another large uncertainty. Did we see the
last of Michael Jordan, basketball player? Charles Barkley says
yes, but if we believed everything Charles Barkley says, we'd be
living a never-ending hallucination.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Jordan doesn't belong to 1998. He's the athlete of
the decade, and even in the year of the glorious runner-up, we
can't find anyone close to him.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL was more obliging. In early 1998, it found a Super Bowl
to suit John Elway, a runner-up who finally broke through.
</P>
<P>
   Later, it saw Buffalo, the ultimate also-ran, link up with a
castoff quarterback for a new spin on a heartwarming holiday tale:
Doug Flutie as Rudolph the Red-Nosed Reindeer. Dismissed for being
different, Flutie proved that conformity stinks.
</P>
<P>
   As the NFL season comes to a close, the year of the runner-up
has morphed into the year of the backup on a comeback. Randall
Cunningham and Vinny Testaverde join Flutie in this scenario, all
of them hailing from the island of misfit quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But as a whole, the year belonged to the sluggers and the
skaters. The winners conducted themselves admirably. McGwire went
after the difficult, uncomfortable issue of childhood sexual abuse
as if it were a fat fastball over the middle of the plate. Lipinski
chose to stay in the Olympic Village and attend the Opening
Ceremonies, to enjoy every moment of her Nagano experience, not
just the gold-medal part.
</P>
<P>
   But neither of them would have been as compelling if it weren't
for the two people behind them. Sosa's beaming face cast a
wonderful light on McGwire. His smoking bat put more fire in
McGwire's swing.
</P>
<P>
   On his own, McGwire would have passed Roger Maris. But 70 home
runs? Sosa, charging at him with 66, pushed Big Mac to that level.
</P>
<P>
   On the ice, Kwan's skating defied anyone to be better, and when
Lipinski was, the accomplishment was that much greater. When
Lipinski accepted her gold medal, Kwan watched her carefully,
waiting for just the right moment to step over and hug the new
champion. She didn't want to intrude on any of the applause, on any
of Lipinski's bowing to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan had cried privately in her mother's arms and then was done
with it. After that, whenever tears started to come, she pushed
them back and smiled bashfully, determined not to show an ounce of
self-pity.
</P>
<P>
   This year produced a lot of amazing numbers: 70 for McGwire, 66
for Sosa, $105 million for Kevin Brown, a sixth crown for Jordan
and the Bulls, 15 years for Lipinski, the youngest skating gold
medalist in history. But the best of them all, the one that usually
connotes also-rans, the one that gained unexpected prestige, was
the No. 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1541EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
