</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG SHAKESPEARE FINDS HIS JULIET IN BAWDY COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED ``But, soft! what light through yonder window breaks? It
is the east, and Ethel is the sun!'' Ethel?
</P>
<P>
   That's what might have happened to Juliet if an uninspired
Shakespeare had finished his for-hire comedy, ``Romeo and Ethel,
the Pirate's Daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Bard struggles through his writer's block in
amazing, amusing fashion in the bright, witty romp, ``Shakespeare
in Love.'' This romantic comedy takes an askew look at
Shakespeare's times and comes up with the holiday season's smartest
delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' is a joy for people who love
Shakespeare's plays, but it is also fun for people who run at the
mention of his name, afraid they'll never understand what he's
talking about with all that Elizabethan English.
</P>
<P>
   Because so little is known about the great playwright's personal
life, director John Madden and his writing team take liberties with
Shakespeare _ just as the Bard took with Julius Caesar or Richard
III. They use Shakespeare for their own purposes, making nasty
sport of two centuries: the 16th and our own.
</P>
<P>
   They've imagined Will Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) as a rakish
writer, employed by the lesser of London's two theaters to devise
some trivial comedy that will attract enough riffraff to keep the
creditors at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare is miserably unhappy, unable to write, even unable
to chase women. But he is pressed by the head of his theatrical
troupe, who is in debt to Elizabethan gangsters, to write
something, anything that will amuse the masses and shake free some
coins.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to write low comedy, Shakespeare finds an
inspiration for grand passion through Lady Viola (Gwyneth Paltrow),
daughter of a wealthy family who yearns for adventure and the
poetry of the theater.
</P>
<P>
   English women at that time were not allowed to act upon the
disreputable stage. So Viola disguises herself as a man and
auditions for Shakespeare's new play, winning the role of the young
Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   When Will discovers that his lead actor is really the flame of
his heart, they rehearse romance during the day and practice it at
night.
</P>
<P>
   But their idyllic passion is star-crossed, threatened by the
arrogant nobleman (Colin Firth) to whom Viola is betrothed.
</P>
<P>
   From these elements, director Madden fashions a wicked comedy
that is as romantic, bawdy and funny as anything Shakespeare wrote
to please the audiences of his day.
</P>
<P>
   Madden (``Mrs. Brown'') directs with great vigor and irreverence
but also with a deep love for the power of the theater to move
men's hearts. He amplifies the tale with Hollywood in jokes and
analogies to moviemaking to brighten the fun and give the story
resonance for our time.
</P>
<P>
   The sophisticated script _ rich in repartee, mistaken identity
and foiled passions _ comes from Marc Norman (Waterworld'') and Tom
Stoppard (``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead''). They capture
the boisterous egos of the buffoons who people Shakespeare's world
and toss in a wealth of wit that will delight theater lovers.
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare, a master of ribald comedy, would be proud to be
pictured as the hero of a tale that lives up to his standards.
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow (Sliding Doors'') makes a wonderful Juliet, and quite a
good Romeo.
</P>
<P>
   As the ink-stained wretch whose importance to history is
completely missed by his contemporaries, Fiennes makes an inspired
rogue. He is far better here than in the costume drama
``Elizabeth,'' where he can also be seen murking about in the same
century.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars still argue about the details of Shakespeare's life,
indeed, about whether he or someone else wrote his plays. So, the
liberties taken by the film's writers and director seem entirely
appropriate because they're done in the name of fun.
</P>
<P>
   These embellishments illuminate the maneuverings of a playwright
using his wits to keep wine in his cup. The movie invites us to
rejoice in the excitement of the theater. It's an invitation you
should accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' is rated R for nudity and sex. The love
scenes are far more bawdy than anything Shakespeare dared to hint
at in his plays. 5 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1546EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
