<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIGITAL-TECH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL HAPPENING AT THE ZOOG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While everyone is puzzling over when exactly the
convergence of computer, television and Internet will happen, the
Disney Channel actually is trying to do something about it with its
Zoog Disney offerings on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The cycle starts on Sunday nights, when a two-hour block of
programming targeted at children between 9 and 14 is overlaid with
a variety of animated show hosts called Zoogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to really create an entertainment experience that
converged the two interests in our audience,'' said Eleo Hensleigh,
the Disney Channel's senior vice president of marketing. ``They
spend a lot of time with television, a lot of time with the
Internet. We want to make sure we're where kids are spending
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zoogs prompt viewers to go online, where they act as online
guides to contests, chat rooms, discussion areas, games, polls,
``shoutouts'' and more, all of it related to themes from that
week's programs, Hensleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   The site then takes the children's responses and incorporates
them into the reruns of the shows the next Saturday, Hensleigh
said. The Zoogs show high scores in the games, contest winners,
shoutouts and more.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out how to get viewers to also get on the Web site was
a tricky proposition for the channel, which doesn't want to
cannibalize its audience. It's less of an issue for a
commercial-free outlet such as Disney, but Hensleigh said company
officials thought hard about how to knit together the Web and TV
experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to see this new medium to be a replacement for
television, it's to broaden the experience,'' said Hensleigh.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment has paid off big time since it began Aug. 7,
Hensleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've seen is, most importantly, a 50-percent increase in
9- to 11-year-old (TV viewers) in that day part,'' Hensleigh said.
``And we've basically seen a 350 percent increase in our online
traffic. We're now the No. 1-trafficked site on Disney.com. That's
a robust site but we have been the most trafficked area.''
</P>
<P>
   It also may help Disney deal with the difficult transition it
faces in keeping its young fans' attention as they lurch toward
puberty and more sophisticated viewing desires, Hensleigh said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we embrace this computer and online world, we've moved
that acceptance level with older kids just a little bit,''
Hensleigh said. ``As they grow older, it's a challenge for
Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as figuring out how to marry the Internet and television
has proved a challenge to virtually everyone in either business.
Zoogs, however preliminary, offers a glimpse of what that future
might hold.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOUND OF SUCCESS: For most of the past two decades, Donald
Katz wrote about technology for publications such as Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's busy creating technology that lets you listen to
publications such as the Wall Street Journal as well as such audio
treasures as John Cleese reading Dante's ``Inferno'' or Walt
Whitman reading his own ``Leaves of Grass,'' with Thomas Edison on
the sound board.
</P>
<P>
   What he's done with Audible Inc. is create a Web site
(www.audible.com) loaded with 17,000 hours of programming that you
can buy inexpensively over the Internet. And his company also makes
a listening device that copies the audio files from your computer
so you can listen to them anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's moved into the world of audio, Katz and his company
remain dependent on print resources as the basis for nearly all
their recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Print is still the mother lode of information,'' said Katz
during a recent promotional swing through Los Angeles. ``When you
think about Audible, all it does is leverage the superior impact of
print over a new medium. People who love this love reading so much
that they want to extend that to places where they can't read.''
</P>
<P>
   It's actually a wonderful idea: Use the Internet and home
computers to cheaply distribute a vast array of digital
information; listen to it on a tiny player that links to the
computer, sort of like the tiny MP-3 music players from Diamond
Multimedia and Saehan.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is so smart that it has attracted a Murderers' Row of
heavy hitter investors, and dozens of content partners.
</P>
<P>
   The product itself is cheap, only $99 if you agree to buy at
least $10 of content every month for a year. That'll get you the
Wall Street Journal and a book a month. If you don't buy the
subscription, the player costs $199.
</P>
<P>
   Among the zillions of other products are Ezra Pound and the
Harvard Business Review, Alan Greenspan speeches and National
Public Radio's ``Fresh Air,'' Stephen King's ``Bag of Bones'' and
the Starr Report, self-help tomes and audio book thrillers.
</P>
<P>
   And you soon won't need the Audible player to take your
information with you, Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, free player software will be available for owners of
Windows CE-based hand-held computers and personal digital
assistants. And in March, the software will be standard issue on
the machines sold by four manufacturers, Katz said.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is getting interest from companies who see it as
a way to distribute such in-house information as product
descriptions and motivational speeches to their sales forces, Katz
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company also is coming out soon with a beefed-up version of
its player, making it capable of storing seven hours of recordings,
compared to the current two, Katz said. New software will include
cover art and author information with each download.
</P>
<P>
   So what's that you hear? It's the Audible sound of a great idea
coming.
</P>
<P>
   FACE TO INTERFACE: And from music critic Fred Shuster comes a
Web recommendation for all you underground music fans. It's called
InterFACE Pirate Radio and is the legal Internet successor to an
illegal broadcaster in London spinning great drum-and-bass, jungle,
house and other electronic dance music.
</P>
<P>
   The music streams in on the RealPlayer plug-in for your Web
browser, but even cooler is the ability to talk with the disc
jockeys and other listeners in an online chat room and to watch a
video feed of the DJs as they mix and play music. Point your
Internet radio dial to www.interface.pirate-radio.co.uk.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE PALM OF YOUR HAND: If you have a PalmPilot, those
delightful little personal organizer gadgets that are proliferating
like mosquitoes in a Minnesota summer, you should check out the
PalmPilot Gear HQ, at www.pilotgear.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has hundreds of downloadable software files for the
Palm Pilot and its successor, the Palm III, along with answers to
basic technical support questions, and information about
accessories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
