<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOT-TIPS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE MARRYING MAN' GETS GROOMS IN LINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Brides get the guy, the gown, and all the showers
held in their honor.
</P>
<P>
   But they also do most of the work. Remember how George's fiancee
died from licking all that cheap glue on the wedding invitations in
``Seinfeld''?
</P>
<P>
   Miz Hot Tips thinks George should have been helping, but then he
didn't know the rules. He didn't have ``The Marrying Man,'' a
groom's guide published by the Men's Apparel Group.
</P>
<P>
   It says the groom and his family are supposed to help the bride
with all kinds of stuff, like paying for the bride's engagement and
wedding rings, the marriage license, the boutonnieres for the
ushers, accommodations for out-of-town attendants, the rehearsal
dinner, the minister's honorarium and the honeymoon. On the latter,
the groom should book the hotel at least two months in advance.
</P>
<P>
   And one month in advance he'll need to get the marriage license,
arrange for tuxedo fittings, and have his insurance policies and
bank accounts adjusted to accommodate his new wife.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet has a glossary of fashion terms, so you'll know that
cutaway coats are for weddings between 11 a.m. and 4 p.m., that
white dinner jackets are for spring and summer, and that white tie
is the ultimate choice for formal weddings any time of day or
night.
</P>
<P>
   For a free copy, write to Marrying Man, care of Ogan/Dallal,
1185 Avenue of the Americas, New York, N.Y. 10036.
</P>
<P>
   BABY TALK: Just when you thought the yuppie puppy trend was
gone, the Gap brings it back. Miz Hot Tips is talking about the
store's new line of luxe looks for the diaper set, featuring
elegant outfits made of velvet, silk and cashmere. There's even a
tuxedo vest-and-pant set for $84, designed for the child who never
spits up or leaks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Origins cosmetics is busy on a new line of toiletries
for toddlers that will hit cosmetic counters in March. Origins will
include Short Cake baby cleansing bars, First Sun chemical-free
lotions and Powder Puff baby powder.
</P>
<P>
   And they're not the only ones wiping baby's bottom with pricey
products. Start looking for Bubbe's Special Cream for Special
Tushies, Kiehl's Diaper Rash Treatment Cream and Baby Bee products
at department stores in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S IN THE BAG: Pet carriers are the latest fad, and as any
trendie knows, labels do count. For the fashion-conscious, Chanel
has created a black nylon carrier with red lining for $385. It's
even quilted like Chanel's signature purse design.
</P>
<P>
   OH, DONNA: Donna Karan may not be dressing Demi Moore anymore,
but Miz Hot Tips heard that the New York designer has the entire
cast of Fox's ``That '70s Show'' wearing her DKNY jeans and
activewear. According to DKNY president Mary Wilberding, ``It's a
match dressed in heaven ... since both are young, thriving in their
fields and very excited about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   So start looking for them on the tube _ and also making personal
appearances at a mall near you in youthful drawstring pants, baggy
sweaters and funnel-neck dresses.
</P>
<P>
   AFTER CHRISTMAS: Waiting until New Year's to undress the tree?
Instead of just dumping the strings of lights in a box as usual,
Miz Hot Tips suggests wrapping them around a piece of cardboard to
keep them from getting tangled. Or you could try wrapping them on
the Evergreen-Light Caddy, which has a spool-like mechanism that
eliminates tangles and quickly dispenses lights as you need them
next year. It's $19.95 at Target stores. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
