   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOR FRIDAY:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CONSERVATIVES-SENATE (Washington) _ A consensus around censure
may be building in the Senate, but a dozen or more of its most
conservative members are firmly opposed to anything short of a full
trial of President Clinton. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OCTUPLETS-FATHER (Houston) _ Does the father of the world's only
surviving octuplets know how to change a diaper? ``I'll learn,''
says Lyke Louis Udobi, father of the octuplets. And of his
September arrest for assaulting his mother-in-law, he says the
family had some problems but had worked through them. By LEIGH
HOPPER.
</P>
<P>
   ARKANSAS-SUSPECT (Laredo, Texas) _ A fugitive captured in Mexico
for crimes in Arkansas and two other states was released by Mexican
authorities and is being held in Texas. James Edward Tillis, 30, of
Lambert, Miss., is now in custody at a lockup in Laredo, Texas. By
DANE SCHILLER.
</P>
<P>
   AUDIT-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ A draft state performance audit
recommends the elimination of 1,500 state workers who determine who
is eligible to receive welfare assistance. The draft report by the
Texas comptroller's office said such a cut would save $18 million
in state money and $24.8 million in federal funds in the next
fiscal year. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you're firing up your first
computer for the first time, this should be a very merry Christmas
indeed. Welcome to the Digital Age! Few things are as exciting as
owning that first personal computer, except maybe buying a new PC
after holding onto an ancient one for far too long. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A consumer who is shopping around
for his first scanner is confused and asks, ``What are the pros and
cons for the different types of scanners?'' By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The irony of the House impeachment
of President Clinton is that if a presidential election were held
today he would be re-elected. Why have a hefty majority of voters
rallied behind him? By MARIANNE MEANS. (This column was filed
Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-MACK (Austin, Texas) _ Mack Brown has made all the right
moves since taking over the University of Texas football program a
year ago. As he wraps up his first season with the Longhorns' first
appearance in the Cotton Bowl since 1991, Brown reflects on his
inaugural year and where he and his program are headed without
Ricky Williams. By TERRY BLOUNT
</P>
<P>
   FBC-A&AMP;M (College Station, Texas) _ With a new coach, a new
building and new-found confidence, the Texas A&AMP;M basketball team is
off to its best start since the early 1980s. By W.H. STICKNEY.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-LOPEZ-COLUMN (Houston) _ A profile of Olympic gymnast
Dominique Moceanu as she spends her first Christmas without her
parents. By JOHN LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 27:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MALNUTRITION (Tlahuitoltepec, Mexico) _ Malnutrition
stalks the children of southern Mexico's highlands, killing some,
stunting the physical and mental growth of many others, robbing
almost all of a future. By some estimates, more than one-fourth of
Mexico's 95 million people suffer from some level of malnutrition.
But experts say the malady falls with particular wrath upon
children in the southern states of Chiapas, Guerrero and Oaxaca. By
DUDLEY ALTHAUS.
</P>
<P>
   FILED WEDNESDAY FOR SUNDAY:
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE (Washington) _ Doug Pfaff and Rand Snell are guinea
pigs in the first large-scale test of a preventative AIDS vaccine.
By next June the national experiment will involve 5,000 high-risk
participants _ mainly sexually active homosexual men. Researchers
face this dilemma: They are ethically obliged to encourage safe sex
but, on the other hand, there is no way to determine whether the
vaccine is effective unless the volunteers are exposed to the HIV
virus, which causes AIDS. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed in the ``w''
and ``l'' categories. Seven photos are on the Wieck database. They
are slugged AIDS-VACCINE1 through AIDS-VACCINE7.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-VACCINE-OTHERS (Washington) _ Approximately 40 AIDS
vaccines are being studied around the world and three of them
already show promise, according to Dr. Anthony Fauci, the director
of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases and a
leading AIDS expert. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Filed in the ``w'' and
``l'' categories.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ Even though the curtain will
descend this week on 1998, the tumultuous events of the past few
weeks, both here and abroad, will continue to resound through the
new year and even beyond. They demonstrate the accuracy of those
wise words of William Shakespeare's etched into the wall of our
National Archives: ``What's past is prologue.'' By ROBERT E.
THOMPSON. (Filed in the ``k'' category.)
</P>
