<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WONDER OF A DAY WITHOUT CHEMOTHERAPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEDFIELD, Mass. _ So this is what hell looks like: A little girl
of 11, doubled over on the soccer field by a mysterious explosion
of pain, helplessly clutching her side in search of relief she
wouldn't find. And the next day, a doctor who informs two heartsick
parents that a grapefruit-sized tumor threatens to end their
daughter's life.
</P>
<P>
   The outlook could not have been worse, the uncertainty more
rampant. Specialists were not clear if the cancer had invaded her
lungs or her diaphragm or spread into her bones. The survival rate
for Ewing's sarcoma, a rare, childhood disease, is only 60 percent.
And for those fortunate enough to recover, the route home is a long
and tortured one, marked by major surgery, months of devastating
chemotherapy treatments and scars that spread from body to mind.
</P>
<P>
   That was in April. What followed is a tale of courage and
compassion that brings us to this Christmas morning, a day when
young Lindsey Beggan of Medfield personifies the hope of the season
and the comforting -- though unfortunately contrarian -- belief
that people are essentially good. Lindsey's cancer became a town's
cause, and everyone involved seems the better for it.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days after the diagnosis, a group of 6 to 10 women
began meeting nearly every Friday to plan how the town could best
help the Beggans. They scheduled an endless stream of babysitters
for the three children, aged one-and-a-half, three and eight,
allowing the parents time in the hospital. More than 85 others
around town volunteered to cook and deliver meals. Others
redecorated Lindsey's room with new paint, a flower border and a
rose-colored rug. Still others delivered gift baskets for Lindsey
and her family everytime they returned from the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A local lawn care company tended to the Beggan's property, no
charge. A maid service was hired to clean house. The women even
bought a First Communion cake for the eight-year-old. ``To this
day, I'm in awe at what people are doing,'' says Melinda Beggan,
Lindsey's mother. ``I've had people I've never met coming in with
meals. You think you know everyone in town, but you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause is a remarkable one. Lindsey looks to be all arms and
legs in that way fifth graders so often are. She is the fastest
runner on her soccer team, the oldest of four sisters. She plays
the clarinet. Her favorite subject is math, and when the topic
turns to her report card, she is more than willing to present it
for inspection, mostly, it seems, because she received all A's.
When she smiles, as she so often does, it is as if someone has
flicked a light on the tiny, chiseled features of her innocent
face.
</P>
<P>
   It's heartbreaking to picture her at the edge of the abyss last
April, surrounded by surgeons at Massachusetts General Hospital
performing invasive, awful tests, helpless as doctors warned her
parents of the serious consequences ahead. ``It had to be
overwhelming, to be constantly bombarded with docters and nurses
converging on her all the time,'' says her father, Paul Beggan.
``She was just very quiet, never complained, never shed a tear.''
</P>
<P>
   She was diagnosed on Thursday, April 16, the tumor lodged to her
ribcage. Her first good news came on Friday, when doctors told her
there was no sign of cancer in her lungs. Still, there was one more
crucial result remaining: Whether the cancer had metastasized in
her bones. On Monday morning, when the doctor came to her hospital
room to tell them it hadn't, Paul Beggan bolted out the door
shedding tears of relief and joy.
</P>
<P>
   Next came six long rounds of chemotherapy treatments in three
week intervals, all in an attempt to obliterate the tumor and halt
any spread. The treatments caused vomiting, throat soars and
weakness. Her blood counts regularly plummetted and her parents
would race her to the hospital. Her long, light brown hair fell
out.
</P>
<P>
   By August, surgery. When doctors opened her chest, they weren't
sure what they would find, whether the cancer had spread into her
lungs, whether her heart might be damaged, whether the tumor had
shrunk enough. The Beggans, sitting silently, glumly in a room just
outside the surgical suite, received a call from inside saying
there was no sign of spread into her diaphragm. An hour later, her
doctor, Harvey Weinstein, came into the room to announce there was
no damage to her heart or lungs. Three hours later, the surgeon
declared the operation ``fantastic.'' He had removed five of her
ribs, but she would likely be cured.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month, the arduous chemotherapy regimen began anew,
though Lindsey refused to allow it to upend her life. She pleaded
with doctors to stop the treatments long enough for her to attend
her first day of fifth grade at the Dale Street School, and her
parents brought her from the hospital to Medfield, then rushed her
back that afternoon. Cancer doctors, as accustomed to grappling
with death as appreciating life, have been smitten. ``She is a
remarkable youngster,'' says Weinstein. ``This hasn't slowed her
down at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents tell of Lindsey vomiting in the morning, then
insisting on being allowed to go to school by afternoon. She has
resumed playing soccer with a special shield covering her chest.
Friends around town see her walking nonchalantly with a backpack
over her shoulders holding an intravenous hookup to her body. ``I
don't think I've ever heard her complain,'' says Sue Reardon, one
of the women in the core group that has helped the Beggan's.
</P>
<P>
   The chemotherapy treatments will continue until April. Lindsey
and her parents will keep shuttling back and forth between Mass
General and home. And at every level, there is still more help.
Meals are still delivered to the Beggan home during the hospital
stays. Lindsey's school still keeps a watchful eye on their
student. Lindsey's friends still keep their hair cut short in a
show of unity. Other parents around town still wonder what more
they can do.
</P>
<P>
   And about those volunteers, the cooks, the babysitters, the
gift-givers -- they say they've learned something about themselves
in all this, about each other. ``No matter what, I know I could
pick up the phone now and ask anyone for help and say, `Look I'm
having a bad day,' and they'd boost my spirits,'' says Reardon.
</P>
<P>
   At the Beggan house, Lindsey was walking around in a Santa Claus
cap one recent day. When a visitor asked what she missed most about
a life without chemotherapy, she looked around the room at nothing
in particular, deep in thought, then smiled in sudden realization.
``My hair,'' she said simply. And with that, she pulled off her
hat, revealing her perfectly bald head. When something is so
wonderful, there's really no need to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   (Brian McGrory is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
