<HEADLINE>
WEIGHING POWER IN FOREIGN FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.D.)   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of late, domestic films have made a drab lot on video. Not so
the foreigners. On Tuesday, for example, Fox Lorber issued ``Lola
Montes'' (1955), Max Ophuls' last film, with Martine Carol as the
19th-century Mexican circus performer and collector of men from
Franz Liszt to the King of Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   And from New Yorker this week comes ``La Promesse,'' Jean-Pierre
and Luc Dardenne's exceedingly powerful film about a 15-year-old
boy (Jeremie Renier) whose loyalties are torn between a domineering
father and the family of a laborer from Burkina Faso whom the boy's
father has exploited.
</P>
<P>
   With a journalistic eye on racist xenophobia, the Dardennes'
movie has much to say about what ails French society. In its own
way, Deepa Mehta's ``Fire,'' also released by New Yorker, does the
same for India.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could leave me, but life can be hell for a divorced
woman,'' a husband smugly tells his wife in the film. That's from a
man who on the advice of his swami has been celibate for 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Soon she enters a lesbian affair with her beautiful young
sister-in-law, who has moved into her household and whose own
husband thinks a baby would keep his wife happy while he is busy
with his Chinese mistress. ``Two heroines in one kitchen,'' the
houseboy observes laconically.
</P>
<P>
   In India their screen rebellion has riled conservative elements
to such an extent that theater owners, fearing for their
establishments, have refused to show the film. Lesbianism by itself
is not so much the problem. ``It's the role of women in a
patriarchal society,'' Ms. Mehta said from New Delhi. ``They are
reduced to being pets.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hiroshi Teshigahara's classic ``Woman in the Dunes'' (1964),
released this month by Milestone (distributed by New Yorker), a
woman (Kyoko Kishida) and a man (Eiji Okada) are equal-opportunity
sufferers, making love out of almost crazed loneliness and all the
while shoveling to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Their antagonist, but also their provider, is sand, great
undulating seas and collapsing walls of it that threaten to bury
them as they did the woman's husband and child. An entomologist and
schoolteacher from the city, the man wanders vast beaches by the
sea. Needing a place to stay for the night, he is directed by
villagers to a house at the bottom of a sand pit.
</P>
<P>
   He descends by ladder to be welcomed and fed by the woman, who
lives and works there alone. All night she shovels sand into a
bucket, which is hauled to the top of the pit by the villagers. In
the morning the man discovers that the ladder is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Shovel they must to earn their food and water, which is lowered
to them. ``Sand makes things rot,'' she tells him. Later he
discovers that for himself as he tries to make a ladder from
crumbling boards he's torn from the house.
</P>
<P>
   Looking appropriately and richly desolate, the film retains its
allegorical mysteries and fascination. Here is the inevitable
futility of life. Having escaped the pit at last, the man won't
leave. ``No need to rush and escape,'' he says. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss
</P>
<P>
   On one level, Tommy O'Haver's film pushes the romantic-comedy
envelope several steps beyond the gender-bending ``Prisoner of
Sex''; on another, it is really about the way idealized 40s and 50s
Hollywood fantasies still influence our lives.
</P>
<P>
   A geeky-looking homosexual art photographer named Billy Collier
(Sean P. Hayes) falls for Gabriel (Brad Rowe), a 19-year-old
aspiring musician and ``Baywatch''-style boy toy who works in a
coffee shop. Landing on whatever side of the sexual fence the
situation calls for, Gabriel cooperates with Billy's idea to
restage great love scenes using drag queens as screen goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   Later, on the island of Catalina, sexual chaos erupts in a
sweet, goofy movie in which, Stephen Holden wrote in The New York
Times, everything ``feels playfully surreal.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Trimark. $101.99. 92 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawn Dogs
</P>
<P>
   In a sterile suburb, a smart 10-year-old girl named Devon
(Mischa Barton) and a free-spirited mower of lawns named Trent (Sam
Rockwell), both of whom can't stand the place, form an alliance for
friendship and survival.
</P>
<P>
   Trent lives the hermit's life with brio, and his insouciant
attitude attracts Devon, who gradually wins him over as a sidekick
and confidant. Though Devon's precociousness becomes cloying and
the pair's shared vulnerability can be heavy-handed, John Duigan's
film ``does breathe life into a story that rails against
conventional wisdom'' (Janet Maslin). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Trimark. $96.99. 111 minutes. Closed captioned. R. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Avengers
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely nothing sparks between Ralph Fiennes and Uma Thurman
in the roles of John Steed and Emma Peel, the super-suave British
sleuths resurrected from the popular television series of the
1960s. No help is available from a thin story about a madman (Sean
Connery, foppishly decked out and looking like Burt Reynolds)
scheming to control the world's weather. Which way for the exit?
Pared down to cut its losses, `` `The Avengers' is short but not
short enough'' (Maslin).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Warner. $107.37. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baseketball
</P>
<P>
   Two overgrown 20-something adolescents (Trey Parker and Matt
Stone) invent a game that is played in the driveway and is a cross
between basketball and baseball. Shoot a hoop and run around the
bases. Yes, it's beyond idiotic, but in a sports-crazed society,
baseketball catches on with the great unwashed, who dote on its
every moronic nuance.
</P>
<P>
   Soon there are baseketball teams around the country, inane
telecasts, a months-long playoff season and a money-grabbing
operator (Robert Vaughn) who would defile the pure spirit of
beer-soaked fun in a ``funny, gleefully offensive spoof of
professional sports'' (Holden). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 103 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   FIVE DOCUMENTARIES BY ROBERT MUGGE. Works by a filmmaker who
specializes in American music and musicians include ``Gospel
According to Al Green'' (94 minutes), about the soul star of the
70s who turned to gospel; ``Sonny Rollins: Saxophone Colossus''
(101 minutes), about a master of improvisation; ``The Return of
Ruben Blades,'' which accompanies the salsa star to Panama; ``Black
Wax: Gil Scott-Heron'' (80 minutes), featuring the jazz and rap
musician's 1982 concert at the Wax Museum nightclub in Washington,
and ``Sun Ra: A Joyful Noise'' (60 minutes), about the composer and
keyboardist's mix of music, ritual dance and theater. Winstar.
$24.98 each. Information: (800) 414-1690.
</P>
<P>
   TREVOR. Peggy Rajski's acclaimed film, based on James Lecesne's
stage show, is the monologue of a 12-year-old gay boy (Brett
Barsky) who after being ridiculed for developing a crush on the
most popular boy in school (Jonah Rooney), makes a semi-comical
attempt at suicide before moving on positively with his life. 1997.
Water Bearer. $14.95. 23 minutes. Information: (800) 551-8304.
</P>
<P>
   FM. Money-hungry corporate overseers try to put some crimps in
the cool style of Jeff Dugan (Michael Brandon), Los Angeles'
leading disk jockey. Dugan responds by locking the doors and
pumping up the volume. John A. Alonzo's film features concert
appearances by Jimmy Buffett, Tom Petty, Linda Ronstadt and REO
Speedwagon. 1978. Anchor Bay. $14.95. 104 minutes. PG. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
