<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5969 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAS-DEREG25-COX     12-24 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-DEREG25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gas Guy making his presence felt
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Natural Gas Services is off to a fast start as
one of the top competitors in the state's newly deregulated natural
gas industry.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing affiliate of Atlanta Gas Light Co. has the
daunting task of luring its share of the 1.4 million customers now
served by its sister company. Those residences and businesses
already have started signing up for service with rival marketers.
</P>
<P>
   To meet the challenge, the company has launched an ad campaign
featuring its increasingly popular ``blue flame'' Gas Guy mascot
and promises prices for gas service that it says beat its rivals'.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got tremendous momentum,'' says A. Clifton Payne, vice
president for marketing. The company hasn't released figures on how
many customers it has signed up. After two months of competitive
gas sales, its top rivals are SCANA Energy of South Carolina and
Houston-based Shell Energy Services.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its link to Atlanta Gas Light, Georgia Natural Gas is
seen as the player to beat among the dozen marketers now providing
service. Many observers believe consumers used to dealing with
Atlanta Gas Light will flock to Georgia Natural Gas when it comes
time for them to choose a marketer or be assigned to one by the
Public Service Commission sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Natural Gas won't disclose how much its advertising and
marketing effort is costing. But Stephen J. Gunther, president of
the company, said he expects his company to become profitable
sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company had a rocky beginning. At first, AGL Resources Inc.,
parent of the gas company, wanted to call its marketing affiliate
Atlanta Gas Light Services.
</P>
<P>
   But competitors complained that would confer an unfair
advantage. AGL's marketing wing finally won the right in an
out-of-court settlement in July to call itself Georgia Natural Gas
Services and to use the same blue-flame logo that has identified
Atlanta Gas Light Co. for years.
</P>
<P>
   Many competitors are watching carefully for any sign Georgia
Natural Gas is gaining favored treatment from Atlanta Gas Light Co.
The utility is supposed to do business on an equal footing with all
marketers as the entity responsible for delivering gas to homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Critics note Gunther, Payne and Senior Vice President Clayton H.
Preble all worked previously for AGL Resources or the gas utility
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of any evidence that Georgia Natural Gas Services
has received special treatment that would be prohibited by law,''
said David Adelman, an attorney who represents several marketers.
``But it's very early in the ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunther insisted, ``We are treated like any other marketer.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter M. Higgins, president and chief executive of AGL
Resources, said he does speak to Gunther occasionally. But he said
Georgia Natural Gas Services is a ``separate company'' that reports
to a board of a joint venture called SouthStar Energy Services.
SouthStar is, in turn, a partnership of AGL Resources,
Charlotte-based Piedmont Energy and Houston-based Dynegy Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Natural Gas Services has also contracted its billing and
customer service to Utilipro Inc., an Atlanta-based utility billing
services company in which AGL Resources has an 85 percent stake.
Utilipro's call center is in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizes a link
</P>
<P>
   The Gas Guy, dreamed up by the Atlanta ad agency BBDO South, has
allowed Georgia Natural Gas Services to promote its affiliate
relationship with Atlanta Gas Light and to build an identity with
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a marketing expert, but it seems to be accomplishing
its purpose,'' Higgins said. One marketing expert, Georgia State
University Professor Kenneth Bernhardt, also said the Gas Guy has
been effective.
</P>
<P>
   Using a mascot is an unusual tactic for utility companies, which
until the recent advent of deregulation have been monopolies that
did not have to fight for market share.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Pillsbury Dough Boy and Ronald McDonald, a mascot
allows a company to ``break through all the clutter'' and establish
an identity with consumers, Bernhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you stopped the average person in the street and asked
which gas company could they name, they couldn't name more than two
or three,'' he said. The Gas Guy ensures Georgia Natural Gas has
that awareness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gas Guy is also getting under the skin of rival marketers.
One has pinned a picture of the mascot on the wall and throws darts
at it. Another finds the ubiquitous blue blob ``aggravating.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Natural Gas identifies the Gas Guy as ``Matt.'' He has
his own office in Georgia Natural Gas Services' executive suite on
Glenridge Drive, off Johnson Ferry Road and Ga. 400 in north
Atlanta. There he plans public appearances and answers e-mail on
his own personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   The mascot has been quite busy in recent weeks in a round of
``true-blue'' public appearances that have included a televised
fund-raiser for Georgia Public Television, Egleston Hospital's
Christmas parade and a visit to Hughes Spalding Children's
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Bernhardt says such ``cause-related marketing'' is effective
because it ties a product to a cause and ``transfers good will''
from a cause consumers may hold dear. But he said good will and
consumer awareness won't carry the day by themselves if the product
is not competitive on price and other things consumers care about.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Georgia Natural Gas prices have been competitive. Its
prices for an average residential customer were among the lowest in
a recent survey of rates offered by nine of the 10 marketers
selling gas this month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the company's most popular pricing plan, gas charges are
subject to change monthly according to market fluctuations, and
customers are credited in the 13th month of service for an average
monthly bill. Georgia Natural Gas also offers a fixed gas rate,
with a one-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our price is a competitive price,'' said Payne. ``Consumers
who have gone to Georgia Natural Gas Services are seeing a lower
price.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGIA NATURAL GAS SERVICES INC.
</P>
<P>
   Headquarters: Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Business: natural gas marketing company formed in July as joint
venture of AGL Resources, parent of Atlanta Gas Light Co.; Piedmont
Energy, a Charlotte-based utility company; and Dynegy Inc., a
Houston-based wholesale energy marketing company.
</P>
<P>
   Targeted customers: residential, commercial, industrial
</P>
<P>
   Rates: fixed, variable, combination
</P>
<P>
   Contract: will vary
</P>
<P>
   Deposit: based on credit
</P>
<P>
   Expected profitability: sometime next year
</P>
<P>
   Web site: http://www.gasguy.com
</P>
<P>
   Phone: 1-888-878-3258
</P>
