<HEADLINE>
SIMMS EXPECTS DIFFERENT PATRIOTS TO TAKE FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Phil Simms covered the Patriots, the team whupped
the Kansas City Chiefs in Week 6.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment wasn't a household word back then, and Scott Zolak
was just another backup quarterback. But now he's leading the
limping Patriots down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Simms expects to see a different team than the one
that pummeled KC. Against the New York Jets, he'll see one that
made the playoffs but has relied on a wing, a prayer, and a yellow
flag to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to be interesting to me is who is going to play
for the Patriots,'' Simms said. ``I mean physically. Who is going
to be physically capable of playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms knows that Drew Bledsoe is out, but he also believes that
Zolak is a solid citizen, capable of keeping the patriots
competitive in the short run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is going to make a case that Zolak is better than
Drew,'' Simms said during an interview. ``But with his performance
against the 49ers, Zolak is driving his market price up.
</P>
<P>
   Backup quarterbacks took a big hit after the NFL instituted the
salary cap. Simms said teams would slash their salaries to
$500,000, take it or leave town. But now, the value of backups has
risen, especially considering that at one point during the season
more than half of the starting quarterbacks were either injured or
not performing well. Simms now figures the price for a good backup
QB is about $1.5 million, ``right where it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms was quick to point out that the Patriots' defense has been
keeping them in games, and while it's still solid, inexperienced
players such as Chris Canty and Tebucky Jones make the team
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has taught me one thing,'' Simms said. ``The teams
that have the best chance of succeeding in this league have quality
veterans. At the beginning of the season, a lot of people were
talking about their teams having the youngest average age. But most
of the teams that are in the playoffs are loaded with solid
veterans, making plays and leading their teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, everything is pointing to them,'' Simms said.
``They won their division. Even Bill (Coach Parcells) is giving
them praise, and you know how rare that is. He was telling me that
he was very happy with his offense. He thinks they are smart. They
don't make a lot of mental mistakes. He told me that they can go
through a week of practice with one, maybe two mental errors. The
blitzes are picked up, the receivers change their routes to beat
the coverage and the quarterback makes the right decision. Now
there are times when the running game is not clicking but its not
because the linemen don't know who to block. They just can't block
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms said Parcells returns to his old self when he talks about
his defense. According to Simms, Parcells says his defense makes
``seven or eight mental mistakes on every play.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Uphill struggle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keith Olbermann has an apparent Sisyphean task at Fox Sports
News. Olbermann inherits a network running in last place among the
11 p.m. cable sports shows. ESPN's Sports Center (959,700
households) has a 10-to-1 lead over Fox (96,000 households), and
CNN's Sports Tonight (220,500) has a 2-to-1 advantage . . . Dick
Schapp hosts a two-hour radio show on the most compelling sports
stories of 1998. Schapp is joined by a slew of sports reporters,
including the Washington Post's Tony Kornheiser and Michael Wilbon,
New York Daily News columnist Mike Lupica, Detroit Free Press
columnist Mitch Albom, author John Feinstein, New York Times
columnist William Rhoden, Philadelphia Daily News columnist Bill
Conlin, and Bob Ryan, the Boston Globe's voice of hysteria.
</P>
</TEXT>
