<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV27-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HERO FOR OUR TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 27, 1998)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One day next spring, the Clinton boom will surpass the Reagan
years and enter the history books as the second longest peacetime
expansion on record. Steady growth now seems likely to continue
into the next century, surpassing even the long war boom of the
1960s and becoming the most remarkable period of sustained growth _
ever.
</P>
<P>
   The man responsible is one of the few in Washington not to have
been sullied by the events of this dreadful year: Alan Greenspan,
chairman of the Federal Reserve Board.
</P>
<P>
   Man of the year? How about accomplishment of the decade? We
won't see many years more dangerous to good financial order than
the one just past.
</P>
<P>
   Few would have guessed when he replaced Paul Volcker in 1987
that Greenspan would achieve a star status surpassing that of the
man who _ by sheer dint of personality _ stopped a runaway global
inflation at the end of the 1970s and laid the foundations for the
Reagan era.
</P>
<P>
   But Greenspan has served three presidents now. The graying
former economics consultant has continued to build the integrity of
the Fed with good appointments to its board of governors and
regional banks. He has forged an excellent relationship with
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, another official whose stock has
risen throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The result: America and the global economy have dodged a series
of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan prevented the spilling-over of the long-running Asian
financial crisis _ itself largely the result of mismanagement of
the Japanese economy. He avoided a currency devaluation in China,
dealt with the Russian government default, contained an incipient
crisis in Brazil and liquidated a huge American hedge fund. Had it
been allowed to fail, Long-Term Capital Management could have
precipitated financial gridlock and tumbled the world into
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the US economy has grown at annual rate of nearly 4
percent for the last three years -- with prices virtually flat.
Greenspan raised rates only once, before triming them slightly in
three steps last autumn. Even his ``irrational exhuberence''
warning of two years ago looks pretty good in hindsight _ a warning
that manias could take hold in unexpected ways in unexpected
markets.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the crisis is entirely over. Some threats remain. But
DRI/McGraw-Hill recently dropped its probability-of-recession
estimate to 20 percent from 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To grasp the magnitude of Greenspan's achievement, however,
compare the three expansions of the Sixties, the Eighties and the
Nineties. Until recently this was a favorite ploy of the
Clinton-bashers, who complained that the 1990s expansion lacks
``the oomph'' of previous recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, growth often has been more robust in the past. The
economy grew by an astonishing 50 percent between the beginning and
the end of the 1961-69 boom, according to calculations by the
Institute for Policy Innovation. During the 1983-90 boom, the
economy grew 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, when the current boom began, the economy has grown
only by about a 25 percent. Does that mean that the Nineties boom
has been weak and insipid?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. The Sixties boom was fueled by Vietnam War. When it
ended the international monetary system had been wrecked and a
decade of stagnation was in store.
</P>
<P>
   The Eighties boom was stimulated by those huge tax-cut deficits.
Only extremely nimble footwork by Greenspan in the years since 1987
_ and budget- balancing by three consecutive Congresses _ prevented
a crash.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the Nineties booms looks like the model of
sustainable growth _ low inflation, a balanced budget and rising
real incomes, thanks to resumed productivity growth. .
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say that Greenspan has bought continued
growth only by initiating an American ``bubble'' _ an inflation of
share prices through excessive monetary ease. They are mostly
partisans of former president George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   They may be right. But they often have been wrong. And in any
event, nobody doubts that the expansion eventually must end. The
question is when _ and whether it will be hard landing or soft.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's achievement has been to set a high standard both for
technical excellence and for bipartisanship in the management of
the economy. Future presidents, whatever their party, will have to
find central bankers whose stature is sufficient to permit them to
attempt to match his record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)nws.globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
