<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miracle man: Bethune-Cookman's Frink
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just a few years ago, the board of trustees of
Bethune-Cookman College was discussing the possibility of dramatic
cutbacks in the athletic programs of the church-supported school in
Daytona Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Bethune-Cookman did not enact most of those measures _
fortunately for the football team, or the Wildcats would not be
preparing to face Southern University on Saturday in the Heritage
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With about 2,500 students, Bethune-Cookman plays football at the
Division I-AA level in the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference.
Fielding 16 athletic teams, including football, had put a
tremendous strain on the school's resources.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, a former executive of Atlanta Life Insurance Co.
became Bethune-Cookman's executive vice president. Jno. ``John'' S.
Frink, a graduate of Bethune-Cookman, had spent 40 years with
Atlanta Life, the last 18 as a vice president with expertise in
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started, things were so difficult financially, we
had some trustees who felt that we should go back to the (Div. II)
SIAC,'' Frink said. ``A lot of others felt we should discontinue
football _ since it was so costly.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of Frink's work with Bethune-Cookman president and
former classmate Oswald Bronson, talk of moving football to a lower
level, or even dropping the sport, has subsided. Frink convinced
the skeptics among the trustees that the school could survive at
the Division I-AA level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them I could raise $25,000 that first year,'' Frank
said. ``We began to organize (booster clubs), and we ended up
raising $80,000.'' Last year, the goal of the athletic-support
groups was $100,000; they raised $145,000. With the increase came a
boost in the athletic teams' morale and performance, including the
football squad. Teams were able to practice at improved facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an athletic foundation back in the '80s, but we
couldn't get beyond the city limits of Daytona,'' said athletics
director Lynn Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were raising nothing,'' Thompson said. ``But Dr. Frink came
here in '96, and what he has done since has been incredible.
Because of the support of booster clubs he helped organize all over
the country, we've gone from being also-rans in the (MEAC) to the
upper tier in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
