A5976 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES25-C     12-24 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-Ole Miss standout likely starter for Miami
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Rookie running back John Avery, Miami's first-round
draft choice out of Mississippi, apparently will get his first NFL
start Sunday against the Falcons (13-2) in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   Karim Abdul-Jabbar, who leads Miami (10-5) with 960 yards and
six touchdowns on 270 carries (3.6-yard average), suffered a
concussion in the fourth quarter of Miami's 26-21 loss to the New
York Jets Dec. 13 but missed no practice last week.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul-Jabbar was knocked woozy again on the third play of Monday
night's 31-21 win over Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Avery was told Wednesday that he probably will start.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the chance I've been waiting for all my life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Avery (5-foot-9, 190), has carried 129 times for 480 yards and
two touchdowns. He is very fast but has been impatient in letting
plays develop. He also tends to dance around looking for the
perfect hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's very athletically gifted,'' tight end Troy Drayton
said. ``There's more of a chance when John is in the backfield to
have a big play. When John touches the ball, he's a big play
waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami's rushing average of 3.4 yards per carry is the worst in
the NFL, and in recent weeks quarterback Dan Marino has thrown the
ball 57 and 38 times, for 321 and 355 yards, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jimmy Johnson, however, continues to insist that he wants
to rely on the running game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Injury update
</P>
<P>
   Two names were added to the Falcons' injury list Thursday after
a 2 1/2-hour practice at the Georgia Dome. Defensive end Chuck
Smith (back) and free safety Eugene Robinson (leg) are listed as
probable. Joining them on the injury list are reserve cornerback
Randy Fuller (shoulder), linebacker Cornelius Bennett (knee) and
defensive end Lester Archambeau (broken thumb). All are listed as
probable. . . . Miami offensive tackle Richmond Webb, who at one
time was listed as out, is doubtful because of an a triceps injury.
Right guard Kevin Donnalley is questionable because of a sore knee,
and defensive end Kenny Mixon (knee) remains questionable.
</P>
<P>
   _ Schedule update
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons next year will play preseason games at home against
Detroit and Baltimore and will travel for games at Tennessee and
Cincinnati. In the regular season, Atlanta will play four teams
from the AFC Central. Also, because the Falcons finished first in
the NFC West, they are assured of playing at least one of the other
NFC division champions, Minnesota or Dallas, and the second-place
team in both of the other divisions, Green Bay and Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   _ Playoff possibilities
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons' playoff schedule is set, inasmuch as they know they
have a bye the first week and will play a home game the second week
against Dallas, San Francisco or Green Bay. The Dolphins' situation
is not as clear-cut.
</P>
<P>
   If they win Sunday in their first Atlanta appearance since 1980,
they will be the No. 4 seed in the AFC and will host either Buffalo
(9-6) or New England (9-6), whichever ends up the higher seed.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo plays at New Orleans (6-9) Sunday, and New England plays
in New York, against the Jets (11-4).
</P>
<P>
   If both teams finish with the same record, New England will be
the No. 5 seed, and will travel to Miami for the first round of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Streaks
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's record of 19-4 since the middle of the '97 season is
the best in the league, one victory ahead of the Denver Broncos. .
. . Miami has beaten four NFC teams in a row, dating back to last
year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Super D
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins lead the NFL in scoring defense, having allowed 227
points, or an average of 12.8 per game. The Miami record for fewest
points allowed in a 16-game season is 242, in '90. With 25 points,
Atlanta, which has scored 404 points, can surpass the team record
of 426, set in '81.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's defense is what one would expect out of Johnson _ big in
the middle and fast everywhere else. They're also young.
</P>
<P>
   The starters average 3.8 years of experience, making them the
second-youngest defense in the NFL. The Falcons are oldest at 8.1,
now that cornerback Ronnie Bradford has moved back into the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphin keys are fifth-year defensive left tackle Tim Bowens
(6-4, 315 pounds) and third-year defensive right tackle Daryl
Gardener (6-6, 315). They keep guards busy while allowing middle
linebacker Zach Thomas, who has a team-high 157 tackles, freedom to
roam.
</P>
<P>
   With 45 sacks, Miami's defense often forces opposing
quarterbacks to rush throws, helping to explain the Dolphins'
league-leading 29 interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerbacks Terrell Buckley and Sam Madison have eight each,
tied for second in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an active, quick defense,'' Falcons interim coach
Rich Brooks said. ``Hopefully, we'll be able to take advantage of
their under-sized ends . . . but you saw what they did to Terrell
Davis.''
</P>
<P>
   In Monday night's 31-21 win over the Broncos, the Dolphins
allowed the NFL's leading rusher just 29 yards on 16 carries.
</P>
<P>
   _ Fish tales
</P>
<P>
   In their first four games, the Dolphins averaged 225.8 yards and
16.8 points per game. Since then, they've averaged 345.8 yards and
26 points. . . . Miami is third in the league in average time of
possession (32:09), trailing only Atlanta (33:32) and Buffalo
(32:38). . . . Miami wide receiver O.J. McDuffie leads the league
with 85 receptions, 55 for first downs.
</P>
<P>
   _ The last time
</P>
<P>
   When these teams met last, in 1995 in Miami, the Dolphins
rallied from a 20-9 deficit, scoring two touchdowns in the final
eight minutes, missing both two-point conversion tries.
</P>
<P>
   Marino completed 35 of 50 passes that day for 343 yards and two
touchdowns as the Dolphins had 428 yards of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Miami, in fact, has averaged 375.3 yards in the last four
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
