<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TESTAVERDE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME FOR THE HOLIDAY FOR TESTAVERDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ They're expecting 22 for dinner Friday at what Al
Testaverde likes to call his ``little bungalow'' on Hunnewell
Street. Josie Testaverde will be serving the usual fare _ roast
beef, roast pork _ and for the first time in years, the couple's
only son will be at the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde has spent Christmas the past few years in
suburban Baltimore and Cleveland and makes his offseason home near
Tampa. But this stretch of western Long Island is really home. This
is where he still goes for pizza at Carmela's and gets his hair cut
by John Gigante at A Cut Above. This is the only home he knows. His
parents moved here from south Brooklyn 35 years ago when their
third child, named for Al's father, was 18 months old.
</P>
<P>
   The couple saw their son blossom into a star at nearby Sewanhaka
High School and win the Heisman Trophy playing for the University
of Miami. They watched him struggle in Tampa Bay as a rookie and
then enjoy moderate success at Cleveland and Baltimore. They
watched him play for teams that almost unfailingly were horrid and
forlorn.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 12 years into what largely had been an unremarkable pro
career, the son has literally returned to his roots. He lives down
the road in a rented house in West Merrick and practices at Hofstra
University, a 10-minute drive down the Hempstead Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   That stretch of road is a dreamer's delight, with discount
outlets and fast food joints on almost every block. But furniture,
office supplies, and hamburgers are not the only bargains here.
Vinny Testaverde may be the best deal of all this season.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, his dream was to play for the Jets. He hung posters of
Joe Namath in his bedroom. He finally got a chance last summer,
signing as a free agent, seemingly destined to be the cagey,
dependable backup quarterback and No. 1 clipboard holder. What
happened instead, of course, has been quite different. No one,
anywhere, has been playing quarterback this season any better than
Vinny Testaverde. The homecoming has been a smashing, magical
success.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are 11-4 heading into Sunday's game with the Patriots,
and one very big reason is their 6-foot-5-inch quarterback, who has
flourished in Bill Parcells's system. The Jets are 11-1 in the
games he has started. He has 25 touchdown passes, one shy of the
club record held by Namath and Al Dorow. He has thrown only six
interceptions, none on third down, and his TD/INT ratio is the best
in the league and fourth best in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   Want more? His 100.6 quarterback rating is tops in the AFC and
second only to Randall Cunningham's 107.3. His QB rating on third
downs is 122.9. All of the above earned him a richly deserved spot
on the AFC Pro Bowl team, an amazing feat given that he wasn't even
on the fan ballot, which accounts for one-third of the vote totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a part of what I've always wanted to accomplish,
part of what I always dreamed about,'' Testaverde says, matter of
factly. ``But if I take too much time to smell the roses, I'm
afraid it will become a distraction. I don't want to be in a
position where I'm happy with what I've done. There's a lot left to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be a risk in going home, be it in literature or
athletics. Bill Fitch once cut Ronnie Perry because he didn't want
people in the Boston Garden stands wondering why the local phenom
from Holy Cross wasn't playing. The New York Knicks last season
passed on a deal for Kenny Anderson, worried that he would get
caught up with all his buddies from Queens. Testaverde has had no
such problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Testaverde means in Italian?'' asks Carmela's
proprietor Anthony Calia, rolling the ``r'' as he speaks. ``It
means green head. And what color are the Jets' helmets? They're
green (and white). So, to me, it makes perfect sense. It's full
circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gigante has ben cutting hair at the corner of Crest Road and
Hempstead Turnpike for 23 years. Vinny has been a regular customer,
or as regular as one can be given his many pit stops. This summer,
the two talked about the perils of coming back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sat in that chair over there,'' Gigante says, motioning,
``and said that if had happened 14 years ago, he would have been
nervous. But he said that he wouldn't be now. He said, `Why should
I be?' I know I'm not nervous giving a new customer a haircut,
because I'm a pro. Well, so is Vinny.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde understood the situation all too well even before he
signed with the Jets last summer. He still understands it, even as
his agent works with Jets management on the final details of a
four-year contract extension. There can be distractions, hangers
on, false friends, and out-of-the-woodwork buddies. But there also
was Josie's lasagna and an opportunity he really thought could
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure,'' Testaverde said, ``it was a big concern of mine. You
never know how it's going to work out. If it's good, it's twice as
good. If it's bad, it's twice as bad. So far, it's been good. And
to be able to share it with your friends and family has been a
thrill for all of us. But once you're on the field, you really
don't think too much about where you're from.''
</P>
<P>
   But he constantly thinks about where he is. It wasn't until the
season was 15 weeks along that Testaverde finally acknowledged that
he had felt all along that he would emerge as the starter. It
wasn't any reflection on preseason and opening-day No. 1 Glenn
Foley or any overinflated opinion of his own ability. He just felt
that everything was right: the timing, the team, the coach, the
situation.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Al Testaverde about his son's success this year, and the
father has two words: Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't make any difference if they were playing in China
_ Vinny always has had the talent,'' the elder Testaverde said.
``He's always been the same. He never gets rattled. He never
complains. What Coach Parcells did was bring that all out.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells didn't worry _ does he ever worry? _ about any risks.
He has overhauled the Jets in his own image in his two years here,
and Testaverde is one of many veterans brought in to, as John
Calipari likes to say, ``change the culture.'' The Tuna saw a
35-year-old hungry for a chance to come home and play. That's all
he saw, or so he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look,'' he says, ``I think he's glad that he can share this
with his parents. That's about it. And he can have dinner at his
mom's house. That's about it. It's no big deal. We're by all
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The regular season ends Sunday in the Meadowlands. Vinny
Testaverde will make his 13th start and Josie Testaverde will make
the short trip to New Jersey _ ``she's the real trouper,'' says her
husband _ to see the game. And Al? He has to settle for a
tape-delayed replay, a grudging concession to a heart that once
quit on him during a 1987 game in Tampa. By the time the tape
starts to roll, Al will have discovered the outcome and the way in
which his son contributed to it. He can't even listen to the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know who I am,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Jets get to the Super Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think I'll take a chance on that one,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   That might even be better than Christmas dinner for 22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
