A5983 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIRTHORDER25-COX     12-24 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTHORDER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pecking order: Rank in family hard to outgrow
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the family gathers around the Christmas tree this
morning, remember this: You never outgrow your birth order.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get together with my brother and sister and they're in
the car, they still want to sit in the back seat and put me in the
middle,'' says psychologist Kevin Leman, 55, author of the 1985
best seller ``The Birth Order Book.'' ``And that same older brother
or sister who told you how to run your life as a kid is in the
kitchen telling you how to make the stuffing.''
</P>
<P>
   Family get-togethers bring out the best, the worst and the child
in everyone, Leman says. ``That little boy or girl in us always
pops out.''
</P>
<P>
   Like birth order, interest in family placement seems unwavering.
Leman is back with an updated and expanded ``The New Birth Order
Book,'' which is flying off the shelves like a group of firstborn
children on a mission. He expanded some popular parts of the first
book _ such as explanations of marital relationships _ and added a
whole new section about how birth order affects business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's interested in birth order,'' Leman says,
``Everybody has one.''
</P>
<P>
   Leman behaves himself for a series of CNN interviews, but admits
he's a classic youngest child. ``I lose things. I forget things. I
wore two different colored shoes'' on TV one time.
</P>
<P>
   On ``CBS This Morning,'' when asked his own place in the family,
he picked his tie up off his chest, wiped his nose with it and
said, ``The baby. I'll do anything to get attention.''
</P>
<P>
   He made terrible grades, got into college only after sending
Scripture verses about forgiveness to a Christian school that had
rejected him, then got kicked out for ``ripping off the conscience
box'' where people were supposed to pay for ice cream on the honor
system. ``It's a long, involved story and I was actually
innocent,'' he protests.
</P>
<P>
   In a few years, he had a master's degree and a doctorate and was
dean of students at the University of Arizona, which had refused to
admit him as an undergraduate student, and using all his insight on
his own unwitting minions. He has written 19 books, including
``When Your Best Is Not Good Enough'' and is co-host of the radio
show ``Parent Talk.''
</P>
<P>
   A newfound belief in the Christian faith at age 22 turned his
life around, he says. ``I had thought Christians were a bunch of
wackos,'' he said. ``I did a 180. After I believed and developed
faith, motivation came to me.''
</P>
<P>
   For his reintroduction to the faith, Leman, who now lives in
Tucson, Ariz., credits his wife, an organized, color-coordinated
firstborn, ``a regular Martha Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Martha Stewart a firstborn?
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd have to be,'' he says. Or at least the oldest girl.
(Actually, Stewart is the second of six children, but one
biographer has described her as her father's favorite child,
meaning she may have been treated as a firstborn.)
</P>
<P>
   Leman's marriage, between a baby of the family and a firstborn,
is one of the best matches, according to his research.
</P>
<P>
   It has certainly been fruitful, giving him five opportunities to
observe his birth order theories in his own household.
</P>
<P>
   The first three children fit the patterns perfectly, he claims.
</P>
<P>
   Firstborn Holly, 26, was always ``meticulous, perfectionistic,
structured, hard-driving and bright,'' a stickler for the rules who
demanded precision.
</P>
<P>
   Middle-child Krissy, 25, is ``relational,'' inclined toward
mediation and negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, 21, is playful and creative and has a great sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   For 10 years the family functioned as a five-person unit. Then
along came a surprise. They named her Hannah. Because of the large
gap between her and her siblings, Hannah is ``a quasi-only child,''
according to her father, and exhibits many ``tender baby
characteristics.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hannah was a surprise, Lauren, now 6, was a shock. Again
because of a large gap, Lauren functioned as a combination baby
princess and firstborn.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamics of his own family show the variables in birth order
theory. Factors such as age spacing, gender _ being the firstborn
son or daughter in a family _ multiple births, death, adoption,
illness and parental criticism or pressure directed toward specific
children can alter relationships, Leman says.
</P>
<P>
   And when families blend, so that a firstborn suddenly has an
older stepsibling or a baby suddenly finds a younger child in the
limelight, chaos can result.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Leman maintains that birth order theory is solid. He
prides himself in being able to ``nail'' the birth order of
airplane seat mates, television hosts and even audience members at
his speaking engagements. (One secret is that he picks out
firstborns because of their meticulous appearances.)
</P>
<P>
   He has missed a few. He still smarts from wrongly figuring
Bryant as the older Gumbel brother several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Leman thinks his birth order books far outsell more scholarly
volumes on the subject precisely because he's a baby of the family
and treats the subject with fun. So there he is on the best-seller
list with firstborn Danielle Steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically `onlies' and firstborns run things,'' says Leman.
``The baby's the one who can lighten them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Gayle white writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
