A5985 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-XMAS-BDAYS25-COX     12-24 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XMAS-BDAYS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Christmas revelers born on this day often go to great lengths to
make sure their own nativity isn't forgotten
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's your birthday. All you want is a little special
attention from family and friends. Maybe a little party with a
cake.
</P>
<P>
   That's not asking for much _ unless the occasion comes on or
near Christmas, the most celebrated birthday in the Western world.
For those who follow the Christian tradition, it's hard not to be
overshadowed by Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christmas babies think they get the short end of the wish
list. Others, looking on the bright side, believe they are
twice-blessed. Either way, Christmas birthdays require some
celebratory improvising and creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta siblings Leah and Pax Cumming(Ga.), both born Dec. 25,
always have at least two Christmas trees _ one just for birthday
presents, the other for Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty great,'' said Leah, who turns 5 today. ``I like it
because it's the same day as the baby Jesus.''
</P>
<P>
   Leah and Pax hold their birthday parties before Christmas Day so
friends and classmates can attend.
</P>
<P>
   This year, they celebrated last Friday. Leah had a North Pole
theme with Santa and a train. Pax, who's turning 13 and whose name
means ``Peace'' in Latin, had a Cosmic Bowling party later that
evening.
</P>
<P>
   He thinks sharing a birthday with Jesus and his sister is pretty
neat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a lot of commotion with two birthdays. But I kind
of like it. My family makes up for it,'' Pax said. ``They make sure
they don't cheat me out on gifts.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the Cumming children, Martha Marquardt of Avondale
Estates(Ga.) has learned how to get maximum mileage out of her
Christmas birthday. In midsummer, she gives herself a party to
celebrate the half-year mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Christmas in July, like the movie,'' said Marquardt, who
turns 46 today.
</P>
<P>
   She celebrates in December as well. Every year, she and her
relatives spend Christmas in the family's cabin near Blue Ridge. In
the morning, she opens Christmas presents with the rest of the
family. Later she opens some birthday gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do all my birthday presents separately, so there's a special
recognition of my birthday,'' Marquardt explains.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day she and a handful of friends walk to a secluded
waterfall in the Chattahoochee National Forest(Ga.) where they
celebrate her birthday with wine, cheese and cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a very spiritual feeling,'' Marquardt says. ``It helps
me connect with where I came from and the cycle of life. I have
never felt shortchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   But Joshua England, who turns 18 on Saturday, the day after
Christmas, does. If the Duluth resident could have one wish, it
would be to be born as far from Dec. 26 as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's kind of worn out from all the holidays. Then it's
my birthday and they don't feel like going to another party,'' he
says. ``I get presents, but they double as birthday presents. I'd
prefer separate.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents, grandparents and my brother are about the only
people who call me,'' he adds. ``But the rest of the family
forgets.''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Leonard of Union City not only was born on Christmas but
was married that day too, in 1929. By necessity, she says: ``In
those days, you only had one day off from work.''
</P>
<P>
   Her late husband always made sure Leonard had two gifts under
the tree, she said. The only time she received a single present was
when he gave her the keys to a new car.
</P>
<P>
   ``On two different times I got a Karmann Ghia Since it was an
expensive gift, it was for all three occasions,'' says Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   She won't reveal how old she is today, but does admit ``I'll
never see 80 again.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's an ultimate expert on Christmas birthdays, it would
probably be Eula Mae Johnson, of Augusta(Ga.). She turns 100 today.
</P>
<P>
   A matriarch of 10 children and dozens of grandchildren always
made certain the holiday centered around her. The fact that it
happened to fall on Christmas was just an added treat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any feelings about that when I was little. But
since I've been grown, I've been thankful about it being on
Christmas Day,'' Johnson says.
</P>
<P>
   She expects more than 300 friends and relatives to help her
celebrate the century mark. Festivities will continue through the
weekend, but Johnson will make certain she blows out the candles on
her cake today, not Saturday or Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmama always said her birthday was the 25th, not the
24th or the 26th,'' says Joyce Clark, a granddaughter who lives in
Atlanta. ``We can't go out of town because we have to be down there
with her. But we don't mind, because we know it's such a
blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alma Hill writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
