<HEADER>
A5988 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-ADAMS25-COX     12-24 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-ADAMS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wacky doctor Robin Williams shakes up routine procedures
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As likely to give your funny bone as your gag reflex a workout,
the comedy-drama ``Patch Adams'' is a mixed doctor's bag of genuine
warmth and manufactured schmaltz. It's ``Dead Poets Society'' with
lab coats instead of prep-school blazers. Instead of standing on
their desks to show solidarity with nonconformist Robin Williams,
the kids here strap on red clown noses.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps the movie from being a total groanfest is the
significance of its subject: the demoralizing experience of
hospital patients, shunted through a system that identifies them by
their diseases, not their names.
</P>
<P>
   We get a taste of this early, when Patch (Williams) commits
himself to a mental hospital, and finds the doctors more interested
in making coffee than really listening. Oddly inspired by such
indifference, Patch shakes things up in the asylum, cracking jokes
like a furry McMurphy from ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nurse Ratched of this movie is male: Walcott (Bob Gunton),
dean of the Medical College of Virginia, where Patch enrolls,
hoping to become a doctor with a difference. His goal is to heal
with humor, to build ``the first fun hospital in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Patch clowns for kids in the cancer ward. He infiltrates the
room of an old lady who won't eat (Ellen Albertini Dow, the rappin'
granny of ``The Wedding Singer'') and a terminal patient with a bad
attitude (Peter Coyote). And he woos a grim but lovely fellow
student, Carin (Monica Potter, a Julia Roberts look-alike).
</P>
<P>
   If you worry that Patch won't connect with all of them, you're
at the wrong movie. Based on facts but glossed in Hollywood
formula, the film tidies reality into familiar screenplay chunks.
Thus, we get Patch's recurrent confrontations with the tyrannical
Walcott. We watch him court Carin with ever-greater doses of charm.
He wins the respect of his by-the-numbers roommate (Philip Seymour
Hoffman). And for the finale, he makes big speeches to the faculty
about health care while adoring fellow students watch from every
seat of a jampacked assembly hall.
</P>
<P>
   I lost count of how many times people stand up to applaud Patch.
You'd think the Oscar for ``Good Will Hunting'' wasn't gratifying
enough for Williams. He's verging on Kevin Costner's playing a
character whose mythical perfection verges on actorly narcissism.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he has his magic moments. With his energy, wit and
invention, he can't help being an ingratiating performer, even when
he's knee-deep in muck (as in, for example, the maudlin ``What
Dreams May Come'').
</P>
<P>
   The movie compensates for some of its over-the-top moments with
quiet scenes that get to the heart of the matter: When doctors
crowd a bedridden woman, chattering about her symptoms while
ignoring her mortification from the scrutiny, Patch asks simply,
``What's her name?''
</P>
<P>
   But in its second half, ``Patch Adams'' throws a downer of a
plot twist at us, and never really recovers its intended mixture of
humor and heart. The film is the product of writer Steve Oedekerk
and director Tom Shadyac, best known for ``Ace Ventura'' and ``The
Nutty Professor.'' That track record results in some howlingly good
laughs. But when it aims for seriousness, the movie is about as
deep as a bedpan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patch Adams''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robin Williams. Directed by Tom Shadyac. Rated PG-13
for strong language and crude humor. 1 hour, 56 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Think of it as ``Dead Poets Society'' in lab coats.
Another seriocomic role for Robin Williams, who needs to try
something new.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
