u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DANCING25-COX     12-24 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DANCING25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Lughnasa' lame except for Streep
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One thing you'll learn from the movie version of Brian Friel's
acclaimed play ``Dancing at Lughnasa'' is how to pronounce the darn
title. It's LOO-na-sa.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing you'll learn _ or relearn _ is how amazing Meryl
Streep is. Make all the accent jokes you like (the one here is
Irish), but she's still one of the most remarkable talents to
appear onscreen in the past 20 years. That, at 49, she's not
offered the array of roles available to her male counterparts is as
much our loss as hers.
</P>
<P>
   She is almost reason enough to see this well-intended yet
ultimately disappointing film. A 1992 Tony Award winner and a
mainstay of the regional theater circuit, ``Dancing at Lughnasa''
is a memory tale set in rural Donegal in 1936. Our narrator is
Michael (Darrell Johnston), the 8-year-old illegitimate son of
Christina Mundy (Catherine McCormack), youngest of the five
unmarried Mundy sisters.
</P>
<P>
   Not much happens at the home the sisters share. Kate (Streep),
the eldest, teaches at the local school. The rest _ Maggie (Kathy
Burke), Agnes (Brid Brennan), Rose (Sophie Thompson) and Christina
_ look after the house, tend Michael and make tea and soda bread.
</P>
<P>
   Things change during the fateful summer of '36, when the Mundy
household is augmented by two male presences. One is Gerry Evans
(Rhys Ifans), Michael's father. The other is the sole Mundy
brother, Jack (Michael Gambon), a missionary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the nearby hills, the Celtic harvest festival of
Lughnasa is being celebrated. Its pagan bonfires and
pulse-quickening music are like a challenge to the Mundys to
abandon the straight and narrow path their spinsterhood has led
them down and embrace life's passions.
</P>
<P>
   Minus the enticing theatricality of the stage, the flaws in
Friel's script become appallingly clear. The Mundys are something
of a bore: Each sister exists as cliche. Further, Friel's thematic
face-off between heathen and Christian spirits is handled without
subtlety or depth.
</P>
<P>
   Director Pat O'Connor's approach becomes claustrophobically
predictable. Something happens _ Gerry arrives or Rose disappears _
and he cuts to one sister's face. Then the next. Then the next.
</P>
<P>
   Ifans is a disaster as Gerry _ horse-faced and charmless in a
role that asks little more than that the actor be a handsome,
charismatic rogue. Conversely, the infallible Gambon is effectively
addled as the prodigal brother, awash in his dreams of Africa. As
for the non-Streep sisters, each has her moments, but none ever
engages us fully.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, whatever's worth having in this movie belongs to its
star. You almost wish someone had persuaded Friel to change his
play, toss out the other Mundys and concentrate on Kate. As it is,
``Dancing at Lughnasa'' makes for little more than a discouraging
night out with the girls.
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancing at Lughnasa''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Starring Meryl Streep. Directed by Pat O'Connor. Rated PG for
mild sexual talk. At Tara. 1 hour, 34 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Like watching a collective sibling hot flash, but
Streep almost makes it worth it.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
