</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DELTA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Delta' delves deeply into matters of the heart
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta'' doesn't really get down to business until
it actually gets down to the Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The first 20 minutes or so, which take place in Chicago's
Cabrini Green housing project, come off pretty much like the
stilted exposition they are. The scenes serve merely to introduce
us to druggy, irresponsible, chronically unemployed Loretta (Alfre
Woodard) and her two children: preadolescent Thomas (Mpho Koaho),
who's trying to be a decent kid despite his surroundings, and
little Tracy (Kulani Hassen), who is severely autistic.
</P>
<P>
   Fed up with drive-by shootings, drug dealers and her daughter's
general uselessness, Loretta's rock-solid mom, Rosa Lynn (Mary
Alice), pawns the family's one valuable possession _ an antique
candelabra named Nathan (the explanation comes later) _ and buys
them bus tickets south. She's sending them to spend the summer with
her brother, Earl (Al Freeman Jr.), and his wife, Annie (Esther
Rolle, in her last role), in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   It is, for a big-city girl, an altogether alien world. And
because Annie has Alzheimer's disease and Earl is busy running his
chicken restaurant, circumstances dictate that Loretta will have to
either put up or shut up, grow up or give up.
</P>
<P>
   The family's rebirth becomes the movie's rebirth as well. ``Down
in the Delta'' is a warm, funny, utterly engaging film, firmly
anchored by standout performances by Woodard and Freeman (plus,
it's good to see Wesley Snipes _ as Earl's son Will _ back flexing
his acting muscles instead of the other kind).
</P>
<P>
   The director is celebrated poet Maya Angelou. While she
shouldn't give up her day job, her natural empathy for all things
human translates well into another medium. The picture has its
preachy moments as well as its treacly ones, but its sense of
family matters, and why family matters, is sure and strong. And
while the legacy of Nathan is specific to the African-American
experience, it remains a haunting reminder for all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down in the Delta''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Alfre Woodard and Al Freeman Jr. Directed by Maya
Angelou. Rated PG-13 for language and drug references. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 41 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Sometimes you can go home again, even if you've
never been there before.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
