<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MALNUTRITION-$ADV27-2TAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIGENOUS CHILDREN OF SOUTHERN MEXICO SUFFER FROM MALNUTRITION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, Dec. 27) 
(See optional trim) 
 
By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TLAHUITOLTEPEC, Mexico _ Malnutrition stalks the children of
southern Mexico's highlands, killing some, stunting the physical
and mental growth of many others, robbing almost all of a future.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, more than one-fourth of Mexico's 95 million
people suffer from some level of malnutrition. But experts say the
malady falls with particular wrath upon the children of the
southern states of Chiapas, Guerrero and Oaxaca, whose large
indigenous and rural populations remain mired in poverty, isolation
and neglect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a lot to do with social discrimination,'' says Adolfo
Chavez, a physician and investigator with the government's National
Nutrition Institute in Mexico City. ``Society remains deaf to the
problems of the indigenous people, to the problems of the
countryside, to the problems of the South.''
</P>
<P>
   People in rural southern Mexico have long had it tougher than
their countrymen in the more prosperous cities and the North. But
Chavez and other investigators say the disparity has been widened
in recent years by policies that favor industrial exports from
northern cities _ embodied in the 5-year-old North American Free
Trade Agreement _ at the expense of the 28 million Mexicans who
still depend on the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are areas in the South that have deteriorated badly,''
says Abelardo Avila, a surgeon and sociologist working for the
nutrition institute in Oaxaca. ``The gap between the North and the
South is great and getting greater.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigators cite a government-sponsored survey from
several years ago that found that some 70 percent of people in
rural communities in the South suffer some level of malnutrition.
</P>
<P>
   While few, if any, Mexicans actually starve to death as in a
famine, malnutrition levels in some Indian communities of the South
rival those of Africa's hungriest areas, Chavez says.
</P>
<P>
   Children's bellies swell, and their skin bloats, signs of acute
starvation. Minds grow addled for want of nutrients, bones fail to
develop, hair bleaches, and eyes go bad. Too many toddlers never
see their fifth birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many children die here,'' says Alicia Estrada, a nurse and
Roman Catholic nun who runs a church center that houses and feeds
about two dozen severely malnourished children in Tlahuitoltepec
(pronounced Tlah-wee-to-el-teh-peck), a Mixe Indian town in the
frigid, fog-shrouded mountains of Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   ``They die because of the parasites,'' Estrada says, ``because
of lack of nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeding center in Tlahuitoltepec, a muddy hillside community
of 7,000, was founded 30 years ago to save the most desperately
malnourished children in the area from certain starvation, Estrada
says.
</P>
<P>
   Operating with a little money provided by the church, the
government and private aid organizations, the center provides beds
and three meals a day to children ranging from infants in cribs to
youths on the brink of puberty.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catalina Hernandez, a stunted 8-year-old with a shy but engaging
smile, came to live at the center as a toddler, following several
older brothers and sisters who had also flirted with an early
death.
</P>
<P>
   Despite six years of solid meals at the church, Catalina's
health remains fragile.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll stay as long as is necessary,'' Estrada says, pulling
down the bottom lid in Catalina's eye to reveal an off color that
the nun says reflects a level of illness. ``She's still not well,
and it will get worse if she goes home.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Estrada's center cares for the hardest luck cases,
teachers at the primary school run by the Catholic Church around
the corner say that 80 percent of their young students suffer from
malnutrition. Almost every one of their students, the teachers say,
come to school hungry each morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic workers, whose funding is due to run out within a
few months, give the school's 600 children beans and bread for
breakfast and sandwiches for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers and other officials working throughout the Mixe
highlands say the lack of nutrition is most noticeable in the
schools. Malnourished children fail to learn, they fall asleep in
class, their minds wander.
</P>
<P>
   Medical examinations found that 65 percent of the 1,130 Mixe
children enrolled in boarding schools run by the government's
National Indigenous Institute were malnourished, says Amado Miguel
Mejia, a doctor at the indigenous institute's Mixe regional office
in the village of San Pedro Y San Pablo Ayutla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have kids who are 10 years old and haven't passed the
second grade,'' he says. ``Eighty percent of the kids (in the
boarding schools) have failing grades.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of rural southern Mexico survives on a daily diet of corn
tortillas and beans. Potatoes and vegetables become available
around harvest time but often are sold to buy clothes and other
necessities. Although villagers eat turkey at festivals, meat of
any kind usually is rare.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is worse still in Tlahuitoltepec, where poor farm
land and a chilly climate have limited harvest to once a year and
where people survive on wild herbs and the leaves of potato plants
for long stretches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beans are a luxury there,'' says Martha Garzafox, the Catholic
nun who founded the Tlahuitoltepec feeding program three decades
ago and was transferred by the church to a nearby town last summer.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 24 million Mexicans suffer some level of
malnutrition, according to government figures. Serious hunger in
Mexico tracks the astonishing gap between incomes in the cities and
the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rural problem,'' Avila says.
</P>
<P>
   For example, per capita income in Oaxaca's capital city, also
called Oaxaca, stands at $7,080. That is almost equal to the per
capita earnings in Monterrey, northern Mexico's largest and most
prosperous city.
</P>
<P>
   But per capita income statewide in Oaxaca reached just $1,600 in
1996, according to Banamex, Mexico's largest bank. Earnings remain
far lower in the countryside, where 70 percent of the state's
people live.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
