<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Friday, Dec. 25. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GENERAL (Jerusalem) _ Thirty-six years after he joined
the army, Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak turned in his uniform today and
plunged into civilian life in a peculiar role, dubbed by the media
here as ``the great white hope'' of Israeli politics. Shahak, 54,
did not announce his candidacy for prime minister. He voiced no
political opinion beyond a call for ``togetherness.'' But, even as
he tiptoed, Shahak, a silent shadow over the electoral aspirations
of both Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor Party
leader Ehud Barak, finally stepped today into the fray. By Deborah
Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ A news analysis: Just in case anyone
here missed the point, the state-run media have given rare
publicity to the severe sentences dealt to three prominent leaders
of an alternative political party. Most Chinese had never heard of
Xu Wenli, Qin Yongmin and Wang Youcai _ and for months the local
news media had totally ignored their efforts to form a China
Democracy Party. But in reporting the sentences the the press sent
a clear message to any would-be dissidents. And now, after a
draining week of shock and despair, those who worked openly to
promote the new party _ by some estimates, numbering as many as 200
_ are pondering the next steps for the dissident movement, and for
themselves. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ A sustained assault by
government forces on this area in northern Kosovo ripped apart a
tenuous two-month cease-fire Thursday, as more than 40 armored
vehicles and tanks fought through the day with separatist
guerrillas. By Mike O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOON (Undated) _ More than halfway into their nonstop journey
around the world, the three crewmen of the ICO Gobal Challenge
balloon were speeding across the Pacific Ocean toward the United
States on Thursday, trying to avoid a patch of weather that could
force them to end their attempt. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ It has been a general's maxim at
least since the time of the Romans: Let him who desires peace
prepare for war. President Clinton's legal lieutenants are planning
an aggressive defense in the Senate against the impeachment charges
lodged against Clinton even as the president sues for peace in the
form of a speedy and bipartisan resolution of censure. But this
strategy presents a number of problems for the White House. A
Washington Memo by John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-LAW-SCHOOLS (Washington) _ Jonathan Harr's 1995
best-seller ``A Civil Action'' tells the true story of a battle
between a bold but flawed plaintiffs' lawyer named Jan Schlichtmann
and two big corporations over whether they polluted the drinking
water of Woburn, Mass. In the movie that is opening in theaters
now, John Travolta portrays Schlichtmann as, if anything, bolder
and more flawed. But in Professor Lewis A. Grossman's class at
American University's law school here _ and at law schools across
the country _ Schlichtmann is already a star, foibles and all. The
book is playing an extraordinary role in what some legal educators
describe as a movement to modernize the training of lawyers in
America. Across the country, ``A Civil Action'' is required reading
in courses in at least 50 law schools, including Harvard, Yale,
Columbia, Georgetown and here at American University. By William
Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLD-IMPACT (Los Angeles) _ A brutal, four-day Christmas freeze
has destroyed more than a third of California's annual citrus crop,
inflicting upwards of a half-billion dollars in damage and capping
a year of weather-related calamities around the nation, from the
drenching winter storms of El Nino to summer drought in Texas and
fires in Florida. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   PILOT-SUICIDE (Tucson, Ariz.) _ Capt. Craig D. Button, the Air
Force pilot who in 1997 balked before his first bombing run and
flew his A-10 jet into a Colorado mountainside, was in mental
turmoil over ``unrequited love'' for a former girlfriend and over
his mother's Christian pacifist faith, concludes a ``psychological
autopsy'' by the Air Force. The pilots' parents, from Long Island,
have rejected the conclusions of the report, which was released
after Freedom of Information Act requests by the Tucson Citizen
newspaper. By James Brooke.
</P>
