<HEADER>
A5998 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-MALNUTRITION-$     12-24 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-MALNUTRITION-$ADV27-2NTAK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  TLAHUITOLTEPEC, Mexico: state's people live. 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The problems of the Mixe mirror those haunting most of the
Mexican peasant farmers and nearly all of its indigenous
communities: too little land for too many people, poor soil and,
even worse, low crop prices, few good roads to get products to
market, and little private or government investment.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow two-lane highway climbs into the Mixe highlands from
the Mitla, site of an ancient Zapotec Indian village whose ruins
have become a major attraction for the tourists who flock to
Oaxaca.
</P>
<P>
   Although paved less than a decade ago, the road is riddled with
deep potholes. Mudslides are constant in the rainy season. Large
trees and boulders tumble onto the pavement from the ridges above.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers shiver in the bone-chilling cold along the highway.
New satellite dishes sit incongruously atop crumbling tile-roofed
adobe shacks, evidence of money sent back from family members who
have left for work in Mexico's cities or the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest problems are health, education, nutrition and
production,'' says Benito Clara, the director of the indigenous
institute in Ayutla. ``The Mixe still must scream for the (national
political) leaders to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many (government) programs, but they never get
finished,'' complains Clara, as he goes over the books for one
program in the damp library of the Institute's regional
headquarters. ``There is no effort for institutional coordination.
Planning isn't a problem of the (Indian) communities, it's a
failing of the Mexican state.''
</P>
<P>
   Without immediate attention, the problem can only grow worse,
because the poorest families give birth to 75 percent of Mexico's
children, says Chavez, the physician with the the government's
National Nutrition Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Mixtec Indians farther to the west in Oaxaca, who
have traveled to jobs in northern Mexico and California for
decades, the Mixe farmers have only recently joined the mass
migration that defines much of rural Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most malnourished areas are also (those) where migration,
either to elsewhere in Mexico or to the United States, has been the
least,'' Chavez says. ``Those who (do) leave are the best fed, the
most ambitious people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poorest people stay,'' he says. ``(So) in the communities
there is a regressive selection.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of children who die of malnutrition in Mexico remains
open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   In Oaxaca, just 5 percent of the children younger than 5 who
died in 1995 succumbed to ``nutritional deficiencies,'' according
to the Mexican government's census agency. But Chavez and other
nutrition specialists say malnutrition contributes significantly in
six out of every 10 cases of infants who die of prenatal
conditions, congenital defects, pneumonia, flu and intestinal
infections.
</P>
<P>
   Only 12 infants younger than 1 died of all causes in
Tlahuitoltepec in 1995 and nine in 1996, the census agency reports.
But such numbers reflect long-standing traditions by which
children's births and deaths are often not reported to the
government, Chavez and other experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Because an infant's chances of survival are considered iffy at
best, the experts say, many indigenous parents don't register their
children until they enter school at age 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its severity, Mexico's rural malnutrition problem has a
relatively easy and inexpensive solution, the experts say.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-month-old pilot program in an Otomi Indian village north of
Mexico City that provides residents with tortilla corn meal
fortified with soya and vitamins has brought remarkable
improvements in nutrition and overall health, Chavez says.
</P>
<P>
   The fortified tortillas consumed by villagers in El Rincon have
strengthened pregnant mothers and dramatically increased children's
growth and motor skills, according to a study conducted by Chavez,
who devised the project along with professor George Bates of Texas
A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   The program costs about 15 cents per family per day, Chavez
says. Despite praise from Mexican health officials, it has yet to
be implemented on a large scale.
</P>
<P>
   The fortified tortilla program can be put in place across Mexico
for as little as $100 million a year, Chavez estimates, adding,
``This is probably what people in Mexico spend on their pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a problem of money,'' he said. ``It is simply a
problem of giving (malnutrition) priority. There have always been
badly chosen programs, in terms of nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is one of regional development,'' he says. ``The
next generation (in the southern mountains) will all have to
migrate because there is not even interest in solving the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old idea of (economic) development is being erased from
the conversation,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
