<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5993 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-SHAKESPEAR25-C     12-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-SHAKESPEAR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ambitious, witty romp finds Bard acting in his own plots, with a
dynamite cast
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stage love will never be true love,'' says Viola De Lesseps
(Gwyneth Paltrow), a young noblewoman who believes that the ban
keeping women off the Elizabethan stage keeps theater from ever
reaching true emotional heights. Little does she know that reality
and theatricality are about to collide, becoming nigh impossible to
separate.
</P>
<P>
   The witty, breathless ``Shakespeare in Love'' suggests that the
young playwright (Joseph Fiennes) wrote ``Romeo and Juliet'' on the
fly, inspired by his own star-crossed love affair with Viola. The
movie presents a 16th-century London where Will's daily life is
packed with some of his more exaggerated plot devices, including
forbidden love, cross-dressing disguises, scheming maids, fierce
duels and even the occasional appearance of a ghost.
</P>
<P>
   This Shakespeare isn't the remote and laureled Bard of the
lecture hall. He's a struggling writer with ink-stained fingers,
bills to pay and a running rivalry with playwright Christopher
Marlowe (Rupert Everett), whose ``Faust'' is spouted by all young
actors at auditions.
</P>
<P>
   Genius or not, Will also has the vital libido of any young man,
so he can't help falling for the swanlike Viola when he crashes a
party at her family's estate. She feels the same for him. But Will
has an estranged wife in another town, and Viola herself is engaged
to the blunt Lord Wessex (Colin Firth), who sees her strictly as
his property. (``Is she fertile?'' he asks her parents when
negotiating the marriage terms.)
</P>
<P>
   Little does Will know that flaxen-haired Viola is also the young
man he's cast as the male lead in his new, unfinished play, ``Romeo
and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter.'' Yes, that's right. An aspiring
actress, Viola binds her breasts and glues on fake facial hair to
get the role.
</P>
<P>
   There's a wonderful scene when ``he'' listens to Will rhapsodize
about the woman he loves; Viola can't help balking at the way
Will's romantic mind transforms her into an impossibly perfect
creature.
</P>
<P>
   The scene gets to what's most interesting about the movie: its
awareness that people fall in love with love itself, as much as
with the person they adore. It's the exalted, heady feeling of
infatuation that's captured in romantic tragedies like, naturally,
``Romeo and Juliet,'' as well as in comic romps such as ``Twelfth
Night'' or, well, this movie.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Madden (``Mrs. Brown'') at a lively pace,
``Shakespeare in Love'' revels in sly contemporary touches.
``Follow that boat,'' Will commands a ferry captain, because
taxicabs won't appear in London for several more centuries. Even if
you're not a Shakespeare buff, you'll enjoy the ways the script
puts his famous lines into the mouths of Will's friends and
neighbors. (``I say a plague on both their houses,'' someone yells,
but he's talking about two rival theaters, not the fictional
Capulets and Montagues.)
</P>
<P>
   Building a small specialty at British roles, Paltrow can come
off at times as too studied, actressy; you can feel her working at
it. But she has the poise and luminescence the part needs. She's
nicely matched by Fiennes' puppyish, lovestruck Bard. Then there's
the supporting cast, almost overwhelming in its talent: Geoffrey
Rush as a beleaguered theater owner, Simon Callow as the queen's
master of ceremonies, Imelda Staunton as Viola's maid, Judi Dench
as a ghastly, stern Elizabeth I, and Ben Affleck as a swaggering
actor.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's only weakness is an unexpected one: At times, its
cleverness can be almost distracting. The script is by Marc Norman
and, more tellingly, playwright Tom Stoppard, who began his career
deconstructing Shakespeare in ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are
Dead.'' Like other Stoppard works, the movie dazzles in its
wordplay and wit, but there's something cold at its heart. It can
feel like the showoff thesis of a prized lit student.
</P>
<P>
   While Viola tries to prove that stage love can seem real, the
movie she's in never quite pulls off the same stunt. It's too much
about playacting to really move our emotions the way it intends to.
Even so, like some of Shakespeare's own, unclassifiable plays that
bounce between comedy and tragedy, it's a wonderful mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow and Geoffrey Rush.
Directed by John Madden. Rated R for nudity and sexuality. Two
hours, 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: In this clever, literate romp, William Shakespeare
finds himself living a plot as elaborate as his giddiest comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
