<HEADER>
A5995 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-STEPMOM25-COX     12-24 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-STEPMOM25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberts, Sarandon elevate mawkish to moving
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The tangled emotional issues of stepfamily dynamics are a
terrific subject and one rarely tackled by Hollywood _ unless you
count ``Cinderella.'' And in ``Stepmom,'' director Chris Columbus'
holiday comedy/weepy, when the immensely talented and appealing
leads, Susan Sarandon and Julia Roberts, go toe to toe, the results
are funny, feisty and often achingly accurate. These are ``gotcha
last'' scenes done to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   Sarandon plays Jackie, a bona fide supermom who gave up a
high-powered editing career to stay home and sew Halloween costumes
for preteen Anna (Jena Malone) and her little brother, Ben (Liam
Aiken). Jackie's ex, Luke (Ed Harris, trying not to look
emasculated in a badly written role), has fallen for lithesome
Isabel (Roberts), a Manhattan fashion photographer. His kids
haven't. Their steady loathing is countered by Isabel's ready
admission that she's unprepared to be anyone's mother, let alone a
surrogate constantly compared to a paragon like Jackie.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, abandoned by a longtime spouse and threatened,
consciously or not, by a younger, prettier replacement, Jackie
turns everyday parenting into a combo of art form and subtle
assault.
</P>
<P>
   But then director Columbus cops out. Instead of hanging in there
with these people and letting us see how they're going to work it
all out, the movie hands Sarandon a Disease. From there, things get
less challenging and more conventional.
</P>
<P>
   The movie never entirely relinquishes its hold on us, because
the leads are so very good. So good that they make simplistic
answers to complex questions seem perfectly acceptable. So good
that you forgive the script's (five screenwriters, a troubling
sign) cat-fight undertones and the overbearing, time-to-cry-now
soundtrack. So good that you go with the movie emotionally even as,
intellectually, you reject its mawkish manipulations.
</P>
<P>
   They're not good enough, however, to cover the movie's one
gaping hole. Namely, where's Daddy? Much lip service is paid to
Luke's devotion to his kids. Yet he's the one out of town on his
custodial weekends, leaving Isabel to inevitably screw things up on
her own. And he's not the one who has to risk his job in order to
leave in the middle of the day to pick up the chldren at school.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus doesn't like working mothers _ remember Sally Field in
his ``Mrs. Doubtfire''? And while he's certainly entitled to his
point of view, it weakens his take on this particular material in
that it encourages him to shy away from basic, hard-to-resolve
issues. Conversely, to his credit, he honors the traditional mother
beautifully. There is nothing cliched or condescending about
Sarandon; rather, she glows with vitality and humor _ and, on
occasion, a refreshing bitchiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' is like a lot of stepmoms. It may not be the real
thing, but it tries its darnedest to look after those who've been
left in its care. Check your brain. Take your hankie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts and Ed Harris. Directed
by Chris Columbus. Rated PG-13 for language and adult themes. At
metro theaters. 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The Mommy Wars, in which a mushy script is redeemed
by the two stars.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
