<HEADER>
A5996 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-VOICE25-COX     12-24 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-VOICE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The `Little Voice' that got away
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   British actress Jane Horrocks is pretty much the whole show in
``Little Voice.'' And what a show she is _ a gifted mimic who can
knock out tone-perfect impersonations of everyone from Shirley
Bassey and Marilyn Monroe to Judy Garland and Marlene Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the rest of the movie isn't up to her speed.
Based on a London stage hit tailored for Horrocks, ``Little Voice''
onscreen is a fairly feeble show-biz fable. Not stupid or
offensive, just not much of anything when Horrocks isn't doing her
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Horrocks plays LV (short for Little Voice), a painfully
introverted working-class waif who barely speaks above a whisper.
Except, that is, in the privacy of her room, where she communes
with the spirit of her beloved dead father and belts out the
aforementioned imitations.
</P>
<P>
   One night her blowzy mom (Brenda Blethyn from ``Secrets &AMP;
Lies'') brings home her latest ``beau'' (Michael Caine). He's a
seedy, bottom-feeding talent agent who hears LV doing her voices
and realizes she's the chance he's been waiting for his entire
career. One slight problem: how to get this reclusive phenom out of
her room and onto a stage.
</P>
<P>
   There are some affecting aspects to the film. Caine's attempts
to woo LV with his own tattered dreams of making it big are oddly
touching. Blethyn has a fine time tearing around like an ``AbFab''
reject. And Ewan McGregor brings an uncomplicated sweetness to the
role of a telephone installer who's more interested in LV herself
than her impersonations. (He played a similar role in director Mark
Herman's ``Brassed Off.'')
</P>
<P>
   The movie as a whole comes off as something of a hollow showcase
for a heck of a novelty act _ like creating an entire movie around
a ``Saturday Night Live'' sketch (not that anyone would do
something like that . . .). But Horrocks alone may make it worth
your time. She's a transcendent talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little Voice''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jane Horrocks, Brenda Blethyn and Michael Caine.
Directed by Mark Herman. Rated R for language and brief nudity.
Tara. 1 hour, 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Sings when Horrocks sings; doesn't when she
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
