<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MULTIPLE-TRANSPLANTS-     12-24 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MULTIPLE-TRANSPLANTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
100-MEMBER MEDICAL TEAM PERFORMS TRIPLE TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn.: Conn., Maine)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In an overnight medical drama that one surgeon called a
``symphony of movement,'' transplant teams at Brigham and Women's
Hospital recovered two lungs and a heart from a single donor and
implanted them Tuesday into three different patients on the brink
of death, doctors said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 physicians, surgeons, nurses and other specialists
carried out the logistically complex mission that involved many
coming to work in the pre-dawn darkness and required ``bumping''
several patients scheduled for elective operations to clear the
three surgical suites used for the tranplants.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors said the major ``white knuckler'' was bad weather that
threatened the air transportation of the organs from the
unidentified donor's location somewhere in New England. But the
heart and lungs arrived at Logan Airport early Tuesday morning, and
were taken to Brigham and Women's in time for the implants
beginning at about 10 a.m. that day, said the physicians.
</P>
<P>
   It was only the second time In New England _ and one of only a
handful of times anywhere _ that the three major organs were
implanted in three recipients at the same institution, said Dr.
David Sugarbaker, chief of thoracic surgery. Brigham surgeons were
the first to do it in New England, in April of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The patients, men from Connecticut and Maine who received lung
transplants and a Haverhill woman in whom the heart was implanted,
were all doing well Thursday, and their relatives were ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the donor's family knows what an awesome gift
they've given,'' said Aline Santose, daughter of Marie Lowther, 56,
who received the heart in the operations on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The other recipients were Robert Konovaluk, 57, of Waterbury,
Conn., and Robert Downs, 60, of Brunswick, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a call from the New England Organ bank at 10 p.m.
Monday saying the organs were available, doctors held meetings and
traded phone calls through the night to arrange the procurement of
the organs, clear operating room time, and assemble the teams
needed for the transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest of care in planning was necessary to ensure that
the recipients were put under anesthesia at the proper time, said
Sugarbaker, to make certain that the donor organs spent no
unnecessary time outside the body.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Scott Swanson, a thoracic surgeon, called it a ``symphony of
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The effort involved ``a huge commitment by the hospital and the
doctors'' to accept the three organs for simultaneous transplant,
said Sugarbaker. Otherwise, he said, one or more organs would have
gone elsewhere, and ``this is one gift that when it comes, you have
to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sugarbaker and Swanson, the transplant surgical teams
were headed by Dr. Raphael Bueno, a thoracic surgeon, Dr. Gregory
Couper, a cardiac surgeon, and Dr. Lawrence Cohn, chief of cardiac
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The team for each transplant recipient included three nurses,
two anesthesiologists, two or three surgeons, and several other
specialists, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, three surgeons flew in an airplane arranged by the
New England Organ Bank to remove the organs from the donor _
usually a brain-dead person fatally injured in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Fog and stormy weather threatened to force the returning plane
to land somewhere other than Logan, said Sugarbaker, adding, ``we
were concerned that the organs would be stuck in the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Heart transplants have about a 70 percent long-term success rate
and lung transplants from 60 to 70 percent, said the Brigham
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   When donor organs become available, they are allocated to
patients who are sickest and have been waiting the longest, said
Betsy Strock at the organ bank. She said it was just chance that
the three organs all went to patients at the same hospital.
</P>
<P>
   At present, 70 patients in New England are awaiting donor hearts
and 171 are waiting for lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Michele Leach, daughter of Downs, a lung recipient, said, ``Time
was running out for my dad. He had all he could do to get from the
bedroom to the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday morning, only two days after the transplant, she
said, ``he had color in his cheeks again, his hands were warm, and
I could see the sparkle in his eye that hadn't been there for a
long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
