<HEADER>
A6021 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-DATA-BOS &LR;      12-24 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-DATA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON HOLIDAY EVE, CHEERY ECONOMIC NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Offering good cheer for the holiday season, the
federal government reported Thursday that Americans earned more,
saved more and were forced to visit to the unemployment office less
often in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   With most analysts predicting a slowdown in US economic growth
next year, the new data shows that, at least for now, Americans are
enjoying the fruits of a robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The economic slowdown hasn't happened -- not yet -- despite
all the concerns that have arisen this year,'' said Frederick
Breimyer, chief economist at State Street Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Personal income jumped 0.5 percent in November, the largest gain
in nine months, the Commerce Department said. It previsouly
reported solid gains of 0.4 percent in October and 0.3 percent in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Equally important to many economists, the savings rate moved
into positive territory for the first time in three months.
Economists have worried that Americans are spending more than they
earn and might soon have to cut back significantly, which would
slow the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The savings rate -- or savings as a percentage of after-tax
income -- was 0.1 percent in November. That is a meager number, but
better than the negative 0.2 percent in October and 0 percent in
September, after a rate of 0.3 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the Labor Department said that the number of
Americans filing applications for unemployment benefits fell by
13,000 last week to a seasonally adjusted 287,000, the lowest level
in a year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``This draws a picture of a very health economy,'' said Cynthia
Latta, chief US economist at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in Lexington.
``You can find little pockets of problems, but there is so much
ferment in the rest of the country that it offsets these
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, the Asian financial crisis has prompted
big layoffs and Boeing and hurt the economies of Oregon and
Washington State. ``But we read lots and lots and lots about
layoffs this year, and yet you don't see signs of it in the
unemployment rate,'' Latta said. ``So far, there's a job available
for everyone who gets laid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Many economists say the United States is bound to watch its
economy cool amid the global finanical downturn, which started 18
months ago in Asia. Many predict growth next year of about 2
percent or slightly more, compared to growth estimated at well
above 3 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Many economists are trying to figure out why Americans appear to
be saving so little amid the current prosperity. In the mid-1980s,
the savings rate was as high as 6 percent, Latta said, compared to
a near-zero rate today.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation, some economists say, is that Americans are
spending money that they have made in the stock market. Breimyer
believes that mortgage refinancings, which have surged this year,
provided Americans with a second and important source of cash.
</P>
<P>
   However, showing that Americans have money to spend does not
explain why they feel the need to spend it all, and to save so
little.
</P>
<P>
   Americans could be spending so much, Latta said, because of the
``wealth effect,'' a term economists use to explain the increased
spending that comes from a rising stock market. Americans might
just feel more wealthy than if the stock market had been flat, so
they are spending a lot more money.
</P>
<P>
   Breimyer has an additional explanation: the savings rate is
being measured in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the Commerce Department began treating the income
that people receive on mutual fund gains differently. The savings
rate for April, for example, came in at 3.6 percent under the old
calculations, but fell to only 1 percent under the new
calculations, Breimyer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good part of what's going on could be this methodological
change,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its income report, the Commerce Department said that wages
and salaries -- the most important component of income -- rose 0.6
percent in November.
</P>
<P>
   Wages and salaries were flat in manufacturing, a sector that has
been hurt as the Asian financial crisis cut US exports and prompted
a wave of imports. Wages and salaries rose 0.9 in services, which
are less affected by international competition.
</P>
<P>
   Two special factors held down spending and helped boost the
savings rate. Auto buying returned to more normal levels after
shooting higher in September and October. Those months saw a buying
spurt just after the summer's General Motors' strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, mild weather depressed electricity and natural-gas
use, which helped keep spending to a modest 0.2 percent rise.
Spending on nondurable goods such as food, chemical products and
paper rose 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   (Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
