<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEALTHY-FOODS26-COX     12-24 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHY-FOODS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBERGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 26
 &HT;    Resolve to add fruits and veggies to diet
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After weeks of family celebrations, office parties and
nonstop socializing, a lot of folks are feeling as stuffed as a
Christmas goose.
</P>
<P>
   But soon, all that revelry will give way to resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   And chances are, many will resolve to diet _ whether it's to
lose the 5 pounds gained over the holidays or the 20 pounds put on
over the last year. Or maybe it's simply a desire to eat and feel
better.
</P>
<P>
   No matter the reason _ or the particular diet philosophy you
plan to follow _ there's one goal that's good for everyone: Eat
more fruits and vegetables. Shoot for five servings a day at the
least _ the more the better. And most of us can stand to improve.
Only an estimated 10 percent of Georgians are getting their
five-a-day, according to a survey last spring by the public health
division of the state Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   That's dismally low, said Alice Trainer, health communications
manager at the DHR. Nationally, less than 25 percent are meeting
the minimum recommendation. ``People really don't seem to be aware
of how important eating five-a-day is,'' Trainer said.
</P>
<P>
   And many folks are counting french fried potatoes _ the most
popular vegetable dish consumed in America, and a fat-rich
nutritional disaster _ as one of their servings, according to Chris
Rosenbloom, a nutritionist and professor at Georgia State
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to emphasize that five is the minimum and the reasons
go beyond what your grandmother meant when she said to `eat your
vegetables,' '' Rosenbloom said.
</P>
<P>
   Our grandmothers wanted us to stave off vitamin deficiency
diseases such as scurvy and beriberi, explains Rosenbloom. Today,
research is revealing that the disease-fighting power of many
fruits and vegetables is greater than ever imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Scientific evidence indicates that phytochemical and antioxidant
nutrients found in fruits and veggies protect human tissue from the
kind of toxic damage that occurs with everyday living.
</P>
<P>
   That means diets rich in such foods may actually help prevent
some cancers and heart damage in addition to helping to lower
cholesterol, protecting vision and regulating blood pressure and
blood sugar levels.
</P>
<P>
   Vitamin C, vitamin E and selenium are phytochemicals. So are
beta carotene and carotenoids, found in such foods as carrots,
sweet potatoes and red peppers. Carotenoids are believed to be
defenders against lung cancer, heart disease and cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   Lutein and zeaxanthin also help protect vision and are found in
kale, collard greens, broccoli, spinach and tangerines.
</P>
<P>
   Lycopene may help prevent some cancers, especially prostate and
cervical cancers. Tomatoes are a great source, along with
grapefruit, raspberries, strawberries and watermelon. Saponins,
found in garlic, dried beans and asparagus, may help protect
against high cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Those are just a few examples of the kinds of nutrients
scientists have identified in fruits and vegetables that are
proving to be powerful agents of health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research began to show that people in cultures with low rates
in cancer and heart disease ate a lot of fruits and veggies,''
Rosenbloom said. ``From there, research began to focus on what
exactly in those foods might be responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   But if all that scientific talk has you overwhelmed, then focus
on other good reasons why eating fruits and vegetables will help
you succeed in meeting your New Year dietary goals.
</P>
<P>
   They taste good. They are colorful and crunchy. And they are
something you can add to your diet rather than subtract.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not as hard to add to your diet as many people seem
to think,'' Trainer said. One point of confusion, she said, is that
people believe only fresh fruits and vegetables meet the
requirement. But in fact, canned and frozen vegetables are just as
good.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer said surprisingly, the same survey of 800 Georgians
statewide that showed only 10 percent are eating five servings a
day, also showed that more than 50 percent said time for cooking
and shopping was not a barrier. The problem, it seems, is folks
simply aren't shopping for and cooking vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a number of health organizations have formed the
Georgia Coalition for Nutrition Education, which is sponsoring a
campaign called ``Take Charge of Your Health.'' And one of the key
messages is the five-a-day advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is a great time to start. Folks who are trying to cut back
or diet will find they don't have to deprive themselves,'' Trainer
said. ``They can satisfy their sweet tooth, crunch and munch and
never get hungry if they've included fruits and vegetables in their
diet plan.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SERVING SAVVY
</P>
<P>
   It's not as hard as one might think to get a serving of fruits
or vegetables. All it takes is a half-cup of cooked vegetables or
fruits; three-quarters of a cup of juice; 1 cup of raw leafy
greens, such as lettuce or 1 medium-size piece of fresh fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  3-5 spears of broccoli
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  7-8 baby carrots or carrot sticks
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1 ear of corn
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  6 spears of asparagus
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1 medium stewed or fresh tomato
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1 medium baked potato
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  4-5 dark green lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Five a day the easy way
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Serve a variety of fresh, frozen and canned fruits.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep fruit handy. Carry a piece in your purse or briefcase.
Create a community fruit bowl at work. At home, keep a fruit bowl
near the family's spot for watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cut up raw fruits and veggies and keep healthy dips in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Keep dried fruits, such as raisins, apples or apricots in the
car.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drink 100 percent fruit juices more often.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Start early. Breakfast is a great time to work in two servings
of fruit _ try fresh fruit with cereal and a glass of juice.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make salads healthier with dark greens such as spinach. Feel
free to use the salads in a bag.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add frozen vegetable mixes to rice, pasta or broth for a quick
meal.
</P>
<P>
   Source: American Dietetic Association
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
