<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6040 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TULANE-BICKLEY-AZ     12-24 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TULANE-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNBEATEN TULANE CAN'T WIN RESPECT IN BCS SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS - Eleven and oh, and anarchy rules.
</P>
<P>
   The head coach is gone, punched his ticket. His replacement is a
mystery man, rarely seen on campus. What once was an office is now
a storage room brimming with packed boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Half the assistants are lame ducks, the others unsure of their
future. The seniors have turned into counselors, helping the young
ones cope with the lessons of change. Amid the swirl of emotion,
there is one last game, one last chance to be remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven and oh, and a football team dealing with a whole lot of
BCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``Respect us,'' Tulane defensive end Kevin Reavis said. ``Look
at our record, look at our scores. We're not 11-0 by some fluke.
We're 11-0 because we can play football.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Away from the French Quarter and cobblestone filth, up St.
Charles Street and past the old-money mansions, Tulane University
sits under a shroud of abandonment.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Green Wave was a novelty, a team that had a
cornerback named Michael Jordan and a trainer named Scott Pippin.
This season, they are one of two undefeated teams left in the
nation, a team that started out No. 43 and ended up No. 10. A team
that might have been hosed by the process.
</P>
<P>
   They have a quarterback _ Shaun King _ who set an NCAA record
for passing efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   They have an offense that has scored more than 40 points eight
times, beating a pair of bowl teams in Southern Mississippi and
Louisville. They toppled Navy, 42-24. And in the only barometer of
relativity, they beat Houston, 48-20.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA beat Houston, 42-24. Tennessee beat Houston, 42-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (King) is the MVP in the country,'' Houston Coach Kim
Helton said after losing to Tulane. ``Without that QB, they don't
win five games. I'm not ready to bronze his shoes, but if there's
another QB who's done as much for his school, I haven't seen him.''
</P>
<P>
   So the best snapshot of Tulane is this: An explosive offense, a
mediocre defense and a wonderful quarterback. In other words, no
different than UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're upset because we feel more worthy than some of the teams
playing on January 1,'' King said. ``But we understand. We're not
bitter. When you start out about 40, it's hard to work your way up.
And if you don't play a top-20 schedule, you're not going to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   So Tulane is off for the Liberty Bowl on the afternoon of New
Year's Eve. Against Brigham Young (9-4). They are a team that got
lost inside the BCS computer, which is really the reason their head
coach isn't around anymore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QC; 
Tommy Bowden became a commodity about three weeks into the season,
when he was the only undefeated Bowden left in college football.
</P>
<P>
   Before he arrived in 1997, Tulane had won five games in the
previous three years. Its record in the previous six years was
16-62. It hadn't been to a bowl game since 1987. But in his debut
season, Tulane went 7-4, showcasing an innovative passing attack,
causing a major ripple in college football.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Green Wave beat up everybody. Bowden had turned
things around quickly, too quickly, and in early December, he was
gone. Off to Clemson, taking four assistants with him.
</P>
<P>
   Those four will hang around until the conclusion of the Liberty
Bowl, but the rest of the staff is in jeopardy. Those men may or
may not make the cut of Coach Chris Scelfo, whose credentials are a
bit murky. He was an assistant coach for three years at Georgia. He
is the son of a legendary Louisiana high school coach. No one knows
much about him because Scelfo is staying out of the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guy is to be commended,'' King said. ``He knows
these coaches got us to this level, and he's staying out of it.
It's hard to become the head of something and then sit and watch.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it hard to say goodbye? Last year, Mack Brown left
10-1 North Carolina before its bowl game. It's ridiculous, and it
happens all the time.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're 11-0? It may be a first in NCAA history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of young guys at every position that Coach Bowden
had recruited,'' defensive tackle Phil Henderson said. ``The Bowden
name is very big in the South, and there were guys who thought they
were going to run his offense, guys who thought he would be here a
long time. We had to tell them what was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, there were rumors that the Sugar Bowl might select Tulane,
spotlighting the hometown heroes. That the Orange Bowl once
pondered pitting Bowden vs. Bowden. Even the yellow jackets from
the Fiesta Bowl paid a courtesy visit.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, there was reality, followed by a hard-line decision:
</P>
<P>
   If you can go 11-0 at Tulane and not crack the BCS, well, it's
never going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tulane offered me everything that Clemson did, except what I
was looking for,'' Bowden said. ``And it was the challenge to play
in the arena we've got to play in and the people we've got to play
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Funny thing about college coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Once they get where they're going, they're going someplace
else. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QC; 
New Orleans rests below sea level, a city flanked by the
Mississippi River and Lake Pontchartrain, a city on constant alert
for disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Before a game at Southern Methodist, a tropical storm flooded
the area, forcing police to escort players to the airport. A home
game against Navy was played as the city braced for Hurricane
Georges. After it was over, Bowden immediately dispatched his
players to be with family _ most of whom had evacuated the city.
</P>
<P>
   And the following week, in preparation for Southern Miss and the
biggest game of the season, they had no indoor site to practice
(the Superdome was being used as a homeless shelter) and discovered
King had a broken bone in his left wrist. The underrated star wore
a cast for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, they have prevailed. A team that completely
upstaged Louisiana State, the local powerhouse. The architect who
stepping-stoned his way to a bigger stage and better rewards.
``We've been through obstacles all season long,'' Reavis said. ``So
a coach leaving isn't going to bother us too much. Not after what
we've been through.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an example of right and wrong, the resiliency of young
athletes and the residue of a system gone wrong. Had Tulane been
rewarded, Bowden would've likely stuck around for the bowl game,
maybe another season.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, would it have killed Bowden to spend another
three weeks in New Orleans, to finish what he started?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but coaches come and go, and December is the month of
musical chairs. You can't waste all that free recruiting time with
players who can't help you next season, now can you? As for those
players stuck with broken hearts and broken promises, well, sorry,
that's just the way it goes.
</P>
<P>
   They are acting tough, talking mature, but inside, the Green
Wave knows what's up. It's Christmas Eve and they're on their own,
with one last chance to escape the vacuum of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, nobody will care where we were ranked or what bowl
we played in,'' King said. ``We'll be undefeated. Forever. And
people will remember.'' &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
