<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0185 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6042 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIFESTYLE-CHANGES26-C     12-24 1394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIFESTYLE-CHANGES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 26
 &HT;    A new year is around the corner, and with it come resolutions
for personal improvement
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I do not understand what I do. For what I want to do, I do not
do, but what I hate I do. . . For I have the desire to do what is
good, but I cannot carry it out. . . . What a wretched man I am!''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Apostle Paul
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's no mistaking the anguished tone of Paul as he
wrestles with a struggle common to most people _ the fierce quest
for personal transformation.
</P>
<P>
   Paul never revealed what he grappled with, only that it was a
``thorn in my flesh.'' But anyone trying to kick an addiction,
embarking on a new career, attempting to save a marriage or
friendship, or making any other such change in their life
understands how agonizing change can be.
</P>
<P>
   Still, people persist, especially at this time of the year when
New Year's resolutions are made. Yet by spring, many of those
resolutions have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Change is difficult, but it adds zest to life, said Atlanta
psychiatrist Frank Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you change your pattern, it makes you more alert to
everything,'' Pittman said. ``When you take an unfamiliar route
home, or when you're around people you don't know as well, you
become more alert. You get bright-eyed and bushy-tailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other therapists, pastors and recovering addicts agree.
They offer some suggestions that might prove helpful as the New
Year approaches:
</P>
<P>
   DEVELOP A NEW HABIT ``I can resist everything except
temptation.''
</P>
<P>
   That line, from the 19th century Irish playwright Oscar Wilde,
contains a truth that many people are reluctant to admit. Bad
habits are hard to kick because people derive great pleasure and
comfort in them.
</P>
<P>
   Find a new set of habits to replace the old ones, Pittman said.
When he kicked a 30-year smoking habit in 1985, he discovered that
exercise gave him the physical satisfaction that he once craved
from cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Extend that principle to any bad habit, even ones that involve
moral failures, Pittman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people who have been in the habit of messing around and
keeping things secret will substitute honesty and intimacy in their
marriage, they'll discover all sorts of wonderful things,'' Pittman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Millman, a speaker and best-selling author of ``Everyday
Enlightenment'' (Warner Books, $22), said sheer willpower isn't
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't focus on not doing something,'' he said. ``Focus on
doing something else.''Be wary of sweeping resolutions _ ``I'll
never do that again!'' Some people never change because they try to
tackle too much too soon, Pittman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They make it all or nothing,'' he added. ``If they eat one
cookie or leer at one passing person, they feel as if they've
failed and they give up on the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Do what Michael Stanley, an Atlanta reiki and meditation
teacher, did when he quit smoking after 40 years. He started small.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't say, `I'm going to stop smoking,' '' said Stanley,
57. ``I said, `I will not smoke the next cigarette.' If we start
off with something too big, we're doomed to fail. If you have small
success, it encourages you to keep trying. Small success spurs us
on to make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   GET UP AND MOVE
</P>
<P>
   Some change is not planned, but forced upon people. Newt
Gingrich and House Speaker-elect Bob Livingston resign from public
office, victims of political intrigue. Dallas Cowboy Deion Sanders,
reeling from divorce proceedings, contemplates suicide, but instead
embraces Christianity. Televangelist Jim Bakker is convicted of
swindling thousands of supporters of millions of dollars and
rethinks his life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   People are fired, get divorced, become victims of crime and
nature. Often they become paralyzed.
</P>
<P>
   Keep moving. That's what Russell Malone did after being dropped
by a recording company in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, a jazz guitarist, was ``stunned'' at the time. The
Georgia native was settled comfortably in Atlanta and his solo
career seemed strong.
</P>
<P>
   But after learning that he had been dropped by Columbia, Malone
didn't miss a beat. He moved to New York and became a sought-after
sideman, playing with jazz greats such as Jimmy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Now Malone, 35, is a nationally known jazz guitarist. He
recently released a solo album, ``Sweet Georgia Peach,'' and is a
member of one of the most popular jazz acts today, the Diana Krall
Trio.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is clear. As the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. said,
don't get frozen by the ``paralysis of analysis.'' When change
shakes up your life, do something tangible: Move if you have to,
fill out that job application, learn a new skill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody once told me, `You can be sitting on the right track,
but if you don't get up and move, you'll just get run over,' ''
Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   DON'T BE LONE RANGER
</P>
<P>
   America loves cowboys. The image of the solitary lawman,
epitomized by actor Gary Cooper in the legendary film ``High
Noon,'' is embedded in the country's national psyche. And while
lone rangers may lick the bad guys, they rarely kick bad habits,
addiction counselors warn.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to kick an addiction, join a community of people
with the same mission. Don't try it alone.
</P>
<P>
   That is what saved Michael Stamps, an assistant pastor at
Antioch Baptist Church North.
</P>
<P>
   Stamps, 44, struggled with cocaine and alcohol addiction for
many years. He flirted with change but wasn't successful until he
joined a Christian recovery group at Antioch.
</P>
<P>
   Stamps has been clean for nine years. Recovering addicts he met
in church inspired him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured if they could do it, maybe I could do it, too,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Change your playmates if you want to change your habits, Stamps
said. ``If you want to be a millionaire, you don't hang around
broke people. All they can teach you is how to be broke.''
</P>
<P>
   HAVE A LITTLE FAITH
</P>
<P>
   ``You have made us for yourself and our hearts are restless
until they can find peace in you.''
</P>
<P>
   The quotation comes from St. Augustine, a man who knew about bad
habits. In his autobiographical ``The Confessions,'' Augustine said
only God's power delivered him from his hedonistic lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Bad habits are often driven by a hunger that only a belief in
God can satisfy, many say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Behind any major addiction is a deep spiritual hunger,'' said
Margaret Bullitt-Jonas, a speaker and Episcopal priest whose bout
with overeating is detailed in ``Holy Hunger'' (Alfred Knopf, $23).
</P>
<P>
   ``In all of us, there's a hunger for intimacy, belonging and
communion with the source of life itself,'' she said. ``You need to
find a spiritual practice and spiritual community that feeds your
soul.''
</P>
<P>
   BE COMMITTED
</P>
<P>
   There's hope, even if you don't believe in God. Something in the
universe will still believe in you if you are committed to change,
some say.
</P>
<P>
   Stacy Mayo not only believes that, she's seen it happen. The
41-year-old Smyrna resident founded the Center for Balanced Living,
where she ``coaches'' people on how to realize their dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell people, when you get clear on what you want to do, what
you're passionate about and you commit to it, resources line up
that you never expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That is what W.H. Murray, a Scottish mountaineer, discovered
when he led an expedition to Mount Everest in 1951. His words are
worth noting:
</P>
<P>
   ``Until one is committed, there is hesitancy, the chance to draw
back, always ineffective concerning all acts of initiative (and
creation),'' Murray wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one elementary truth, the ignorance of which kills
countless ideas and splendid plans; that the moment one definitely
commits oneself, then providence moves, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``All sorts of things occur to help one that would never
otherwise have occurred. A whole stream of events issues from the
decision, raising in one's favor all manner of unforeseen incidents
and meetings and material assistance, which no man could have
dreamt would have come his way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have learned a deep respect for one of Goethe's couplets:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Whatever you can do, or dream you can, begin it.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Boldness has genius, power and magic in it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
