<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS SAYS NEW ENGLAND EXPERIENCE PAST HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ He's been gone for two years. But absence only
has made Bill Parcells's shadow grow larger over his old team,
especially with the progress he's made with his new one.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has put New England behind him. Maybe he has. But New
England certainly hasn't put Parcells behind it, and the Jets coach
addressed that phenomenon Thursday before his team's late-morning
workout in preparation for Sunday's game against the Patriots at
the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media makes more of this,'' he said. ``I know a lot of
players on that team. I know what the relationships are. But what
it really is is good copy. I don't let the personal stuff get into
it. I never have. That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he's no different than a lot of coaches and
players who are moving around in this era of free agency. He said
it will continue to happen and that football is a ``transient
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his former players in New England, the coach said,
``The only thing I allow myself to be satisfied about is that in
the time I was there, I brought in seven Pro Bowl players. That's
what makes me feel good. And I'm pretty sure Ted Johnson is going
to make it, so that will be eight. But I can't take credit for what
they've done the last two years.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach said New England now is just another division rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good rivalry,'' he said. ``I expect the game to be
clean and hard-hitting. You acquire a respect for a quality
opponent and that's what they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you say, coach.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parcells ran his troops through an indoor practice because an
overnight snowstorm made the outside field too icy. The Jets will
have Friday morning off, but will report Friday afternoon for
practice at 1 _ outdoors _ and another outdoor walk-through
Saturday . . . There was no change on the status of either Keith
Byars (arm) or Aaron Glenn (ankle). Byars is expected to play, but
Glenn may have to miss his third straight game . . . Parcells said
he's still fond of Patriots quarterback Scott Zolak and revealed
that he and his wife used to dog-sit for Zolak's bulldog, Molly.
``There were couches in our house that I couldn't sit on, but they
were OK for Molly,'' Parcells said. He said Zolak had another
pooch, Boomer, but he was much larger and thus was not welcome in
the Parcells home . . . The Jets and Vinny Testaverde will not
complete a new contract for the quarterback anytime soon. There was
some incentive money moved to next year, Testaverde's option year,
and negotiations will continue probably into February. ``Fellas,
you might as well forget about this one for a while, because
nothing is going to happen,'' Parcells said. ``The urgency is
off.'' The Jets had hoped to have the deal done by Saturday for
salary cap reasons . . . The Jets are 3-0 in December, including
successive road victories vs. Miami and Buffalo. Parcells prides
himself on having December-ready teams; overall, his record for the
month is 35-20 for a 61.5 winning percentage . . . The Jets have
won five straight and nine of 10. The only loss in that stretch was
a 1-pointer at Indianapolis. Of course, one of the wins was the
disputed victory over Seattle. Of the Jets' four losses, three have
come to losing teams: Indianapolis, Baltimore, and St. Louis . . .
Only six Jets remain from Patriots coach Pete Carroll's stint as
New York's head man. Eight who played for Parcells in New England
have followed him to New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
