<SLUG> BC-CHRISTMAS-GULF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLIDAY PERVADES, EVEN ON A MILITARY MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE USS BELLEAU WOOD, Persian Gulf _ On schedule in the
rec room tonight: ``It's a Wonderful Life,'' by order of the
chaplain. Plastic holly leaves and strips of tinsel are taped to
bulkhead doors within the vast hull of this amphibious assault
ship. A dungareed sailor absently whistles an off-key ``Angels We
Have Heard on High'' as he scans the shimmering heat-hazed horizon
with powerful binoculars.
</P>
<P>
   It is the season of peace on earth, good will toward men. But
this season seems preposterously incongruous with the mission of
the thousands of American soldiers, sailors and aviators massed in
a region that has become synonymous with bloodshed and turmoil. And
the official line spouted on the Belleau Wood is that Christmas is
just another routine working day for its stretched-to-the edge
complement of 2,200 Navy personnel and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   Not that many buy the official line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the spirit of Christmas will find you no matter you
are, no matter how strange the setting,'' said Maj. John A. Wilson
of Lynn, Marine pilot and operations officer for the helicopters
and Harrier ``jump jets'' stationed aboard the 820-foot vessel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say, `Hey, I can't be thinking of Christmas out here,' ''
he said. ``But, truth is, you can't stop thinking about Christmas,
or your loved ones. It can be a bittersweet time of year for
military people. You just try to stop that ache and count your
blessings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson spent the four-day Desert Fox operation flying helicopter
support missions for the Marines who were landed on the desert
shores at the outset of the latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   If the peace holds, he'll spend Christmas flying ``Santa
missions'' _ his Huey gunship laden like St. Nick's sled with the
first hot chow deliveries for the devil dogs, as Marines call
themselves, still hunkered in foxholes near the Iraq border.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our Marines onshore, a taste of hot turkey and some mail
would be like _ well, like Christmas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mail from home is pouring into the Persian Gulf at nearly
the volume of the ordnance and other military supplies: Christmas
cards, boxes of candy and _ aboard the Belleau Wood at least _ one
20-inch-tall living Christmas tree sent to devil dog Staff Sgt.
Eric Tausch. Love, Mom.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way from Durango, Colorado, and that good American
dirt is still fresh,'' said Tausch, showing off the
merrily-decorated little tree to the flight deck crew crowding
around. ``Smell that spruce! Is that the smell of Christmas, or
what?''
</P>
<P>
   The ship courses smoothly back and forth across the green
swells. On a sweep close to shore, the white minarets of Muslim
mosques can be seen rising from a settlement on the edge the
dazzling sands. Giant oil field flare towers, coincidentally
painted red, burn like a long row of holiday candles.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bill DeVine of Boston, a Roman Catholic priest by vocation,
a lieutenant commander by naval rank, is chaplain for the Belleau
Wood and two accompanying vessels, the USS Dubuque and the USS
Germantown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a dangerous world, as events of the past few days
have demonstrated,'' he said. ``Everyone aboard this ship is
working very hard to keep in readiness for a job most hope they
never have to do _ fight a war. So even with a Christmas sing-along
at 19:00 hours, decorations in the cafeteria or cookies from home,
the season is going to seem a little off-key out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``Our celebration can perhaps be a bit more
spiritual. A time of quiet prayer or reflection, not just
presents.''
</P>
<P>
   Up on the bridge, Lt. Commmander Jim Hruska of Brookline, Mass.,
navigator of the Belleau Wood, is preoccupied with electronic
charts and guidance systems. ``My job is to get the ship from Point
A to Point B as quickly and as safely as possible,'' he said. ``By
naval standards, the Persian Gulf is a tight body of water for
manuvering. There are lots of hazards, from mines to offshore oil
rigs. So I can't say I'm overflowing with the season's spirit. But
it's there.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Kelly, also from Massachusetts, is back at the ship's
base in Sasebo, Japan. And he acknowledged that it's a particularly
tough time of year to be apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cards and letters from home soften the blow. Believe me, a
Christmas card counts as something real precious when you are this
far from everyone you love,'' he said. ``I just hope my wife can
take comfort that I'm on a real life mission, serving the real
interests of our country. I know I take comfort from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course there's the occasional scoffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christmas? Just another 24 hours out on the boat, that's
all,'' said Maj. J.E. Szewczynski, a Marine Harrier pilot from
Yuma, Arizona. ``Sure I'd rather be with my wife and four children.
But I'm not, so I just focus on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   A warship is basically a floating delivery system of death and
destruction, a thing of cold steel and hard edges. But it's also a
community. And for all their tough talk and strutting, the sailors
and Marines aboard are bound by more than just duty and military
routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got family back in the states who I miss worse than words
could possibly say,'' said Lt. Kristen A. Lasica of Chicago, part
of the Marine expeditionary unit transported to the Gulf by the
Belleau Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, corny as it sounds, the people aboard this
vessel, they're like family, too,'' she said ``We'll just be doing
our jobs on Christmas, sure. But we'll carrying the season in our
hearts and taking strength from each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
