A6099 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN27-COX     12-24 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIBLEY-COLUMN27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    Hastings' `Rich Harvest' plants ideas for spring
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The days between Christmas and New Year's are
traditionally time spent with seed catalogs and dreams of spring
planting.
</P>
<P>
   I didn't realize that H.G. Hastings, the famed and most
respected seedsman, fostered that idea until I read the new book by
his grandson, Don Hastings. Family and plant workers hurried in the
days after Christmas to get the seed catalogs in the mail, Don
wrote, and I remember that it renewed the excitement that could
have dissipated otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   My mother, a strong devotee of the Hastings company, and all my
farmer friends in the Roswell area, who swore by Hastings and
especially Hastings Prolific corn, probably felt there was no more
constructive way of using that between-holidays time.
</P>
<P>
   Reading Don's book is another good way to use the time. If you
have or haven't received the pretty catalogs yet, you will be
happily engrossed in the pleasures and problems of tilling the
soil, with ``Rich Harvest: A Life in the Garden'' (Longstreet,
$20).
</P>
<P>
   The story of an enduring seeds and plants enterprise has not
been told before, so far as I know. The Hastings family, going back
to 1889, have been the authoritative voice on Southern gardening.
Don's grandfather and father, Harry Hastings and Donald Hastings,
and Don's mother, Louise Hastings, have written, demonstrated,
grown and sold almost every vegetable, flower, tree and vine known
to the South.
</P>
<P>
   Don himself served as a talk show host on radio and television
for 14 years, cheering, encouraging and sometimes scolding fumbling
tillers of the soil. He has spent years in Malaysia, Egypt and the
Philippines instructing horticulturists there in the commercial
growing of vast fields of vegetables to feed that part of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Don and his wife, Betsy, and their two sons are my neighbors,
and I have known when the family departed for one of their overseas
adventures. But I didn't know the fascinating details of problems
encountered and problems solved, as related in this book.
</P>
<P>
   The night I finished reading ``Rich Harvest,'' rain was
hammering on my cabin roof, or I think I would have been out in the
yard with a shovel trying to get ready for a vegetable garden. Don
is that inspiring. Although horticulture is his career (and also
that of his younger son, Chris, who is getting his master's degree
in horticulture from Don's alma mater, Cornell University), you get
the idea that his heart really belongs to his own personal acres in
north Fulton County(Ga.). He has many amusing stories to tell of
growing up at the Hastings home, Floweracres(Ga.), near Griffin,
and toiling in the fields with the hired hands.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's gardens close to the house were an education in
themselves, but he gives abundant credit to Georgia's plain
farmers, who knew instinctively many secrets of the earth that
Cornell didn't teach him. He is also grateful to the professors
there, who instructed him in the science of the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed with the personal adventures here and abroad are concrete
facts about fertilizer, pesticides and the turning of the soil.
With typical generosity, Don gives credit to people who helped him
along the way, many of them well-known to all of us who showed up
at Hastings' Atlanta garden center with limp-leafed plants and
burning questions.
</P>
<P>
   I especially liked his chapter on old and distinguished trees on
Atlanta's streets. I'm planning a pilgrimage to see the grandpappy
of all our Burford holly shrubs in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Celestine Sibley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
