<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6101 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      12-24 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES AND NEWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nod to Olmsted and the Ice Age
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Public Art Fund has big plans for the southeast
entrance to Central Park, officially known as the Doris C. Freedman
Plaza. The nonprofit Art Fund has orchestrated projects like the
water tower that the English artist Rachel Whiteread cast in resin
and installed on a SoHo roof this summer. For the last year and a
half, it has been working with Andrea Zittel, the American
installation artist, on a project for the park.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Zittel will create a series of faux-rock outcroppings, made
in Palmyra, Va., with a steel infrastructure and layers of
carefully painted concrete. The work, ``Point of Interest,'' will
mimic the use of boulders by the park's original designer,
Frederick Law Olmsted, and echo those in the nearby zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The $75,000 project will be installed in April and is expected
to be the largest one that the organization has done for the plaza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be up for nearly a year and will change with the
backdrop of the seasons,'' said Susan K. Freedman, president of the
Public Art Fund. The plaza was named after her mother.
</P>
<P>
   New Sotheby's Venture
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has taken another giant step into territory once
reserved for dealers. The auction house announced this week that it
had organized an exhibition of Buddhist ritual and ceremonial
objects in association with Rossi &AMP; Rossi, London dealers who
specialize in Asian art.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said it has a financial interest in the items in the
show, but declined to discuss the details.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years Sotheby's has bought art galleries and helped
dealers finance purchases. It also has gone into partnership with
dealers on private sales. But this is the first time it has entered
a retail venture with a gallery. Everything in the show is for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the show is another unexpected bit of news. It will
be held in the former Andre Emmerich Gallery in the Fuller
Building. Sotheby's, whose headquarters in New York, bought the
Emmerich Gallery two years ago but in October announced it was
closing the 45-year-old business and consolidating its operations
at Deitch Projects, a SoHo gallery partially owned by Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   When Sotheby's announced it was closing Emmerich, it said space
in the Fuller Building was too expensive to keep. ``We haven't
given up the lease,'' said Matthew Weigman, a Sotheby's spokesman.
``In addition to exhibitions, the space will be used for
auction-related exhibitions and private sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's declined to say how long the lease runs.
</P>
<P>
   From March 24 to April 3, when collectors and dealers will be in
New York for the Asian art auctions and the International Asian Art
Fair, the old Emmerich space will become a showcase for about 60
artworks. These will include gold and silver objects, textiles,
painting and sculpture, all from Tibet and the Himalayan region and
dating from the 12th to the 19th centuries. The objects were
gathered over several years by Rossi &AMP; Rossi from collectors and
private dealers in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area that's never been shown before,'' said Carlton
C. Rochell Jr., who heads Sotheby's Asian departments worldwide.
``It's totally cutting edge. It won't compete with our auctions.
It's a great opportunity to educate the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Why will the show be at the Fuller Building?
</P>
<P>
   ``The show needs more time and space than Sotheby's premises
could allow,'' Rochell said. ``We will be able to give the show
4,000 square feet. It's a retail exhibition and should be on middle
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, there is a financial benefit for them, as there is for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first Rossi &AMP; Rossi show in New York. In 1996 it
exhibited 30 Tibetan wooden covers made for manuscript containers
from the 12th to 15th centuries. That show was at the Barbara
Mathes Gallery, which is also in the Fuller Building.
</P>
<P>
   Fabio Rossi, an owner, said he did not believe the public or the
art world would have a negative reaction to Sotheby's involvement
in the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antagonism between dealers and auction houses may have existed
in the 80's, but it's a situation we are moving away from,'' he
said. ``Sotheby's can help us create a market. They have an
infrastructure that's useful. Their marketing powers are bigger
than any single dealer.''
</P>
<P>
   Branching Out
</P>
<P>
   The Sterling and Francine Clark Art Institute in Williamstown,
Mass., has been adding to its collection in significant directions.
For starters, it recently bought an important Old Master painting,
``Virgin and Child with Sts. Elizabeth and John the Baptist,''
painted around 1520 by Quentin Massys. The 25-by-20-inch panel
painting was reportedly bought by the museum for less than $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have mostly 19th-century and Impressionist art, but we do
have some Old Masters,'' said Michael Conforti, the director of the
Clark. ``This is a devotional panel in its original frame and in
perfect condition, which is highly unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Conforti said the Clark had known about the painting for about
three years. It came from a private British collection and will be
displayed with Renaissance works by Piero della Francesca, Perugino
and Hans Memling.
</P>
<P>
   The Clark spent the last eight months forming a serious
collection of 19th-century photographs. This is the institute's
first new area of collecting since its founding in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was either now or never,'' Conforti said. ``We've combed
private collections and auction houses to see what's interesting in
the field.''
</P>
<P>
   At Christie's in London in May the Clark spent more than
$250,000 on five photographs. It also bought a Baldus, ``The House
of the Faloise'' (1857), from a private French collection and a
Degas photograph at Sotheby's in New York this fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1739EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
