<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-DEMENIL27-COX     12-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-DEMENIL27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    Pair's unflagging drive cleared a path to culture
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ You don't have to walk into one of the two chapels in
this city's unique arts compound to get the feeling you are in a
sacred precinct.
</P>
<P>
   You can, instead, visit the artwork in the Menil Collection.
Whether you fall under the magic spell of the African masks or
enter the dream world of surrealist Belgian painter Rene Magritte,
this repository of John and Dominique de Menil's private art
collection is a spiritual experience.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique de Menil once wrote, ``Through art, God constantly
clears a path to our hearts.'' For the de Menils, many kinds of art
cleared the path. Modern and contemporary art may dominate this
highly regarded collection, but it also encompasses folk art and
ancient western and tribal arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Menil sets a standard for private collections that one
could only hope to have in one's city,'' said Atlanta's High Museum
of Art director Ned Rifkin.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the serenity-inducing calm of their complex,
these French sophisticates kicked up quite a storm when they
arrived in provincial Houston of the early 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They decided to do something, and they dragged everyone along
with them,'' said Peter Marzio, director of the city's Museum of
Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   They stamped Houston with their aesthetic vision, their taste,
even their liberal politics. Like a tornado spinning in off the
prairie, they stirred things up, bringing in speakers, getting
involved in arts organizations, even starting the equivalent of a
stock club for purchasing art. Theirs was a life of cultural
ferment, and they shared it with their fellow Houstonians.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never knew who you'd meet when you went for dinner,''
recalled Louisa Stude Sarofim, president of the board of directors
of the Menil Foundation. ``It could be Roberto Rossellini or Marcel
Duchamp,'' referring to the Italian movie director and the
French-born artist.
</P>
<P>
   The de Menils, both deceased, didn't start collecting art in
earnest until after they came to Houston, where John ran
Dominique's family's business, Schlumberger Ltd. But once they got
going, their enthusiasm was unstoppable. It extended to
architecture as well as art. They asked Philip Johnson to design
their home, the first modernist residence in Houston, as well as
the master campus plan for the University of St. Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   The Contemporary Arts Museum was initially a focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they even bought works to fill out shows,'' said
retired art critic Ann Holmes. ``But they liked to be in charge.''
When a dissident faction fired Jermayne MacAgy, whom they had
brought in as director, the de Menils shifted their attention to
the University of St. Thomas, where MacAgy taught and curated.
After MacAgy's sudden death, Dominique took over.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to bring (ancient pre-Greek) Cycladic figures to
class in her purse,'' recalled gallery owner Fredericka Hunter, who
studied with her. ``People like (director Michelangelo) Antonioni
and (artist Andy) Warhol came through, and the students got to pick
them up at the airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever seeking the sacred in art _ not necessarily the
conventionally sacred _ the de Menils built the Rothko Chapel in
1971. Fourteen brooding, monumental, almost monochrome paintings by
the abstract expressionist master hang around the octagonal
interdenominational meditation room.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique carried on after her husband's death in 1973,
commissioning Italian architect Renzo Piano to design a museum
building for the collection and a smaller one devoted to Cy
Twombly's paintings and sculptures. A deceptive simplicity and
special attention to the quality of light characterize both highly
acclaimed buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Indefatigable even at 75, Dominique, who died last year at 91,
saw to the rescue and restoration of some stolen Cypriot fresco
fragments. She commissioned her architect son Francois to design a
home for them. The Byzantine Fresco Chapel Museum, which opened in
1997, is exquisite. Like an abstracted orthodox church, its simple
exterior makes the otherworldly experience of interior that much
more dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dominique changed Houston,'' said Sarofim. ``She made art
acceptable, made people more conscious of art as being an essential
part of our life. Houston would be emptier, more soulless, but for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
