<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-HOUSTON27-COX     12-24 1741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-HOUSTON27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    With its philanthropic tradition and Texas-size hunger for
top-tier status, the Houston's an arts-embracing role model
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ This city of almost 4 million people is a booming New
South metropolis, sprawling all over the place and proud as punch
about it. Its downtown is an Oz of glass and steel and stone
skyscrapers rising from the plains. Freeways slice through the
cityscape.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Houston might seem to be just a more humid
version of Atlanta. Take a closer look. That hole in the ground
downtown is not a new high-rise in the making but a two-theater
performing arts center. The building under construction a few miles
down the road is not a new mall but a $55 million addition to
Houston's Museum of Fine Arts. Off in a quiet residential
neighborhood in between, the Menil Foundation has added another
building to an arts complex that draws pilgrims from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is home to the kind of visual arts philanthropy that
Atlanta institutions can only envy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giving,'' says Peter Marzio, director of the Museum of Fine
Arts, ``is a very Houston thing to do. It's in the water.
</P>
<P>
   People here believe in less government (and less government
funding), but they are willing to fill the gap. People give out of
a notion of public responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   As the High Museum of Art movesll deliberateness to start
a fund drive for its addition in Atlanta, Houston's Museum of Fine
Arts is in the midst of a campaign so successful that it upped the
ante from $100 million to $112 million. Starting off with major
gifts also helps, such as $20 million from the Houston Endowment
and $15 million from longtime patron Carolyn Weiss Law, who also
purchased the land for the addition.
</P>
<P>
   The MFA already boasts a $400 million endowment, the
fifth-largest in the country, ahead of the Museum of Modern Art's
$300 million in New York and substantially beyond the High's $52
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their endowment is almost 10 times ours,'' said High director
Ned Rifkin. ``That speaks volumes about people's understanding of
what an endowment means to an institution. It's not a priority for
this community. Although we are working to orient future donors
that way, it takes a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the improvements the wistful Rifkin could imagine with
such an endowment is a significant upgrade in the quality of the
collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We depend on gifts, which is very different from targeting
works of art and purchasing them in a strategic way,'' he said.
``We do have significant endowments in the decorative arts, and you
can see the results.''
</P>
<P>
   The sense of public responsibility is evident in the magnitude
of Houston's gift giving as well. When Audrey Jones Beck was
building her collection of late 19th-century and early modern
paintings, now a highlight at the Houston museum, she acquired not
just out of personal passion but, as she wrote, because of her
``dream to collect a representative group of impressionists works
for Houston.'' (Italics mine.)
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropy is a value passed on through the generations. Beck
is the daughter of Jesse Jones, an oil and newspaper magnate who
founded the 50-year-old Houston Endowment, the largest foundation
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Marzio, 56, said that most of his board is younger than he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were raised in a world of philanthropy,'' explained Louisa
Stude Sarofim, a patron of the Contemporary Arts Museum and many
smaller organizations. ``It was part of our upbringing to give and
make things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at a desk covered with postcards of works of art and
surrounded by examples of the works on paper she collects, the
Houstonian, president of the board of directors of the Menil
Foundation, remembers her mother reading letters from students her
family had helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to give if (the organization) is really original and
weaves into the fabric of the city,'' Sarofim said.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents started the Brown Foundation, one of five or six
family foundations whose giving has been critical to Houston's
cultural life. None is as big as Atlanta's network of
Woodruff-related foundations, which boast $8.8 billion in combined
assets and have been key supporters of the city's cultural
institutions, among its wide array of interests. (The Houston
Endowment, for example, has $1.4 billion.) But together the Houston
foundations have formed an effective network of support. Also, like
the Woodruff, they provide validation that spurs other giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they take a chance, we might, too,'' said Jack Doherty,
director of the Shell Oil Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family foundations are it,'' said Fredericka Hunter, owner
of Texas Gallery in Houston. ``No other city has foundations like
these.''
</P>
<P>
   Oil wealth is the source of much Houston foundation money, but
that shouldn't let Atlanta off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get lots of $55,000, $60,000
</P>
<P>
   checks (from individuals),'' Marzio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what this place runs on. Givers set examples for the
others. Someone says, `If he can do it, I can.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just money, however; it's attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is content with achieving second-tier status and
doesn't feel inspired or moved to become truly world-class in the
arts,'' said Louise Shaw, former director of Nexus Contemporary Art
Center. ``That's reflected in our facilities, the quality of our
institutions, their support. We never seem to want to go the extra
mile to reach the top level.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, said Ann Holmes, who was art critic for the Houston
Chronicle for almost 50 years, ``When Houstonians get behind a
project, they want to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   And they don't wait around. ``People came back from World War II
after living in other places and wanted what they had seen
(elsewhere) in their own town,'' said Marti Mayo, director of the
Contemporary Arts Museum. ``They wanted a more cosmopolitan city.''
</P>
<P>
   A group of contemporary art devotees founded CAM in 1948. At
that time, it was only the third institution in the country devoted
to modern and contemporary art. Even today, there is no equivalent
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, CAM, which now has a $2.1 million budget,
aimed high. Early exhibits included a van Gogh show in 1951; ``The
Family of Man,'' Edward Steichen's milestone photography exhibit,
in 1956; and a Mark Rothko exhibit in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   One CAM patron attributes the support of the arts to the way
Houston welcomes all comers. ``Houston is very open,'' said Sissy
Kempner. ``You might not get into the Bayou Club (an exclusive
private club for old-guard Houstonians), but you can be on any
board in town if you can write the check.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a sunny room crowded, like the others in her home,
with modern and contemporary art, from a small Joseph Cornell
collage to a huge Pat Steir painting, the down-to-earth Kempner
relishes her role.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a bigger city, I would have never been on this board,'' she
said. ``This is an opportunity to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   More than one observer links this openness to the wildcatter
mentality of early 20th-century Houston: It doesn't matter who you
are or where you are from as long as you produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston is not very hierarchical,'' the Texas Gallery's Hunter
said. ``All boundaries are pretty porous.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in the wildcatter mode, the city values innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of place where people are more accustomed to
taking risks,'' said artist Rick Lowe, who founded Project Row
Houses, an imaginative combination of art and community service in
the largely African-American Third Ward. ``They'll support
something because they think, `This is just weird enough to
happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   This we-can-do-anything mentality may have been an impetus for
the Menil family, which has had a profound effect on the arts in
Houston. The French couple settled in Houston in the 1940s so that
John could run the family's oil-related business, Schlumberger Ltd.
Their complex of museums and chapels is only the most obvious
legacy of the indelible mark their infectious passion for art has
made on the history and direction of contemporary art in this city.
As CAM's Mayo said, ``They were utterly critical in forming a taste
for contemporary art and artists in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to benefiting from individual benefactors, Houston
institutions have learned that working together has its advantages.
Although the city is often cited as an example of the perils of no
zoning, 10 museums cluster midway between downtown and the medical
center. The Contemporary Arts Museum is across the street from the
Museum of Fine Arts. The children's and natural science museums are
nearby. Recently, they formed a district and are making a joint
effort to increase visibility.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is just starting to figure out the benefits of
cooperation, as exemplified by the Atlanta Convention and Visitors
Bureau's cultural tourism initiative. Museum of Fine Arts patron
Nina Cullinan gave Houston an object lesson 40 years ago. When she
donated the money for the museum's second addition, Cullinan
included the proviso that the Contemporary Arts Museum could
exhibit in the new space when the MFA's schedule permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the three major fine art institutions _ MFA, CAM and
the Menil Foundation _ jointly hosted the retrospective of former
Texas artist Robert Rauschenberg organized by New York's Guggenheim
Museum. With their collective clout, according to Mayo, they were
able to find sponsors in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A few arts administrators and artists suggest that Houston is
not a paradise for the arts. As is true most everywhere, the larger
institutions get a larger slice of the dollar pie. Emily Todd,
director of DiverseWorks, a smaller alternative space, worries
about ``a lost generation of givers, middle-class baby boomers,''
while Mayo dismisses the image of bountiful Texas philanthropy as
``a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a core of Houstonians and foundations who do the bulk
of the giving. The challenge of arts institutions is to expand that
base,'' Mayo said. ``I see it changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing Houston's generosity to the arts from this side of the
bayou _ where getting support is, as Shaw says, ``an uphill
battle'' _ one can't help feeling that Mayo doesn't realize how
lucky she is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
