<HEADER>
A6105 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARTS-ROWHOUSES27-COX     12-24 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTS-ROWHOUSES27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    Row house rehab project brings art and aid together
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The sound of children at play is a familiar one at
Project Row Houses, but then so is the thwack of an artist's hammer
or the recitation of a poet.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of 37-year-old artist Rick Lowe, this unusual
public art effort nurtures artists, community and even preservation
in 22 renovated shotgun houses in Houston's primarily
African-American Third Ward. Not to be confused with Habitat for
Humanity, which builds permanent homes for needy families, Project
Row Houses offers temporary residences for single mothers and a
slew of complementary programs as well as opportunities for
artists.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the white houses are devoted to giving women a chance to
turn their lives around. They may live in one of the homes with
their children free for 12 to 18 months while they go to school and
attend in-house workshops. The organization uses some of the houses
as classrooms for child care as well.
</P>
<P>
   Artists do installations in eight of the houses. Their projects
have encompassed paintings on the walls, music, poetry and
discussion groups. They also mingle with and give workshops for the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The proximity to creative people and the philosophy that
creativity comes in all forms is one of the characteristics that
distinguishes this from other social programs, according to alumna
Assata Richards, who lived there in 1995-96 and is now pursuing a
doctorate in sociology at Penn State University. She also
appreciates how the program combined art and practical issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was an emphasis on personal development,'' said
Richards, 25. ``We had workshops on sexuality, spirituality,
parenting skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Project Row Houses gave me an opportunity to finish my B.A.,
to build relationships with other women and with artists, to be
part of a larger community. It was so vibrant and busy, always
something going on. It has shaped who I am and who I will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Radcliffe Bailey, one of the participating artists, is
also high on the project's concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of my best experiences as an artist working on
neighborhood projects,'' he said. ``In other places, I felt like it
was missionary work, almost a violation. . . . I brought my father
with me, and we met a lot of interesting people who would just walk
by. I think the neighborhood is very proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Using wood and other materials found in the community as well as
photos, electric candles and sound, Bailey turned a row house into
a series of shrines to a fictitious family he imagined living
there. He considers it one of his best installations.
</P>
<P>
   None of this would have happened without a patron. In 1993, Lowe
was about to give up because the houses were going to be
demolished, and he couldn't come up with the money to buy the
property. Serendipitously, his partner, Deborah Grotfeldt,
mentioned the problem to Isaac Heimbinder, president of
Houston-based U.S. Home Corp., at a cocktail party.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked to his wife and immediately arranged a crucial
$120,000, no-interest loan,'' Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I were able to see that this would be a tremendous
opportunity for the community,'' Heimbinder explained. ``The
program is very creative, and the mothers' program gives back to
the community immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, it offers access to art via living artists
and insight into how art is made. ``If you want people to go to the
ballet or the museum, you have to give them some education first,''
said Heimbinder, also a benefactor of DiverseWorks, an alternative
art presenter. ``Project Row Houses should be a role model for
other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heimbinders have continued to be important patrons, in
various ways. At their instigation, sponsors, vendors and local
interior designers involved in Houston's 1996 home show made
Project Row Houses their cause, furnishing the residential units
and donating all the fixtures instead of creating the standard
in-show vignettes. As a result, the houses have an individuality
and sense of permanence that support the project's goal.
</P>
<P>
   Help has come from local volunteers, who have come out and done
the hands-on renovation work, as well as grants from local
foundations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Houston Endowment supports us, and the Menil Foundation
was very instrumental,'' Lowe said. ``This is one of those moments
when everything comes together.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Project Row Houses won an award from the National Trust
for Historic Preservation. Proud as that makes him, Lowe sets his
priorities on less tangible achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art must enhance our ability to create a more humane
environment and serve as a process that brings people together,''
he said. ``We need new ways of thinking about improving these
communities.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Fox writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
