<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE27-COX     12-24 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    Compilation of Times reviews reflects a century of transience
and trends
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The carcasses of junked automobiles, lying in forgotten heaps
like discarded toys, testify to mortality of another kind. If the
showroom was the nursery, this is the graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   We do better by people, usually, and sometimes by books as well.
A used-book store can be depressing or restorative, depending on
the air of neglect or quiet tribute. But it takes a hopeful heart
to think any book, brightly swaddled in its dust jacket, is
destined for a long life. Most, as David Hume would recall of his
first, ``A Treatise on Human Nature'' (today a classic in modern
philosophy), fall stillborn from the press.
</P>
<P>
   No obituary marks their brief existence. With books, it is the
birth notice, not the obit, that one looks for, and the review _
good or bad _ sometimes attends (or dogs) a book all its life.
Nowhere does one matter more than in The New York Times Book
Review. Indeed, the book that has not been reviewed in the Times is
almost an orphan; as far as its publisher is concerned, a book
doesn't exist until the Times has spoken.
</P>
<P>
   For a century now the Times has been American publishing's
herald and arbiter, pronouncing with magisterial authority on the
work of Henry James and Don DeLillo and an astonishing gallery in
between. Some do the job with equal dedication and others, on
occasion, with greater wit. But none does it as thoroughly, week
after week, year after year.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the cumulative result of so much excellence is, in one
respect, impermanence. ``To read through 100 years of The New Times
Book Review,'' its editor, Charles McGrath, writes in his
introduction to ``Books of the Century,'' ``is to be reminded,
forcefully, that almost nothing lasts. The 99 blue-bound volumes
containing the Book Review so far are crammed together on metal
shelving at the back of the Times's editorial library, some of them
unopened for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what is in that dusty repository is something to behold,
like the jawbone and metatarsus of a creature that has passed out
of existence. ``It is generally conceded,'' an anonymous reviewer
wrote on April 25, 1903 (signed reviews did not appear until the
1930s), ``that Booker T. Washington represents the best hope of the
negro in America, and it is certain that of all the leaders of his
people he has done the most for his fellows with the least friction
with the whites who are most nearly concerned, those of the
South.''
</P>
<P>
   The book under review was ``The Souls of Black Folk'' by W.E.B.
Du Bois.
</P>
<P>
   Half a century later, on April 13, 1952, Wright Morris was
responding to Ralph Ellison's ``Invisible Man'' this way: ``His
report in this novel might be subtitled, `Notes From Underground
America,' or `The Invisible Black Man in the Visible White Man's
World.' That is part of his story, but the deeper layer, revealed,
perhaps, in spite of himself, is the invisible man become visible.
The word, against all odds, becoming flesh.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout, from 1897 to 1997, there is close attention not just
to the book at hand but to the world in which we live. If, here and
there, that world today seems antiquarian, perhaps it is a measure
of its topicality yesterday. From Henry James' ``The Spoils of
Poynton,'' reviewed on Feb. 20, 1897, to DeLillo's ``Underworld,''
reviewed on Oct. 5, 1997, this centennial volume speaks to more
than the rise and fall of literary reputations or the fleeting
familiarity of this book or that. It speaks to a cultural
continuity, one whose breaks and interruptions are sometimes
jolting, to be sure, but nonetheless parts of a whole.
</P>
<P>
   James Joyce and Marcel Proust, Sigmund Freud and Carl Jung,
Virginia Woolf and Simone de Beauvoir, Norman Mailer and Norman
Vincent Peale, James Michener and Aleksandr Solzhenitzyn, Grace
Metalious and Kate Millett, Margaret Mitchell and Thomas Pynchon _
all passed into view and some out of view.
</P>
<P>
   They often were greeted, as Charles McGrath says, with
surprising prescience. When Joyce's ``Ulysses'' _ canonized only a
couple of months ago as the Novel of the Century _ appeared in
1922, the Times' reviewer, one Dr. Joseph Collins, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I venture a prophecy: Not ten men or women out of a hundred
can read `Ulysses' through, and of the ten who succeed in doing so,
five of them will do it as a tour de force. I am probably the only
person, aside from the author, that has ever read it twice from
beginning to end. I have learned more psychology and psychiatry
from it than I did in ten years at the Neurological Institute. . .
. Stephen Dedalus . . . will pretend indifference to the
publication of a laudatory study of `Ulysses' a hundred years
hence, but he is as sure to get it as Dostoyevsky, and surer than
Mallarme.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a quibble, but in this instance and others a reader
wonders who the reviewer was. Dr. Joseph Collins, for one, was not
afraid to pat his own back in the midst of a prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   It's surprising, in fact, what reviews saw beyond the moment.
The unsigned review of ``Gone With the Wind,'' published on July 5,
1936, was sure-footed as it was flat-footed: ``This is beyond a
doubt one of the most remarkable first novels produced by an
American writer. `Gone With The Wind' is by no means a great novel.
But it is a long while since the American reading public has been
offered such a bounteous feast of excellent story telling.''
</P>
<P>
   Organized by decades, ``Books of the Century'' is not a catalog
of hits and misses but a kind of cultural retrospective _ even when
the subject seems almost too slight to notice. That, in fact, was
sometimes precisely the case. One of the amusements of this book is
the acknowledgment of occasional oversight. On Page 465, in a box
under the heading Oops!, there appears the following: ``The Bridges
of Madison County. By Robert James Waller.'' It was published, the
box notes, on April 1, 1992. It was in March of the following year,
after Waller's lachrymose elegy to impossible love had sold in the
millions and prompted who knows how many buckets of middle-aged
tears, that the Times got around to reviewing it.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Times' reviewer had to say at that late date, the
editors of ``Books of the Century'' thought it could be omitted
without grievous harm. (You wonder, though, what unfortunate was
dragooned into duty as reviewer.)
</P>
<P>
   Most books may be transitory and their reviews even more so, but
the enterprise of writing and reviewing leaves its traces. ``If you
look at enough reviews,'' McGrath writes, ``and at reviews over a
long enough period, amid the accidental changes you can spot some
trends or alterations that seem instructive, if not reliably
permanent. The dramatic emergence, for example, of that generation
of writers _ Hemingway, Dreiser, Fitzgerald, et al. _ who in the
years after the First World War transformed the literary landscape
and shifted its center to America. Or the flowering, in response to
the baby boom, of children's literature in the '50s and '60s, the
outpouring of extraordinary and original fiction in the '60s and
'70s, and the great age of biography that seemed to sweep along
afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Not the least of these changes is the maturation of book
reviewing and, eventually, criticism itself _ ``informed,'' as
McGrath writes, ``and readable and aimed at a discerning general
audience.'' Books come and go, and most go for good, never to be
seen again. But there is something reassuring in knowing they were
even here, and in seeing how strong an imprint they made. The
record of it is in the reviews that announced their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Books of the Century: A Hundred Years of Authors, Ideas and
Literature. Times Books. $30. 384 pages.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
