<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTA     12-24 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: all (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `ENEMY OF THE STATE,' starring Will Smith, Gene Hackman, Jon
Voight and Regina King. Directed by Tony Scott (R, 128 minutes).
Smith goes on the run in a paranoid thriller whose high-tech gizmos
are a main attraction. He also carries the story ably in his first
real leading role, that of a successful lawyer who suddenly finds
himself under surveillance by a sizable nerd squad at the National
Security Agency and a satellite in space. Fortunately, it all
hurtles by too fast for audiences to stop for plot questions.
Sterling cast members like Hackman as an eccentric technology whiz
and Voight as a chilly advocate of surveillance tactics bring an
additional touch of class (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `GODS AND MONSTERS,' starring Ian McKellen and Brendan Fraser.
Directed by Bill Condon (not rated, 105 minutes). In a performance
that well deserves to be remembered at the end of the year,
McKellen becomes the deliciously urbane James Whale, the gay
``Frankenstein'' director, playing him late in life. Shaken by the
aftereffects of a mild stroke, this Whale finds his past coming
back to greet him just as the present offers new fascination in the
Adonis-like form of the gardener (Fraser, also fine), whom Whale
finds mowing his lawn. This beautifully acted, witty and
heart-tugging film, from a Christopher Bram book, imagines what
Whale's final days might have been like while shaping a splendid
character study and a droll portrait of closeted gay Hollywood.
Lynn Redgrave provides ballast and comic relief as Whale's
perpetually scandalized housekeeper (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `HAPPINESS,' starring Jane Adams, Dylan Baker, Philip Seymour
Hoffman and Lara Flynn Boyle. Directed by Todd Solondz (not rated;
135 minutes). In a much bigger film than his ``Welcome to the Doll
House,'' this audacious, deadpan filmmaker explores loneliness in
his murderously funny fashion. Outrageous touches _ none more so
than its title _ come easily to ``Happiness,'' and so do the dark
secrets that would surely have brought it an NC-17 rating. No point
in cataloguing this film's perverse details: what emerges most
clearly is a ruthless yet tender portrait of suburban characters
seeking romance, captured with enough acid precision to make this a
``Bob and Carol and Ted and Alice'' for totally dysfunctional
times. Ms. Adams plays the dartboard in a three-sister family with
hilarious tremulousness. Baker's gutsy portrayal of a bland-seeming
pederast who is also a respected doctor and a loving father is
impossible to forget (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL,' directed by and starring Roberto Benigni
(PG-13, 122 minutes). Italy's most antic funnyman dares to find
humor and tenderness in the midst of the Holocaust, and his risk
pays off. This Cannes prize winner is as stubbornly entertaining as
its central character, a Jewish waiter named Guido who jokes his
way through the nightmare for the sake of his loved ones. Daring
also to combine an opening hour of romance and pranks with a more
somber second act, Benigni avoids all traces of the maudlin and
effectively creates a situation in which comedy is courage. In this
unpretentious, enormously likable film, he shines as a father whose
fibs and hilarious buffoonery know no bounds, and no fear (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `JACK FROST,' starring Michael Keaton, Kelly Preston and Joseph
Cross. Directed by Troy Miller (PG, 100 minutes). Keaton stars as
the title character, one of those rock-and-roll musicians who are
also great husbands and devoted dads. The film is about what
happens after Jack dies in a Christmas Eve automobile accident and
returns to his family as a large, wisecracking marshmallow man
parked on the front lawn. As one more Hollywood effort to look on
the sunny side of fatality, this one is so sugarcoated that it
makes other recent efforts in the genre look blisteringly honest by
comparison. The actors are as plausible and nice as possible in
displaying emotions as sincere as the soap-flake snow that coats
the sets (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `LITTLE VOICE,' starring Jane Horrocks, Brenda Blethyn, Ewan
McGregor and Michael Caine. Directed by Mark Herman (R, 99
minutes). The main attraction here is watching wispy Ms. Horrocks
put on a spectacular one-woman diva festival, with her phenomenal
mimicry of musical grande dames from Judy Garland to Marilyn
Monroe. What works less well is the broad and stagy story built
around her. As the timid title character, she is harangued by her
blowsy mother (Ms. Blethyn), latched onto by the talent agent who
is the mother's boyfriend ( Caine) and courted by a nice young man
who loves his pet pigeons. In that last role, McGregor makes a
telephone installer scintillating and once again shows that he can
do anything. Incidentally, the soundtrack is divine (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `PLEASANTVILLE,' starring Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon, Joan
Allen, William H. Macy, Don Knotts, J.T. Walsh and Jeff Daniels.
Written and directed by Gary Ross (PG-13, 116 minutes). This
cleverly executed fantasy, with a back-to-the-future trip into the
small-town, squeaky-clean paradise of a 1950s television show,
tends toward the black and white, visually and otherwise. The
missionary zeal with which teen-agers from the 1990s try to awaken
benighted '50s types from their slumber is an attitude that wears
thin. But in the meantime there are witty tricks integrating color
into black-and-white images, and nice little touches abound. The
cast is poignant and amusing, with Ms. Allen especially touching as
a pre-feminist housewife who's the prime recipient of '90s
hindsight (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE PRINCE OF EGYPT,' starring the voices of Val Kilmer, Ralph
Fiennes, Sandra Bullock and Michelle Pfeiffer. Directed by Brenda
Chapman, Steve Hickner and Simon Wells (PG, 93 minutes). First came
the great expectations for this animated magnum opus from
Dreamworks. Then came reality, in a film struggling mightily to
balance animated whimsy and biblical stature. The upshot is an
admirably worthy rendering of the Exodus story, even if Moses must
initially be seen as a playful young scamp. Biblical plagues and
miracles serve as special inspiration for the animators'
reality-bending ingenuity (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
