<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BROADWAY27-COX     12-24 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROADWAY27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EMBARGOED UNTIL DECEMBER 27
 &HT;    Face it: On Broadway, talent doesn't always rule
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This may sound like a plea for the existence of the
Easter Bunny, but wouldn't it be great if a Nicole Kidman could get
on a magazine cover purely for her talent in a Broadway drama even
if she looked like Ernest Borgnine?
</P>
<P>
   Or if dozens of ordinary-looking stage actors with extraordinary
talents could also get that exalted level of exposure?
</P>
<P>
   Dream on. In America, more than ever, cuties rule.
</P>
<P>
   To Newsweek's credit, the recent article on Kidman (hair flowing
in a machine-made breeze) celebrates both her talent and sex
appeal, pulling ``The Blue Room,'' her U.S. stage debut, up from
the basement of public consciousness where Broadway dramas usually
languish.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its vaguely skinflick-ish title, ``Blue Room'' is
intelligent and timely. It's David Hare's updated take on Arthur
Schnitzler's 1900 ``La Ronde,'' in which Man A trysts with Woman B,
who does likewise with Man C, and so on through a chain that comes
back to Man A. Amid the randy humor there's the melancholy sense of
a planet (the blue room) where human connections are mostly
physical. Kidman has received well-deserved kudos for playing five
women _ from coke-addled model to narcissistic actress _ opposite
the equally versatile Iain Glen. The London-bred production sold
out its Broadway run (through March 7) with dizzying speed when
word spread that Kidman briefly flashes full-length nudity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's only backal, as opposed to frontal,'' wrote tabloid
gossip priestess Liz Smith with obvious disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway, like Washington these days, gets bent out of shape by
sex, glamour, celebrity. Ideas and quality still count but are
increasingly upstaged by Whatever's Hot This Week _ and ``Blue'' is
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Nicole were playing, say, `Hedda Gabler,' '' says John
Istel, editor in chief of Stagebill, ``I doubt that things would be
this crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   How crazy? As patrons exited the Cort Theater the other night,
30-odd people were packed in layers against a few feet of police
barricades, waiting for the possibility of seeing the Aussie
actress _ or at least a bundled up figure that might be her _ dive
about 15 feet from stage door to limo. Kayla Margenot, 24, with a
prime spot on the rail, explained that she doesn't much care about
Tom Cruise's coltishly lovely wife but was holding the place for a
Cruise-crazy friend ``who wants to see if Nicole is really that
beautiful'' and had gone to get something to eat after waiting for
hours in raw weather.
</P>
<P>
   It reminded me of when Al Pacino played ``Richard III''
off-Broadway around 1980 and two teenage girls behind me kept
hissing ``Gross!'' in stage whispers whenever his saliva-spray
(admittedly copious) caught the light. Even Shakespeare is not safe
from the surreal effects of stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Klieg lights blaze on the beautiful; deserving talents are
thrown in the shade. Nobody stalks the balding, paunchy, brilliant
Phillip Bosco, but it was purely his performance and not Carol
Burnett's that made 1995's ``Moon Over Buffalo'' worth watching.
And I found no autograph seekers last week by the stage door of the
Ethel Barrymore Theatre, even though Claire Bloom, who played Lady
Anne to Laurence Olivier's ``Richard III'' 43 years ago, is giving
an electra-fying performance in ``Electra.'' (I also happen to
think that Bloom at 67 is almost sexier than the fashionably thin
Kidman, but Newsweek doesn't consult dinosaurs like me in choosing
its covers.)
</P>
<P>
   Titillation sold on Broadway even before Mae West wrote and
starred in ``Sex'' in 1926; scalpers then got an unheard-of $50 per
seat. And there's always been at least a steady trickle of movie
stars returning for more serious projects with fulfillments (a live
audience response, for instance) not found in film. Dustin Hoffman,
Glenn Close, Kevin Kline, Denzel Washington, Bernadette Peters and
Alec Baldwin have had two or more New York stage roles in the past
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   There are movie stars whose voices, it turns out, are too weak
for theater: Elizabeth Taylor in 1981's ``The Little Foxes,''
Jessica Lange in 1992's ``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' There are
stars who keep their stage muscles so well-toned that they can
carry a mediocre show on their backs: Julie Andrews in
``Victor/Victoria.'' In the words of publicist Richard Kornberg:
``Stars are your insurance policy _ nobody comes to see nobodies
with mixed reviews.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater is both grateful for movie stars and resentful of
their power, so you often get wildly split, schizophrenic reviews,
as for Madonna in 1988's ``Speed-the-Plow.'' I agreed with The New
York Times that she was artfully understated in the David Mamet
play, but other critics went out of their way to cut the superstar
down to size.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason you don't see more movie stars onstage is
their knowledge that they're going to get kicked in the teeth,''
said Gregory Mosher, who directed the Madonna and Lange projects.
``The issue is usually not money, though it's laughably smaller
than in film. It's this attitude of, `Are you really good enough to
play in my club?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Newsweek and USA Today noted the many movie and TV stars on
Gotham stages in 1998: Helen Hunt in ``Twelfth Night''; Christian
Slater in ``Side Man''; Jennifer Jason Leigh in ``Cabaret''; Angela
Bassett in ``Macbeth''; Holly Hunter in ``Impossible Marriage'';
Martin Short in ``Little Me''; Marisa Tomei and Quentin Tarantino
in (the short-lived) ``Wait Until Dark''; Toni Braxton in ``Beauty
and the Beast.'' But those articles missed a key point: It's not
the number of stars but the fact that they tap a Gen X audience
that's otherwise oblivious of theater.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Uta Hagen _ probably the last actress whose legend
status is based entirely on stage work _ is starring off-Broadway
in ``Collected Stories.'' After her generation is gone, it will be
harder than ever for audiences to know, before they buy a theater
ticket, which of the pretty faces can actually deliver the goods.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
