<HEADER>
A6109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTA     12-24 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: ingenuity (Maslin). 
<TEXT>
<P>
   `PSYCHO,' starring Vince Vaughn and Anne Heche. Directed by Gus
Van Sant (R, 100 minutes). It turns out that the apparent rocks in
Van Sant's head, as he contrived this near-exact color replica of
Alfred Hitchcock's 1960 classic, were only pebbles. His remake (a
modest term, but it beats plagiarism) is artful and good-looking,
faltering only when it tries to improve on the brilliant original
blueprint. The casting of Vaughn as Norman Bates is the film's
biggest Achilles' heel, since the performance Hitchcock elicited
from Anthony Perkins remains an impossible act to follow. Still,
Van Sant has tried an outlandish experiment and come up with what
are, especially for fans of the original, intriguing variations on
a theme (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE RUGRATS MOVIE,' starring the voices of E.G. Daily,
Christine Cavanaugh, Kath Soucie, Tara Charendoff and Tim Curry.
Directed by Norton Virgien and Igor Kovalyov (G, 90 minutes). Dil
Pickles is not the first baby whose resentful older sibling wanted
to return him to the hospital, but he's probably the only one who
has such an interesting trip back. Dil (full name: Dylan Preston
Pickles) is the newborn hero of the first film starring the five
talking babies of Nickelodeon's hit children's series ``Rugrats.''
The pleasant surprise is that the film is a delight, from
encounters with wolves, wizards and circus monkeys in the forest to
musical numbers at the ``baby store.'' There's material for
grown-up moviegoers, too, including a scene with some pathetic
reporters who turn up at the Pickles house when the children
disappear, getting everybody's name wrong and asking, ``Is it true
a dingo ate your baby?'' (Anita Gates).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,' starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth Paltrow,
Geoffrey Rush and Judi Dench. Directed by John Madden (R, 113
minutes). A witty, sexy and merrily literate delight, with an
exhilaratingly clever premise that only gets better as the film
unfolds. The screenplay, originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm
and turned by Tom Stoppard into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of
his ``Rosencrantz and Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine
whatever it likes about the link between Shakespeare's artistic
passions and his mad yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty.
Meanwhile, this tirelessly inventive comedy also envisions an
Elizabethan theater fraught with the same backbiting and conniving
we enjoy today, and has great fun presenting the creation of
``Romeo and Juliet,'' glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow
make a fine, tempestuous duo, and she gives the first great, fully
realized starring performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `A SIMPLE PLAN,' starring Bill Paxton, Billy Bob Thornton and
Bridget Fonda. Directed by Sam Raimi (R, 120 minutes). This onetime
cult horror director makes a flawless transition to mainstream
storytelling with a quietly devastating thriller. And its fine cast
plays out the consequences of a harmless-sounding error in judgment
that winds up leveling everything in its path. The catalyst is $4.4
million that literally falls out of the sky, and Scott Smith's
story proves how deadly the morality of expediency can become. When
you get the shivers watching this wintry tale, which features an
especially memorable performance from Thornton, it won't be from
the cold (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `STAR TREK: INSURRECTION,' starring Patrick Stewart, Jonathan
Frakes and Brent Spiner. Directed by Frakes (PG, 105 minutes). The
latest movie episode of the series that will not die finds Captain
Picard (Patrick Stewart) and the crew of the Enterprise saving a
tribe of utopian space pioneers who live on a planet where everyone
enjoys eternal youth. The bad guys want to relocate the people
forcibly and exploit the planet's life-giving properties. Picard,
standing up against the admiral of Star Fleet and risking
court-martial, delivers impassioned speeches about the ugly history
of forcible relocation and also falls in love with a 309-year-old
beauty (Donna Murphy). Although in its ninth movie episode, the
series has retained its sincerity and multicultural
right-mindedness. It's hokum, but executed deftly and with a warm
heart (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   `TOUCH OF EVIL,' starring Orson Welles, Charlton Heston and
Janet Leigh. Directed by Welles (not rated, 108 minutes). Anyone
familiar with Welles' 1958 film-noir landmark knows that it could
just as well have been called ``Truckload of Evil,'' and that its
crazily sinister plot turns and breathtaking camera work remain
astonishingly fresh. ``Touch of Evil'' is, among so many things,
the other film to find Janet Leigh at a lonely motel under
strangely menacing management, and the one in which Welles gave one
of his most droll, swaggering performances as a corrupt police
captain in an American town on the Mexican border. As visually
thrilling as it is sin-soaked, this artfully reconstructed version
of ``Touch of Evil'' remains one of the brightest lights on the
cinematic landscape this season (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `WAKING NED DEVINE,' starring Ian Bannen, David Kelly and
Fionnula Flanagan. Directed by Kirk Jones (PG, 91 minutes).
Delightful shenanigans greet the news of a winning lottery ticket
in a tiny Irish village. Especially after the winner turns out to
be dead. Bannen and Kelly are wonderfully funny as two old coots
who concoct a plot to claim the winnings and unite the town's cast
of hearty characters in the process. Jones' prize-winning career
directing television commercials means that everyone here is an
amusing eccentric with colorful quirks, and that the septuagenarian
stars' naked motorcycle-riding scenes are played for all they're
worth. This comedy doesn't have the tart edge of ``The Full
Monty,'' but it knows how to coax laughs from making a spectacle of
elderly gentlemen in the buff (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `YOU'VE GOT MAIL,' starring Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks. Directed by
Nora Ephron (PG, 110 minutes). This cozy, inviting comedy
romanticizes the rivalry between two bookstore owners, while also
finding time to fall in love with books themselves, the instant
intimacy of e-mail and a picture-perfect rendering of Manhattan's
Upper West Side. With a feel-good ambiance much less forced than
that of ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' Ms. Ephron borrows adroitly from
``The Shop Around the Corner'' while making this knowing, urbanely
funny film very much her own. Ms. Ryan is fresh and adorable
without trying, while a ruefully lovelorn Hanks proves that he can
do anything. Again (Maslin).
</P>
</TEXT>
