<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COAL IN STOCKING FOR THEATERS  
 NO ROAD TO RICHES   
 A DEPARTURE  
 LUCKY/UNLUCKY BREAK  
 ALONG THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Christmas is here, and that means just one thing:
it's time to play Grinch.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, midseason box office figures are at record heights, and
yes, there's more competition for theaters than at any time in the
last decade. But cynics would remind you that the bulk of the
critical reaction suggests that the fall season has been a creative
disappointment on Broadway. No one has escaped the barbs. The
season's biggest financial hit, ``The Blue Room,'' was given cool
notices by many critics. Even the well-liked ``Electra'' took lows,
with John Simon of New York magazine calling it a ``junk
production.''
</P>
<P>
   As rough as those assessments have been, critics have had a
particularly hard time with the season's musicals. That, in turn,
has meant hard times for some of the musicals' producers. At the
Gershwin Theater, there was an ominous dip last week in the gross
for ``On the Town.'' According to figures from the League of
American Theaters and Producers, attendance for the revival dipped
below half-capacity last week, with ticket sales registering only
$322,332. That is an estimated loss of about $125,000 for the week.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producer, the Joseph Papp Public Theater, has bought
television commercial time, to begin on Monday. The advertisements,
which feature Lea DeLaria, will be broadcast in the early mornings
and late in the evening, said Carol Fineman, the theater's
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   At the Vivian Beaumont at Lincoln Center the recently opened
``Parade'' is starting its advertising campaign in earnest,
emphasizing the good reviews the show received, a majority from
out-of-town critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes the reviews are murderous and there's no comfort
anywhere,'' said Bernard Gersten, the executive producer of Lincoln
Center Theater. ``But that's not the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, which has a large built-in audience of subscribers,
has had a decent box office response, with sales of $288,229 last
week. Gersten said the break-even point of the show was about that.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the healthiest of the bunch is ``Footloose,'' whose
reviews were, well, just plain bad. Its producers say they are
happy with their weekly sales, which have been around $475,000 and
peaked a month ago at just over $600,000. The show's weekly costs
are about $350,000. A national tour began last week. ``Our intent
has always been to appeal to the widest variety of audience,'' said
Michael David, a producer for ``Footloose.'' ``The critics are a
very small percentage of that audience.''
</P>
<P>
   NO ROAD TO RICHES
</P>
<P>
   As if any more reason were needed to discourage future actors,
consider this figure: $14,936.
</P>
<P>
   That's the average annual income of a member of Actors' Equity,
according to the latest statistics compiled by the 36,000-member
union. The median income is even more depressing, a whopping
$6,276, which is more than $2,000 below the federal poverty line
for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   (Just to put the actor's lot in perspective, according to the
Bureau of Labor Statistics, the average yearly salary for a dental
hygienist is about $40,000, plus dental benefits.)
</P>
<P>
   The Equity figures are even more alarming when one considers
that it includes only union members, not the tens of thousands of
nonunion actors who prowl the boards Off Off Broadway and in
smaller theaters around the nation, usually for little or no pay.
</P>
<P>
   In the silver lining department, the average annual income is up
about $1,000 from last year and shows a gain of nearly $6,000 from
a decade ago. Not that that was much solace for union officials.
``People think of Broadway and just think of the stars,'' said Alan
Eisenberg, executive director of Equity. But the majority of actors
and all artists in this country are vastly underpaid.''
</P>
<P>
   A DEPARTURE
</P>
<P>
   Bebe Neuwirth, who was to star in ``Over and Over,'' the new
musical by John Kander and Fred Ebb, has left the cast. The show,
based on Thornton Wilder's apocalyptical comedy, ``The Skin of Our
Teeth,'' is to begin on Jan. 6 at the Signature Theater in
Arlington, Va. Ms. Neuwirth, who won a Tony for her performance in
the Broadway revival of ``Chicago,'' by Kander and Ebb, was to play
Sabrina the maid, the role created on Broadway by Tallulah
Bankhead. Her replacement has not been announced.
</P>
<P>
   Phone calls Thursday to Kander and Signature officials were not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   LUCKY/UNLUCKY BREAK
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Kathryn Meisle was sitting at home, looking for work
and anticipating a pinched holiday season. She had not had a paid
acting job since the summer, and the autumn had been short on
auditions. ``I was planning a very, um, relaxed holiday season,''
she said. ``I was going to do a lot of baking.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, fate. Jenny Bacon, an actress in Paul Rudnick's ``Most
Fabulous Story Ever Told,'' fell during a Saturday night preview,
fractured her foot and after performing on it was told by doctors
that she would have to leave the show.
</P>
<P>
   In a spate of frantic auditions, Ms. Meisle landed the part at
11 p.m. on a Tuesday, read the script for the first time that night
and by Wednesday at 8 p.m. was onstage in a wig, performing with a
script in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the classic actor's nightmare,'' she said. ``Except I
was awake.'' She managed to perform without a script after three
days, just in time for the critics. And then the nightmare turned
into a dream, as the show and its cast received strong reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations are under way to move the production after it
closes at New York Theater Workshop on Jan. 10. Still, it may be a
short-term gig for Ms. Meisle; Equity rules allow Ms. Bacon to
return to the role if the show moves and she is healed.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, Ms. Meisle is counting her blessings. ``I'm
just enjoying it for all it's worth,'' she said. ``I'm not much of
a baker anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ALONG THE WAY
</P>
<P>
   The Signature Theater Company in New York has decided against
trying to present three John Guare plays this spring as part of its
all-Guare season. Instead the company will produce the world
premiere of Guare's ``Lake Hollywood,'' which follows the lives of
a married couple in New Hampshire and New York. It is to begin
performances on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Theater people _ and their publicity agents _ just love
anniversaries, and 1999 offers plenty, including the 50th
anniversary of ``Death of a Salesman,'' which will be celebrated
with a Broadway revival of the play at the Eugene O'Neill Theater
on Feb. 10. Then there's the 100th anniversary of the birth of Noel
Coward. The producer Alexander H. Cohen says he will present the
U.S. premiere of Coward's ``Waiting in the Wings,'' a 1960 play
about a dozen elderly women. Michael Langham will direct; the
opening is to be on Dec. 16, Coward's birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
