<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VIETNAM, LONG TIME COMING': MAKING PEACE WITH THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a rehab center south of Hanoi, a man blinded in the Christmas
bombing of 1972 gives a traditional Vietnamese massage to an
American veteran blinded in a Vietcong land-mine explosion in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   At the Troung Son National Cemetery along the 17th Parallel, in
what used to be the DMZ, or demilitarized zone, two amputees
embrace: One fought on the side of Ho Chi Minh, the other on the
side of Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Outside a memorial to the massacred innocents at My Lai,
American veterans make a stand in the parking lot, refusing to
enter the shrine, declaring that they won't take part in a ceremony
there, that they won't be tools of propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   These are scenes from ``Vietnam, Long Time Coming,'' a
documentary on NBC on Saturday about a journey of reconciliation by
American veterans and their former enemies. And if the scenes seem
loaded with symbolism, that's apparently the idea. A kind of forced
symbolism underpins and sometimes overwhelms this otherwise worthy
film, beginning with the very occasion for it.
</P>
<P>
   What brings these former foes together, many of them physically
disabled, is an elaborately staged event: a 16-day, 1,200-mile
bicycle trip from Hanoi to Ho Chi Minh City, a destination the
Americans still tend to call Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   The road they travel _ through humble villages, over jungly
mountain passes, across rice-paddied valleys _ is Highway One, a
two-lane blacktop that on a map looks like the spine of that
vaguely seahorse-shaped land, linking the once-divided North and
South. There's something fittingly symbolic about that too.
</P>
<P>
   The film was created in part by the makers of the acclaimed 1994
documentary ``Hoop Dreams,'' Peter Gilbert and Gordon Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Like the trip, it was sponsored by Sports Illustrated Television
and World T.E.A.M. Sports, a nonprofit group that conducts similar
events all over the world and whose stated mission is ``to
demonstrate what people of different abilities and backgrounds can
accomplish by working together through sports.'' (The acronym is a
more useful term than the awkward name it stands for: The
Exceptional Athlete Matters.)
</P>
<P>
   For this goodwill tour, which took place last January, the
sponsors mobilized a small army of men and women: 45 American and
20 Vietnamese bicyclists, as well as vans of support staff, coaches
(the Tour de France champion Greg LeMond among them), a medical
team and, of course, a camera crew.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the bicyclists were middle-aged veterans. Some were sons
of vets. Others were children in Vietnam during the war. Three
participants, riding on the back seats of tandems, were blind.
Eight lost legs or the use of them in combat, and a half-dozen or
so were confessedly crippled in spirit, still haunted by the
terrors and barbarities of that war. (``We chased a guy into a
village,'' one American recalls, dazed by the memory. ``A girl came
out carrying hand grenades. I killed her.'')
</P>
<P>
   Videotaped in cinema verite style, the documentary often
fascinates with a kind of in-motion immediacy: The camera rolls
right along with the bicyclists, capturing their recollections and
reactions, pausing to visit peasants along the road, serving up
postcard views of the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   With that comes a mood of sustained intimacy, even
intrusiveness. Time after time the camera is present as veterans,
confronted by the ghosts of war, break down in one another's arms,
often during anguished group meetings.
</P>
<P>
   These scenes are moving, sometimes understatedly harrowing _ one
veteran calmly itemizes his suicide attempts _ and a viewer can
only be sympathetic. But they begin to pile up. Like too much of
anything, they cumulatively dull the impact they're meant to
deliver individually. The viewer begins to weary, as someone might
while listening in on a long group-therapy session.
</P>
<P>
   The film, too, never quite escapes the staginess of the event.
For all the human drama portrayed, the uneasy thought persists that
what we're watching has shades of a promotional stunt. The
bicyclists' black-and-gold riding togs and snazzy matching helmets
only reinforce the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   But what isn't contrived, and what makes the film worth watching
_ even while football games are raging all around it _ are the
moments of pain and revelation that these battle-scarred men and
women share. Many still rail against the government that sent them
to fruitless war; some marvel at the gentleness of the rural
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   And not everything recorded here was planned. The impromptu
protest outside the My Lai memorial seems to take the filmmakers by
surprise. The Americans fear they're being set up to take the blame
symbolically for the 504 civilians murdered there. ``I don't want
to pay no homage to the dead,'' one veteran says. ``The dead are
dead, the dead are gone. They're in God's hands, not in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Reconciliation is a long road. The war, on many fronts, goes on.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `VIETNAM, LONG TIME COMING'
</P>
<P>
   4 p.m. ET Saturday on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Directed and produced by Jerry Blumenthal, Peter Gilbert and
Gordon Quinn; cinematography by Gilbert, Quinn and Tran Le Tien;
original music by Ben Sidran; narrated by Joe Mantegna. A
production of Sports Illustrated Television, in association with
Kartemquin Films and Long Shot Films, Jim Benson, Paulette Douglas
and Steven Whisnant, executive producers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
