<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6121 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-98TV-AZR &LR;      12-24 2009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-98TV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORABLE TV MOMENTS OF '98'  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - A TV critics's list of 1998's top trends and topics,
in no particular order of importance:
</P>
<P>
   - The last minutes of Bobby Simone's life were the most riveting
minutes of prime time television all year. As he slipped away, the
detective, powerfully portrayed by Jimmy Smits, conversed with his
ghostly birding buddy, who served as Simone's guide to whatever's
next. Put your heart in the deep freeze if you weren't moved on the
night of Nov. 24 by the fine writing and acting on ``NYPD Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, it was hard not to open your heart to Rick Schroder,
beset with the awful luck of being a former cute child star, as he
joined ``NYPD Blue's'' cast Dec. 1. Schroder brings surprising
gravity and subtle humor to his character, and brings the show
robust new life.
</P>
<P>
   - Laughs weren't large on TV this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unintentional humor was everywhere, of course, from the halls of
Congress on up. But you know you're in a dry spell when the most
loveable programming on television isn't the actual programs.
Madison Avenue commercials _ for Taco Bell, Jack-in-the-Box and
ESPN's SportsCenter _ upstaged all but the most creative Hollywood
minds. Talking dogs always score laughs, and the ESPN commercials
have been cutting-edge for years, but who knew that the
bubbleheaded burgermeister could be so drolly funny?
</P>
<P>
   - On the non-commercial front, PBS in November built a temple of
tribute to ``Frank Lloyd Wright.'' Co-directors Ken Burns and Lynn
Novick honored the famed architect by not spackling over his deep
personal flaws, and their exquisitely paced, two-part special was
respectful-but-real documentary filmmaking at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   - There's never been a better argument that too much TV destroys
souls than Monica Lewinsky, whose mindless girltalk with Linda
Tripp could be outtakes from lesser episodes of ``Melrose Place,''
or any number of daytime soaps. Which zip code does Monica hail
from again? Oh, that's right, 90210. What'd'ya say we impeach Aaron
Spelling instead of the president?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the supremely seduceable Bill Clinton fared no better
in 1998, and TV's most profound influence in his life _ all that
fund-raising pays primarily for campaign TV commercials _ has
proved no less damaging to the national fabric.
</P>
<P>
   But it was all preface to the long, lost weekend of impeachment,
Iraq and the self-immolation of yet another Speaker of the House.
Dec. 19 was one of the most intense ``news days'' in history, at
least according to the television anchors, reporters and
commentators who presided over it. But, oddly, not in many viewers'
eyes, most of which were focused elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   What those viewers chose to ignore _ emerald green night-vision
images of Baghdad rooftops in one split-screen box, the bright red
faces of angry partisan pols in another _ was truly a nightmare
before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   From the earliest Drudge Report murmurs to the release of the
Lewinsky-Tripp boxed set, the national news media fed on the lurid
story like a school of hammerheads. The public never really bit,
however, and ratings from Big Saturday seem to echo what all those
approval-rating polls said all year: ``We, the people, don't care
about the president's personal problems. Stop trying to make us
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, thanks to Monicagate, this has been a banner year for
cable-news networks, who would otherwise have to dig for real news
to fill that 24-7 news wheel. With, for example, programs like
CNN's terrific ``Cold War'' miniseries. Early episodes proved gray
and grim, though still riveting for history lovers. Now, the
24-hour documentathon has finally swung into the James Bond years
of the 1960s, so at least the sound track has a back-beat. ``Cold
War'' is a heroic work of telejournalism, a valuable keepsake of a
genuinely scary era.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with its cast of real-life characters on both sides of
the Iron Curtain, the players in the Clinton-Lewinsky potboiler are
all toy poodles. Can it be true that the Cold War was fought in the
same world now hypnotized by the pathetic couplings of the
president and his no-mind intern? In 1998, TV viewers saw too much
of these two.
</P>
<P>
   - No matter how it arrives, David E. Kelley's writing comes
special delivery. Consider just two of the characters he created
and writes for every week. On one show, ABC's ``The Practice,''
there's Ellenor Frutt, a larger-than-life attorney played by Camryn
Manheim.
</P>
<P>
   On another Kelley show, Fox's ``Ally McBeal,'' Calista Flockhart
gives the wispy title character an elasticity that only
occasionally needs special-effects enhancement. Size matters for
both actresses. Manheim dedicated her September supporting-actress
Emmy win to ``all the fat girls!'' Flockhart has attracted tabloid
attention by seemingly vanishing toward the other extreme. Large or
small, however, Kelley's heroines are the complete package.
</P>
<P>
   - ``Seinfeld'' got the big send-off, but ``The Larry Sanders
Show'' is the departed series I miss the most. Both shows ended
distinguished runs in the spring. While NBC gave its cash-machine
comedy a farewell fiesta of hype, the finale itself was a busted
pinata. Oh well, we'll always have those great reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HBO's classic dark comedy, a ruthless spoof of
late-night talk-show titans, went out with a memorable last blast.
Jerry Seinfeld scored the big syndication money, but Garry
Shandling and co-stars Jeffrey Tambor and Rip Torn made a place for
themselves in TV critic heaven.
</P>
<P>
   - Phil Hartman and Frank Sinatra, linked only by Hartman's
devastating ``Saturday Night Live'' impersonation of the Vulgarian
Years Frank, both got fitting TV memorials. Though Sinatra's main
media were nightclubs, recording studios and movie sound stages,
news producers had enough cool performance footage after his death
to fill the airwaves with beautiful, timeless music for a few days.
For example, TV Land's ``Frank, Dean and Sammy: An Evening with the
Rat Pack'' special _ salvaged from a St. Louis union benefit in
1965 and originally aired in April _ offered a vision of Sinatra
near the tail end of his most vividly swinging period. Replayed
after the singer's May death, the special showed again how Sinatra
_ singing ``Fly Me to the Moon,'' ``I've Got You Under My Skin''
and other fine tunes _ will swing forever more.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman died a couple of weeks after Sinatra, in a stunning
murder-suicide, so his loss hasn't been as easy to reconcile.
Sinatra led a big, brassy life, most of it in public. Hartman, age
49 at his death (Sinatra's age in the TV Land special), still had
many creative years left, and though the amazing body of his work
for ``SNL,'' ``The Simpsons'' and ``NewsRadio'' will also replay
forevermore, there were characters in him that we hadn't yet met.
In person, he was a sweet prince.
</P>
<P>
   - The baseball season opened with a mess _ the bungled local
telecast of Bank One Ballpark's opening night _ and ended with a
mess of majestic home runs. The Mark McGwire-Sammy Soza dinger
derby was captivating, the kind of culture-stopping story that TV
just owns. After-homer close-ups of both sluggers revealed that
sports could still be joyous and fun, and not always just another
greed-fueled racket.
</P>
<P>
   - They were both commercials for the moribund American space
program, but Tom Hanks' HBO miniseries ``From the Earth to the
Moon'' was much better television than John Glenn's return to
space. The Apollo program might've been the century's greatest leap
of imagination, and Hanks, working with a cast and crew of
thousands from the blueprint drawn by Andrew Chaikin, in the book
``A Man on the Moon,'' found the little stories that told the
larger tale. In doing so, he made heroes of the Earth-bound
engineers, geologists, astro-spouses and journalists who helped
lift men to the Moon. He also created top-flight television.
</P>
<P>
   Coverage of Glenn's shuttle junket was overwhelmingly
uncritical, which is perhaps forgivable given the emotions
generated by returning the aging space pioneer to orbit, but
probably shouldn't be forgotten by students of the medium.
Statements by Walter Cronkite and many others aside, Glenn's
mission was a publicity stunt, not science, and journalists who
contributed to the hype (without repeatedly pointing out the
cost-to-taxpayers reality) did their fellow Americans a huge
disservice.
</P>
<P>
   - Snappy dialog, original characters, unpredictable stories and
a genre-busting attitude are the shared traits of the fall TV
season's best new shows, ``Sports Night'' and ``Cupid.'' If you're
not watching these two, both products of the ``We Love TV'' network
_ that would be ABC, bucko _ you just don't love TV.
</P>
<P>
   The new season's biggest disappointments, the NBC sitcom
``Encore! Encore!'' and the WB drama ``Felicity,'' veered from
success at different stages of their development. ``Encore!
Encore!,'' coming from can't-miss production auspices (the creators
of ``Wings'' and ``Frasier'') and headlined by a truly gifted star
(Nathan Lane), entered the schedule D.O.A. thanks to a bungled
preseason publicity plan and just plain slipshod execution.
``Felicity,'' the fall season's most hyped freshman, took a couple
of weeks to become supremely annoying. Though the network has made
ongoing promises to de-mope the lovely lead character, the changes
have been (now here's a good word for this season of charity)
subtle. Though I admit I'm a long way outside the young and female
target demographic for this show, I do reside in the middle-aged
male demographic that probably best understands unfulfilled
potential.
</P>
<P>
   - CBS washed the Winter Olympics out with soap. Melodramatic,
emotion-baiting, portrait-painting, relentlessly sappy storytelling
has ruined the Games for genuine sports fans. Commerce,
specifically the belief that mass audiences have to be fed
artificial plot-enhancement trickery to stay interested in the
actual events, is the culprit, and NBC (which owns the rights to
both winter and summer Olympics for years to come) is just as
guilty. Give the events back to the athletes, lose the soft-focus
approach, maybe give the irreverent ``SportsCenter'' anchors and
producers creative oversight, and there'll be hope, not soap.
</P>
<P>
   Odd as it seems, it's soapy storytelling that's at the heart of
the latest revival of pro rasslin', which is grinding through yet
another of its cyclical moments in the artificial sun. Most nights,
there's as much or more over-the-top emotin' as over-the-top-rope
body-slammin' on the WCW and WWF cablecasts, and the young males at
the audience core for the hyper-theatrical virtual sport couldn't
be happier. Next: a roller derby revival, which signals the end of
this current ``up'' cycle for fake hair-pulling and
throat-chopping.
</P>
<P>
   - In the spirit of Spinal Tap, we're amping this Top 10 list up
a notch to recognize a truly remarkable turn of events for
TV-heads. It's called Tuesday night, and where did it come from?
Thursday was once the see-it-all night, but NBC's insistence on
dragging along rocking-chair wrecks like the must-miss ``Single
Guy,'' ``Jesse'' and ``Veronica's Closet'' has gradually killed the
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' is fine, ``ER'' still thrills, and ``Frasier'' will
come out of its current slump to thrill again, but Tuesday has
become the don't-call-me-after-7 night, which actually starts
earlier with the WGN airing of ``Buffy, The Vampire Slayer.'' Then
comes Fox's ``King of the Hill,'' NBC's ``NewsRadio'' (taping WGN's
``Felicity'' all the while), ABC's ``Spin City'' and ``Sports
Night'' (taping, meanwhile, NBC's ``Just Shoot Me'' and ``Will &AMP;
Grace''). Finally comes the resurgent ``NYPD Blue.'' Total, that's
six (sometimes time-shifted) hours of top-notch tube on one night.
Six-and-a-half if you throw in ``3rd Rock From the Sun.'' Whew! And
wow! &QL; 
 &QL; 
Comments? Questions? Criticism? Contact Dave Walker at
dave.walker(at)pni.com &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
