<HEADLINE>
GOOD IDEAS GOT BIGGER IN '98  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD NILSEN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Things bubble up. An idea may be around for years, but
all of a sudden, it's on every magazine cover and Ted Koppel does a
town meeting on it for ``Nightline''.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, there were many bubbles. Some popped, others floated.
The success of an idea in pop culture is not related to whether it
is a good one. Sometimes it is the utterly trivial that keeps us
talking for months.
</P>
<P>
   This year, we did dry-cleaning, home runs, hurricanes and
professional wrestling. We considered the death of network TV, the
hybrid gas-electric car, and whether El Nin o might not be the
Ultimate Cause, the Prime Mover, the Right Wing Conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   We looked at the Euro, we bashed the press, we tsk-tsked both
sides in the NBA lockout. But these are the top-10 ideas of the
year:
</P>
<P>
   1. ``Celebrity Deathmatch'' _ Forget ``South Park;'' it's last
year's news. Nothing on TV, nothing anywhere, better sums up
American culture than this MTV animation, which pits computer
animated media stars against each other in a no-holds barred
catfight to oblivion. Look for Carmen Electra to destroy Jenny
McCarthy, Jack Nicholson to trash-talk Leonardo DiCaprio. In one,
the Artist Formerly Known as Prince faces off with the prince
formerly known as Charles. And don't miss the tag-team slammathon
when Nicole Kidman and Tom Cruise face Demi Moore and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   2. Institutionalized Excessiveness _ It doesn't matter if you're
Bill Clinton, Ken Starr or the nation's media, we've all gone
overboard this year. We can't help ourselves. No one seems able to
get off the trolley as we motor our way to Toonerville. Let's face
it, the word ``sagacity'' is no longer in our national vocabulary
and the rest of the world is giggling.
</P>
<P>
   3. Top 100 lists _ It's hard to remember a time when lists took
up quite so much of our attention. Obviously, we don't have enough
time to actually read the books or watch the movies, but we can all
talk about lists. Lists are efficient and give the impression you
have actually done something with your time.
</P>
<P>
   4. Genetic research _ Last year, it was Dolly; this year, it's
whole herds. We have also discovered the genetic blueprint for an
entire organism. Granted, it's a tiny wee worm no one ever heard of
before. But we can gene splice and make it possible for humans to
digest dirt. We just haven't decided whether that's a good thing,
and whether dirt will count as a vegetable in school lunch
programs.
</P>
<P>
   5. Hedge funds _ No. 1 bad idea of the year, come up with by
really smart people, including Nobel Prize winners. It turns out to
be an excellent way to lose money. What is it that is born every
minute?
</P>
<P>
   6. Political accountability _ What do we do with Augusto
Pinochet? What do we do with Slobodan Milosevic? What do we do with
Saddam Hussein? What do we do with Bill Clinton? What do we do with
Newt Gingrich? Only one of these questions has been answered. Yet,
we cannot make up our minds to what extent an individual is to be
held to account. If we become too moralistic, will any policy be
possible? And can any of us stand up to the same kind of
examination we give others? The new Puritanism begins to question
itself.
</P>
<P>
   7. Asteroids _ We're getting nervous. If it could happen to the
dinosaurs, it could happen to us. And it isn't just Bruce Willis in
the movies. Sunday science news is dominated by the real-life
questions of celestial bumper cars. Just because it hasn't happened
in 165 million years doesn't mean it can't happen next week. You
know what they say, ``You can't win if you don't play.''
</P>
<P>
   8. Reality programming gone nuts _ Networks are dying and they
look for cheap profits in five ``Datelines'' per week, three
``20/20s'' and even a clone of ``60 Minutes.'' But they're only the
tip of the iceberg. Look to syndication to find real-life car
chases, drug busts and people being eaten by animals. Fiction is
expensive; Jerry Springer is cheap. Someone else's video is even
cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   9. Online Shopping _ Sure, we don't really know what happens to
our VISA numbers in the quasi-nimbus space of the Internet. But
Amazon.com seems to have everything. Soon, even Third World
countries will be able to purchase Mirage jets and cruise missiles
online. If things continue, it will soon be possible never to leave
your home ever for anything. You'll even get sunlight at
www.solardisc.com
</P>
<P>
   10. Big mergers _ The century began with trust-busting and it
ends with all the king's horses and all the king's men putting
Humpty together again. John D. Rockefeller gets the last laugh, as
Standard Oil is reincarnated. Ma Bell rises from the ashes. And
what's good for Daimler-Benz Chrysler is good for America. It is
predicted by 2015, Time Warner will be a nuclear power and what's
worse, everyone in America will have a button on his remote and a
finger on the button. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
