<TEXT>
<P>
   (th) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Thursday, Dec. 24. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Tim Hilchey; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
hilchey(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-GENERAL (Jerusalem) _ Thirty-six years after he joined
the army, Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak turned in his uniform Thursday
and plunged into civilian life in a peculiar role, dubbed by the
media here as ``the great white hope'' of Israeli politics. Shahak,
54, did not announce his candidacy for prime minister. But, even as
he tiptoed, Shahak, a silent shadow over the electoral aspirations
of both Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor Party leader
Ehud Barak, finally stepped Thursday into the fray. By Deborah
Sontag. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-ASSESS (Beijing) _ A news analysis: Just in case anyone
here missed the point, the state-run media have given rare
publicity to the severe sentences dealt to three prominent leaders
of an alternative political party. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ATTACK (Podujevo, Yugoslavia) _ A sustained assault by
government forces on this area in northern Kosovo ripped apart a
tenuous two-month cease-fire Thursday, as more than 40 armored
vehicles and tanks fought through the day with separatist
guerrillas. By Mike O'Connor. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Washington) _ It has been a general's maxim at
least since the time of the Romans: Let him who desires peace
prepare for war. President Clinton's legal lieutenants are planning
an aggressive defense in the Senate against the impeachment charges
lodged against Clinton even as the president sues for peace in the
form of a speedy and bipartisan resolution of censure. But this
strategy presents a number of problems for the White House. A
Washington Memo by John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL-GENERAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLD-IMPACT (Los Angeles) _ A brutal, four-day Christmas freeze
has destroyed more than a third of California's annual citrus crop,
inflicting upwards of a half-billion dollars in damage and capping
a year of weather-related calamities around the nation, from the
drenching winter storms of El Nino to summer drought in Texas and
fires in Florida. By Todd S. Purdum. (With a photo and a map.)
</P>
<P>
   PILOT-SUICIDE (Tucson, Ariz.) _ Capt. Craig D. Button, the Air
Force pilot who in 1997 balked before his first bombing run and
flew his A-10 jet into a Colorado mountainside, was in mental
turmoil over ``unrequited love'' for a former girlfriend and over
his mother's Christian pacifist faith, concludes a ``psychological
autopsy'' by the Air Force. The pilots' parents, from Long Island,
have rejected the conclusions of the report, which was released
after Freedom of Information Act requests by the Tucson Citizen
newspaper. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FLEXIBLE-HEALTHCARE _ For many Americans, December is a month
for compulsory shopping sprees, with the urgency escalating as
Christmas approached. But for many the seasonal panic goes beyond
choosing between a Furby or a Barbie. For more than four million
Americans who have Flexible Spending Accounts _ tax-free money set
aside by employers for health-care expenses not covered by
insurance _ it means last-minute doctor visits. By Andrew Jacobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
