<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-YEAREND-$ADV27-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADING ON THE CURVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27) 
(af) 
 By JAMES G. COBB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sport utilities or sports cars? I'll take the latter, though
today's four-wheel rockets are so good that roads in the Northeast
_ with low speed limits, radar traps and darting deer _ cannot
really test their capabilities. But even when driven mildly, new
Porsches and BMWs stood out, as did more practical, less pricey
machines. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AM GENERAL HUMMER ($66,522-$99,645) There are perfectly good
reasons to drive this mammoth, sluggish, uncomfortable, deafening,
costly _ but virtually unstoppable _ vehicle. Like, if you're in
the Army. Or you have a ranch half the size of Saskatchewan. Or
you're a celebrity and want everyone to know it. For most of the
rest of us, it makes no sense at all.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: D &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AUDI A4 1.8T ($24,290-$32,640) Why is the A4 such a joy? Is it
the clean, sculptured lines? The steering, so close to perfection?
The all-wheel drive? Or is it, with the arrival of a free-revving
turbo four-cylinder, the satisfaction of fine German engineering at
prices that start in Subaru territory?
</P>
<P>
   A &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW M COUPE ($42,370) Forget ``Titanic'' and the Monica tapes,
the year's best entertainment was this lean, mean Go Kart on
17-inch wheels. If you'd like to commute in a roller coaster,
here's your ticket.
</P>
<P>
   A(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW M ROADSTER ($43,270) With a thumping engine from BMW's ``M''
works, this speedy variant of the Z3 softtop finally lives up to
the styling's promise. Just don't push it too hard; the tail may
wag the dog.
</P>
<P>
   A(minus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BMW 3-SERIES ($26,970-$45,300) The quintessential sport sedans
have been cautiously remade, with a bit more room, a little more
luxury and an even more solid structure. The 323i and 328i remain
thoroughly wonderful drivers' cars.
</P>
<P>
   A &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC ESCALADE ($46,525) Of folks who pretended to have more
than they really had, my grandmother would say they were ``putting
on airs.'' Well, Grandma, here's a Chevy truck in a mink stole.
</P>
<P>
   C(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET CORVETTE ($38,777-$48,978) Muscular and impressive,
America's sports car is a wild beast: awesome, but hard to keep on
a leash. Long trips may wear on you, but compared with its
predecessors, this 'Vette is easy to live with. A cheaper hardtop
puts it within grasp of the Camaro crowd.
</P>
<P>
   A(minus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHEVROLET SILVERADO ($15,995-$32,343) General Motors' most
crucial vehicle is new from bow tie to tailgate, with excellent
driving dynamics and a great new cabin. Unfortunately, it doesn't
look much different and it doesn't yet offer four doors. Otherwise,
a class act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHRYSLER LHS ($29,445-$31,055) Chrysler's luxury leader is a
glorified Chrysler Concorde. Nothing wrong with that, but the LHS
is neither as refined nor as sophisticated as some cars it aspires
to compete with. Still, the design is a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   B &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DAEWOO LEGANZA ($14,790-$19,360) This Korean flagship has
interesting styling and decent workmanship. But it lists on turns
and bounces on bumps, and the engine stumbles for no obvious
reason. You can't take on Toyota with a car like this.
</P>
<P>
   D(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORD RANGER ($12,850-$32,690) A freshening for '98 enhanced the
appeal of Ford's little hauler _ still the class act among small
pickups.
</P>
<P>
   B(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INFINITI G20 ($21,520-$25,320) Infiniti would have you think
this is a Japanese BMW, a bargain sport sedan to run with the big
dogs. Alas, it's just a puppy. The steering is too slow, the
chassis is too soft, the shifter is too imprecise, the engine is
too meek. Not a Bimmer, but a nice Nissan Sentra.
</P>
<P>
   C(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LEXUS GS 400 ($45,505-$53,755) BMW's 5-Series has been, in my
view, the gold standard of sedans, a four-star balance of luxury,
performance, style and comfort. Lexus took aim at the 5-Series and
hit the bull's-eye: The GS is fast, poised, comfortable,
exhilarating. It's virtually the equal of the 540i; it may be even
better.
</P>
<P>
   A(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERCEDES-BENZ CLK320 ($41,195-$51,795) Proof that Mercedes is
becoming American, the CLK coupe and convertible are
ever-so-slightly-daring and nicely appointed _ a Teutonic update of
the '67 Buick Wildcat.
</P>
<P>
   B(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN FRONTIER
</P>
<P>
   ($12,010-$22,420) As trucks become ever more like cars, Nissan's
small hauler seems stuck in the 70s. It handles nicely and the
workmanship impresses, but it is cramped, uncomfortable, hard-edged
and very old-feeling.
</P>
<P>
   D(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE INTRIGUE ($21,735-$27,965) This midsize sedan
impresses more each time one drives it. Solid and stylish in a
quiet way, it is the kind of bread-and-butter car G.M. has needed
for two decades, but had seemed incapable of pulling off.
</P>
<P>
   A &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PONTIAC GRAND AM ($16,595-$22,200) The '99 remake of this
perennial hot-seller wins, hands-down, the award for Most Improved.
A rigid new body smooths the ride, but the handling falls short of
the promise of the sporty styling.
</P>
<P>
   B(minus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PORSCHE 911 ($65,795-$84,540) The 911's first redesign in 34
years is stunning, from the coupe's clean, simple lines to
high-speed handling best appreciated on a closed track. The
downside is the window sticker, especially the Cabriolet's, which
makes one appreciate the $42,000 Boxster all the more.
</P>
<P>
   A(plus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOLVO C70 ($37,570-$48,165) The turbo is a screamer. The styling
is _ for Volvo _ a show-stopper. The appointments are posh. Yet
these top-end coupes and convertibles feel unrefined and
overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   C(minus) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VOLKSWAGEN NEW BEETLE ($16,425-$21,250) Sure, it's adorable.
Yes, you (your mother/your swami/your financial planner) drove one
of the originals (to Woodstock/to Haight-Ashbury/to Kabul,
Afghanistan). But beyond all that, this is a fine car: stylish,
comfortable, reasonably priced. It scores well in crash tests. The
design is clever, the execution is brilliant and the materials set
new standards for small cars.
</P>
<P>
   A &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
