<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMLAND-MOVE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMLAND INDUSTRIES SELECTS NEW HEADQUARTERS SITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In one of the biggest economic development
deals of the year, Farmland Industries Inc. announced Tuesday that
it plans to consolidate area offices near Kansas City International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland, which has about 1,800 area employees, plans to sign a
contract to buy a 122-acre site near the junction of Interstate 29
and Interstate 435 from interests controlled by Floridian William
Parma.
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for construction of a 250,000-square-foot building at
the site to house about 900 employees; those employees now work in
seven buildings north of the Missouri River. The company also plans
to build a new headquarters building and move from the current
location at 3315 N. Oak Trafficway.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland said no dollar estimate of the multiple phase project
was available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Cleberg, Farmland's president and chief executive officer,
announced that the consolidation would reduce Farmland's operating
costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The site is convenient to the majority of our employees who
live north of the river and, with excellent highway access, easily
accessible to those who do not,'' Cleberg said. ``It also is
convenient to the airport and to our world headquarters building.
The parcel of land is large enough to give us the flexibility we
need as we plan for the future, and it was fairly priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmland and Kansas City attorney Mike Burke, representing
Parma, declined to comment on terms of the land sale.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland noted that the land sale is not final and depends on
several factors, including ``negotiating a satisfactory economic
development package with local and state governments.''
</P>
<P>
   The Farmland project has been one of the area's most hotly
pursued development plums in recent months. Despite uncertainties
about the final form of the project, and related financial
incentives, city officials expressed pleasure with the news.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland spokeswoman Sherlyn Manson said Kansas City, Platte
County and the state of Missouri had told Farmland to pick a site
and then enter talks about economic development incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been courted by other municipalities,'' Manson said.
``We want to know that the city of Kansas City, Missouri, wants us
to stay here. We just want them to think about retaining business
in the same way they approach attracting new business.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmland, one of only a handful of Fortune 500 companies based
in the Kansas City area, is a cooperative owned by about 600,000
North American farmers. It had $8.8 billion in sales in 1998, plus
$3 billion in sales from Farmland's share of business in affiliated
entities.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland said it had selected Chicago-based Walsh, Higgins &AMP; Co.
to develop the property. The developer will own the facilities, and
Farmland will lease them. Farmland expects to move about 900
employees into the building in the fall of 2000 and will retain
ownership of the undeveloped land.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland said it was negotiating to sell its current
headquarters building to a real estate firm and to lease it back
for an undetermined period. Farmland declined to identify the real
estate firm it is talking to.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland said that within three to five years construction would
likely begin on headquarters at the new site. Walsh, Higgins would
also develop the new headquarters and lease that to Farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Farmland processes and markets pork, beef and grain products. It
produces and markets fertilizer and petroleum products. Some of its
wares in supermarket meat cases include Farmland bacon and Farmland
Black Angus beef. It also owns meat brands such as OhSe.
</P>
<P>
   The consolidation will involve only administrative offices and
will not affect production and processing facilities in the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
