<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OCTUPLETS-FATHER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OCTUPLETS' FATHER `STUNNED BEYOND BELIEF,' PROFOUNDLY HAPPY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking publicly for the first time since becoming father of
eight world-famous babies, Iyke Louis Udobi had a quick answer for
the all-important question:
</P>
<P>
   Do you know how to change a diaper?
</P>
<P>
   He laughed and said, ``I'll learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Flanked by his brother-in-law and the doctors caring for his
wife and children, Udobi, who wore a light-blue Nigerian caftan and
matching hat, answered questions, ranging from what his thoughts
were when he first laid eyes on the octuplets to how he and his
wife, Nkem Chukwu, had met.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other recent fathers of multiples who have been
quick to tell the world of their paternal joy, Udobi, who also goes
by the name Iyke Paul Louis Jr., has kept a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I'm stunned beyond belief. I'm still taking it
in,'' he said. He went on to express profound happiness and
gratitude for the eight children, who remain in critical condition
at Texas Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi, 41, is a Nigerian-born respiratory therapist who has
lived in the U.S. for more than 20 years and earned degrees in
business and respiratory therapy at Texas Southern University. He
met his wife in Nigeria on one of his annual trips home.
</P>
<P>
   They were married five years ago, he said, with ceremonies
conducted both in Nigeria and in the United States. Udobi and
Chukwu, 29, come from large families and have eight siblings
apiece. Chukwu miscarried a set of triplets earlier this year. The
octuplets, all of whom were given Nigerian names with a surname of
Louis, to honor Udobi's father, were conceived with the help of
fertility drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Some doctors have said the birth of octuplets is not a medical
miracle, but a medical disaster. They say the outlook for the eight
children is uncertain and their care will cost about $250,000
apiece by the time they are discharged, a total of $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi said his wife had been seeing several doctors at a clinic
in Houston, but declined to be more specific about her infertility
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited and grateful to God for giving us these blessings.
Me and my wife are very elated and we thank God, we thank the
doctors, the therapists that made this possible,'' he said. ``We
thank the world that's been praying for us.''
</P>
<P>
   When she gave birth, Chukwu had been in the hospital 2 1/2
months, and on strict bed rest for six weeks, the last two
positioned with her head down to take pressure off her cervix.
</P>
<P>
   One girl was delivered naturally on Dec. 8, the other seven were
born Dec. 20, 2 1/2 months premature, by Caesarean section at St.
Luke's, with healthcare workers handing them off bucket-brigade
style to be taken to Texas Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Udobi said he was unable to attend the births because they were
earlier than expected and he could not find anyone to relieve him
at his job in the St. Joseph's Professional Building.
</P>
<P>
   He deflected questions about the charge of misdemeanor assault
filed against him in September. He is scheduled for trial in
February, accused of striking, biting and hitting his 63-year-old
mother-in-law, Janet Chukwu, over the head with a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family has a problem we have worked through. The main
concern now is the welfare of my wife and my kids,'' said Udobi,
who has been visiting his infants daily.
</P>
<P>
   His brother-in-law Oni Chukwu, echoed his remarks: ``There are
times when there are problems. These have been worked out. The
family is together.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I want to make something clear. We're here talking about
the lives of babies that might actually . . .'' he said, pausing,
then adding, ``Some of them are sick and need prayers, need support
of all kinds. Let's focus on the good news this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Brian Kirshon, a high-risk pregnancy expert at St. Luke's
Episcopal Hospital, said the mother is very weak due to her
prolonged hospitalization and medication and has not seen them
since they were born.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given what she's gone through in the last three months, she's
making steady progress,'' Kirshon said, adding that she would be
hospitalized at least through the weekend. ``She's had lots of loss
of muscle mass. She's quite weak. As she gathers her strength,
she'll soon be seeing the babies.''
</P>
<P>
   The babies continued to make progress, too, as doctors on
Thursday stopped their sedation and gave them caffeine to improve
their breathing. Seven of the eight were expected to be breathing
on their own, without the help of ventilators, by Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest, Odera, will remain on a ventilator for weeks. The
surfactant, a chemical given to the newborns to help their lungs
function, had very little effect on her, said Dr. Leonard Weisman,
chief of neonatology at Texas Children's. He said her lungs may
have been compressed by the crowded conditions in the womb.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's substantially more ill than the others,'' he said. It's
a good sign that she has been weaned from 100 percent pure oxygen
to 70 to 75 percent, he said, ``but it can change dramatically. In
one day it can all turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Odera is the hospital's smallest survivor, weighing just 10.3
ounces at birth, or 320 grams. The smallest baby ever to leave the
hospital weighed substantially more at birth, 444 grams.
</P>
<P>
   The infants' pediatrician, Patti Savrick, said she was
``guardedly optimistic'' about Odera. ``She has done better than we
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Udobi's brother-in-law, Oni Chukwu, said support has come from
diverse quarters, including the Roman Catholic church, Houston's
estimated 50,000-member Nigerian community, businesses and
individuals. On Thursday, the Embassy of Nigeria in Washington,
D.C., announced a $10,000 gift to the family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We, our family, both here in the U.S., Nigeria and all over
the world, are extremely, extremely grateful for the outpouring of
support,'' Oni Chukwu said. ``There are absolutely no words to
express our joy at this time. I wish I could make my smile a little
bit wider, but I can't. I'm the proudest uncle. (The octuplets are)
the most wonderful gift, especially at this time of year.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
