<SLUG> BC-MONT-SPEED-LIMIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA COURT OVERTURNS SET-YOUR-OWN SPEED LIMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dw) 
 By JIM ROBBINS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HELENA, Mont. _ Montana's one-of-a-kind daytime speed limit _
written in law as whatever speed is ``reasonable and proper'' but
widely interpreted as wide open _ has been struck down by the
Montana Supreme Court, prompting fears that the lack of even the
vague limit will lead people to drive at breakneck speeds.
</P>
<P>
   In a 4-3 ruling on Wednesday, the court said the law was
unconstitutionally vague and did not give drivers fair notice of
what speed was fast enough to be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court held that based on speed alone you cannot cite
somebody because they don't reasonably know what speed will violate
the law,'' Beth Baker, Montana's chief deputy attorney general,
said Thursday. ``The Highway Patrol will still be citing for
careless or reckless driving but won't be issuing tickets based on
speed alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to the speed limit was brought by Rudy Stanko, a
cattle buyer in Billings who had contested three tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked a cop how fast I could go and he never gave me an
answer,'' Stanko said Thursday. ``They said it's up to the
discretion of the cop and that ain't right. Let us decide how fast
we want to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the court threw out a speeding ticket Stanko had
received for traveling 102 mph, it upheld two reckless driving
counts _ one for traveling 117 mph, the other for 121 mph. Both
violations were on two-lane highways as he crested a hill.
</P>
<P>
   Montana's legislature will convene in January and plans have
been drawn up by state officials and legislative leaders to impose
a numerical limit: 75 mph on interstate highways, day and night,
and 70 mph on two-lane highways during the day and 65 at night.
</P>
<P>
   Montana's current nighttime speed limits are 65 mph on
interstates and 55 mph on two-lane highways, and those are not
affected by the court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   A violation of the old rule, called the ``basic law,'' brought a
$70 fine. Under the proposed new law, anyone traveling less than 10
miles over the limit would be fined $25 with no mark on the
license. The fine would be higher for higher speeds.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Barry Stang, who opposed a move to re-instate a
numerical limit in the Legislature two years ago, now favors the
new law. ``Two years on the road with the crazies out there''
changed his mind, he said. He drove 50,000 miles in 1998 alone, and
said it was worrisome to be ``going along at 80 and someone from
out of state, who doesn't understand the road conditions, passes
you at 100.'' He said he expected that the bill would pass.
</P>
<P>
   Montana is the only state without a numerical daytime speed
limit. Before a federal 55 mph limit was imposed to save energy in
the 1970s, Montana's ``basic law'' was any speed deemed
``reasonable and proper.'' When the federal limit was repealed by
Congress in December 1995, Montana's basic law was automatically
reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   The number of traffic deaths has risen since the speed limit was
repealed in 1995, though not by much. In 1994 there were 202
deaths, in 1995 215, in 1996 196, in 1997 261, and so far in 1998
223.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1942EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6197 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-PATROTS-BOS &LR;      12-24 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATROTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS-JETS A CLASH OF PHILOSOPHIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It isn't just the Patriots vs. the Jets, or
Pete Carroll vs. Bill Parcells. Sunday's regular-season finale is a
battle of philosophies, new vs. old.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has rebuilt the Jets by bringing in his usual
assortment of veterans _ Keith Byars, Dave Meggett, Pepper Johnson,
etc. _ whom he utilizes not only for their performance on the
field, but to help motivate other players.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots, meanwhile, have gone with younger players in an
attempt to stay a top team now, and in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It's as different a philosophy as those Parcells and Carroll
have in regard to how they run practices. Parcells runs rough and
tough practices, with hitting every day, while Carroll has his
players work one day a week (sometimes two) in pads and uses the
rest of the time for repetitions of the plays the team will be
using in a particular  &UR; week &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Which way was the best in 1998? Both teams made the playoffs.
But one development of note: When the Patriots suffered major
injuries to many of their key starters, the younger players had to
step in, ready or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a faster, younger, more athletic team,'' Carroll
said Thursday. That may be the end result, but it appeared to hurt
them at times during the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, last Sunday against the 49ers, some of the young
players played crucial roles in the win. Second-round pick Tony
Simmons started at one wide receiver spot and caught five passes
(though he dropped two others). Fullback Chris Floyd, a third-round
pick from Michigan, blocked well and showed signs he may be a
decent runner, too. Defensive end Greg Spires had a sack and four
tackles, making two huge plays at crunch time. Rookie Robert
Edwards ran decisively and went over the 1,000-yard mark for the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sticking with these guys,'' said Carroll. ``We knew as
young players it was going to take time to experience playing in
this league and what it takes to be successful at this level. But
as time has passed, we've seen improvement from each of them. They
all show talents that are helping us now and in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are still confident in the decision they made on
Curtis Martin. The statistics for Edwards and Martin are
comparable, although the Jets running back now is claiming he had a
leg injury the first 10 weeks of the season. Martin has gained
1,185 yards and has a 3.5 yards per carry average. He has scored
eight rushing touchdowns. Edwards has gained 1,068 yards, has a 3.8
yard average, and has nine rushing scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've received good production from Robert, but the big factor
is the upside is so big because of the way it's worked out,'' said
Carroll. ``It's still a work in progress, but we can see that
Robert is going to be a top back in this league for years to come.
We know there'll be improvement with things like consistency. But
we're not unhappy with any aspect of what he's done for us in his
rookie season.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the Jets don't have their share of younger
players. Rookie Jason Fabini starts at right tackle. Second-year
linebacker James Farrior is a big part of the their substitution
packages.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells did bring in good young players during his four-year
stint with the Patriots and recently even beamed about the fact
that seven of the players he had a hand in bringing to New England
have gone on to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have been criticized in some circles for keeping
all but one of their draft picks the last two years. In fact, the
Patriots have kept the most draft picks on their 53-man roster of
any team in the league _ 10. One of them, Ron Merkerson, a
linebacker from Colorado, was placed on injured reserve during
training camp. Last year, receiver Tony Gaiter was cut, put on the
practice squad, cut in training camp, brought back for two weeks,
and then cut again. Otherwise the picks are intact.
</P>
<P>
   The other thing the Patriots are trying to prove is that they
can pick players without Parcells around, and that the players they
selected after they were awarded draft picks when the Jets signed
Parcells can help make up for the loss of a great coach.
</P>
<P>
   That might be a stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will get their final Parcells pick after this
season. If the Jets go deep into the playoffs, that would give the
Patriots a pick somewhere at the end of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Patriots have received seldom-used running back
Sedrick Shaw, sometime starting left guard Damon Denson, and
Simmons. For the loss of Martin, the Patriots were awarded a
first-rounder (they took Edwards with the 18th pick) and a
third-rounder (Floyd).
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, another of the Patriots' young players, Tebucky Jones,
their second first-round pick, will get to go one on one against
Pro Bowler Keyshawn Johnson when New England switches to its
substitution packages in passing situations.
</P>
<P>
   This was the matchup Carroll and vice president of player
personnel Bobby Grier envisioned when they drafted Jones,
considered a surprise and risky pick at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope is they'll go up against each other a lot over the
years,'' said Carroll. ``Tebucky is a big-time athlete and even
though the perception is he didn't contribute that much (this
season), he came along tremendously. Really, just as we had hoped
he would.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, philosophies will clash Sunday. And, more than ever, the
young players on the Patriots need to continue to grow up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
