<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL LAW DECRIES SHREDDING OF WELFARE SAFETY NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In his annual Christmas message, Cardinal Bernard Law
condemns what he sees as the shredding of the welfare safety net
for thousands of destitute children at a time of unprecedented
prosperity in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   In the message published in The Pilot, the newspaper of the
Archdiocese of Boston, Law notes that up to 12,000 children and
their families will be dropped from the welfare rolls this month as
the state's new two-year limit on cash assistance begins taking
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Another 4,000 poor children born over the past 30 months have
never received public assistance because they were conceived while
their mothers were on welfare, Law says.
</P>
<P>
   ``What child is this that we treat with such indifference and
contempt?'' Law asks. ``When we no longer welcome new life _
including the child born of a poor mother _ as a sign of hope and
wonder, does not our celebration of the birth of Jesus Christ
become emptied of its truest and deepest meaning?''
</P>
<P>
   However, state policy makers argue that the old welfare system
had ensnared children in a cycle of inter-generational poverty, and
the best way to break that cycle is to push able-bodied parents to
become positive role models by working.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the cardinal and the state have the best interest of the
children at heart,'' Dick Powers, spokesman for the Department of
Transitional Assistance, said Thursday. ``We just disagree on how
to help them most.''
</P>
<P>
   In his message, however, Law says that thousands of families
left the welfare rolls over the past two years, although half of
the caregivers in those families apparently did not have jobs and
most of those who did were not earning enough to climb out of
poverty, Law says. At the same time the welfare caseload was
falling, the child poverty rate increased 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new welfare laws have been harshest to children,'' Law
says.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinal urges the ``people of this archdiocese and
Commonwealth'' to exhibit the same compassion and generosity for
poor children in Massachusetts and in other parts of the world that
they showed for victims of Hurricane Mitch in Central America.
</P>
<P>
   Law says these needy children also include the 230,000 Iraqi
children under age 5 who have died of malnutrition and dysentery
over the past eight years and the countless others whose lives
remain at risk because of the ``deadly weapon of embargo'' placed
on their country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
