A6208 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-USC-SCALABRINE-LA     12-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-SCALABRINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALABRINE TURNING HEADS AT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brian Scalabrine is always surprised when he
watches himself play basketball, and it has nothing to do with how
many points he scored or rebounds he grabbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I see the videotape, I'm like `Man, I'm like nobody else
out there,''' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   All Scalabrine sees is the colorful glow of red hair sticking
out among the players. It's impossible to ignore in person, and it
``looks even brighter on tape,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine is easily turning heads besides his own at USC, and
it has little to do with his locks. The 6-foot-9 junior-college
transfer is arguably the Trojans' best player and possibly its most
impressive big man since Cliff Robinson played in the late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   With his muscular 240-pound body and Opie Taylor persona, even
Scalabrine's teammates needed a couple of minutes before the season
started to realize the considerable talent they were getting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image a lot of people have is that white guys are not that
athletic,'' USC guard Jeff Trepagnier said. ``But when Brian was
here during his recruiting visit last year, he shocked everyone
when he played with us. He was dunking and running the floor and
just killing people.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Scalabrine is only stunning USC's opponents. He's averaging
a team-high 15.9 points and 7.6 rebounds per game, shooting 55.4
percent from the field and has led USC to a 7-1 start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody ever thinks I can play. I don't ever turn heads,''
Scalabrine said, obviously referring to his basketball ability and
not his hair.
</P>
<P>
   If Scalabrine is a bit of a hidden gem, it's because he didn't
play organized basketball until his freshman year of high school,
and because he grew up in Enumclaw, Wash., a small farming town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no talent, no skills,'' Scalabrine said. ``They only
liked me my freshman year because I wore a size 17 shoe. They
thought I would be big.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine did have one factor in his favor: An intense desire
to work and improve his game. It was driven in part by his aversion
to being just another player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a fear in life of being an average person,'' Scalabrine
said. ``I didn't ever want to grow up to be an average guy. It's
kind of a competitiveness I have.''
</P>
<P>
   That work ethic led him to former UCLA center Swen Nater, who
lives in Enumclaw. Nater saw an unpolished kid with a great work
ethic, and decided to start tutoring Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was raw in the sense that he had a lot of ability but not
the fundamentals,'' Nater said. ``I worked with him on fundamentals
a lot. He has a tremendous mind for grasping information and
putting it into practice. I would just gave him a pointer and he
really soaked it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nater improved Scalabrine's ballhandling by having him dribble
two balls at the same time, one high and one low. It's not unusual
at USC games to see Scalabrine lead a fast break, dribbling the
ball like a guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``He actually could play shooting guard,'' Nater said.
</P>
<P>
   Does Scalabrine remind Nater of his famous red-headed UCLA
teammate, Bill Walton?
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a lot different, those two,'' Nater said. ``Brian's a
small-town kid, but he has a good, common-sense approach. He's got
a good balance and perspective on how he wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   It might be safe to say Scalabrine is the best redhead in Los
Angeles since Walton.
</P>
<P>
   But he's too modest to admit being concerned about accolades or
the attention he has received in barely a month of Division I
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``The spotlight is nice, but it's still a team sport,''
Scalabrine said. ``I didn't look at coming to USC like I would
prepare myself to be the Man. I looked at it like I had to prepare
myself to be on the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, some people think Scalabrine could have gone to a bigger
basketball power. But coming out of high school, there were few
scholarship offers and he didn't have the grades anyway. So he
attended Highline Community College in Des Moines, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine started to receive attention after playing on a
Basketball Congress International All-Star team in Seattle, which
he only made after a few coaches pulled some strings.
</P>
<P>
   The experience turned out to be an epiphany for Scalabrine, even
if he scored just one point in his first five games with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``My breakthrough was to make the team. If I hadn't gotten on
that, I wouldn't have met a lot of people who helped me,''
Scalabrine said. ``That was such a turning point in my life. I
might be a Division II player or I might not even be that today.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those who witnessed the transformation was then-Highline
coach Joe Callero, who is also from Enumclaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just one of many faces,'' Callero said. ``But in six
months, that was the most improvement I'd ever seen a kid make.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year at Highline, Callero took Scalabrine and guard
Quincy Wilder to a JC camp in Cal State Dominguez Hills. Scalabrine
was so dominating that more than 40 schools had called him by the
time he got back to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for USC, it had already been recruiting Scalabrine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kind of got me before all the hype,'' Scalabrine said.
``I could have gone to a bigger school, but I felt I fit in here. I
could never say if I didn't go here I wish I could have gone to
another school.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those schools Scalabrine spurned was Nater's alma mater,
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they wanted me just because they didn't want me to
come here,'' Scalabrine said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Callero has been hired as assistant at USC, and Scalabrine
and Wilder are both on the team, there has been plenty of
speculation that the trio arrived as a package deal, which Callero
denies.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people don't get what they want, they come up with their
own implications,'' Callero said. ``Any implications, they only
come when you're successful. We finished over a two-year period (at
Highline) with a 63-2 record. They say the wind blows hardest when
you're at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine would never consider himself to be a special-enough
player to worry about such accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a big deal when I came down here,'' he said. ``I
think everybody thought USC got a pretty good role player to come
off the bench, and take a couple charges.''
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore. He's already got NBA scouts charting his progress.
And he's got his own unique nickname: Big Redd. That's with (begin
ital)two(end ital) Ds, not one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a stick of gum,'' Scalabrine said. ``I got a little
bit of character.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
