<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRUDENTIAL-SUIT-1100&AMP;     12-24 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRUDENTIAL-SUIT-1100&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS OF PRUDENTIAL CUSTOMERS STILL WAITING FOR SETTLEMENT
FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Ill., Mass., N.Y.)  (dw) 
 By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1991, a Prudential life insurance agent suggested that Irvin
R. McMath and his wife, Anna, replace their $75,000 policy on
McMath with two $100,000 policies, one on each of them.
</P>
<P>
   They had not felt they needed more insurance, McMath said the
other day, but they bought it anyway, on the understanding that
when they reached 65, each would have $100,000 to $125,000 to draw
on to supplement Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agent's sales pitch centered on income retirement
benefits,'' McMath said. ``But I've since learned that we do not
have policies that provide these things.''
</P>
<P>
   The McMaths, who live in Skokie, Ill., are among millions of
policyholders that Prudential Insurance Co. of America agreed to
compensate to end a class-action suit contending that for more than
a decade, company agents made false promises. Often, the suit said,
they told customers that they could trade in old policies for more
coverage at no extra cost, that premiums would vanish after a few
years, and that the policies they were buying were retirement
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, though, can be slow, and some critics say the process
is needlessly complex. Two years after the insurer said it would
pay unhappy customers at least $410 million, and perhaps as much as
$2 billion, the compensation program is running months behind
schedule, and across the country, people are complaining. In
Massachusetts, the attorney general's office says it gets six to
eight calls a day from Prudential policyholders. In Florida, the
Insurance Department says it receives 75 a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the calls,'' said Joanna Connolly, an assistant state
attorney in Massachusetts, ``are: `Where is my claim?' `What's the
delay?'''
</P>
<P>
   The McMaths, also waiting for answers, say they have been making
phone calls to the company and sending letters and documents back
and forth for 17 months. ``You talk to different people on their
help line and you get different answers,'' McMath said.
</P>
<P>
   A Prudential spokesman, Robert DeFillippo, said that the insurer
understood the frustration but that ``to do the kind of evaluation
that insures a fair and equitable settlement takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the settlement was approved by a U.S. district court
judge and by regulators in every state, and reaffirmed by a federal
appeals court, critics, including some regulators, have argued that
the deal is better for plaintiffs' lawyers and Prudential than for
customers. The lawyers are seeking fees totaling $90 million, and
Prudential sidestepped potential punitive-damage awards in
individual suits.
</P>
<P>
   The most that customers can get, provided they demonstrate that
they were misled, is a refund of their premiums paid, plus interest
and minus annual charges while the policy was in effect.
Alternatively, they can receive a paid-up policy or a conversion of
their policy into an annuity. Customers who file a claim, but do
not submit supporting material, can buy something else from the
company _ life insurance, an annuity or a mutual fund _ at a
discount or get a low-interest loan to pay Prudential premiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement is totally inadequate,'' said Michael P.
Malakoff, a Pittsburgh lawyer who has been trying both to overturn
the settlement and to reduce lawyers' fees. ``It doesn't give
anyone very much. Those who have not affirmatively sought
restitution lose the ability to make claims later. And it could be
years before many policyholders realize they have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, two Prudential customers who sued
separately won jury awards of $25 million each, but settled for
presumably lesser amounts rather than wait for the company's
appeals to play out.
</P>
<P>
   Early in 1997, Prudential notified the owners of 10.7 million
policies that they might be eligible for claims. About 1.6 million
filed claims, including about 500,000 who indicated they would
settle for discounted insurance, say, or a low-interest loan. The
holders of the approximately 1.1 million other policies were
required to complete 16-page questionnaires. At that point, about
500,000 dropped out, leaving roughly 650,000 policies for
Prudential to consider for compensation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the owners of most of the policies, 9.6 million of
them, decided not to bother.
</P>
<P>
   This shows, said DeFillippo, the Prudential spokesman, that as
the company has maintained, ``the vast majority of these people
were not misled.''
</P>
<P>
   Candy Crawford, a deputy insurance commissioner in Florida, sees
it differently. ``Did you ever get anything in the mail and it was
too much to read, and you just tossed it?'' she asked. ``That's
what people did in this case. In Florida, we had 300,000 people
eligible. Only 80,000 filed the first forms and only 50,000 are
still in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Camil, a financial investigator for the Florida attorney
general's office, said in a deposition in August involving other
Prudential litigation that a former senior Prudential executive
told him the company had conducted focus groups to see if people
understood the compensation procedures. ``After determining that
people could not understand them,'' he said, ``they went forward
and mailed them.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFillippo acknowledged the focus groups but said it was
``simply not true that we deliberately sent out material that was
unclear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Connolly, who has been overseeing the settlement in
Massachusetts, said the delays had resulted in part from problems
with Prudential's computer system. In addition, Prudential
executives, disregarding a court order, destroyed thousands of
documents related to disputed transactions. More documents were
destroyed in a fire. Trying to figure out which customers making
claims had documents missing also slowed things down, DeFillippo
said. Under the terms of the settlement, customers' claims are to
be upgraded if there is evidence that their records were destroyed,
and they may be offered a policy refund, annuity or other
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   By its own timetable, Ms. Connolly said, Prudential was supposed
to have evaluated the claims on all 650,000 policies and notified
customers of its conclusions by May. But by the end of last month,
New York regulators said, 85 percent of the claims had been
evaluated and a little more than a quarter of the findings had been
reported to policy owners.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Keren, the New York regulator following the settlement,
said Prudential had pledged to get the remaining evaluations done
by the end of the year and to notify most policy owners by the end
of March 1999. Policyholders have 45 days to accept or appeal
Prudential's findings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the meantime, customers remain frustrated. On a spreadsheet
projecting how McMath's $100,000 policy was to perform, his agent
wrote, ``Retirement Fund to Assist with Social Security Income.''
The agent had drawn an arrow to highlight the amount of cash
available to McMath at age 65. It read $39,528, not $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   McMath, who is 52 and provides technical support to Internet
users, said he and his wife only remember the agent talking about
the larger amount. They trusted her, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this matter hadn't been brought out,'' McMath said,
referring to the suit, ``I probably would never have looked at the
papers until the time for retirement arrived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
