<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON BUSINESS AND PRODUCTS  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Niche Food Makers, Some Unlikely Hits
</P>
<P>
   You never know what is going to take off in the world of
specialty foods, or how.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Trappist monks have turned a tidy dollar for their
abbey in Gethsemane, Ky., by selling fruitcake, cheese and bourbon
fudge they make. Their kitchen methods are steeped in tradition,
but they have tried to keep their sales practices up to date: They
added order-by-fax to their mail-order operation a few years ago,
and this year they ventured onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In came the flood. By early December, their site on the World
Wide Web, www.monks.org, had attracted 1,600 orders, far more than
the 75 brothers of the Abbey of Gethsemani could keep up with
working four and a half hours a day each _ practically every minute
they are not sleeping, reading or praying.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't hire outside people and they have a limited
capacity,'' said Ray Schuhmann, president of the Kinetic Corp.,
which operates the Web site for the monks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of food,'' said Brother Anselm, head of the abbey.
</P>
<P>
   The monks have unplugged the fax machine and stopped taking
orders on line.
</P>
<P>
   Priorities Straight
</P>
<P>
   Angry at the United States for its missile attacks on Iraq
earlier this month, the national unions of pharmacists and doctors
in Jordan called for a boycott of American drug companies last
Wednesday, the Associated Press reported. The next day, Jordanian
authorities approved Pfizer's anti-impotence drug, Viagra, for sale
in the country. Organizers said Viagra would be exempt from the
boycott because no substitute is available. ... Twice this year,
the Zapata Corp., a former Bush family oil company that now makes
fish oil and sausage casings, has tried to turn itself into an
Internet stock through acquisitions. Twice the stock has surged,
only to tumble when plans unraveled. What did the company announce
last week? That it would try again (no details given). What did the
stock do? It soared. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 1959EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6213 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV27-NYT     12-24 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BRIEFS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHORT NEWS ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Executive Wish Lists: Icy Nights and Natty Dogs
</P>
<P>
   If there is a theme to their New Year's resolutions, it is to
get out of the office and breathe some fresh air. Movers and
shakers of the American business scene were asked what personal
goals they have set for 1999, and vigorous outdoor exercise headed
the list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go hiking in Patagonia,'' declared Edward Vick, the
chief operating officer of Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc., the New York
advertising agency. ``I've been hiking in places all over the
world, but I've never been there.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick, who is in his mid-50s, says he has been hiking ``ever
since my knees started to give out,'' forcing him to give up
running. He worries that he has only about five more years before
the hiking trails, too, are denied him. So he is thinking
worldwide. Vietnam, where he fought 30 years ago, is also on his
wish list.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daniel Vasella, president of Novartis AG, the world's
biggest health care company, rattled off six ambitious goals for
his company but only one for himself. Vasella, who lives in
Switzerland, hopes to vacation next year in Alaska, long one of his
favorite playgrounds. ``I want to go to Alaska in the winter, when
the wolves are out and howling in the night and the moon is white
and gorgeous,'' he said. So what if daylight lasts only two hours?
``I'd go ice fishing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ira M. Millstein, a partner at the New York law firm of Weil,
Gotshal &AMP; Manges and an expert on corporate governance, said he
wanted to make 1999 a relaxing year, spending time as he wants _ on
``my family, GM and a few other trusted clients, teaching at Yale
and spreading the gospel of good corporate governance
internationally.'' Pressed for more on his personal resolutions,
Millstein said, ``I'd like to stop falling off bicycles.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth Jr., R-Del., chairman of the Senate Finance
Committee, said he wants to go to the dogs, or rather, wants a
certain kind of dog to come to him. Roth, 78, takes his two St.
Bernards, Tsunami and Zigfried, along on political campaigns. His
goal for 1999? ``To find a St. Bernard that doesn't shed and
doesn't drool,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   A Quiet Night for the Trump Clan
</P>
<P>
   If anybody is planning a mega-party to usher in the new
millennium on New Year's Eve 1999, surely it should be Donald J.
Trump, the Manhattan real-estate mogul known for appearing
courtside at the U.S. Open with socialites and models affixed to
his arm and for throwing lavish parties in his lavish apartments
and inviting party-circuit figures like the rap impresario Sean
(Puffy) Combs.
</P>
<P>
   So, what'll it be, Trump? A Caribbean cruise? Dinner for 600 at
Cipriani? A midnight schuss in Gstaad? ``I'm not doing anything,''
he said, a touch of pride in his voice. What? Is the great party
marathoner humbled?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Trump said. ``But I just decided that I will spend that
New Year's Eve at Mar-a-Lago, in Palm Beach, Fla., with my
children, and with my son Donny, because his birthday is on Dec.
31.'' (The younger Trump will be turning 21.)
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as it is to make plans a year in advance, other
figures in the business world are either following Trump's lead and
making it a Blockbuster night, or going to unusual lengths to honor
the passage of the millennium. Bill Fischer, a travel agent whose
roster of 400 wealthy clients includes Jonathan Tisch, the
hotelier; Bruce Wasserstein, the financier; Sanford I. Weill, the
chairman of Citigroup, and Diane Sawyer of ABC News, said his
clients were already busy making plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are lying low,'' Fischer said, in hushed, secretive
tones. ``And others are making big, big plans. Certain people want
to be in Paris. Certain people want to be in Hong Kong. Certain
people want to be in the Caribbean.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said one his clients was making plans to hire a yacht _
currently anchored in the Caribbean _ for a cruise in New York
Harbor on the big night. ``You're talking about two weeks of travel
to get the boat here, and then back to the Caribbean,'' Fischer
said. ``It costs a fortune.''
</P>
<P>
   His utterance of the word ``fortune'' is meaningful, considering
he won't even book a client on a bus to Newark until his agency is
paid a $10,000 membership fee. His clients, he said, will variously
be attending a ball at Versailles, flying around the world on a
Concorde and staying at the Ritz Hotel in Paris, booked solid for
New Year's 1999 since 1995. But Fischer declined to say who was
heading where.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have money,'' he said. ``They're not the type of
people who want'' _ he paused _ ``other people to know what they
are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
