<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREEZE IN CALIFORNIA DECIMATES CITRUS CROP
</P>
<P>
   A four-day freeze has destroyed more than a third of
California's annual citrus crop, inflicting nearly $500 million in
damage and leading to predictions that orange prices would triple.
</P>
<P>
   Across California, cold air from the Gulf of Alaska sent
temperatures below freezing on Monday, with readings in the high
teens and low 20s in the agriculturally rich Central Valley on
Thursday _ the worst cold spell since a 10-day freeze in 1990.
Officials pronounced the lemon crop a near total loss in the valley
and said perhaps half the state's orange crop was lost as well.
</P>
<P>
   A CASE OF USE IT OR LOSE IT
</P>
<P>
   More than four million Americans who have Flexible Spending
Accounts _ tax-free money set aside by employers for health-care
expenses not covered by insurance _ must spend what is left in
their accounts before Jan. 1 or forfeit the money. Some health care
advocates say the program encourages unnecessary _ and therefore
wasteful _ medical care.
</P>
<P>
   HELP OFFERED FOR HOG FARMERS
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture secretary announced steps to slow the slide in
hog prices and offered farmers hope for easier credit.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN EXPRESS AND CHASE SETTLE
</P>
<P>
   Chase Manhattan said it had reached a settlement with American
Express, two days after the charge-card giant filed a lawsuit in
federal court contending that Chase used false advertising and
deceptive acts in marketing its platinum credit cards. The terms of
the settlement were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   ISUZU MOTORS TO CUT 4,000 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu Motors, a Japanese affiliate of General Motors, said it
would cut 4,000 jobs and sell assets in an effort to return to
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN TO START LOAN PROGRAM
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's central bank said it would start a plan to help home
buyers and industrial companies get loans as the island's economy
grows at its slowest pace in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END MIXED IN SLOW TRADING
</P>
<P>
   The stock market, which closed three hours early because of the
holiday, ended mixed in the slowest trading of the year. The Dow
rose 15.96 points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 9,217.99. The S&AMP;P
500, which had set records for three straight days, fell 2.27
points, or two-tenths of a percent, to 1,226.27. Nasdaq also
retreated from its record, falling 9.51 points, or four-tenths of a
percent, to 2,163.03.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices fell for a fourth session, driving the yield on the
30-year Treasury to 5.21 percent from 5.18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SANOFI IN TALKS TO SELL UNIT
</P>
<P>
   Sanofi, France's No. 2 drug maker, said it was in talks with
suitors interested in its cosmetics and fashion unit after LVMH
Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton, the world's biggest luxury-goods
maker, bowed out of bidding.
</P>
<P>
   TRYING TO IGNORE ANTITRUST SHADOW
</P>
<P>
   With Microsoft embroiled in an antitrust case, ceaselessly
depicted as the bully of the cyberworld, the company's nearly
15,000 workers at its headquarters outside Seattle have a rude
reminder that the software giant is not necessarily the master of
its own fate. The case lurks on the Microsoft campus as a large
menace that no one really wants to acknowledge but one that can
hardly be ignored.
</P>
</TEXT>
