<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
WHO'S THE NEXT McQUARTERBACK? 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Cade McNown on the December banquet circuit
in New York, Louisville and Orlando, the Bruins took a week-long
look at their young quarterbacks. While the future isn't clear,
it's not as murky as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bob Toledo and offensive coordinator Al Borges must
evaluate the four returning quarterbacks in a month of spring
practice and prepare two players for the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see who the first guy will be, then make a decision on
No.2,'' Toledo said. ``We need to come out of spring with two
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's an early look at the contenders:
</P>
<P>
   _Sophomore Drew Bennett has been McNown's backup for two seasons
and will be the only returnee with game experience, however scant.
He's one of UCLA's best athletes, fast and mobile, but the concern
is arm strength. His passes tend to flutter. Familiarity with the
complex offense makes him the heavy favorite for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   _Redshirt freshman Scott McEwan, of Thousand Oaks, has improved
significantly since last season. He's big and strong but lacks the
mobility of McNown and Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's made a lot of strides,'' Toledo said. ``He's what we
thought he was when we recruited him.''
</P>
<P>
   _Freshman Cory Paus, of New Lenox, Ill., resembles McNown
physically, although he's right-handed and, at 6-foot-2, is
slightly taller. He has a solid arm, he's tough, and he has shown
glimpses of McNown-esque leadership skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of ability,'' Toledo said. ``He throws a little
better than Cade did at this stage. The players like him a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus isn't as experienced as Bennett or even McEwan, but don't
count him out.
</P>
<P>
   _Freshman Ryan McCann, of Agoura, injured his back and missed a
December scrimmage and practice time. He's big and gifted, but he's
got a slew of bodies ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   _Recruit J.P. Losman, from Venice, hopes to graduate this winter
and enroll at UCLA in time for spring practice. He's the most
talented of the group, with mobility, accuracy and a rocket arm.
But it's unlikely a true freshman can outplay four returnees.
</P>
<P>
   Contract update: Sources said UCLA officials have agreed in
principle on a new contract that will make Toledo one of the
highest-paid coaches in the Pac-10. (He's currently ninth, at
$453,000 per season.) However, it may be weeks before the
slow-moving administration finalizes the deal.
</P>
<P>
   One of Toledo's greatest concerns is that athletic director
Peter Dalis, who hired Toledo on Jan. 4, 1996, is nearing
retirement.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could bring a new guy in who doesn't know Bob Toledo from
the man in the moon,'' Toledo said. ``That's why I want some
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is seeking a seven-year deal with a rollover clause.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell update: The Bruins have delayed a decision on Freddie
Mitchell's Rose Bowl availability until early next week. Toledo is
skeptical that Mitchell, who has made a remarkable recovery from a
Sept. 19 broken femur, will play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put him in a position where he could hurt
himself more,'' Toledo said. ``And we've got good chemistry on
offense. We don't need him to come back. After Christmas, we'll
have a better gauge.''
</P>
<P>
   If Mitchell does participate, Toledo said, it'll only be for a
few plays.
</P>
<P>
   Practice update: The Bruins will return to campus Saturday and
hold a brief afternoon workout. All post-Christmas practices are
closed to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
