<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6257 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      12-24 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Workers' Comp Lags Inflation  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My cousin was injured on the job last year when his
right palm was punctured by an injection molding machine. The
insurance company had him evaluated by a doctor, whose final report
concluded that his hand was permanently disabled by 5.75 percent.
The insurance company offered him total compensation of $2,280 for
his injury. Doesn't my cousin deserve more than this? The doctor
said he is cured, but he still suffers from pain in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  California's workers' comp system was set up decades
ago to provide a relatively easy and straightforward way to
compensate people who have been hurt on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the system does allow thousands of injured workers to get
help without having to face long and costly court battles.
</P>
<P>
   But it also has its arbitrary and bizarre aspects _ some of
which your cousin has discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Your cousin has reached a point where the workers' comp system
considers him ``permanent and stationary.'' That means his injury
has healed as much as it is ever going to heal.
</P>
<P>
   The system then assigns numerical values to particular injuries,
based on how much an injury limits activities like gripping objects
or moving a limb.
</P>
<P>
   Each numerical value _ in your cousin's case, 5.75 percent _
automatically triggers a certain level of compensation that is set
by the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Want some gruesome examples? If your thumb is amputated, that's
considered a 16 percent disability and gets you $8,600. If you lose
your arm at the elbow and can't use a prosthesis, that's considered
a 75 percent disability and gets you $108,000.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason your cousin's payment is so low is that since
1984, the Legislature hasn't increased compensation levels for
injuries that leave people with disabilities of less than 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certain dollar figures attached to certain injuries,
which sometimes are pathetically small,'' said Julius Young, a
workers' comp attorney with Boxer &AMP; Gerson in Oakland. ``That
$2,280 figure (for a punctured palm) isn't fair, but it's in the
ballpark for what the system says a 5.75 percent injury is worth.''
</P>
<P>
   What recourse does your cousin have? He can try to challenge the
medical opinion that said he was only 5.75 percent disabled. He
might also be able to sue a third party, such as the manufacturer
of the machine that injured him.
</P>
<P>
   Your cousin should talk to an experienced workers' comp
attorney. He can get a referral from his local bar association or
from the California Applicants' Attorneys Association at (800)
648-3132.
</P>
<P>
   He may also want to place a call to his Assembly representative
or state senator _ telling them it's high time they raised
compensation levels to keep up with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   401(k) Contributions
</P>
<P>
   Q: My company recently instituted a 401(k) savings plan, with
automatic withdrawals from our bimonthly paychecks. How much time
does an employer have to forward our contributions to the
investment firm? We were under the impression that our
contributions would be directly deposited, but this is not the
case.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Most employers transfer money to 401(k) accounts
immediately, according to Deene Goodlaw, an attorney with Sigman
Lewis &AMP; Feinberg in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   But federal law doesn't actually require firms to transfer
401(k) money at once.
</P>
<P>
   Companies must transfer employee contributions into their 401(k)
accounts ``as soon as practical,'' or within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   They have even longer _ up to 90 days _ to transfer  &LR; employer &LR; 
contributions into workers' 401(k) accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials left such a large window of time so it would
be as easy as possible for employers to offer 401(k) plans. But
that window also creates a potential for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years, there have been a lot of problems with
employers going bankrupt in the interim before employees'
retirement contributions have been deposited,'' Goodlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   If your company is holding onto your 401(k) contributions for a
week or two, there's not much you can do about it. But if the
company is holding onto your money for more than 30 days, you
should file a complaint with the local office of the U.S. Pension
and Welfare Benefits Administration, a division of the Department
of Labor.
</P>
<P>
   Low Waitress Wages
</P>
<P>
   Q: I work as a waitress in Colorado and earn $2.25 an hour. Is
this legal? Or should I be getting minimum wage?
</P>
<P>
   A: Colorado's minimum wage law is modelled on the federal one,
which allows companies to pay less than minimum wage to employees
who receive tips.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law and Colorado state law say that most employees must
receive a minimum of $5.15 an hour. But waitresses and other tipped
employees can be paid as little as $2.13 an hour, as long as their
base wage and their tips add up to the equivalent of the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   So yes, your wages of $2.25 an hour are probably legal.
</P>
<P>
   But here's an interesting note: In some other states like
California, your wages wouldn't be legal.
</P>
<P>
   First off, California's minimum wage is $5.75, higher than the
federal standard. And secondly, California doesn't allow a lower
base wage for tipped employees.
</P>
<P>
   So if you were doing the exact same job in the Golden State,
you'd be bringing home a bit more gold _ $5.75 an hour plus all
your tips.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
