<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-YEAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR '99, NO LIMIT TO EXCITEMENT IN GOLF 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The past year in golf was intriguing because of what happened,
and because of who made it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody expected Mark O'Meara or Se Ri Pak to win two majors.
Even people who did not care about golf found themselves caring
about Casey Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Also, a 17-year-old named Justin Rose became the darling of the
British Open. When an amateur named Matt Kuchar smiled his way
through the Masters and the U.S. Open, fans smiled back.
</P>
<P>
   Look for more unexpected and compelling moments between the
first tee shot and the final putt of 1999. Three international
events making up the new World Golf Championship _ each offering a
$5 million purse and a $1 million first-place check _ will bring
together the world's best players more often.
</P>
<P>
   The first WGC tournament, the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship in February, will feature the world's 64 top-ranked
players.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of seeing head-to-head matches such as Tiger
Woods versus Ernie Els; Justin Leonard versus David Duval, or Greg
Norman versus Colin Montgomerie should provide attractive theater.
</P>
<P>
   The lucrative new events, coupled with the growing purses in
other tournaments, will allow the rich to get richer. Twenty-six
golfers on the PGA Tour earned more than $1 million last year. Glen
Day, Scott Hoch, and Scott Verplank all won more than $1.2 million
without winning a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, with prize money even higher, the number of
millionaires will undoubtedly increase. But it could create a class
system of tournaments, possibly inducing star players to skip
lesser events and focus on the big-money events instead.
</P>
<P>
   Individual story lines will also make 1999 interesting. Norman,
back from shoulder surgery last spring, will write the next chapter
of a career that has been successful, heartbreaking, but never
boring. Woods begins 1999 as the world's No. 1-ranked player, but
his mystique has been diminished. Eight golfers won more often on
the PGA Tour in 1998 than did Woods, whose lone victory in America
came at the BellSouth Classic in April.
</P>
<P>
   Woods carries enormous expectations after brilliantly winning
three consecutive U.S. Amateur titles, then dominating during his
first nine months after turning professional.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is so good, people forget Woods is so young; he turns
23 next Wednesday. While he lost his flair for the dramatic last
year, Woods became a more consistent player, leading the tour in
top-10 finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it remains to be seen if Woods will clearly separate himself
from other top players in his generation. Duval, Leonard, Els, Jim
Furyk, Phil Mickelson and Lee Westwood have all yet to turn 30
years old. O'Meara, Montgomerie, Davis Love 3d and Vijay Singh are
in their primes.
</P>
<P>
   That formidable group will make it difficult for Woods, or for
any player, to dominate like Jack Nicklaus, who won 18 majors
during his career. So while, Woods does not hide his desire for
greatness, to approach Nicklaus' record in majors presents Woods
with a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   With Woods looking to win his first major since his memorable
1997 Masters victory, and Duval, Mickelson and Montgomerie looking
to win their first majors at all, each of the four majors will be
much-anticipated as always.
</P>
<P>
   When the players arrive for the Masters in April, they will see
a different Augusta National. The second and 17th holes have been
lengthened, clusters of trees have been added to tighten the 15th
and 17th fairways, and the 11th green has been raised.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 1999 U.S. Open will be held at Pinehurst (N.C)
Course No. 2 for the first time. The British Open will be held at
Carnoustie Golf Course in Scotland, where Tom Watson won his first
British Open title in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship will be held at Medinah (Ill.) Country
Club, where Hale Irwin won his third United States Open title in
1990. The Ryder Cup, the biennial pressure cooker won by Europe in
1995 and 1997, will be held at the Country Club in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The Ladies Professional Golf Association Tour had one of its
most exciting seasons in 1998, topped by the United States Women's
Open, which may have been the year's best overall tournament. Pak
won a 20-hole Monday playoff over the 20-year-old amateur Jenny
Chuasiriporn, who forced the playoff by making an incredible
50-foot birdie putt on the 18th hole on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Pak, who is just 21 years old, has the potential to be the
LPGA's biggest attraction since Nancy Lopez. Meanwhile, Annika
Sorenstam, who became the first LPGA player to end the year with a
scoring average under 70, leads a young group of under-30 players
like Pak, Karrie Webb, Brandie Burton and Pat Hurst who give the
LPGA a solid foundation to build on. More talent is on the way,
with Chuasiriporn and Grace Park, the 19-year-old U.S. Amateur
champion, turning pro in the not-to-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   The big question on the Senior Tour concerns whether anyone will
challenge the supremacy of Hale Irwin and Gil Morgan. In the last
two years, Irwin has won an incredible 16 senior events, while
Morgan has won 12. Give them both credit, particularly Irwin, for
playing superb golf. But the Senior Tour needs a shot of variety.
Tom Watson, Tom Kite and Lanny Wadkins all turn 50 years old in
1999, so the Senior Tour has a potential influx of new
attention-getters on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But as 1999 prepares to start, 1998 proved that a year in golf
can take more interesting turns than a 40-foot putt at Augusta.
There will be drives that sail out of bounds and putts that lip
out, but at least there will not be a lockout. For that, golfers
can be thankful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
