<HEADLINE>
THE JOB TO FORGET  
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, DEC. 27)
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By MICHELLE COTTLE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. After taking night courses in business and finance over the
last three years, I have moved from office support to management
and now work at an entertainment services company. My resume shows
that I'm not one to hop from place to place, yet after just four
months at my new employer, I'm deeply unhappy and want to move on.
How do I explain my desire to leave so soon?
</P>
<P>
   A. Don't torture yourself over one bad decision. And don't
bother trying to concoct a complicated cover story for why you want
to flee after such a short time. It's time to face your mistake,
admit it and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just tell your employer that you were mistaken as to what
being in the job would be like and that you now see that it's not a
good fit for your talents,'' said Edward Emde, chief executive of
Blessing/White, a consulting firm in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Take responsibility for your mistake, agreed Marti D. Smye,
author of ``Is It Too Late to Run Away and Join the Circus?''
(Macmillan, 1998). ``Often people blame the organization, instead
of saying, `I didn't do a good assessment for myself,' '' she
observed.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how miserable you are, don't just drop your two weeks'
notice on the boss's desk. Express your regret over any problems
your departure may cause and offer to stay long enough to help find
a replacement, Ms. Smye advised. Promise to make your successor's
transition as painless as possible. ``How you leave is more
important than staying in a job you don't like,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, before breaking the news to your employer, you should
determine exactly what the problem is. Do you hate the bureaucratic
nature of the company? Or its unstructured work style? Or do you
dislike being in charge? Your boss will want to know why you are
leaving, and you should be prepared to offer a more thoughtful
explanation than simply, ``I'm unhappy.''
</P>
<P>
   More important, in seeking other jobs, you will need to
articulate how they will suit you better than your last position,
Emde said. That can assure hiring managers that you've learned from
your mistake and are now far less likely to repeat it.
</P>
<P>
   Just because you're being straightforward, however, don't forget
the first law of job-hunting: Accentuate the positive. Don't
emphasize your recent career fiasco when calling on prospective
employers, advised Tom Jackson, author of ``Guerrilla Tactics in
the New Job Market'' (Bantam, 1991).
</P>
<P>
   Four months wasn't really enough time to get settled, so you
might not even want to update your resume to include your last job,
he said. You need to be honest, however, so mention in your cover
letter that the job hasn't proved a good fit.
</P>
<P>
   And in all correspondence, he said, focus less on your last
position and more on the type of environment where you think you'd
be most productive. ``Put forward what it is you want and what you
can do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Just make sure you know what that is. Your next employer is
likely to be much less understanding if, come spring, you decide
you've made another horrible mistake.
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Cottle is a Washington writer. Each week, she will
respond to readers' questions about career and workplace issues.
Send them by e-mail to working(AT)nytimes.com or by mail to
Working, Money &AMP; Business, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd St.,
New York, N.Y. 10036. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
