<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAR FADED FAST; NOW LOVITTO FIGHTS TO PROLONG LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1972, he was the Rangers' star of the future. Except baseball
eventually didn't work that way for Joe Lovitto. As it turned out,
neither did the rest of his life go as planned.
</P>
<P>
   But the most important gift Lovitto will open this morning at
his Arlington home is the one he gave himself.
</P>
<P>
   It's the gift of living. The will to live does not come
gift-wrapped or only once a year. Lovitto fights it for 365 days,
win or tie. Losing has never been a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I've got it figured,'' he said this week, laughing,
``is the day the doctors in Houston tell me I'm totally cured of
cancer, I'll get hit by a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   At nationally acclaimed M.D. Anderson Hospital in Houston, the
medical staff has seen it all when it comes to the horrors of
cancer. But Lovitto is somewhat of a legendary M.D. Anderson
patient. The fact he's still here this morning, opening his gifts,
is why the doctors call Lovitto a man ``with nine lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five years since he heard a diagnosis of testicular
cancer, Lovitto has had nine ``major'' surgeries, lost half his
stomach, one kidney, and the use of the other kidney. Since June
1996, he has spent more than 250 days in the hospital in Houston,
and made some 40 other ``day'' trips to Houston for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The news also doesn't get better. A new tumor has been found in
his stomach. Dreaded chemotherapy will start again in January, with
surgery to follow at some point. But first things first for
Lovitto. There's Christmas to celebrate with his wife, Kathy, and
their two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all this started, I didn't have a clue about what was
ahead for me,'' Lovitto, 47, said. ``But I become more
strong-willed about it every day. There was a time in '96 when I
was in bed for six weeks and taking pain killers with both hands,
and I finally told my wife I couldn't take it any more.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what kept me going then, and keeps me going now, is the
support of my family and my friends. I want my daughters to grow up
with a real father, because they've had to put up with me when I'm
on chemo. That stuff causes some nasty mood swings.''
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for his kidney failure, Lovitto goes to dialysis
three days a week, four hours a session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, I hate that,'' he said, ``but it's either go and live, or
don't go and die. So, what's the option?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a lot better because of dialysis. I didn't know how bad
I used to feel until I started feeling good again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a 20-year-old in '72, Lovitto showed up in Arlington with the
body of a lean, mean baseball machine. As then manager Ted
Williams, the Hall of Famer, once said about the
outfielder-infielder, ``God had a baseball player in mind when he
made Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   The one knock on Lovitto was being too ``carefree,'' that he
didn't take the game seriously. But actually, he was hiding arm and
shoulder problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I finally asked to be checked by the doctors, the Rangers
sent me all over the country. But doctors kept telling me it was
nothing, that it was in my head.''
</P>
<P>
   When the problem was finally discovered, it took eight hours of
surgery to correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hurt anymore, but my career was also over,'' said
Lovitto, who remained in Arlington after retiring from baseball in
'75.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found out in baseball that I had a high tolerance for
pain,'' he said, ``but I had never planned on testing that
tolerance again. Now, it's kind of what my life has become.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovitto admitted he waits on the new round of chemotherapy
``with dread, but I decided a long time ago I wouldn't quit. I
can't. My family means too much to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like God is ready for me to be healed, but
he's also made it clear he isn't ready for me to die. I've been
told several times in Houston that if this treatment or that
surgery didn't work, then there was no hope. They didn't work
either, but I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   Lovitto never became a major-league baseball hero, but years
later, in his private fight to live, he has become a more important
kind of hero.
</P>
<P>
   Christmas is a celebration of life. And today, Joe Lovitto
celebrates another day of survival.
</P>
<P>
   (Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
