<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MODANO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER WAKE-UP CALL, MODANO SNAPS DROUGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the kind of hit that would have made Mike Modano crumble
in the past. It was the kind of hit that would have had Modano
feeling sorry for himself, either writhing in pain on the ice or
slowly pushing himself up off his stick while the action flowed the
other way and his team gave up an odd-man rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's'' the kind of hit Toronto Maple Leafs defenseman
Dimitri Yushkevich put on Modano when he knocked the Stars center
for a loop a minute into Wednesday night's game in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, might have fazed the old Modano. But not
Wednesday. Modano, instead, bounced up from the hit that would have
easily qualified as a ``pancake'' in football, and scored three
goals to lead the Stars to a 5-1 whipping of the Eastern
Conference's then-hottest team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank him for hitting me,'' Modano said. ``It kind
of woke me up.''
</P>
<P>
   Modano could laugh afterward. He earned his first hat trick
since Oct. 10, 1997, and only the fifth of his career. The first
goal broke a seven-game, goal-scoring drought. The third gave him
11 on the season and tied him with linemate Jere Lehtinen for the
team's lead in goal-scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just him, the whole line is clicking,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. ``The line has chemistry. The wingers are
looking for Modano so they can give him the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   And when one of those wingers is sniper Brett Hull, that's
saying something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we're all about playing defense first,'' Hull said with a
smile.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process of playing defense, the Stars' top line is
really starting to roll up points. It has 31 of the Stars' 94 goals
and 68 points.
</P>
<P>
   When the first line is clicking and the other lines also are
scoring goals, it's easy to put together a 10-game (7-0-3) unbeaten
streak. The Stars have not fallen since a 4-1 loss in Vancouver on
Dec. 4. Amid one of the toughest months in team history _ 15 games,
including a franchise-record 10 on the road _ the Stars are 8-1-3
in December with three games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing much better five-on-five, and that's been a big
key,'' Hitchcock said. ``The season is starting to settle in and
you can't rely on the power play anymore like we did earlier in the
season. We've had, what, two chances in the past two games, that's
what we have to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The combination of a strong top line, strong support play, more
offensive-minded defensemen and strong goaltending has resulted in
the Stars' playing their best hockey of the season to post a
league-best 20-5-6 record. They have even dispatched the Phoenix
Coyotes, who for much of the season kept the Stars from being the
best team in their own division, let alone the best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   After the Coyotes' 4-3 loss against the Chicago Blackhawks on
Wednesday night, the Stars have more points (46) than the Coyotes
(42). The Stars also lead in winning percentage at .741, compared
to the Coyotes' .724.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are two games shy of tying the franchise-record
unbeaten streak of 12 games (9-0-3) set in 1981-82, and they
already have matched the 10-game unbeaten streak they had last
season, also set in December _ when Modano was nursing a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really a part of the team last year until after
Christmas,'' Modano said. ``That's why now it makes things a lot
more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   A healthy season and a good smack by Dimitri Yushkevich _ Modano
really does have much to be thankful for during the holiday season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
