<HEADER>
A6305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MILITARY-BASES-N     12-24 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MILITARY-BASES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL:   CLEANING UP AFTER THE PENTAGON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Panama, The Philippines)    c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Dec. 25:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. forces are withdrawing from military bases all over the
world, but in many cases what they are leaving behind is dangerous
to the local population and environment. Fuels, cleaning fluids,
lubricants and other chemicals are leaching into groundwater, and
unexploded shells linger on testing grounds long after U.S.
soldiers leave.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Panana Canal Treaties, which require the United States
to give up its bases there at the end of next year, Washington must
take all ``practicable'' measures to remove hazards. Washington
contends it has done that, and is now balking at paying for the
cleanup of the bases, whose chemicals are contaminating the
groundwater. Panama contends that unexploded bombs have killed 21
people in the last 20 years. The Pentagon says the figure is lower.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, the Pentagon has begun to dispose of
waste safely. It is also removing hazardous waste, or paying to do
so, at bases in important allied countries such as Germany and
Canada. But in most nations base agreements are decades old, signed
long before anyone paid attention to environmental damage. Where
there is no legal obligation, Pentagon officials say, Congress bars
them from spending money for cleanup after the base is closed. Many
congressmen feel the security provided by a U.S. military base was
payment enough.
</P>
<P>
   This view is not a popular one in countries that lack the money
to clean up, or even evaluate, hazards. When the United States
pulled out of the Clark and Subic Bay bases in the Philippines
beginning in 1991, it left dozens of sites where toxic chemicals
and asbestos had been dumped or buried in unsecured landfills.
These may now be the cause of disease among people living nearby.
Washington has paid the Philippines nothing for cleanup and has
released only perfunctory information about the hazards.
</P>
<P>
   New laws are needed to provide the Pentagon with funds to repair
its environmental damage and develop new technologies for sweeping
up live bombs. The risks do not stop at the border, and neither
should U.S. accountability.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
