<HEADER>
A6312 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT     12-24 1979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 12/24/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- SANTA-NORAD-FLOATER, 12-24
-- These are computer-generated photos provided by NORAD, the North
American Aerospace Defense Command, showing the progression of
Santa Claus during the start of his Christmas run. The progression,
starting clockwise from upper-left, was said to have been started
at 1:00 p.m. EST and shows how Santa has advanced every hour ending
at 6:00 p.m. when the last photo posted is seen at lower left.
NORAD is a joint American and Canadian military organization
responsible for the aerospace defense of both America and Canada.
This year's Santa tracking program is the 42nd conducted by NORAD
and the 44th overall. NORAD's predecessor, Continental Air Defense
Command (CONAD) started the tradition after a local store's
advertisement for kids to call Santa on a special ``hotline''
included a misprinted telephone number. Instead of Mr. Kris
Kringle, the number put kids through to the CONAD
Commander-in-Chief's operations ``hotline.'' Since that time, phone
calls from children have been responded to personally by Canadian
and American NORAD personnel. (/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SAYREVILLE, N.J. -- Dec. 24, 1998 --NJ-BUSCRASH-2, 12-24
-- Rescuers work to recover victims of a bus crash on Thursday on
the Garden State Parkway. A bus carrying 23 people from New York to
Atlantic City for a gambling junket overturned when the driver lost
control, killing at least eight. Eight people were hospitalized.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
ABOUT-CARS-YEAREND, 12-24 -- Sure it's adorable. But the Volkswagen
Bug, seen at top, is also a fine car. Along with being stylish and
comfortable, it is reasonably priced between $16,425-$21,250. The
Porsche 911 has seen its first redesign in 34 years. The downside
is the window sticker, especially the Cabriolet's, priced between
$65,795-$84,540. (Volkswagen, top, Porsche/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- ADV. FOR SUN., DEC. 27 --
EURO-CARS, 12-24 -- The Toyota Century, a V12-powered limousine
that rivals rivaling the Rolls-Royce, outside Japan. Toyota said
that only 10 to 20 of the cars would be sold in Europe annually,
but the Century will put the company in the premium luxury class
where BMW, Daimler Chrysler and Volkswagen all plan to expand.
(Toyota/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BAGHDAD, Iraq-- Dec. 24, 1998 -- IRAQ-WOMEN, 12-24 --
Widad Abdul-Latif was once the matriarch of a thriving family. Now
she is a street vendor, selling falafel sandwiches to support her
almost destitute family. The sanctions have been ruinous for women,
many of them say. (Murad Sezer/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- SANTA-FLOATER-2, 12-24 -- A
Santa's Helper from the Volunteers of America suits up for a day's
work. Children in Manhattan have long debated this question: Does
Santa clone himself up and down New York's Fifth Avenue, or are
they all his helpers? Mom will tell you. (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- SANTA-FLOATER-1, 12-24 -- A
bus full of Santa's Helpers from the Volunteers of America are
driven to their street locations. Chil dren in Manhattan have long
debated this question: Does Santa clone himself up and down New
York's Fifth Avenue, or are they all his helpers? Mom will tell
you. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) DORVAL, Canada -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- BOMBARDIER-4, 12-24
-- Electrical wiring is installed in the nose section of a Canadair
jet at the Bombardier plant in Dorval, Quebec. Bombardier, the
Canadian company best known for making snowmobiles, has become an
aggressive international transportation-equipment giant, with $6.1
billion in annual revenues, 47,000 employees in 11 countries and a
reputation for being a gutsy company willing to take big risks.
(Robert Galbraith/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LA LIMA, Honduras -- Dec. 24, 1998 --
HONDURAS-ASSISTANCE-3, 12-24 -- The town of La Lima was flooded by
Hurricane Mitch forcing many of the residents to live in this tent
city erected on the highway to the airport. Six weeks later, they
still live here because it is too wet to rebuild. (Suzanne
DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LA CEIBA, Honduras -- Dec. 24, 1998 --
HONDURAS-ASSISTANCE-2, 12-24 -- The bridge spanning La Bonita River
washed away during Hurrican Mitch. During recent rains, the
replacement bridge was also destroyed leaving residents last week
to cross a small pedestrian bridge for free or be pulled across in
a cage for a fee. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LA CEIBA, Honduras -- Dec. 24, 1998 --
HONDURAS-ASSISTANCE, 12-24 -- The bridge spanning La Bonita River
washed away during Hurrican Mitch. During recent rains, the
replacement bridge was also destroyed leaving residents last week
to cross a small pedestrian bridge for free or be pulled across in
a cage for a fee. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- IMPEACH-CLINTON, 12-24 --
White House Counsel Charles Ruff, left, confered with Gregory
Craig, President Clinton's special counsel, as Clinton's private
lawyers David Kendall, right rear, and Nicole Seligman looked on
before testimony began in the House Judiciary Committee earlier
this month. Clinton's legal lieutenants say they are planning an
aggressive defense in the Senate against the impeachment charges
lodged against Clinton even as he sues for peace in the form of a
speedy and bipartisan resolution of censure. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)(/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PORTERVILLE, Calif. -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- COLD-IMPACT,
12-24 -- Icicles hang from trees in an orange grove in Tulare
County just south of Porterville on Thursday. A brutal, four-day
Christmas freeze has destroyed more than a third of California's
annual citrus crop, inflicting upwards of a half-billion dollars in
damage and capping a year of weather-related calamities around the
nation, from the drenching winter storms of El Nino to summer
drought in Texas and fires in Florida. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- ISRAEL-GENERAL-2, 12-24 --
-An hour after formally retiring from the Israeli Army, Gen. Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak stops to visit with mothers of soldiers killed in
southern Lebanon who were protesting near the Israeli president's
residence in Jerusalem on Thursday. The sign, held by the mother of
Eyal Shimoni, killed recently in southern Lebanon, reads: ``We are
dying and you are silent.'' (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) JERUSALEM -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- ISRAEL-GENERAL-1, 12-24 --
Thirty-six years after he joined the Israeli army, Gen. Amnon
Lipkin-Shahak turned in his uniform Thursday and plunged into
civilian life in a peculiar role. Though he showed no political
leanings during his departure ceremony, Shahak, a silent shadow
over the electoral aspirations of both Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu and Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, finally
stepped today into the fray. Shahak is seen here in a portrait
taken in July. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- BOMBARDIER-3, 12-24 -- This
is an artist rendering of a special train to be built by Bombardier
for the British-based Virgin Rail Group. The contract, announced in
March, is worth some $1.8 billion. Bombardier, the Canadian company
best known for making snowmobiles, has become an aggressive
international transportation-equipment giant, with $6.1 billion in
annual revenues, 47,000 employees in 11 countries and a reputation
for being a gutsy company willing to take big risks.
(Bombardier/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CIUDAD SAHAGUN, Mexico -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- BOMBARDIER-2,
12-24 -- A worker places a window on a subway car being built at
the Bombardier plant in Mexico's state of Hidalgo. Bombardier, the
Canadian company best known for making snowmobiles, has become an
aggressive international transportation-equipment giant, with $6.1
billion in annual revenues, 47,000 employees in 11 countries and a
reputation for being a gutsy company willing to take big risks.
(Keith Dannemiller/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CIUDAD SAHAGUN, Mexico -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- BOMBARDIER-1,
12-24 -- A worker puts the finishing touches on a locomotive for
the Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railroad at the Bombardier
plant in Mexico's state of Hidalgo. Bombardier, the Canadian
company best known for making snowmobiles, has become an aggressive
international transportation-equipment giant, with $6.1 billion in
annual revenues, 47,000 employees in 11 countries and a reputation
for being a gutsy company willing to take big risks. (Keith
Dannemiller/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAYREVILLE, N.J. -- Dec. 24, 1998 --NJ-BUSCRASH, 12-24 --
Rescuers work to recover victims of a bus crash on Thursday on the
Garden State Parkway. A bus carrying 23 people from New York to
Atlantic City for a gambling junket overturned when the driver lost
control, killing at least eight. Eight people were hospitalized.
(Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NY5) UNDATED -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- FAITH-RESTORED-2, 12-24 -- The
Rev. Johnny Ray Youngblood plays with a child after Sunday service
at the St. Paul Community Baptist Church in the East New York
section of Brooklyn. The Sunday prayer service, with two spiritual
leaders -- a rabbi and a minister, evokes the meaning of
spirituality that transcends all faiths at this season. (Chester
Higgins, Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- FAITH-RESTORED, 12-24 -- The
congregation during a recent service at the St. Paul Community
Baptist Church in the East New York section of Brooklyn. The Sunday
prayer service, with two spiritual leaders -- a rabbi and a
minister, evokes the meaning of spirituality that transcends all
faiths at this season. (Chester Higgins, Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- NY-STAINED-GLASS, 12-24 --
Thomas Hlavacek, left, and Ken Hickman, of Lamb Studios, install a
new stained glass window at the Marble Collegiate Church earlier
this month. The window depicts an Easter scene. Restoration
projects around the city have reclaimed dozens of darkened and
damaged windows bringing new life to the colorful works of art.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- GREEN-COMDEN-1, 12-24 --
Betty Comden and Adolph Green outside the American Museum of
Natural History. Comden and Green, working together since 1938,
have had the longest-running professional partnership in the
musical theater world. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Dec. 24, 1998 -- GREEN-COMDEN, 12-24 -- Betty
Comden and Adolph Green with a photo of Leonard Bernstein in
Bernstein's Carnegie Hall apartment. Comden and Green, working
together since 1938, have had the longest-running professional
partnership in the musical theater world. (Suzanne DeChillo/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
