<HEADLINE>
SENATORS URGED TO CONSIDER UNPUBLISHED CLINTON EVIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE McCLOY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
As U.S. senators consider how to proceed with a trial of President
Clinton, some House members are urging them on with tales of lurid
evidence hidden away in a govern ment office building.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz., joined in waving the bloody shirt
Wednes day, volunteering on talk radio that the secret information
portrays Clin ton as a ``sexual predator.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. John Shadegg, R-Ariz., is concerned about the fuss over
the mystery evidence because it was excluded from the House
Judiciary Committee report that was used as the basis for
Saturday's vote to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg voted for impeachment but, he said, he did not review
the evidence before he voted.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., was one of the congressmen who did
review the evidence. In remarks that ap peared in The Arizona
Republic on Sunday, the day after the impeach ment vote, Salmon
said of his reaction to the material: ``I came away nauseated.
There are things that go far beyond what we've heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg said he decided not to look at the material.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not comfortable with that,'' Shadegg said. ``I'm a
lawyer. I was aware that some arguments could be made that this
material could not be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg declined to discuss the nature of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do so could foreclose the Senate from making an appropriate
decision at some point,'' Shadegg said.
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg stopped short of criticizing his colleagues for touting
the mate rial except to say, ``I understand it to be executive
session material.''
</P>
<P>
   Government rules prohibit outside discussion of issues
considered in executive, or secret, session.
</P>
<P>
   The material was supplied to the Judiciary Committee by
independent counsel Kenneth Starr as part of his investigation of
Clinton but was not included in his impeachment report, which
detailed the president's sexual encounters with former White House
aide Monica Lewinsky and subse quent attempts to cover them up.
</P>
<P>
   When Starr's evidence was turned over to the Judiciary Committee
in September, entire sections of the Starr report were deemed too
sensi tive for public view and blotted out. The Starr report opened
with a list of explanations for the redactions, including
``national security,'' ``pri vacy'' and ``personal identifying in
formation.'' A fourth category was labeled ``sexual description.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eule, chief of staff for Hayworth, described the secret
files as ``re dacted material that was sent over by the Independent
Counsel's Office. It was redacted by the Judiciary Com mittee to
protect people's privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton was impeached for perjury and obstruction of
justice, House members were invited to view the materials, which
had been avail able only to the Judiciary Committee in executive
sessions.
</P>
<P>
   None of the congressmen who re viewed the material, which is
under armed guard, was supposed to dis cuss the documents, but at
least one member of Congress has acknowl edged that they contain
unsubstan tiated hearsay accounts of illicit sex dating back 20
years, when Clinton was attorney general of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   The accounts are believed to involve several women identified as
``Jane Doe'' in a sexual harassment lawsuit filed against Clinton
by Paula Jones, an Arkansas state employee who said Clinton asked
her for sex when he was governor.
</P>
<P>
   Hayworth was Christmas shopping Wednesday when he heard a discus
sion of the secret files on his car radio. He dialed talk-radio
station KFYI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot confirm or deny the content of what is under seal,''
Hayworth said. ``Sadly, it appears that the president of the United
States has a pattern as a sexual predator.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadegg would say only that ``it's not going to help his case''
if the material is introduced at a Senate impeachment trial. When
the Senate convenes Jan. 6, members will decide how to proceed and
what evidence to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under criminal procedures, this information might be relevant
or admissible to show absence of mis take, or intent,'' Shadegg
said. ``That's not a judgment for me to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Wall Street Journal reported House
Republican leaders as saying said ``they don't rule out''
introducing new evidence against the president about women other
than Monica Lewinsky in a Senate trial, including the cases of
Kathleen Willey and another woman who claimed to have had an affair
with Clinton. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
