<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENER LOOKS LIKE EVENT OF THE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ A new thoroughbred racing year begins Saturday at
Santa Anita Park with the promise of good times ahead, thanks to
dynamic new management, higher purses and expanded simulcasting.
</P>
<P>
   But there's some old business to take care of first. Starting
with the opening-day Malibu Stakes, we may finally identify the
most talented 3-year-old of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-furlong Malibu, the first of 10 Grade I stakes scheduled
for the four-month Santa Anita season, marks the comeback of Golden
Eagle Farms' Event of the Year, the undefeated colt who was favored
to win last May's Kentucky Derby before a training injury knocked
him out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet won the Derby and the Preakness, Victory Gallop beat
Real Quiet in the Belmont, and Coronado's Quest later beat Victory
Gallop; those three are likely to get all the votes for the
3-year-old championship. But many handicappers suspect Event of the
Year was better than any of them.
</P>
<P>
   If that assessment is correct, the son of Seattle Slew should
dominate the soon-to-be 4-year-olds in the Strub Series that
includes the Malibu, the 1 1/16-mile San Fernando Stakes on Jan. 16
and the 1[-mile Strub Stakes on Feb. 6, and should have a good shot
to beat older horses in the March 6 Santa Anita Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big test,'' said Richard Mandella, who has trained
Event of the Year since the summer.
</P>
<P>
   When he was trained by Northern California leader Jerry
Hollendorfer, Event of the Year won three races at Bay Meadows by a
combined 15 lengths, then stepped up and won the Jim Beam Stakes at
Turf Paradise by five lengths while earning the highest Beyer speed
figure (114) of any 3-year-old in the first three months of '98.
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year hasn't raced in the nearly nine months since.
He sustained a slab fracture of his right front knee in a workout
eight days before the May 2 Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The healing seems to have gone really well,'' Mandella said
this week. ``He couldn't do better than he's been doing in the
morning. The only thing in the back of your mind is that he does
have a (surgical) screw in the knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can train him and do all that stuff, and you can send him
out in the afternoon and he's not the same. Maybe there's a little
twinge in it and he doesn't want to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Event of the Year, to be ridden for the first time by Corey
Nakatani, is a 5-2 favorite on the Malibu morning line, ahead of
the coupled entry of Sea of Secrets and Yarrow Brae at 7-2 and
Artax at 4-1. The 11-horse field includes eight stakes winners.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these horses have faced each other before. D. Wayne
Lukas-trained Yarrow Brae was the runner-up when Event of the Year
won the Jim Beam. Sea of Secrets just beat Artax by 8{ lengths at
Hollywood Park in the latter's return from a shin injury received
while finishing 13th in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Artax trainer Randy Bradshaw thinks Sea of the Secrets should be
favored in the Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   ``Event of the Year's coming off a long layoff with serious
injury and has a screw in his knee, so there's a question mark with
him,'' Bradshaw said. ``In my opinion, if Sea of Secrets runs that
same race he ran at Hollywood, he's the winner.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Event of the Year runs anything like his Jim Beam, it
isn't even close.
</P>
<P>
   The $200,000 Malibu will be run as the eighth of nine races on a
noon card Saturday. Santa Anita will be open eight of the next nine
days, with Tuesday the only blank on an opening-week schedule that
features seven stakes with purses of $100,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   The 84-day season, which runs through April 19 with racing most
Wednesdays through Sundays, will begin amid unusual optimism:
</P>
<P>
   _The purchase of Santa Anita earlier this month by industrialist
and horse owner Frank Stronach has eased the worst fears about the
track's future. Stronach says he's committed to keeping Santa Anita
in the racing business while adding stores, restaurants and
amusements to the property.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not making alternate plans for income anymore,'' said
trainer Vladimir Cerin. ``There's renewed hope.''
</P>
<P>
   _The passage in August of a Jan. 1 reduction in state license
fees _ the percentage of wagers collected for taxes _ should
translate into an increase of 8 to 9 percent in average purses. And
that should draw more and better horses to California racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   _The loosening of restrictions on out-of-state simulcasts will
allow California fans to watch and wager starting Jan. 1 on full
programs from Florida (Calder, and later Gulfstream Park) and New
York (Aqueduct, and later Belmont Park).
</P>
<P>
   One symptom of the good feeling _ and another good reason for it
_ is the return to full force of the D. Wayne Lukas barn. The
four-time Eclipse Award-winning trainer said he'll make Santa Anita
his focus this winter after concentrating on Gulfstream last year
and saddling only 15 winners at the major Southern California
tracks this season.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas has nominated 21 horses for the April 3 Santa Anita Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, this is the premier meet in the country,''
Lukas said. ``In terms of purse structure and quality of racing,
you just can't beat it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
