<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FACING UP TO AN ALTER EGO  
 CANAPES LITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ JAN SCHLICHTMANN, a lawyer who specializes in cases
involving pollution and the environment, is having trouble keeping
things straight. There is the reality of his own life, and then
there is the slightly spruced-up version, the Hollywood version
that opens on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what happened when he visited a film set in Los
Angeles. The scene being filmed was supposed to have taken place in
his office in Boston about 15 years ago. He felt as if he fit right
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was seeing all these boxes and shelves of books and
pleadings all over the floor,'' he said between bites of a green
salad at a Manhattan restaurant the other night, ``and someone
said, `We want Schlichtmann over here,' so I went walking over.''
</P>
<P>
   But reality intruded. The person being summoned was JOHN
TRAVOLTA, who plays Schlichtmann in the film ``A Civil Action,''
which is based on the acclaimed 1995 book by JONATHAN HARR.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do look at myself as a character,'' Schlichtmann declared,
adding that reading the book and seeing himself on film have been
``like great therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen years have passed since Schlichtmann filed a lawsuit
claiming that industrial pollution was to blame for a cluster of
leukemia deaths among children in Woburn, Mass. The book has been
on the best-seller list for about two years. Schlichtmann said he
has always been comfortable in the spotlight and enjoys revisiting
his past as interpreted by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've long since given up proprietary interest in my life,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Canapes Lite
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes the price of being an A-list guest is
B-minus eating habits: too many nights of grazing at cocktail
parties where waiters serve hors d'oeuvres that would make a
calorie-, cholesterol- or salt-conscious type _ somebody trying to
lose a few pounds, for example _ think twice about reaching for the
politely offered silver tray.
</P>
<P>
   At a benefit for the National Hypertension Association last
month, the hors d'oeuvres included what the waiters described as
beef Wellington: beef-filled puffs of pastry, heavily salted. The
buffet dinner included roast beef and mashed potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't try to curtail all salt,'' DR. WILLIAM MANGER, a
founder of the association, said. ``One time we did that years ago.
We had practically a saltless dinner, which wasn't too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the food at the party last month, which took place at the
Racquet and Tennis Club on Park Avenue, Manger said, ``I didn't
find any of it salty, but I didn't try every hors d'oeuvre and
didn't try every dish. If it had been for a group of hypertensive
patients, I might have said let's go light on the salt, but you
can't do that to people who go out.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Naomi Berrie Diabetes Center at Columbia-Presbyterian
Medical Center did, with help from some celebrity chefs (and a
celebrity who is also a chef), all of whom set out to demonstrate
that healthful food prepared in large quantities can still taste
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `My patients complain that they go to a lot of
benefits and it's very hard to eat,''' said the director of the
center, DR. ROBIN GOLAND. ``They further point out that one in 12
people have diabetes and there's a lot of heart-healthy food but
next to nothing that's diabetes friendly.
</P>
<P>
   I said, `I wonder if we couldn't interest some chefs in cooking
healthy for diabetes.' That fits into the premise of our center,
which is to live with a chronic illness. We have to work it into
people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   So she recruited ERIC BLAUBERG from 21, SCOTT BRYAN from Siena
and Indigo, and MICHAEL LAMONACO from Windows on the World. ITZHAK
PERLMAN, better known for his skills with a violin, volunteered a
recipe of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the people who did not have diabetes, they thought it was
phenomenal food by world-class chefs,'' Goland said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who came couldn't believe that this was OK for
people with diabetes, because sometimes they're under the
misapprehension that you need to eat prisoner's rations.
</P>
<P>
   People often delay going to the doctor because they think we're
going to take away the good stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
