<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6340 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      12-24 1456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
In another intriguing twist during the course of the 177-day
lockout, NBA commissioner David Stern met with Billy Hunter,
executive director of the National Basketball Players Association,
just hours after Stern set a possible deadline for canceling the
rest of the season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stern and Hunter met late Wednesday in the Los Angeles office of
agent Leonard Armato, who represents Lakers center Shaquille
O'Neal, among others. Stern flew in from Aspen, Colo., where he was
vacationing, and Hunter flew in from Oakland, Calif., where he was
visiting family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we talked is positive because we hadn't spoken
in a week and a half,'' Hunter told Fox Sports on Thursday at Los
Angeles International Airport. ``What we basically did was, we
tried to clear up the negative air that had developed over the last
week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed to sit down for a further discussion that might be
meaningful, that might go somewhere. Because we both know time is
running.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first meeting between the two in almost two weeks,
but like most of the other meetings, reportedly there was little or
nothing accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely no progress was made,'' said NBA spokesman Brian
McIntyre. ``There may or may not be another meeting over the
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   There had better be if the sides want to avoid losing the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Stern is scheduled to deliver a report Jan. 7 to the NBA's Board
of Governors on how the labor-relations committee is faring in its
talks with the union. If he thinks no progress is being made, Stern
will recommend canceling the season on that date.
</P>
<P>
   But if he thinks significant progress has been made toward
reaching a new collective-bargaining agreement, Stern will
recommend allowing the negotiations to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, the NBA never had lost a game because of
labor problems. But since the lockout began July 1, the league has
canceled 360 games, including today's scheduled doubleheader that
would have had New York at Chicago and the Lakers at Phoenix _ the
first games of the season in what was to be NBC's television deal.
</P>
<P>
   The lockout has cost the players $500 million in salaries, and
there is no end in sight. Stern and Hunter are trying to correct
that, attempting to reach a handshake agreement they can take to
their respective negotiating committees.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether Armato, who has helped set up at least
one previous meeting between Stern and Hunter, was among a group of
agents rumored to be trying to lobby for a modification of the
proposal Stern mailed to each NBA player last week.
</P>
<P>
   In that deal, only players with a minimum of 10 years of
experience would be eligible for what is called a
maximum-player-salary contract, a seven-year deal worth 35 percent
of the salary cap. Players with less experience _ zero to six years
and seven to nine years _ would be eligible for a maximum of 25
percent and 30 percent of the cap, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But the agents supposedly are lobbying for an NFL-like
franchise-player designation that would make any so-named player,
regardless of experience, eligible for a salary at the 35-percent
level.
</P>
<P>
   The agents are concerned that few 10-year veterans would receive
the highest-paid seven-year deals, so they would like to expand the
number of players eligible for the maximum salary.
</P>
<P>
   So young players such as Allen Iverson, Tim Duncan and Keith Van
Horn would be able to sign rich contracts immediately. The
difference would be tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   According to the numbers in Stern's proposal, Iverson would be
eligible for a seven-year contract at 25 percent of the cap, which
would total $74.5 million _ an average of $10.64 million over seven
years. But if Iverson were able to sign for 35 percent of the cap,
he would get $115.5 million, an average of $16.5 million. Quite a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the franchise-player modification would affect
Stephon Marbury of Minnesota, which has Kevin Garnett signed to a
six-year, $126 million deal. One would assume Garnett would wear
the franchise-player designation for the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal were modified according to the agents' plan, the
young stars _ and their agents _ would be happy. Clearly, something
has to be done, though.
</P>
<P>
   Sources say the union is unhappy with several key points in
Stern's proposal, among them the owners' definition of the
so-called cap hold.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, the salary for a Larry Bird-exception free
agent counted 150 percent against a team's salary cap. Whatever
space remained under the cap when signed players and unsigned
Bird-exception free agents were totaled was how much a team could
offer another's free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But under the new proposal, the cap hold would rise from 150
percent to perhaps 400 percent, meaning teams would have
significantly less room under the cap to sign another team's free
agent, which translates into significantly less freedom of movement
for players.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is the lack of middle-class exceptions for
veterans. The owners' proposal sets aside one middle-class
exception, but many in the union think there should be at least
two, fearing many teams will sign players to two or three of the
maximum salaries available (depending on their level of
experience), have a couple of young players slotted into
rookie-level contracts, have the one middle-class exception player
and then fill out the roster with minimum-wage guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to give up the high end,'' said free agent Eddie
Johnson. ``That's not what we're fighting for. We're willing to
give those guys up. But our problem is this: Where is that money
going to go? That's the point. We'll take Patrick Ewing and say,
`OK, you're not going to make $20 million a year. You're going to
make $15 million.' Now, what we say to the owners is, `What are you
going to do with that extra $5 million? Are you going to filter it
down to the middle-range guys or are you just going to pocket it?'
That's the argument right there. That's what we're fighting over.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps those are the minor changes to which Utah's Karl Malone
referred last week when he deemed Stern's proposal fair and
acceptable if it was tweaked.
</P>
<P>
   But Malone answered Stern's talk about possibly ending the
season Jan. 7 by saying: ``If Stern says no season, so be it. I
won't get down on one knee.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, players such as Toronto's Kevin Willis have talked
about asking Hunter for a secret ballot on Stern's proposal,
believing it will pass, and a handful of agents have been urging
such a vote.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Blass, who represents Mookie Blaylock and Derrick McKey,
among others, thinks such a secret ballot would pass by a 2-1
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players have lost half a year's salary,'' Blass said.
``They'll never make that back. So what value is it to them to
continue this? What they are doing to basketball is not helping. I
asked for a closed vote. If the union votes to refuse the last
offer, I'm satisfied. How can Billy Hunter say this deal is no good
for the players? Shouldn't the players decide that?''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Glass, who represents free agent Matt Maloney, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would find an awful lot of players voting selfishly, to
preserve their own particular situation _ without any foresight,
without any understanding of where this is all going,'' Glass said.
``So it would be unfair to put it up for a vote. The union's
responsibility is to represent 410 players _ not only the stars,
not only the middle class, not only those with guaranteed
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put a vote to 200 players with guaranteed contracts,
and on one hand you say, `OK, say yes and you'll get your money and
feed your family now, but on the other side, it's a horrible deal
for the future,' what's going to happen? They'll still vote for it.
That's just reality. That's the unfortunate truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In other lockout-related news, Texas District Judge David Medina
scheduled a hearing for Wednesday in Houston on a lawsuit by
Denver's Nick Van Exel, New York's Marcus Camby and Toronto's
Reggie Slater, all of whom have NBA contracts but want to be
cleared to play basketball in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Locked-out players are allowed to go overseas to play, but those
with existing contracts would be forced to return and honor those
contracts should the lockout end.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed by agent James Bryant, alleges USA Basketball
is conspiring with the NBA to keep the players from going overseas,
and asks for an injunction against USA Basketball. Bryant would
like the players to play overseas this season and then return as
free agents next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-24-98 2231EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0347 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 22:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6341 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-MOSS-NYT &LR;      12-24 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-MOSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSS, WITH SKILLS AND STATS, IS VIKINGS' RISING STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The play is called ``dot left slot hound right
divide'' and it is not your ordinary football play. That's because
it is often called for Minnesota Vikings wide receiver Randy Moss,
who is not your ordinary football player.
</P>
<P>
   The play is a deep route for Moss, and no one runs them like he
can. He causes more jaws to drop per catch than any other receiver
in football today. After only 15 career games, Moss is developing
into the Lawrence Taylor of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to that play, his 4.3-second speed in the 40-yard dash, a
vertical leap of more than 40 inches, great hands and football
smarts that nicely complement his physical skills, Moss is a
formidable offensive weapon, and the sensation of this year's
National Football League rookie class.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were already good on offense, but he took us to another
level,'' said coach Dennis Green, whose Vikings are 14-1 heading
into Saturday's game against the Tennessee Oilers. ``He's made us
explosive early, and that takes a team out of its game. They have
to chase us, play catch-up, then our defense gets into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Green added: ``I can't think of the last player who has brought
as much excitement to the NFL as a rookie as Randy has. Not only is
he a great athlete, he's a great competitor. He believes he can
lead us to not only one Super Bowl, but a couple of them. How many
rookies have that kind of confidence?''
</P>
<P>
   Compare Moss, who has 64 receptions, to any of the great
receivers in their rookie seasons: Jerry Rice, Lance Alworth, Fred
Biletnikoff, Charlie Joiner, Michael Irvin, Herman Moore, Art Monk,
Cris Carter, Andre Rison, Steve Largent. None had 16 touchdown
catches in their rookie seasons, as Moss does. None had 10
touchdown catches of at least 40 yards, tying Elroy Hirsch's record
set in 1951, as Moss has accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   None was close to Moss in receiving yards. With 1,281 yards,
Moss needs 193 Saturday to break the rookie record for receiving
yards, set in 1960 by Bill Groman of the Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   After the Vikings crushed Jacksonville last Sunday, 50-10, to
claim home-field advantage throughout the playoffs, Moss was asked
if he is unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about that,'' he said. ``I just know that when
our offense is clicking, I feel like it's hard to cover me. It's
very hard to cover me.''
</P>
<P>
   What that deep route for Moss boils down to, minus the football
jargon, is quarterback Randall Cunningham using a play-action fake
to the running back, usually Robert Smith, and then throwing the
ball to Moss, who runs as fast as he can, as far as he can,
stretching the defense like a rubber band.
</P>
<P>
   Double-team him, as Green Bay tried unsuccessfully earlier this
season, and he will still outleap the players to make the catch.
</P>
<P>
   Single cover him? Don't even think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then, when we run that play in practice, I just
watch it and enjoy it,'' Cunningham said, ``and I know when we run
it in a game, most of the time it's going for a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Moss' abilities, a great coaching job by Green and his staff,
and depth have made the Vikings the most powerful offense in
football.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota has scored a league-high 530 points, and if the
Vikings score 12 against Tennessee _ a virtual certainty _ they
will break the single-season scoring record of 541 points set by
the 1983 Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings have scored more points in their last four games _
50, 38, 48 and 46 for a total of 182 _ than any other team in a
four-game stretch in league history.
</P>
<P>
   Moss is a big reason why. But how has Moss, the 21st overall
pick in last year's draft from Marshall University, turned the NFL
into his personal record book? Especially considering the
skepticism that surrounded him before the draft because of his
legal problems in high school and college?
</P>
<P>
   First, it's as simple as talent and size. Moss is 6 feet 4
inches and is often covered by defensive backs who are 4, 5 and
even 6 inches shorter than he is. As Green pointed out, there is
usually a man in Moss' face when the ball is thrown deep, and Moss
just outjumps the defender trying to stick with him. Or Cunningham
will throw the ball short, and Moss will still snag the catch
because he is great at making midair adjustments.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Green and Vikings offensive coordinator Brian Billick
have opened up the playbook. In the past two years, the Vikings
used more conservative formations featuring two backs and two tight
ends. Now, with Moss, they often go to three and four wide
receivers because of the depth at the position with the veterans
Carter and Jake Reed.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Moss' physical skills overshadow the fact that he is
becoming a savvy professional. During a recent practice, Moss
corrected a mistake made by the sixth-year wide receiver Chris
Walsh, who was running a route in the wrong direction. Billick said
Moss' football maturity goes beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about this season,'' Moss said. ``I feel good
about what I've been able to accomplish. I'll be honest _ I thought
I could have this kind of impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a mentor to Moss, was asked what about Moss has amazed
him. ``I haven't been necessarily amazed,'' Carter said, ``because
I knew he would have a tremendous impact in the NFL, not only
talent-wise, but because of the system we run. He would not have
had the kind of year he has had in, say, New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Other teams don't have the kind of talent we have, or a great
offensive system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Moss excels because he is good, but also because
the Vikings have an abundance of weapons and a system in which its
receivers thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Those weapons include Carter, who this season became just the
third player to record at least 100 career touchdown catches (Rice
and Largent are the others with 163 and 100, respectively).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith, the halfback, is healthy and last week
rushed for 101 yards; Andrew Glover is the most underrated tight
end in football; Minnesota's offensive line has played better than
any other except perhaps Denver's, and Reed, who has missed time
recently with a back injury, is a top wide receiver who should be
back for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings, because their skill players on offense and defense
are so fast, will be difficult to beat in the post-season. They
have averaged 35.2 points a game on the speedy artificial turf in
the Metrodome and given up only 11.6 points.
</P>
<P>
   The team that faces Minnesota in the playoffs will know that at
some point ``dot left slot hound right divide'' is coming. Knowing
it is one thing, stopping it, and Moss, is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams try these intricate ways to slow Randy and our
offense,'' Cunningham said, ``but I guess you could say what
they've tried hasn't worked very well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
