<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6342 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HOUSTON-BOWL-HNS &LR;      12-24 1358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HOUSTON-BOWL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEAL FARMER  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
A group of Houstonians backed by the Touchdown Club of Houston,
Astrodome USA and the Houston Convention and Visitors Bureau is
trying to bring a college football bowl to Houston, perhaps as soon
as 1999.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston group has been contacted by Jerry Ippoliti,
commissioner of the Mid-American Conference in Toledo, Ohio, to go
through the application process. Ippoliti started the Motor City
Bowl in Pontiac, Mich., and the Music City Bowl in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the process of filling out the application with the
NCAA,'' Ippoliti said. ``I've visited with people in Houston twice.
I think the process is going well.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the Houston group has the necessary $2 million
letter of credit to host a bowl, Ippoliti repeated, ``The process
is going well.''
</P>
<P>
   Two sources with the Touchdown Club said bank officers have been
interviewed about securing the credit, but that part of the process
is in the planning stages.
</P>
<P>
   Ippoliti and organizers are optimistic they can bring the bowl
to Houston in 1999, even though the policy of the NCAA football
certification committee is to have bowl organizers wait two years
before the inaugural game.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, local organizers continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at three steps,'' said George Koening, vice
president of sales and marketing for Astrodome USA. ``One, to
identify conferences and tie-ins; two, to work out a TV deal; and
three, then go out and get a title sponsorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Koening said he and Houston Convention and Visitors Bureau
officials have been in contact with NCAA officials about 10 times.
He said the Astrodome tentatively has reserved Dec. 26, 1999, for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Puryear, president of Astrodome USA, said stadium officials
have not made lease arrangements with Ippoliti but have indicated
they are willing to host the bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to see big-time college football in Houston,''
Puryear said. ``(Ippoliti) is trying to gain conference support,
and if he can gain conference commitments he can get a TV
commitment. Then, he can come back locally and get a sponsor's
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Curry, a Touchdown Club board member and former club
president, said the board has met with Ippoliti twice and that no
one is against the idea, although some are skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are very interested in supporting and getting a
college football bowl for Houston,'' Curry said. ``I mean, if Boise
and Shreveport can support a bowl, we should be able to, also.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry helped run Houston's last bowl, the Bluebonnet Bowl, which
folded in 1987. Curry thought the event was going well until the
game was moved permanently to New Year's Eve in 1976 to satisfy
television needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they stick us with a Dec. 31 bowl, it will go the way of
the Bluebonnet,'' he said. ``I remember when the Bluebonnet was on
a Saturday afternoon and there would be 50,000 a game _ even when
it was outside at Rice Stadium and I froze my butt off.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice University officials also are interested in pursuing a
Houston-based bowl and will help even if the bowl lands at the
Astrodome. Rice associate athletic director Steve Moniaci, who is
in charge of facilities at the school, said Rice officials want to
be part of the equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we would be, since we hosted the Bluebonnet Bowl
before (1959-67 and in 1985),'' Moniaci said. ``We'd be interested
in hosting any bowl that was feasible for the city of Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Koening said the Houston group has contacted officials from the
Western Athletic Conference, Conference USA, the Southeastern
Conference and the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   WAC commissioner Karl Benson said the WAC is interested in the
bowl and is waiting to see what happens. C-USA commissioner Mike
Slive also said he was interested in the concept.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston group includes Harris County officials, because
after April 1, 2000, Harris County becomes the landlord of the
stadium. Shea Guinn, director of sports and conventions for Harris
County, said he attended the two meetings with Ippoliti. Any
commitments past April 1, 2000, will require approval of the
county, Guinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can put together a bowl and we can help with having
the facility available _ and the numbers work for us in terms of
running the place _ we'd love to see it,'' Guinn said. ``That's
kind of where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Houston bowl group, which has been a loose association of
interested parties, recently added the Touchdown Club as a sponsor.
The club has come up with several names for the bowl, with Energy
Bowl the leading contender. Others are Space City Bowl, Azalea
Bowl, Bayou Bowl and Oil Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hope,'' said one club member, ``is that Enron or Texaco or
some oil and gas company will sponsor it if it is called the Energy
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bluebonnet Bowl debuted in 1959 when a crowd of 55,000 saw
Clemson defeat TCU 23-7 at Rice Stadium. The game moved to the
Astrodome in 1968 and went out of business following the December
1987 game.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluebonnet name no longer can be used, because organizers of
the bowl owed money to teams when the bowl folded, and a bowl with
the same name would be liable, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluebonnet Bowl owes approximately $400,000 to four schools.
They are Texas and Pittsburgh, which played the last game in 1987,
and Colorado and Baylor, which played in the 1986 contest.
</P>
<P>
   But there could be a stumbling block for the Houston bowl to be
in place by next December. NCAA football certification committee
policy is to have bowls give proposals in April, followed by
another April presentation the following year, said Mark Jones,
staff liaison to the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones says certification has been given after only one year
of the process to the Humanitarian and Motor City bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initial application requires two appearances before the NCAA
subcommittee,'' he said. ``There have been cases where exceptions
are made and the committee has granted some waivers.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the previous waivers was that each bowl just
missed a January deadline to apply for the two-year process, so the
bowls were granted an experimental 1{-year process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know that there is a January deadline to apply
for a bowl if you ask after January,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be 21 bowls with 22 games this year, Jones said. The
Jeep Aloha Bowl Christmas Doubleheader Classic is considered one
bowl even though there are two games _ the Aloha and the Oahu, he
said. These do not include preseason games or the Heritage Bowl,
which is a Division I-AA game.
</P>
<P>
   When 10-2 Wyoming was left out of the bowl process in 1996, it
seemed like a good idea to add bowls. In 1997, the NCAA approved
the Humanitarian Bowl and the Motor City Bowl. This year, the Music
City and Oahu bowls will debut.
</P>
<P>
   But there are three other bowls also on track to play in 1999.
They are the Gateway Bowl in St. Louis, the Mardi Gras Bowl in
Mobile, Ala., and the Freedom Bowl in San Francisco or San Jose,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   If Houston succeeds and joins the bowls in Missouri, Alabama and
California, there will be 26 bowl games, requiring 52 teams. There
were 55 NCAA Division I-A bowl-eligible teams this year. Some
believe that would be too many bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need another bowl like we need another impeachment
hearing,'' Richard Green, a special assistant for the Liberty Bowl
in Memphis, Tenn., told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right on the edge,'' Ron Guenther, chairman of the NCAA
subcommittee on bowl certification, told the AP. ``I don't think it
would happen, but can you imagine if we had a bowl and no team to
play? Now that would be funny, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jones said the NCAA has no ceiling on the number of bowls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who want to put on bowls, and
college football is popular throughout the country,'' Jones said.
``Plus, the bowls do put some positives into the community. I think
the ones that have greater community support have more of a chance
to be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
