<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-BROWN-HNS &LR;      12-24 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-BROWN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
AUSTIN _ Unless he put on a red-and-white suit and slid down
chimneys last night to drop off presents, Mack Brown would be
hard-pressed to improve his image in the eyes of University of
Texas fans.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christmas came early for UT fans when Brown became head football
coach of the Longhorns late last year. Some would say he hasn't
taken one false step since he took the job, which is no easy task
at a school that places extremely high demands on its football
team.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has led Texas to an 8-3 record and its first Cotton Bowl
appearance since 1991, an amazing turnaround over last season's
4-7. But it's more than just his skill as a coach that has endeared
Brown to the Longhorn faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has a personality that makes Santa Claus look like a
grump, something UT alumni love and something his predecessor, John
Mackovic, never managed. But Brown scoffs when people suggest he
has done everything right in his first year at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mess up every day,'' Brown said. ``But we have enough great
staff members to get things back in line when I do mess up. I'm
really happy here, and I think when you enjoy what you're doing,
things are more positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anybody who is miserable do a great job in
their job for a long time. I just think happy people have a better
chance of being successful.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to be happy when you win, but Brown wasn't sure that
was possible when practice began last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really didn't know what to expect,'' Brown said. ``After
the 4-7 season, the kids struggled some with their confidence
level. In spring practice, we weren't very good. We made some
progress, but you worry about the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It usually goes either really well or really poorly. There's
not usually an in-between with that first year.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived from North Carolina, after leading the Tar Heels
to back-to-back 10-win seasons, Brown's first order of business was
to develop a rapport with his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to build up a certain level of communication so you
can get some trust,'' Brown said. ``We knew two of our first three
games were against top-five opponents, so we felt like we would
have a confidence problem with the team early in the season unless
we were better than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's calculations proved correct when the Longhorns took
their lumps at UCLA and Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played very poorly in the first half against UCLA (a 49-31
loss) and were beaten soundly by Kansas State (48-7),'' Brown said.
``But I think it's a real credit to the assistant coaches and the
kids that they were able to hang together. We kept fighting
throughout the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to go whip a Top 10-ranked Nebraska team on the
road and later defeat a Top 10-ranked Texas A&AMP;M team here.''
</P>
<P>
   Most UT fans see the 20-16 win over Nebraska as the turning
point of the season, but Brown thinks the change came in beating
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like Oklahoma was the turning point,'' Brown said. ``At
that time they (the Sooners) were 2-2 and off to a good start, and
it's such a big game for this school. When we were able to beat
them 34-3, I thought it sent a message to the kids that we might be
OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the first time I saw confidence in them as a football
team, especially with our defense. It was the first time we played
sound defense and we made some plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown could see players starting to believe in themselves by the
time the Longhorns played Nebraska on Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought we went to Nebraska feeling like we had a
chance to win,'' Brown said. ``But before the Oklahoma game, I
don't think we were sure how good we could be.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns were better than most people thought they would be
this season _ which will lead to even higher expectations for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The University of Texas always is going to have high
expectations, but we want high expectations,'' Brown said. ``This
(coaching) staff has won 28 games in the last three years, so our
expectations also are very high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win, and the truth is we won some games this year
where the team we beat probably was better than we were. We just
want to play the best we can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown has set a standard that could be hard to equal next year
for a team that loses seven offensive starters, including Heisman
Trophy winner Ricky Williams, All-America guard Ben Adams and
All-Big 12 receiver Wane McGarity.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose all the players we're losing on offense and a
team leader like (middle linebacker) Dusty Renfro on defense,
there's no question the challenge is out there,'' Brown said. ``But
I like high expectations because I think it makes the kids play
harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to have some players next year step up and play
better than they've ever played in their lives to be able to have a
good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he learned this seasonthat Texas fans are wise, and
reasonable, about what they want from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fans in this state appreciate a good game plan
because they understand football,'' Brown said. ``And they also are
smart enough to know UCLA and Kansas State were better teams than
us at that time this year, but as long as we did our best and made
a good effort, they look toward the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fans could have turned on us in the second or third week,
but I think they helped us by sticking with us. The thing we wanted
to do this year was have some fun. Three sellouts at the end of the
year were fun.''
</P>
<P>
   College football is fun again in the state, thanks in part to
strong seasons by both the Longhorns and Texas A&AMP;M. Brown said the
ultimate goal for him and Aggies coach R.C. Slocum is to keep the
best Texas high school players in the state for their college
years, and shoot for a national title.
</P>
<P>
   ``R.C. and I talked about this when I first got here,'' Brown
said. ``We can bring the national championship back to Texas. You
have to be lucky to win all your games, but if you do in the Big
12, then you will be in he hunt for the national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas State would have been this year if they hadn't lost
their last game.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas is believed to be headed toward its best recruiting haul
of the decade, and A&AMP;M isn't far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Brown believes the success of other Division I schools in the
state this season gives high school athletes plenty of choices
without leaving Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason for any kid in Texas to ever look
outside again,'' Brown said. ``Rice came back and played well at
the end of the season; Baylor has a great new coach in Kevin Steele
that I know their fans will be excited about; Texas Tech and TCU
are in bowl games; and SMU is competitive again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great for us to have all these schools winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Brown still plans for the Longhorns to come off with
the cream of the crop among the high school talent. When asked what
he can do for an encore, Brown hopes someday soon Texas will win a
national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is a place where you can do it, and that's what we're
trying to sell,'' Brown said. ``It has been done in the past, and
we have tremendous facilities from which to draw. We have
everything here we need to make a run at it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a kid is concerned about national TV, we have that. If he
is concerned about winning, we have been able to do that. I think
most kids want to stay close to home if they can find what they
want, and that's what we're trying to give them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
