<DOCNO> NYT19981224.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      12-24 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By W.H. STICKNEY JR.  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Arizona State dealt Texas A&AMP;M a triple dose of bitter medicine last
weekend, but apparently it's a prescription that could make a
healing basketball program vigorous for the remainder of the
1998-99 season.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Sun Devils on Saturday night came into Reed Arena, the
Aggies' brand-new home, and took the hosts into triple overtime for
only the second time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line was a heartbreaking 96-91 loss. But team
confidence and the resolve to achieve beyond expectation through
the rest of the year were galvanized, said 6-8 sophomore Aaron
Jack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still hurt as much as anything's hurt us in a while,'' Jack
said Tuesday. ``We had our chances to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting to win those games. We're all disappointed.
I'm sure for the fans it was a great game to watch. It hurt us, but
I thought we did some really good things. We've made a lot of
tremendous strides since last year. I think the main thing is our
mentality, as far as us expecting to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit some big shots and done that sort of thing. I think
we're more mature, (that) our mentality is more of a winning
mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Melvin) Watkins has helped us tremendously with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins is in his first season at A&AMP;M. In only a couple of
months drawing up the X's and O's, he had carried the Aggies to
seven wins (7-1 overall) before meeting the Sun Devils.
</P>
<P>
   That's the Aggies' best start in six years. The win total equals
A&AMP;M's entire output for the 1997-98 season, former coach Tony
Barone's last.
</P>
<P>
   Jack said A&AMP;M would have been hard-pressed even to get to three
overtimes in a game last season. But Saturday, said Watkins, isn't
exactly something the Aggies want to hang their hat on.
</P>
<P>
   By no means, the former coach at North Carolina-Charlotte said,
should a triple-overtime loss be considered a moral victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in moral victories around here,'' he said.
``Surely I was proud of our kids. We kind of wore down there, but
we gave a valiant effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Shanne Jones led the Aggies with 26 points and seven rebounds.
But Aldine's Jerald Brown, who has had an up-and-down first two
years, may have typified the inspired effort Watkins has spurred
on.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time this season, Brown reached double figures
with 19 points, matching his second-highest career total in a game.
</P>
<P>
   He skied for nine rebounds, had two blocked shots and was
3-for-6 from behind the 3-point arc.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Watkins has made a huge difference in virtually every
phase of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team this year, we're focusing in,'' he said. ``We've got
a fresh start, a new coach coming in, bringing a new offense in,
giving us confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stepping up and playing well. (Watkins) has made a great
deal of difference, a big difference. He's given a lot of guys
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got more personnel this year, extra bodies. Last year,
we'd get to the midseason or the end of the season and we had only,
like, six bodies who could go out and play. Now, we've got numbers.
We've got guys who can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said he came into the job not knowing what to expect. He
was uncertain of the opponents, uncertain about the talent level he
inherited and aware of a number of team deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Even a tour through Germany with the Aggies during the summer
didn't have Watkins entirely convinced a sizzling start to the
regular season would be possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really appreciated the way the kids have responded this
far,'' he said. ``Right now, we're 7-2 and could easily be
undefeated, with a bounce here and there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely, (Saturday's) was a game we could have won and should
have won. But Arizona State, I think, as we move forward, we'll
realize that was a pretty good basketball team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies are on Christmas break and don't return to the court
until Monday. That will be a clash with Southern University of the
Southwestern Athletic Conference in Baton Rouge, La.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, said Watkins, the focus will turn in earnest to Big
12 competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players, I think the conference race can be
wide-open,'' he said. ``When we get into the conference, we're
going in saying, `Hey, let's make our mark.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we've got seven wins now, (and) that ties last
year. But that's nothing to rest our hat on. We want to be a
winning program, and we want to start it now, not wait until we
rebuild it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
