<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET THE SPIRIT OF GIVING LAST ALL YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've seen them: men crouched in the cold shadow of a downtown
skyscraper, women begging for money to buy food, children abused
and neglected.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the year, they are, maybe, somebody else's problem _
faceless individuals with no name, no address and no connection
with your life. But then the holiday season arrives, and with joy
in your heart, you determine to do what you can to reduce human
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   You sign on at the local soup kitchen to help feed them, you
offer clothes for them to wear, buy toys for their children, and
sometimes you even stay long enough to find them a permanent place
to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the holidays are gone, you mysteriously disappear
inside yourself, closing your eyes again to the misery that
remains.
</P>
<P>
   But let's hope next year will be different. Let's hope that when
the last gift has been torn open, when the last glass of champagne
has been raised to toast the New Year, you'll still see the need,
still want to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so blessed with people wanting to give of their time
during the holidays,'' said Priscilla Oglevie, director of
volunteers at the Community Enrichment Center. ``But many times,
the needs are forgotten once the holidays are over. I'd like to see
that same spirit last all year.''
</P>
<P>
   The enrichment center, dedicated to providing emergency food
assistance and homes and guidance for the homeless, is just one of
many nonprofits throughout Tarrant County that rely on community
assistance to do the work that they do.
</P>
<P>
   Family Pathfinders, which assists families making the move off
the state's welfare rolls, and Child Advocates of Tarrant County,
which assists abused and neglected children, join with Oglevie in
her plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``A volunteer can critically change the course of history for
these children,'' said Natasha Lawry, volunteer coordinator for
Child Advocates. ``But we're able to serve only about a third of
those in protective custody, because there just aren't enough
volunteers available.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates, Lawry said, speak on behalf of children in protective
custody while the courts decide if and when they can go home.
</P>
<P>
   Because the pool of volunteers is so limited, though, many
children move through the system with little or no support.
</P>
<P>
   The same is often true for families trying to make the
transition from welfare to self-sufficiency, said Kate Hephner,
director of Tarrant County's Pathfinder program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing about poverty is it's isolating,'' Hephner
said. ``So we try to use teams of individuals from civic groups,
businesses, churches and other community organizations to sponsor
families.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a community that has 2,040 families struggling to get off
welfare rolls, Hephner said that her agency has been able to
recruit only 29 volunteer teams to help.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you who say every year that you'd like to help,
want to make a difference, any one of these agencies is your
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Some, such as Child Advocates, require that you fill out an
application and undergo a background check. For many more, all it
takes is a willing heart and a phone call to sign on to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the volunteer positions that we have here is we
try to reach beyond the physical needs,'' Oglevie said. ``We want
to be God's hands and do his work in these people's lives. It's a
wonderful opportunity to make a true difference.''
</P>
<P>
   And a commitment that lasts.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
