<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-CHASE-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF MAN IN WILD CHASE IS PERPLEXED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (lb) 
 By ROBERT HANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ Relatives of Andre Battle, the Georgia truck
driver who led the New Jersey State Police on a wild 67-mile chase
on the Turnpike on Wednesday, said they were at a loss to explain
how a man they know as hard-working and free-spirited could have
become involved in such an incident.
</P>
<P>
   An aunt of Battle in Hazlehurst, Ga., Ophelia Moore, said,
``He's not a fighter. I'm surprised, totally surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Police said the incident began after Battle, 28,
kicked Trooper Anthony Duckett in the head after the trooper
stopped him for speeding _ at 73 mph _ and traveling in the
turnpike's passing lane near Exit 5 in Springfield Township.
</P>
<P>
   After talking briefly with the trooper on the highway shoulder,
Battle returned to his rig's cab to get his license and
registration, the State Police said. A few minutes later, the
trooper told Battle to get out of the cab, officials said. Instead,
he opened the door, kicked the trooper and drove off, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The chase ended at the toll plaza in Carlstadt, as the police
opened fire when Battle tried to turn his 18-wheel rig around and
head back south on the highway, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   Another aunt of Battle, Lorene Adams, also of Hazlehurst, Ga.,
said he is fun-loving and not easy to anger. She said she was
perplexed about the origins of the bizarre hourlong chase on the
New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he kicked that policeman, he had to provoke him, and I mean
to provoke him,'' Ms. Adams contended. ``You've got to push him out
of the ordinary to get him mad.''
</P>
<P>
   James Wentz, safety director at Salson Logistics, the Georgia
truck company that hired Battle two months ago, said: ``We've never
had any problem with this man. We just do not understand the
circumstances. I just can't imagine the chain of events.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Berritto, a retired official with Salson and father of the
current chief executive, Anthony Berritto, called the incident a
``fluky thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at this thing from the outside in and you say, `Why
would a driver who has no record, who is a family man, hit a police
officer if he was stopped?'''
</P>
<P>
   The State Police said they had no additional details to report,
beyond the description of the incident that the state police
superintendent, Col. Carl Williams, provided Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the state police, Sgt. Al Della Fave, said the
authorities had started considering charges against Battle but
would not file them until investigators better understood why he
had ignored state troopers' orders to stop, both along the route of
the chase and, later, just before it ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to know his motives and his mind-set,'' Della Fave
said. ``Until we nail that down, we're not going to file charges.''
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the sergeant said, Battle would be charged with
assaulting Duckett and with attempted murder for crashing into
seven occupied state police vehicles at the toll plaza. Any other
possible charges, Della Fave said, would await more investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how many troopers shot at Battle's truck and
how many bullets were fired. A trooper, Matthew Finnegan, was shot
twice in the foot. The state police have not explained whether he
shot himself or was wounded by other troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Battle's condition improved to fair from critical on Thursday at
the Hackensack University Medical Center. He underwent three hours
of surgery Wednesday for wounds to the neck, chest and arm,
hospital officials said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His parents, Willie and Rosezela, of Leesburg, Ga., and his
girlfriend _ the mother of his two children _ visited him at the
hospital Thursday, Ms. Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital spokeswoman, Anne Marie Campbell, said Battle's
parents and his girlfriend would not grant any interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Battle lives with his girlfriend and children, a 9-year-old girl
and 11-month old boy, in Vidalia, Ga., an uncle, Raymond Wallace,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said his nephew paid for the training courses to become
a long-haul trucker and enjoyed the work. ``He liked going from
state to state, to Washington and Florida and New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his truck-driving job, Battle worked as a mechanic and in
a factory, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't like working inside,'' Ms. Adams said. ``He's got a
chance to travel now. He really liked being out in the open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
