<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOCUS IS ON UW'S WINNING-SEASON STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU _ Befitting his status as a member of the Pac-10
All-Academic team, Nigel Burton has a certain reverence for
history.
</P>
<P>
   It has nothing to do with the little novelty of his Huskies
being part of the NCAA's first bowl doubleheader Friday. That's a
swell thing, but it's a bit like being the first guy to hop on one
leg for 24 hours _ doing something odd just because it's possible
doesn't make the list headed by da Vinci, Gutenberg and Edison
(although it does make the list that includes TV's talking
chihuahua).
</P>
<P>
   Burton's current interest in history is Washington's 21
consecutive football seasons with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   The streak may not inspire chills among the great unwashed, and
it's barely halfway to Notre Dame's record of 42 in a row. But only
10 teams in NCAA history have a longer run. Just two, Nebraska (36)
and Florida State (22), have live streaks longer than the Huskies'.
</P>
<P>
   The UW string is, however, in serious jeopardy. The Air Force
Academy (11-1) is a three-point favorite to shut it down this
afternoon in the first Oahu Bowl, thereby affixing Washington with
a Route 66, for which no kicks are available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys don't understand that 6-6 is not a winning
record,'' the senior defensive back and co-captain said of his
teammates. His point is that something of purple value is at stake
in an otherwise frivolous, if colorful, afternoon of holiday
exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss changes things to 22 straight non-losing seasons,''
Burton said. ``That's not the same. Over the next couple of
meetings we're going to try to make sure everyone understands that.
It's important.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably the message was conveyed in the few days since he
made the observation. But it's hard to know whether the history
lesson will resonate among a population whose sense of the past is
often confined to phone numbers of former girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, prized as is the streak, it isn't quite as relevant as the
future.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important thing to come from a win would be the
sense that Washington's worst record in 10 years represents the end
of a down cycle and a succession of fifth-place bowls.
</P>
<P>
   It is too much to suggest that this game is a crossroads moment
for the Huskies and coach Jim Lambright. Last year's Aloha Bowl
appearance, a 51-23 win over Michigan State, was bigger, coming as
it did after ugly beatings in two straight postseason games as well
as a string of eggs laid in national TV games. The Lambright regime
needed something good to happen.
</P>
<P>
   The game can be little more than lipstick on a pig of a season,
at least by the lofty UW standards. Playing a schedule rated the
nation's eighth-toughest, the Huskies emerged surpassingly
ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Depletions via sanctions and early departures for the NFL left
quarterback Brock Huard with a mediocre line and inexperienced
running backs and wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The decay in Lambright's specialty, defense, was dreadful _ the
298 points surrendered are nearly three times the school record
(101) set in 1991 by the national co-champions and the worst total
since the 2-9 team of 1973 gave up 376.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple failures left Lambright's sometimes curious
playcalling more vulnerable than usual to second-guessing, and
helped keep alive speculation about his fitness to be head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors quietly circulated in the Tyee Club booster group that
some prominent members were sufficiently dismayed with Lambright's
tenure to plot his ouster by attempting to buy out his contract.
But the support of UW president Richard McCormick and athletic
director Barbara Hedges has been steadfast, and the threat has so
far gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   A win would be a rare sign that Lambright can coach his way out
of some trouble, and that his learning curve as a head man is
climaxing. But even a close loss isn't terribly damaging, because
Air Force's slick option offense offers the kind of bedevilment
that has flummoxed teams led by more credentialed coaches than
Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of sanctions provide enough cover that he can
be excused a 6-5 season, just as Don James was. What happens next
year, when four of the five Washington classes will be undamaged by
lost scholarships, is a cleaner test.
</P>
<P>
   With Huard graduating early to the NFL, Lambright will abandon
the ill-fated WAC-style passing attack, which lost its surprise
value after the opener. In Marques Tuiasosopo, the Huskies will
have for the first time since Mark Brunell in 1992 a mobile
quarterback who can do more with less. But even Tuiasosopo knows
greater change must happen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need,'' he said, ``to get back to UW football _ tough up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   That won't happen in one bowl game, or in one season. The
Huskies of Christmas 1998 have fallen a considerable way from their
early-decade eminence of three straight Rose Bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Which made a Huard remark this week all the more poignant.
</P>
<P>
   Answering questions at a conference room podium, he paused to
look out a window at a splendid scene of beach, sun and palm trees,
and indulged himself a moment of wistfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little bit of what Pasadena looks like,'' he said.
``So we're close.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. Not really. But the sentiment was understandable. In
the Husky mindset, a 6-5 season borders on the incomprehensible, so
a grasp at the familiar is made.
</P>
<P>
   And a non-winning season? Well, it's been almost a generation
since anybody's had to try to find the words.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
