<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES SURPRISE NEW MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Todd MacCulloch sat blissfully by himself in a corner
of an ecstatic locker room at KeyArena. In his solitude, he was the
most comprehensive statement on what the Washington basketball team
did to 11th-ranked New Mexico Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MacCulloch, the 7-foot preseason All-American and often a team
spokesman, had 21 points on 9-of-9 shooting and 14 rebounds. But it
took an infusion of big efforts by other Huskies to help bring down
the Lobos, 70-61.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fine,'' said MacCulloch, enjoying his peace.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters were busy with other quarry:
</P>
<P>
   -- Greg Clark, the sophomore transfer from Long Beach State, got
his first start since high school and the assignment was New
Mexico's Lamont Long, a 24.1-points-per-game scorer who led the
nation until recently. The 6-6 Clark's considerable reach held Long
scoreless on three shots.
</P>
<P>
   -- Grant Leep, a 6-5 freshman from Mount Vernon, was inserted
with 11 minutes left as a stop-gap against New Mexico's gifted
center, Kenny Thomas. Leep shocked the 6,101 in the building by
finishing it out and limiting Thomas to his last four points on a
day when the Lobo star led all scorers with 26.
</P>
<P>
   -- Deon Luton resurrected himself from a miserable offensive day
that at one point found him 2-for-16 on field goals. When he began
taking the ball to the basket in the final seven minutes against
New Mexico's troublesome zone defense, he scored 12 UW points in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Luton _ 0-for-11 on 3-point shots _ connected on his
last basket with 2:19 left on a flying eight-footer at the
baseline, the Huskies (6-3) had a 68-59 lead on the Lobos (8-1) and
were out of the woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't be happier for our kids,'' said UW coach Bob
Bender, ``going on Christmas break with a win over a team like New
Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies needed this one a lot more than the Lobos, who
should win plenty in the Western Athletic Conference. Washington,
on the other hand, could ill-afford to carry a fourth loss into a
Pac-10 race that figures to be cut-throat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of this team for stepping up and not letting the
opportunity pass,'' said MacCulloch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard they (the Lobos) hadn't really played anybody, and
this was their first game on the road,'' said Clark. ``We knew this
would be something they weren't used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Luton, the Huskies struggled much of the game on offense,
hitting 2 of 21 treys and shooting .429 overall. But they found
strength in their defense, especially Clark's.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Washington with the reputation of a finesse offensive
player, a label he doesn't deny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking two years off, the game changed a little bit,'' said a
smiling Clark, brother of Detroit Tigers first baseman Tony Clark.
``I've never worked this hard before. Maybe in the past, I wasn't
willing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough scorers. I want to take the role as the leading
defensive player.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark stepped into a void created by Donald Watts' third
straight absence with an ankle sprain. Clark could be an invaluable
resource in conference play, with his ability to take on the
league's prolific off-guards and swing players.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico coach Dave Bliss said Long was rendered less
effective by Thomas rolling onto his ankle late in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that,'' Bliss said, ``Lamont didn't seem to have the
same pop and quickness he usually has.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas was the whole team today,'' Clark said. ``He needed
somebody else to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies started sluggishly, but MacCulloch gave them 15
first-half points and they broke to a 39-29 halftime lead. Behind
Thomas, and four threes in a span of 5:17 _ their only treys of the
game _ the Lobos struggled back on top, 53-52, with 9:36 left.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, New Mexico seemed to forget about Thomas,
who went 14{ minutes of the second half without a basket.
MacCulloch answered the Lobos with two hoops inside, one on a sweet
feed from Leep, and with 8:06 left, Washington led, 56-53, and New
Mexico called timeout.
</P>
<P>
   But the real boost came at Washington's end. There, UW coaches
tried to hoist Luton up from his doldrums. He was 2 of 15 from the
floor, every shot was looking worse than the previous one, and
Luton was clearly discouraged as Bender and his staff encouraged
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking like, `What else can I do?''' Bender said of
the 6-3 junior.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely saw my facial expression,'' said Luton. ``I
was a little down on my shot. I never remember missing shots like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   They told him to attack the basket and Luton heard. He had a
layup goal-tended, and he hit two free throws. He drilled a
15-footer from the baseline. And when New Mexico nosed within
62-57, he scored on Washington's next three possessions and the
Huskies were finally secure.
</P>
<P>
   Leep's contribution was huge. He had averaged only five minutes
in the first eight games, and when he went in to guard Thomas, it
seemed a reach. Both Chris Walcott and Thalo Green had three fouls
apiece and the game was wavering from Washington's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to spend a couple of minutes,'' Leep
said, ``and give one of them a break.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I come to practice, I love seeing him,'' Bender
said. ``He's always got a smile on his face. He gives you
confidence as a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anybody associated with Washington was without a smile.
The Huskies can sleep well before Wednesday's game here with
Portland, assured that if they defend and everybody contributes,
some of last March's stardust is still with them.
</P>
</TEXT>
